u2, the irish rock group with a passion for politics, picked up two grammys wednesday for ``the joshua tree,'' their 12-million selling album, and declared, ``this is just a beginning.''
paul simon won record of the year honors for ``graceland,'' the title track from his south african-inflected album which was the grammy album of the year last year
but little richard upstaged everyone as he hijacked the nationally televised ceremony for several frantic moments, declaring that he had won the grammy for best new artist
i have never received nuthin' _ y'all never gave me no grammys, and i've been singing for years,'' declared the man who sang ``tutti frutti'' and ``good golly, miss molly.''
i am the architect of rock 'n' roll,'' he shouted, and the crowd roared approval
after again announcing that he had, in fact, won the award, little richard revealed the academy's choice _ jody whatley, a madonna sound-alike from the old dance band, shalamar
whitney houston, a winner two years ago with her debut album, took honors at the 30th annual grammy awards for best female pop vocalist for her effervescent single, ``i wanna dance with somebody,'' from her lp, ``whitney.''
narada michael walden won a grammy for producing ``whitney.''
bruce springsteen won a combined male and female rock vocalist category with ``tunnel of love.''
somewhere out there,'' a sweet ballad written by veteran songwriters james horner, barry mann and cynthia weil for the animated film ``an american tail,'' won as song of the year. ``we wrote it for the mice,'' weill said
guitarist the edge, born david evans, pulled out a list as he accepted the grammy for best rock group with vocal ``the joshua tree.'' he thanked luminaries such as martin luther king jr., amnesty international, bob dylan, jimi hendrix, archbishop desmond tutu, dr. ruth westheimer, morris the cat, president reagan and college radio stations
after ``joshua tree'' won as album of the year, lead singer bono (paul hewson) quipped, ``it's really hard to carry the weight of the world on your shoulders.''
we don't see this as a peak for u2,'' bono said backstage. ``it's just a beginning. we've got 12 songs ready for the next album.''
u2, miss houston, los lobos and michael jackson each had four nominations this year, but none threatened threatened to equal jackson's eight-award sweep in the 1984 ceremony
and none had a prayer of overtaking sir georg solti, conductor of the chicago symphony, whose recording of beethoven's 9th symphony won a grammy for best orchestral recording and raised his lifetime total to 26 grammys
vladimir horowitz, the pianist who had 20 grammys entering the ceremonies, won two more for best classical instrumental performance and best classical album for ``horowitz in moscow.'' he also received the president's special merit award from the academy
i am so very happy the classical music still has an appreciation,'' the fiery pianist told the crowd as he accepted the special award. after he won the best album award, he simply smiled and carried it away, saying nothing
jackson's ``bad'' album won an early grammy, for best-produced non-classical recording for producers bruce swedien and humberto gatica
ladysmith black mambazo, the south african vocal group featured on paul simon's ``graceland'' album, won a grammy for themselves for best traditional folk recording for ``shaka zulu.''
robert shaw's recording of requiems by gabriel faure and maurice durufle with the atlanta symphony chorus and orchestra won grammys for best engineered classical recording and for producer robert woods. the atlanta group's recording of paul hindemith's ``when lilacs last in the dooryard bloom'd'' won as best choral performance
frank zappa's ``jazz from hell'' beat his son, dweezil, and springsteen for best rock instrumental. ``trio'' by dolly parton, emmylou harris and linda ronstadt won as best country vocal duo or group performance
this year's show at radio city music hall, televised by cbs, saluted recordings released between oct. 1, 1986 and sept. 30, 1987, in 73 categories. most awards were announced before the broadcast began
the show accented the sounds of new york, where the grammyfest returned after seven years in los angeles. one of the big production numbers featured the hot latin rhythms of tito puente and celia cruz, the funky rap of run dmc and the urban ballads of billy joel
jackson, whose music swept up eight grammys during a ``thriller'' of a ceremony in 1984, was nominated for album of the year for ``bad.'' he was also up for male pop vocal performance for the album and male rhythm 'n' blues vocal performance for the title track. jackson and quincy jones, who co-produced ``bad,'' were nominated in the producer category
los lobos, whose version of ``la bamba'' was a bigger hit than the original adaptation of the mexican folk tune by the late ritchie valens, were nominated for record of the year, song of the year and best pop performane by a duo or group with vocal. the group's ``by the light of the moon'' lp was nominated for best rock performance by a duo or group with vocal
whitney,'' houston's second album, was nominated for album of the year. she was nominated as best female pop vocalist for ``i wanna dance with somebody (who loves me)'' and as best rhythm 'n' blues female vocalist for ``for the love of you.'' another track from the album, ``didn't we almost have it all,'' was nominated as song of the year for writers michael masser and will jennings
the winners were elected by ballots cast by members of the national academy of recording arts &amp; sciences in seven chapters around the nation. the academy's 6,000 members include recording artists, songwriters, musicians, producers and technicians
there was no separate category this year for female rock vocalist. the one nominee, tina turner, was included with richard marx, bob seger, bruce springsteen and joe cocker in a category combining male and female
al schlesinger, president of naras, said the academy has a rule that members must nominate 10 people in a category for an award to be presented
kathleen battle, the soprano who starred on four of the five operas nominated for grammys, ended up winning two _ the vienna philharmonic recording of richard strauss' ``ariadne auf naxos'' and her solo album, ``salzburg recital.'' 6th graf pvs, `three former ...</note>
about 200 people staged a candlelight march at dartmouth college on wednesday night to protest as racist a student newspaper's criticism of a black professor
members of dartmouth's afro-american society and others marched down the ivy league school's fraternity row without incident and held a moment of silence on the campus green in the protest aimed at the dartmouth review
the demonstration came a day after a federal judge dismissed a lawsuit filed against the school by three former students involved in a 1986 sledgehammer attack on anti-apartheid shanties
the former students wanted their college records cleared and the school barred from ``intimidating or interfering'' with the dartmouth review and staff members of the conservative student weekly
in 1986, 12 students, mostly review staffers, took sledgehammers to symbolic anti-apartheid shanties on the campus green. the raid, hours after a service marking the birthday of martin luther king jr., sparked a semester of turmoil
racial tensions were revived last week with the review's stinging written attack on a black professor who once sued the newspaper for libel
four review staffers now are charged by the school with harassing professor william cole after confronting him in his classroom over the article, which criticized a music course he teaches and his ability as a professor
critics of the review also plan a larger rally on thursday
three former review staffers involved in the 1986 incident said the shanty attack constituted ``symbolic speech'' similar to that of the group that erected the shanties to protest dartmouth investments in companies doing business in south africa
on tuesday, u.s. district judge shane devine dismissed the lawsuit, deciding that the students failed to prove that their rights were violated
the suit was filed by deborah stone of keene, frank reichel of philadelphia, teresa polenz of katonah, n.y., and the company that publishes the review
the four review staffers now charged with harassing cole face a college disciplinary hearing on tuesday and possible expulsion
the staffers say are being persecuted for taking strong stands on the quality of dartmouth life and education, and deny that race is a factor. the afro-american society believes the review contributes to racial problems at dartmouth
delta air lines' suit blaming federal agencies for the fiery crash of a delta jet that killed 137 people went to trial tuesday with both sides accusing the other of negligence
the delta crew played russian roulette with the lives of their passengers,'' said kathlynn fadely, a government attorney, during opening arguments in the complex case
flight 191 crashed and exploded into flames aug. 2, 1985, as it headed toward a dallas-fort worth international airport runway during a storm. the 137 dead included the driver of a car that was hit as the plane plunged downward. twenty-five people were injured
in his opening statement, delta attorney john martin said the government is to blame, arguing that the federal aviation administration tower and the national weather sevice failed to warn the flight crew of the severity of a weather system at the airport
he said the delta flight happened to be at the wrong place at the wrong time and air traffic control completely broke down at d-fw when the crash occured
but fadely said the crew didn't listen to warnings from the control tower and flew into the storm system
a report by the national transportation safety board concluded that the crash was caused, in part, by the pilot's decision to fly into a wind shear, a violent downdraft
the trial of delta's claims against the government, delayed six months from its original date, seeks to determine who is to blame for the crash and may also decide how much can be recovered in damages
the decision also will determine whether the government must pay part of $91.2 million in claims that delta's insurers have paid so far in connection with the crash
in december, about 90 lawsuits filed by individuals against delta were parceled out from federal court in fort worth to other u.s. district courts. judge david o. belew jr. ruled that lawsuits filed by passengers' families will be sent back to the courts where they were originally filed
about half of those 90 suits have been settled
the non-jury trial between the airline and the government could last up to three months and could include testimony from any of 550 potential fact and expert witnesses named by the two sides
a bill to ban swimming and restrict other recreation at walden pond, the retreat idealized by henry david thoreau in 1845, has sunk in the legislature
the natural resources committee declined tuesday to adopt a bill that would eliminate a manmade sand beach, restrict fishing and boating and require construction of sound barriers beside roadways near the pond in concord, 15 miles west of boston
mary sherwood, whose group walden forever wild inc. opposes continued recreation at walden, contends that 50 years of public recreation at the pond have endangered its fragile banks and spoiled a pristine site
but department of environmental management commissioner james gutensohn told the committee, ``i'm sure the indians swam at walden pond, i'm sure henry david thoreau swam at walden pond and i'm sure the people of boston should.''
the 62-acre pond, in a 333-acre state-owned reservation, has 350,000 visitors a year
government leaders concerned about israel's battered image abroad are arguing increasingly in favor of barring journalists from the occupied territories after nearly three months of violent protests there
most of israel's 24 cabinet ministers support closing the west bank and gaza strip to journalists as long as the unrest persists, defense minister yitzhak rabin said after attending a cabinet session where the issue was raised this week
closing areas to reporters ``is done in various countries around the world where confrontations of this sort take place,'' said prime minister yitzhak shamir
if it becomes clear that indeed it may limit the damage, i would be willing to consider it,'' he said
the executive committee of shamir's right-wing likud bloc voted unanimously monday evening that journalists should be banned from entering the territories
west bank army commander maj. gen. amram mitzna reissued instructions to field commanders to close areas to reporters for several hours if they believe it is necessary to keep or restore calm, army officials told the associated press on condition of anonymity
but shamir's government partner, foreign minister shimon peres of the centrist labor party, warned against further restrictions
if we were to close off the area, in my opinion, rumors of atrocities would be spread around the world that we would not be able to refute,'' peres said
israel is an open society and a free society and even if (journalists) are not always pleasant, we have to allow them to fulfill their jobs,'' he told reporters tuesday
other officials oppose closing the territories on the grounds that such a move might fuel comparisons between israel and south africa, an issue about which israel has been particularily sensitive
south african police, like israeli army officers, have the discretion to declare an area closed to media on the spot because of unrest. journalists then are barred from entry and must leave if already there
cable news network's bureau chief robert wiener said israeli soldiers seized videotape last week from a crew which photographed a palestinian hanging dead from a pole in the village of qabatiyeh after his neighbors lynched him because he was suspected of collaborating with the israelis
the army was criticized afterward for failing to rescue the palestinian. wiener said the soldiers detained the cnn crew for three hours and refused to return the videotape, saying it contained material damaging to israel's security
the israeli military command said tuesday that ``our policy is to keep the administered territories open to journalists. however there are exceptions to the rule in isolated incidents where certain troublesome areas can be closed.''
the latest debate over media access was triggered by a cbs news report last week that showed four israeli soldiers beating two captive palestinians
the two were beaten for more than half an hour while a cbs cameraman photographed it surreptitiously. after the footage was broadcast, embassies in the united states and europe received many complaints and jewish communities abroad also expressed concern, foreign ministry officials said
the four soldiers are being investigated, the army said. the cbs office in tel aviv has received anonymous threatening telephone calls, said cbs bureau chief terry plantinga
one more incident like the cbs film and the territories will be closed to journalists,'' a government official told the ap on condition of anonymity
rabin met monday with a delegation from the foreign press association and said most cabinet ministers supported blocking journalists from entering the territories but he did not, according to fpa chairman robert slater
the voices in favor of closing the territories have become much louder than the others,'' slater said. ``it appears more likely than ever before that such a step will be taken and the fpa is increasingly worried.''
two israeli newspapers, the left-wing al hamishmar and the independent maariv, ran editorials tuesday criticizing discussions in government circles about closing the territories to journalists
without media in the territories we may live in a warm comfortable bubble next to an erupting volcano,'' al hamishmar said. ``but we will be caught by surprise and off guard when the lava overflows and threatens our very existence.''
sarah, the duchess of york, better known as ``fergie,'' has received a scolding from a suburban chicago dermatologist who contends her visits to a tanning parlor set a bad example
the former sarah ferguson who is married to britain's prince andrew is especially prone to sun damage because of her fair complexion and celtic ancestry, said dr. michael greenberg
greenberg said he wrote to the duchess after reading in people magazine about her tanning parlor visits
i am astounded that an intelligent woman such as yourself would, first consent to tan her skin considering the increase in skin cancer caused by ultraviolet (rays) and, second, let yourself be an example for the millions of ordinary, gullible women who follow whatever a member of the royal family does as though it were gospel,'' greenberg wrote
the duchess and her husband, both 28, are on a 10-day visit to california. they are expecting their first child in august
i think she would be grateful for his concern,'' said francis cornish, a spokesman for the british consulate in los angeles, which delivered the letter tuesday to the duchess' private secretary
the duchess and her husband plan to leave los angeles on friday for a two-day stay in the desert resort palm springs, calif., before heading back to britain, cornish said
chinese authorities have crushed efforts at peaceful dissent by the nationalist monks of tibet as swiftly as they did last year's bold and violent protests by the buddhist holy men
hundreds of monks boycotted the opening of a prayer festival, in the first major clash of wills since at least 14 people were killed in a demonstration oct. 1
by the second day, however, a major monastery that led the boycott yielded to chinese pressure and sent more than 200 monks to the festival, other monks reported. official media had called the gathering a sign of normality in the troubled himalayan region
the monks didn't want to come,'' one holy man whispered at the jokhang temple in central lhasa, where the prayer festival began last thursday and continued this week
they finally did, he said, because ``they were afraid _ afraid that the police will grab them.'' he glanced over his shoulder at an approaching plainclothes policeman, one of dozens patrolling the temple
fear remains the primary legacy of the three pro-independence demonstrations led by monks over a two-week period in september and october in lhasa, the mile-high tibetan capital whose name means ``holy ground.''
the monks dispute china's claim to sovereignty and want independence under the leadership of their exiled god-king, the dalai lama
chinese authorities have removed all remnants of a police station near the jokhang temple that was burned oct. 1 by hundreds of angry monks and lay tibetans, prompting police to fire on the crowd. a new stone building is being built on the site
military roadblocks have been removed from outside the three main monasteries in the lhasa area _ sera, drepung and ganden _ and police who were billeted inside the monasteries have been withdrawn. plainclothes chinese agents now keep watch
all but 15 of the 80 people arrested during the protests have been released from jail after repenting, according to official reports
the prayer festival, called moinlam qenmo, has been held at jokhang temple every year since 1409 except for the period 1960-85, when it was banned by china. it gathers monks from the lhasa area for eight days of continuous prayer and is one of the the most important tibetan buddhist events
as a precaution, beijing sent the highest-ranking tibetan buddhist leader in china, the panchen lama, to tibet in early february to persuade monks to cooperate
he is regarded as second in prestige only to the dalai lama, who fled to india nine years after the chinese army entered tibet in 1950
the panchen lama said `don't demonstrate,''' said a 20-year-old monk at the sera monastery, whose whitewashed stone buildings cling to a mountainside on the southern fringe of the city
some (monks) said ok, but some were quiet, didn't answer,'' he said, gathering his blood-red robes against a chill wind
their answer came thursday, when fewer than 600 showed up in jokhang's silk-draped central courtyard for the opening of the prayer festival, which attracted more than 1,000 monks last year
those attending quickly spread the word: ``not one monk from ganden is here.''
a monk from sera said the holy men of ganden stayed away because ``the situation is not good. too many chinese are here; too many police.'' other monks said the same
sera and drepung sent fewer monks than usual, and those who remained at drepung conducted their own, small-scale prayer festival
we're afraid of the police,'' said one boycotter at drepung. ``it's a very big festival, but if we make a small mistake we will be in trouble.''
in addition to plainclothes officers inside, uniformed police were stationed every few yards around the whitewashed stone jokhang temple, which is the size of a city block
several policemen watched from the roof of a nearby police building and others photographed foreign visitors, some of the few allowed into tibet since the protests last year
the ganden monks finally arrived quietly thursday night from their home on a holy mountain 35 miles west of lhasa. their presence brought to nearly 800 the number of monks who sat cross-legged most of the day in the stone courtyard, chanting
a stream of pilgrims, including herdsmen in tattered furs, edged around the courtyard and spooned offerings of butter into lamps that flickered in racks along the wall
tibetan sources and westerners who have seen previous festivals said there were fewer pilgrims, as well as monks, this year
one tibetan said lhasa's population of 40,000 usually doubled with the influx of monks and pilgrims during moinlam qenmo. no count of pilgrims was available because most stay only a few days and sleep in the streets
china's official media said festival attendance was up, from 1,100 monks and pilgrims last year to more than 2,300
dozens of chinese reporters wrote of the event and the official news agency xinhua quoted local authorities as saying: ``last year's riot has not had any impact on the ceremony.''
monks who stayed behind at the the ganden monastery, which was leveled by radicals during the 1966-76 cultural revolution and is only partially restored, were not allowed to talk freely to visitors
of more than a dozen monks interviewed at the jokhang temple and at sera, drepung and smaller monasteries, none expressed regret for the violence of the protests. all were emphatic in disdain for the chinese
chinese are no good,'' a 12-year-old novice monk said in english. ``but we are not afraid.''
a lay tibetan said: ``tibet had its own culture, its own religion, its own border guards. how can they say we are one country?''
danny the red, leader of student revolts in france and west germany in the 1960s, jokingly says he was never quite as leftist as his nickname implied
they only meant my hair color,'' said daniel cohn-bendit, referring to his rust-colored hair during an interview in his frankfurt office. ``i've always been an anti-communist, more of one than reagan.''
he's now 42 years old and an active member of west germany's anti-establishment, environmentalist greens party _ the moderate wing _ and publishes a left-leaning regional magazine in frankfurt
he ran unsuccessfully for mayor of frankfurt in 1986 in a purely symbolic move, he said. but he is considering seriously running for frankfurt's city council next year
cohn-bendit has also become an author. a collection of interviews with other 1960s activists around the world was published in west germany in september
american activists featured in the book include jerry rubin and abbie hoffmann, leading yippies of the era, and the black panther activist, bobby seale
the book, ``we loved it so, the revolution,'' portrays rubin as a yippie-turned-yuppie and seale as hoping for commercial success as a cookbook author
his book isn't the only look back: west germany's news media have carried numerous articles on the tumultuous times of 1968
cohn-bendit said that he has basically remained true to many views he had 20 years ago
i believe that i can still legitimize everything i do from my standpoint in 1968,'' cohn-bendit said
as a moderate member of the greens, cohn-bendit favors forming coalitions with west germany's liberal social democratic party, which the greens' radical wing opposes. nor does cohn-bendit favor a west german withdrawal from nato, as some of the radicals do
west german militarization is more dangerous on its own than embedded in a larger context,'' he said. ``that's the lesson of world war ii.''
cohn-bendit has always been a figure who defied traditional national, political, and religious labels. he was born in montauban, france, on april 4, 1945, the son of german jews who fled hitler's persecution in the 1930s
his parents moved to west germany when cohn-bendit was 13. in 1961 cohn-bendit became a west german citizen
i did it only for pragmatical reasons,'' he said. ``i didn't want to serve in the military.''
jews whose parents or siblings were persecuted under the nazis are by west german law exempted from the country's mandatory military service
cohn-bendit, who speaks french and german fluently, said he doesn't assign his national identify to either country. as a french citizen, he would have been subject to the military draft in france
i'm just me. i'm not german or french,'' he added. ``i don't need a national definition.''
cohn-bendit's views have led to occasional flaps with frankfurt's jewish community. in a highly publicized dispute in 1985 he publicly supported the city playhouse in presenting a play by rainer werner fassbinder, which many jews wanted banned as anti-semitic
in the feb. 18 issue of his magazine ``pflasterstrand,'' cohn-bendit described himself as a ``convinced anti-zionist.''
in the interview, he said he favored the existence of israel but also a separate palestinian state and ``a limitation of zionism.''
tenants' housing rights and terrorist amnesty are among other issues that have made cohn-bendit a household name
but the era that propelled the activist to world fame, the 1960s, is a topic cohn-bendit said he no longer wants to talk a lot about
in his book, originally published in france, he writes that people have used him ``like a machine that turns back time.''
cohn-bendit captured world attention as a university student in france, at a time when youth protests were rocking the globe
he was a spokesman for students whose demands included greater social equality and an end to war, in vietnam and elsewhere. danny the red became the leader of paris' tumultuous _ and occasionally bloody _ student revolts
we had the will to change our lives, to participate in history right at the moment it happened,'' cohn-bendit writes of his revolutionary days
in may 1968 french authorities expelled him from the country on grounds of disturbing the peace. the ban was not officially lifted until 1978,cohn-bendit wrote in his book
cohn-bendit lives with his girl friend, but he said he doesn't intend to get married
elevated rates of colon cancer in the nation's northeast and north-central region may be due to an acid rain pollutant that absorbs sunlight, impairing the body's ability to make vitamin d, reseachers say
preliminary studies have suggested that vitamin d and calcium combine to lower the risk of colon cancer
according to the new theory, sulfur dioxide in the atmosphere absorbs ultraviolet rays from the sun that trigger the production of vitamin d in the skin, researchers said at a press conference tuesday
sulfur dioxide, produced by the burning of high-sulfur coal, is a principal ingredient of acid rain
a similar effect was observed in london more than 350 years ago, said the originators of the new theory, said cedric garland of the university of california, san diego and his brother, frank, of the naval health research center in san diego
around 1629, londoners began burning high-sulfur coal from newcastle, they said. within a short time, children began exhibiting the leg malformations characteristic of rickets _ a vitamin d deficiency disease
vitamin d aids the absorption of calcium, and calcium and vitamin d together appear to lower the risk of colon cancer, the garlands said
dr. martin lipkin of new york's memorial sloan-kettering cancer center said the garlands' theory ``is a legitimate theory'' and work is in progress to clarify the role of vitamin d and calcium in colon cancer
we're looking into how many individuals might be benefited by calcium _ and the degree to which they might be,'' said lipkin. two years ago, he showed that calcium supplements could change the growth of cells in the colons of people at high risk of colon cancer and might therefore lower colon cancer risk
an authority on diet and cancer, regina ziegler of the national cancer institute in bethesda, md., cautioned that because this was only a theory, people should not begin taking vitamin d supplements to protect against colon cancer
people have trouble distinguishing theories from proven effects,'' she said. ``with evidence such as this, you certainly don't want to start taking large doses of vitamin d. vitamin d in high doses can be hazardous to your health.''
the garlands' explanation is not the only theory to explain why colon cancer rates are highest in the north-central and northeastern states
other people have hypothesized that increased exercise, increased fruit and vegetable intake and differences in drinking water may lead to the lower incidence in the south,'' said ziegler
the garlands cautioned that people should not spend more time in the sun to increase their vitamin d production because exposure to sunlight increases the risk of skin cancer. they suggested instead that people eat foods high in vitamin d, which include anchovies, sardines, salmon and tuna. milk is fortified with vitamin d, but most other dairy products are not, they said
breast cancer also occurs at an increased rate in the areas where colon cancer is highest, and the garlands suggested that breast cancer, too, might be indirectly related to sulfur dioxide in the atmosphere. that theory is more speculative than the colon cancer theory, frank garland said. previous texas winners, other detail. picks up at dash.</note>
courtney gibbs became the fourth texan in a row to win the miss usa crown tuesday, besting miss california in the nationally televised pageant
it feels fabulous,'' ms. gibbs, 21, said moments after being crowned by her predecessor and fellow texan, michelle royer. ``one of the gifts michelle gave me was a dictionary with the word `impossible' whited out. so of course it was possible.''
ms. gibbs, of fort worth, won the right to compete in the miss universe pageant may 23 in taiwan. ms. royer, of keller, came in third in last year's worldwide competition, which was won by miss chile
the blue-eyed brunette, a junior in advertising and public relations at texas christian university, won over diana magana, 22, of rancho palos verdes, calif., the first runner-up
miss usa spokeswoman stacy sacco said she was stunned by the fourth miss texas victory in a row. ``what are the odds?'' she said
second runner-up was miss georgia, donna rampy, 24, followed by miss florida, monica bruni farrell, 23, and miss mississippi, dana michele richmond, 20
soon after the beaming new miss usa ascended her throne, the last three title holders posed with her for photographers
ms. royer's predecessor, christie fichtner of dallas, called the last four winners ``four aces in a deck of cards.''
the woman who started the string, laura martinez-herring of el paso, said: ``it's always been known texas is full of beautiful women, and this just proves it. i just feel sorry for the next miss texas.''
actress tracy scoggins and actor alan thicke served as co-hosts for the program, televised by cbs. ten semifinalists, who had been chosen last week, were announced as the pageant opened tuesday night
the pageant capped three bizarre weeks in which two contestants quit because of police records, animal-rights activists protested the awarding of fur coats and the co-host, miss scoggins, was attacked in a hotel elevator
the hosts made no mention of the various problems during the television show
the late departures of two contestants, both from minnesota, opened a spot for julie nelson, 20, of minneapolis, but the lateness meant she arrived about a week after the other contestants
actually, i've found this oddball situation to be quite an advantage,'' she said before the pageant opened. ``having so short a time to pull myself together, getting all my clothes together, finding a fur coat, dropping everything _ when all the other girls had months to prepare. it shows off my abilities.''
miss nelson was not among the 10 semifinalists
besides a mink jacket and full-length coat worth a total of $15,000, miss usa wins a $25,000 personal appearance contract, $46,000 cash, a sports car, $10,000 worth of jewelry and other prizes, including a portable home tanning center
about 25 animal-rights activists picketed tuesday outside the el paso convention center to protest the awarding of the furs to the winner
members of the el paso and las cruces, n.m., chapters of sangre de cristo animal rights contend fur ranching and trapping are cruel to the animals
bob young, director of sangre de cristo's las cruces chapter, had asked thicke to do as longtime host bob barker had done earlier: resign in protest over the awarding of the furs
thicke refused, saying the furs were taken from ranch-raised minks that had been treated humanely. he and young released a joint statement monday saying they agreed that fur-trapping is cruel but disagreed on fur-ranching
in another prepageant incident, a man accused of attempted sexual assault in the attack on miss scoggins last week was released on $100 bail. prosecutors usually ask for $15,000 bail in third-degree felonies like attempted sexual assaults
a man ripped miss scoggins' dress and shoved her into the back of a hotel elevator, authorities said. she fought the man off and a man was arrested at the hotel
the man's bail was later raised to $100,000, which he posted
another person connected with the pageant has a date with the law. suzanne pitman, miss kentucky-usa, is awaiting trial on drunken-driving charges
two other contestants with arrest records, both from minnesota and both accused of shoplifting, elected to bow out
the original miss minnesota-usa, sue bolich, resigned after it was disclosed she'd been accused of shoplifting $370 worth of clothing. her replacement, first runner-up jolene stavrakis, quit after disclosing she had pleaded no contest to stealing from a store in march 1986
the first miss usa pageant was in 1952 in long beach, calif
three-fourths of the democratic party leaders who will be national convention delegates are not yet supporting any of the presidential candidates as the initial round of primaries and caucuses draws to a close, an associated press survey found
since late last year, the candidates together have attracted support that will add up to fewer than three dozen votes at the convention, according to the survey, in which hundreds of the party's ``super delegates'' were contacted
and despite the months of debates and the weeks of primaries and caucuses, many of the automatic delegates, who include democratic national committee members, democratic governors and others, are not closing in on which candidate they plan to suppport
the more i hear, the more uncommitted i become,'' said ruth moss, a democratic national committee member from maine
massachusetts gov. michael dukakis, the winner of the new hampshire primary, leads the pack with commitments totaling just 31.5 votes at the convention. by comparison, the runaway favorite so far is ``uncommitted,'' a category in which delegates with 247.65 votes at the convention place themselves, the ap survey found
missouri rep. richard gephardt, winner of the iowa caucuses, is next behind dukakis with commitments amounting to 21 votes at the convention, followed by jesse jackson with 19.55, tennessee sen. albert gore with 16.55 and illinois sen. paul simon with 15.5
only gary hart, who has acknowledged his chances of winning the democratic nomination are remote at best, has not received a commitment from any of the delegates contacted by the ap
when added to delegates won by the candidates in the primaries and caucuses so far, that brings the total to 63.5 for dukakis, 47 for gephardt, 35.5 for simon, 27.55 for jackson, 16.55 for gore and none for hart. a total of 258.65 are counted as uncommitted
the survey, conducted during the last two weeks of february, indicates that the iowa caucuses and the new hampshire primary, along with nearly weekly debates, have made little impression on democratic party leaders. the survey found that just 35.25 more convention votes have been won by the candidates since a similar ap survey late last year
i'm still not convinced that iowa and new hampshire are representative of the cross section of the united states,'' said new mexico party chairman sam pick
call over to the grammar school and talk to any first-grader _ he knows just as much as i do,'' said j.t. rose, a dnc member from arkansas. ``it's up for grabs. i'm just sitting back enjoying it.''
that's not what the gephardt campaign had hoped to hear after the victory in iowa
i think we expected a bigger bounce,'' said jude barry, a gephardt campaign aide who works on delegate selection. ``we would like people to commit sooner, but we're encouraged by what they're telling us.''
rick hutcheson, a gore campaign aide involved in delegate selection, said he is not surprised to see the super delegates holding back
these are political people; they want to wait and see what the voters in the primaries decide and then they will exercise their judgment,'' he said
however, barry said party leaders may feel some incentive to begin committing themselves after next week's super tuesday contests, when nearly one-third of the party's delegates are at stake
at that point i think that people start looking at the calendar,'' barry said. ``people who come in after new york (which holds an april 19 primary) are really going to be seen as coming late to the party.''
the democratic party allots 362 convention votes to members of its national committee, some of whom will cast only fractions of votes. an additional 25 votes are given to governors of states and territories and five to former leaders, including former president carter and walter mondale, a former vice president who was the party's nominee in 1984
delegates representing 352.75 convention votes were contacted for the ap survey in february
an additional 253 delegate slots will be awarded to democratic members of congress in april
the republican party makes no such provision for automatic delegates, awarding all the seats to its national convention through the primaries and caucuses
in all, 4,162 delegates are to attend the democratic national convention in atlanta july 18-21, and 2,082 are needed to win the presidential nomination
that masterpiece of music comedy and nostalgic americana, ``the music man,'' suffered from a lack of strong, clear singing as the new york city opera opened its annual season of musical comedy
the acting, directing, dancing and scenery were first-rate tuesday at the new york state theater. but some of the verve and excitement of those glorious, fast-paced songs was lost during the first act as the singing did not carry well over the orchestra
the problem was alleviated after intermission. perhaps it was the shift to mostly ballads, or perhaps the level of the singers' microphones had been boosted, but act 2 was the rich, delightful experience one hopes the whole show will be for the rest of its run through april 10
bob gunton, debuting with the company as harold hill, had the most trouble. a broadway performer, he moves as gracefully as a dancer and sold his ``76 trombones'' to the folks of river city with more charm than brass. but his light voice didn't project in act 1's ``ya got trouble'' and ``the sadder but wiser girl.''
the female chorus also was difficult to understand in ``pick-a-little, talk-a-little,'' and the townspeople blurred the words of joyful anticipation in ``the wells fargo wagon.'' david burdick, smaller than most boys who play the lisping winthrop, also is no belter, and didn't get his words across the footlights
opera singers learn to project their voices and they came out best, making themselves understood and never sounding too operatic for the music. leigh munro was a pretty and sympathetic marian the librarian, muriel costa-greenspon a natural leader of ladies as the mayor's wife, richard mckee as the pompous mayor, james billings as harold hill's cohort, brooks almy as marian's mother and william ledbetter as the constable
the dancing chorus was splendid, with choreography by marcia milgrom dodge, making her company debut. there's a generous amount of dancing, in the library, in rehearsals for a ``social,'' in the center of town several times. david jenkins' set of business buildings pulled back to give the dancers room. andrew marlay's costumes for 1912 were glorious, from feathered hats to peppermint suits for the four school board members who squabbled every minute they weren't harmonizing ``lida rose.''
donald pippin, a broadway conductor, was conducting at the new york city opera for the first time. it was wonderful to hear the overture played by a big orchestra, less wonderful later when words were covered
the late meredith willson wrote the book, music and lyrics. he and frank lacey wrote the plot, which came out as a memory of bygone innocent days of mason city, iowa, where willson grew up. one wonderful song follows another _ ``goodnight, my someone,'' ``my white knight,'' ``till there was you'' _ and the audience greeted each gem like a reunion with a long-lost best friend
the reagan administration is trying to soften earlier accusations that the federal reserve's tight monetary policies are nudging the country toward a recession
in separate forums, a trio of reagan administration officials said tuesday they believe the nation's central bank is doing a good job of supplying money to the economy
just a few weeks ago, administration officials worried about the prospect of a recession during an election year had been complaining that the fed wasn't pumping enough new money into the economy
on tuesday, however, treasury secretary james a. baker iii told the senate appropriations committee that he has ``absolutely no disagreement'' with the fed's monetary policy
speaking at the national press club, budget director james c. miller iii said, ``there seems to be a little bit of easing, and i welcome that.''
and at a meeting of the national association of business economists, beryl sprinkel, president reagan's chief economic adviser, said the administration is ``supportive of present policy as well as the plans for the future'' the fed revealed last week
the suddenly conciliatory administration tone follows a sharp counterattack by fed chairman alan greenspan, who had responded to the administration complaints with some pointed remarks of his own
greenspan said that a looser monetary policy could spark higher inflation. he also said pressure by the administration could push the fed into asserting its independence by doing the opposite of what the white house wanted
the administration began pulling back from its criticisms last week. sprinkel said he supports the fed's policies so far in 1988, and reagan said at his news conference last wednesday that he had confidence in greenspan, whom he appointed to the fed job last summer
the central bank can usually increase the flow of credit by easing interest rates
baker told the senators tuesday that when it comes to finding the balance between keeping interest rates low and avoiding inflation, ``i think the fed is doing that and doing a very good job of that.''
in other testimony, baker played down concerns raised by senators about the growth of the national debt
projections by the congressional budget office, cited at the hearing, are that the national debt could reach $4 trillion by 1993. the debt was below $1 trillion when reagan took office in 1981
there are some risks in the growth of debt of this magnitude, but i think they tend to be overstated,'' baker said. ``i think to some extent that's a consequence of the fact that we're moving into 1988, which happens to be an election year.''
baker also said, however, that ``an increase in the debt is not a development about which this administration nor the congress can be very happy.''
the head of comedie francaise, actor and director jean le poulain, died tuesday night. he was 63
le poulain died at his home on the avenue de l'opera, near the famed theater he had administered for the past two years. no cause of death was given
it is the theater of yesterday and today which cannot, tonight, hide its tears,'' culture minister francois leotard said in a statement. ``the curtain of the (comedie) francaise has fallen on a great voice.''
le poulain had been a member of the comedie francaise since 1979 and was placed in charge in 1986
during his 40-year career in the theater, he acted in and directed dozens of plays from the classics to contemporary pieces
with his disappearance, french theater loses one of its most brilliant servants, an inheritor of the tradition of the comedie francaise, that which runs from moliere to jacques charron,'' leotard's statement said
le poulain was born in marseille sept. 12, 1924, but spent much of his childhood in cambodia, where his father worked
returning to france at the age of 19, he studied at the paris conservatory, which he left in 1949 with the first prize in acting
in 1952, he founded his own theater company, directing a variety of plays from shakespeare to jean anouilh
le poulain was known to the public as both a buffoon and a tragedien, but he received the most acclaim for his portrayals in the plays of moliere, such as ``tartuffe'' and ``le bourgeois gentilhomme.''
after taking over the comedie francaise, as the candidate proposed by president francois mitterrand, le poulain neither acted nor directed. he said he concentrated his time to running the institution _ ``i am the protector of its soul.''
alarmed by a rise in drug production and the violence that goes with it, the reagan administration is warning colombia and mexico that their anti-narcotics programs will receive close scrutiny in the coming months
they were singled out tuesday in the president's annual drug report to congress as countries that are making some efforts to stop narcotics traffic but need to improve
they were not classed with iran, afghanistan, syria and a new entry on the list, panama, as countries whose support for drug trafficking makes them ineligible for u.s. aid
ann wrobleski, assistant secretary of state for international narcotics matters, said the message to colombia and mexico is: ``we believe that you're cooperating and you deserve certification, but we want to put an asterisk next to it and we will be watching closely in 1988.''
in the annual report to congress, the president certifies whether countries are doing enough to battle narcotics to deserve u.s. assistance and other benefits
panama made the list this year because its military chief and de facto leader, manuel antonio noriega, has been indicted by a u.s. grand jury on drug conspiracy charges. panama is not a major narcotics producing country, but according to wrobleski, ``panama has been a drug traffickers' and money launderers' haven.''
putting panama on the list will have no immediate impact, because the country had lost u.s. aid even before noriega's indictment. but tuesday's action does permit further steps by the administration, including some tariffs and tightening of customs rules that could hurt panamanian exports
sen. alfonse d'amato, r-n.y., said he would introduce legislation to go further by imposing a trade embargo on panama
the good news is that panama is on the list,'' said sen. lawton chiles, d-fla. ``on the other hand, mexico and colombia aren't. ... i think we have to continue to apply pressure against these countries.''
the president's report faulted colombia for not breaking a cartel of drug dealers and for not fully backing u.s. requests for extradition of drug suspects wanted in the united states. at the same time, it noted that whatever efforts colombia made in the fight were ``at great peril to its officials.''
it said mexico is the largest single source of heroin and marijuana entering the united states, and officials there need to do more to eradicate opium poppies and deal with allegations of official corruption
three countries said to be doing little to stop narcotics escaped inclusion on the list due to special ``national security concerns,'' the report said
laos was kept off the list out of concern that a condemnation would harm u.s. efforts to win laotian help in accounting for more than 500 u.s. servicemen listed as missing there after the vietnam war, wrobleski said. laos doesn't get u.s. aid anyway
paraguay escaped decertification because officials think it would be counter-productive at a time the united states is trying to woo that country toward democracy
lebanon retained its certification because there isn't much the central government can do to stop trafficking and production in regions of the country it does not control
in its estimates of worldwide drug production, the report predicted that coca leaf output would increase from a high of 211,400 metric tons in 1987 to as much as 213,650 metric tons this year
marijuana production will drop from a high of 17,625 metric tons to 10,100 tons, and opium output will drop from a high of 3,017 metric tons to 2,992 metric tons in 1988, the report said. a metric ton equals 2,200 pounds
ms. wrobleski said one of the gloomiest outlooks is for control of coca leaf growth, especially in peru and colombia, the origin of a vast majority of the world's cocaine
bolivia has made some strides in eradicating the crop by sending work crews into the production areas to kill the plants. that's impossible in peru and colombia, she said, because the growers control the regions. in peru, for example, 27 eradication workers have been killed, she said
a girls clubs of america leader says the organization's identity and fund-raising are threatened by a competing group it is suing
the suit filed monday in u.s. district court asks for an injunction to prevent the boys clubs of america from changing its name to the boys and girls clubs of america
the importance of this is the perception of the public as to who they are and who we are,'' margaret gates, national executive director of the girls clubs, said tuesday
thomas garth, national director-elect of the boys clubs, said that organization has about 300,000 girls among it 1.3 million members, and their parents are demanding the name change
the girls clubs says it serves about 250,000 girls and that about 40,000 boys participate in its activities. the organization says about 80 percent of it $2.7 million operating budget comes from contributions and grants that benefit its many members who come from lower-income families
presidential candidates are turning to increasingly aggressive television advertising in the week before the high-stakes super tuesday contests in 20 states and american samoa
vice president george bush is taking some heat on the iran-contra affair from sen. bob dole. sen. albert gore jr. is moving onto the populist turf claimed thus far by rep. richard gephardt. and gephardt is continuing his broadside against massachusetts gov. michael dukakis
gephardt, d-mo., also is running an ad in which rep. marvin leath of texas praises him for standing ``with us for lower taxes, for an oil import fee to make america strong, for a tough trade bill to stand up for american workers.'' leath says gore and dukakis oppose all three
gore spokesman arlie schardt said tuesday it had not been decided yet whether the tennessee senator would release his own cache of hard-hitting ads
we're prepared for any needs that may arise,'' schardt said. ``we're considering what other messages we may still want to convey over the next few days.''
gore did mount an indirect tv challenge to gephardt on tuesday, when he started running three new ads promoting populist themes similar to the ones gephardt has adopted
one new ad depicts gore as a fighter against polluters, price-fixers and big corporations _ exactly the type of anti-establishment image gephardt has tried to cultivate
the other two ads feature gore talking to groups of texas oil workers. in one spot he says corporations need to invest in america and create jobs at home, while in the other he tells the workers that ``it's time to put people back to work in the united states and have the rigs in libya and iran stand idle for a change.''
the ``blame foreigners'' message is strikingly similar to one of gephardt's strongest ads, the ``hyundai'' spot that helped him win the iowa caucuses and is now being used across the super tuesday states
in that ad the congressman criticizes south korea for putting high import tariffs on u.s. autos and asks how many hyundais the koreans could sell here at $48,000 apiece
gephardt has also revived a highly effective south dakota spot, now retooled for super tuesday, alleging that dukakis is a tax-raiser and mocking his suggestion that depressed iowa farmers recover by growing belgian endive
the dukakis campaign was planning to take aim at gephardt's newly acquired reputation as an anti-establishment crusader and possibly run an ad featuring a swirling weathervane to raise questions about his consistency
leslie dach, dukakis's communications director, said no final decisions had been made about which ads would be used where and when
but he said the general thrust of the spots is that gephardt ``says he is leading the little guy's fight but his campaign is financed and supported by the big guys. his biggest contributors are america's biggest corporations. he has failed to show a set of principles or a set of values that give a rudder to his policies.''
he said dukakis was also prepared to counter-attack against gore, if necessary
dukakis has commercials on the air in texas and florida, the biggest super tuesday states, plus maryland. his ad campaign was to expand this week into washington state, oklahoma, arkansas, alabama, georgia and north carolina, aides said
dole, r-kan., went on the air tuesday in north carolina and south carolina with an ad contrasting his and bush's positions on a number of issues, including the iran-contra affair
the narrator says dole ``opposed selling arms to iran. bush supported the arms-for-hostages deal.'' the ad also accuses bush of waffling on taxes, taking a soft line on the u.s.-soviet arms control treaty, and opposing a textile bill popular in several southern states
another dole spot running in florida depicts a man walking through snow but leaving no footprints. dole campaign manager bill brock said the message is that bush ``has held all these big jobs'' yet left no mark
the vice president, in west palm beach, fla., called the ``footprints'' commercial ``terribly ineffective.''
bush's campaign refused to disclose any details of how or whether it planned to respond. but the vice president said: ``we're not going to sit out there unprotected. ... i think i have every right to set the record straight.''
bush used a negative ad against dole in new hampshire last month, but it ran for only a couple of days before the primary
as the super tuesday tv campaign grew more heated, rep. jack kemp, r-n.y., questioned pat robertson's judgment in radio ads throughout south carolina, which holds a gop primary on saturday
the kemp ad asks if the former television evangelist has ``the qualifications and the judgment to be our next president'' and cites some of his more unusual positions such as a 1979 suggestion that public schools be eliminated. robertson later changed his mind about that
in addition to negative ads, the candidates are using more traditional biographical spots and political testimonials. among them: former sen. barry goldwater endorses bush, former house speaker thomas p. o'neill of massachusetts praises dukakis, and rep. claude pepper _ an elderly florida legislator with enormous clout among senior citizens _ speaks kindly of gephardt
at least two candidates, gore and dukakis, are using spanish-language ads in texas. dukakis does the talking himself. ``the governor is fluent in spanish, so it seemed like the thing to do,'' said tom cosgrove, dukakis's texas campaign director
there are 712 republican delegates and 1,307 democratic delegates up for grabs on super tuesday, march 8. television is the candidates' major tool in seeking to win them. ventures</head>
academics and business managers from the soviet union and the united states will team up to study four industrial sites in each country in an effort to develop management guidelines for joint ventures
the study will mark the first time westerners will be allowed to participate in on-site research of soviet decision-making methods, project director paul r. lawrence, a professor at harvard university's graduate school of business administration, said tuesday
the study is not aimed at encouraging joint ventures, but to ``make sure the projects that do get started are operated successfully and the combined management teams of soviet and american managers will be able to work with each other effectively,'' lawrence said
two faculty members from the harvard business school and two representatives of the research institute of external economic affairs in moscow, the research arm of the soviet foreign economic commission, will work on the study
the study, scheduled to begin in may and end in september, will include electrosila, a leningrad-based manufacturer of heavy industrial equipment. the other sites have not been determined, lawrence said
we want to prepare guidelines that will help the day-to-day management of joint ventures in the soviet union with american firms,'' lawrence said. ``this could be in any number of fields.''
the research will focus on capital investments, appointing and terminating a middle manager, introducing a new product and formulating and implementing an annual business plan
lawrence said the choices are a good cross-section of real business decisions. ``they represent quite a range of the kinds of things operating managers do,'' he said
four case studies based on the research are expected to be completed by november and the final version is scheduled for publication by july 1989
the co-director of the harvard team is charalambos vlachoutsicos, a research fellow at the school. co-chairmen of the soviet team are igor faminsky, director of the institute and b.i. fomin, general director of electrosila. the project will be jointly funded. another paper</head> add comment from tribune editor, picking up 5th graf, `broder's story...'. deletes last graf, now outdated.</note>
a correspondent for the chicago tribune in the middle east has resigned after writing a story that contained some material taken, without attribution, from a story printed in the jerusalem post, the tribune said
the tribune published a brief notice of jonathan broder's resignation monday under its ``corrections and clarifications'' headline
broder's story feb. 22 ``included a number of sentences and phrases taken, without attribution, from a column by another writer that had been published previously in the jerusalem post,'' the tribune said
that material ``constitutes only a fraction of the total story and contributed significantly only to organization and imagery,'' the tribune said
there's no justification for what he did. there's an explanation, but no justification,'' tribune editor james d. squires said tuesday
we said he cribbed the story and he resigned,'' squires said. he declined further comment
broder's story began:
anyone traveling the roads of the west bank these days cannot fail to notice the fundamental change that has overtaken the area in the last 10 weeks.''
the jerusalem post story began:
anyone traveling the roads of the west bank these days cannot fail to sense the change that has come over the area in the last two months.''
the tribune said broder's story was accurate, but ``the byline inaccurately implied that it was all mr. broder's work.''
broder, a full-time reporter with the tribune since 1979, was with family in san francisco, said a chicago tribune staff member who asked not to be identified. the staffer declined to provide a telephone number for broder. grafs after 2nd pvs to give bush, dole reactions, picking up 3rd pvs, former president; inserts one graf after 4th pvs, bush sounded, to give poll results; subs 7th and 8th grafs pvs, in vermont, to update percentages; inserts graf after 8th pvs, dukakis rolled, to give jackson reaction. ^by david espo</note>
bob dole assailed george bush on the iran-contra affair in a tough new television commercial tuesday and richard gephardt used an advertisement to attack democratic rivals michael dukakis and albert gore jr. as the presidential campaign spread across the south one week before super tuesday
bush defeated dole tuesday night in vermont's non-binding gop presidential primary, and dukakis won the state's democratic contest, with jesse jackson running second
this win gives us three out of three in new england, and i'm hopeful we can be as successful this saturday in south carolina and on super tuesday,'' bush said
mary ellen grupp said the dole campaign was very pleased with dole's ``strong showing'' and would use the primary results to build up for the gop caucuses in april
former president carter, the last democrat to occupy the white house, said he thought the chances were 50-50 that no democrat would arrive at the party nominating convention with enough delegates to claim the nomination
bush sounded confident that nothing of the sort would happen in the republican race. bush, in a strong position in virtually all of the southern states that will vote next week, said, ``i'm convinced that whoever wins super tuesday will be the next president.''
bush was further buoyed by the results of a washington post-abc news poll released tuesday, showing him with a nearly 3-to-1 lead over dole among republicans likely to vote super tuesday. dukakis and jackson were battling for the democratic lead
gop hopeful pat robertson, meanwhile, said he intends to drop his $35 million libel suit against former rep. pete mccloskey rather than go to trial on super tuesday
robertson has accused mccloskey of defaming him in a letter contending that the former television evangelist used the influence of his father, the late sen. a. willis robertson, to avoid combat duty in the korean war. but robertson may not be able to walk away from the suit without paying mccloskey's legal fees
with nearly all the precincts reporting in vermont's ``beauty contest'' primary, bush had 49 percent to dole's 39 percent. robertson had 5 percent and rep. jack kemp 3.4 percent
dukakis rolled to a solid win with 56 percent; jackson had 27 percent; gephardt 8 percent; paul simon 6 percent and gary hart 4 percent. gore was not on the ballot
we have found the common chord that is linking the american people, whether they are in iowa or maine or new hampshire or mississippi,'' jackson said about his impressive showing
the vermont contest did not involve allocating any delegates to the republican and democratic national convention
in contrast, super tuesday on march 8 involves 1,307 delegates in democratic primaries and caucuses in 20 states and 712 delegates in 17 contests on the republican side
the broad sweep of that day's contests means candidates must place greater stress than ever before on costly television commercials. gone are the days of ``retail politics,'' consisting of six stops in iowa or new hampshire in a single day
the new campaign style features chartered jets, trips to two or three regions of two or three different states _ and a heavy dose of commercials scattered across several states
in his new advertisement, dole says that bush has refused to say he would veto an increase in income tax rates, that he won't support a textile import bill and that he ``supported the arms for hostages deal'' in the iran-contra affair
that's precisely what he did _ he supported the sale of arms to iran,'' the kansas senator said as he campaigned in durham, n.c
bush campaigned in florida, where he said of dole's iran-contra comments, ``i support the president. i have nothing to say about dole's charges, nothing at all.'' instead, he touted his own role in the decision to invade grenada with u.s. troops in 1983, as well as the part he has played in the administration's anti-drug program
if bush is heavily favored in most republican super tuesday states, the democratic contest shapes up as a struggle among massachusetts gov. dukakis, missouri rep. gephardt, tennessee sen. albert gore jr. and jesse jackson
ironically, it was a democratic idea to develop a regional southern primary, in the hopes that it would give a candidate from the deep south a springboard to the nomination
it hasn't worked that way, and carter, who invited gephardt to his home in plains, ga., said he is no longer sure whether the idea is good or bad
he added, ``my hope is that out of the primary and caucus season will come a clear winner. i'm not sure that's a likelihood now.''
gephardt said he traveled to carter's home in rural georgia ``not to enhance my prospects but to greet an old friend.''
at the same time, he began running a new commercial in which texas rep. marvin leath says gephardt ``stood with us for lower taxes, for an oil import fee to make american strong, for a tough new trade bill to stand up for american workers.''
on all these issues, gore and dukakis were opposed to us,'' he says
there was no immediate response from either gore or dukakis
among the other democrats, jackson was in washington, where he met with officials from south africa about the recent arrests of black leaders in that country
sen. paul simon, largely skipping southern states, campaigned in seattle for support in the washington caucuses
rep. jack kemp, struggling to survive in the republican race, said if either bush, dole or robertson wins the gop nomination, ``the reagan revolution is over.''
robertson, under pressure for several comments he has made in the past two weeks, said a transcript of 1967 senate subcommittee testimony supports his belief that there are nuclear missiles in cuba. he quoted testimony by a state department official who said a cuban refugee told him of the missiles
this is documented evidence,'' robertson said
an assembly began an 11-day session tuesday to elect a new president and vice president
the session opened with a 35-page report by president suharto on the affairs of state since he was re-elected in 1983 for a fourth five-year term
the 1,000-member assembly is expected to re-elect suharto, a 66-year-old former general and the sole candidate for president
the people's consultative assembly, dominated by the president's governing golkar party, is a special body summoned every five years
the post of vice president, though largely ceremonial, has been the subject of intense speculation in recent weeks because it is likely to be filled by a figure considered to be suharto's chosen successor
two people have been viewed as possible candidates for the vice presidency: state secretary sudharmono, 61, golkar chairman, and try sutrisno, 52, newly appointed armed forces commander, who has served four years as a suharto aide
in his report to the assembly, suharto said his administration in the last five years has had to overcome an economic recession and a sharp drop in oil prices, a major source of foreign exchange in indonesia
suharto also said indonesia's economic growth rate was estimated to reach an average of 3.8 percent annually in the current five-year economic plan ending march 1989. the original target was set at 5 percent
in foreign affairs, the president reaffirmed indonesia's position that it will not normalize relations with china until beijing pledges it will not provide support to communist guerrillas in the region, including indonesia
jakarta suspended relations with beijing in 1967 after accusing it of complicity in the abortive communist coup attempt of 1965
however, trade relations between the two nations have been restored since the signing of a memorandum of understanding in july 1985
texas will seek a court order to stop the shipment of florida citrus to texas and other citrus-producing states, officials say
the move was prompted by a judge's order tuesday that overturned a texas ban on the florida fruit
texas imposed the ban last month after a federal rule took effect allowing the shipment of florida citrus that meets certain standards to other citrus-producing states
the new rule lifted a 3{-year-old federal quarantine on florida citrus that was prompted by discovery of the citrus canker disease in that state
u.s. district judge james nowlin said he overturned the ban because the federal regulation takes precedence over the state rule
texas agriculture officials said the ban was needed to protect texas' $65 million-a-year citrus industry from canker
when chancellor of the exchequer nigel lawson steps before the house of commons on march 15, he is expected to unveil one of the rarest of british commodities _ a budget surplus
the expectation is so real that already there is widespread talk of a massive tax cut _ and also widespread criticism of the government's reputed plans for the extra money
the budget on march 15 should be the most momentous of britain's postwar history,'' the economist magazine said
anything could happen in the next two weeks, and the budget may turn out very different from what is now forecast
but for the moment, analysts are assuming a tax cut is in the works, and the government's critics are attacking the budget as a gift to the rich at the expense of the poor
last autumn the government announced its planned expenditures of $278 billion for the fiscal year ending march 31, 1989, and the spring budget day is when it discloses how it will raise the money
for the first time in almost 20 years, prime minister margaret thatcher's conservative government might produce a budget surplus for the current fiscal year, which ends march 31, said a treasury spokesman, who wasn't identified, in accordance with british custom
the government expects to out-perform its most recent forecast of a deficit of $1.77 billion, which was down from a previously forecast deficit of $7.1 billion, the spokesman said
it will probably turn out to be a surplus,'' said diane coyoe, economist for the private forecasting firm dri europe
very definitely a surplus,'' said anthony thomas, an economist at the london investment firm kleinwort grieveson ltd
the surplus will be $2 billion to $5 billion, the economists estimated
if they are right, the surplus will have resulted from the government's tight grip on spending, its buoyant tax receipts and proceeds from its giant and continuing privatization program of selling off to the public billions of dollars' worth of state-owned companies
the surplus has sparked speculation that the government will slash its top income tax rate of 60 percent to 50 percent or even lower in what would be the biggest cut in almost 10 years
the cut, which applies to people earning more than $72,900 annually, would be effective in the fiscal year beginning april 1
thomas said there was much speculation that lawson would cut it below 50 percent. ``we suspect he will want to do those cuts over an extended time period. it will seem like too much of a giveaway (otherwise).''
but the times of london said lawson might slash the rate to as low as 35 percent, adding: ``the chancellor has been stung by criticisms from his own party that president reagan's tax reforms in the u.s. have overtaken britain with a simplified system ....''
in her first budget, in june 1979, mrs. thatcher cut the top rate from 83 percent to 60 percent. it has remained unchanged since
in the united states, the top federal income tax rate is 33 percent this year, although for most individuals, the maximum rate is 28 percent
lawson also is expected to cut the lowest tax rate, which applies to income up to $31,600, to 25 percent from 27 percent. that rate stood at 33 percent in 1979
the expected tax cuts _ part of mrs. thatcher's long-term, sweeping reform of the tax system _ would be highly controversial in a country where the welfare state prevails despite the prime minister's capitalist revolution
the government is bracing itself for the charge that ... it will be introducing `a rich man's budget,''' the observer newspaper wrote
critics of mrs. thatcher's tight spending policies already have raised a furor, demanding that surplus money go to the national health service rather than toward tax cuts
in february, nurses staged a one-day walkout to protest the state of the health service, which has 700,000 people waiting for surgery at state hospitals
other critics fear that cuts could spur consumer spending enough to ignite inflation and force up interest rates
but mrs. thatcher's supporters say her fiscal policies have helped boost britain's now-strong economy
the budget proposals must be approved by parliament, where they are assured passage because of the conservative party's 102-seat majority in the 650-seat house of commons
actress molly ringwald, whose movie ``for keeps'' was criticized as glamorizing teen-age pregnancy, is doing a commercial aimed at keeping teen-agers from getting pregnant, a spokeswoman says
ms. ringwald is recording the 30-second spot for a state program called parents too soon, said audrey stewart, a spokeswoman for the program
the public-service announcement, which ms. ringwald is doing at no charge, will be sent to radio stations across illinois and may be broadcast as early as this month, ms. stewart said tuesday
illinois officials criticized ms. ringwald's movie shortly after its premiere in january
for keeps'' features the actress as a middle-class teen-ager who has a baby, marries her boyfriend, finishes high school and goes off to college with her husband _ both on full scholarship
rock sensation michael jackson thrilled the united negro college fund with a check for $600,000
there aren't many days like this,'' uncf president christopher edley said after accepting the check from the singer at a jam-packed news conference tuesday
jackson, wearing a striped shirt and bright red blazer, waved as more then two dozen camera crews and twice as many still photographers took hundreds of pictures of the usually reclusive superstar
thank you. i'm very honored and very thankful,'' jackson said during his 15 seconds at the microphone. ``i love you all. thank you.''
the check represented the proceeds from jackson's scheduled thursday night show at madison square garden, his first solo performance in new york
jackson earlier created a ``michael jackson scholarship'' for the uncf. in the past three years, 97 students have received financial aid through the program
president reagan played pizza deliveryman for nato ambassador and ``junk-food freak'' alton keel
air force one, taking reagan to a meeting of nato leaders tuesday, also carried three pizzas across the atlantic, said white house spokesman marlin fitzwater
fitzwater said the pizzas were purchased in a washington suburb by deputy white house chief of staff kenneth duberstein
keel, a former national security adviser, is a ``junk-food freak,'' fitzwater said
entertainer bette midler, who grew up in hawaii, and her husband have purchased a $1.5 million piece of the islands that was confiscated in a federal drug case
midler and husband, martin von haselberg, paid cash for the 38-acre parcel on kauai island, which includes a partly completed tri-level home and a panoramic view of the pacific ocean and a river, said u.s. marshal faith evans
midler attended the university of hawaii before moving to new york to pursue her career as a singer and actress
the property, near the town of kilauea, was among 141 acres seized by the justice department in 1986 after authorities charged the owners had purchased it with money from illegal drug sales, evans said monday
rudolf nureyev will dance three performances of ``giselle'' during the american ballet theater's three-week engagement in los angeles, artistic director mikhail baryshnikov announced
nureyev will play count albrecht in the 1841 romantic ballet on march 17 and 18 with marianna tcherkassky as giselle, and on march 19, with alessandra ferri as giselle, baryshnikov said tuesday
nureyev first danced with the abt in 1962 and has done a wide variety of ballets with the company, including ``giselle'' and his own staging of ``raymonda.''
the abt will perform at the shrine auditorium in los angeles march 1-20. the schedule does not list baryshnikov as dancing during the engagement
the country music hall of fame is putting together a black, white and silver exhibit honoring the ``man in black'' _ johnny cash
the $70,000 exhibit is scheduled to open march 23, the hall of fame said monday
this collection provides unprecedented documentation of country music's most distinguished career,'' said hall of fame director bill ivey. ``it is extraordinarily rich due to cash's unusual level of cooperation and interest, and the availability of his extensive personal archives.''
at cash's suggestion, the entire exhibit is being mounted and displayed with black, white and silver graphics. it will be divided into sections devoted to various periods of cash's life
this is the third biographical exhibit at the hall of fame. dolly parton and willie nelson also have been honored
cash's hits include ``i walk the line,'' ``a boy named sue,'' ``folsom prison blues'' and ``ring of fire.''
republican presidential candidate pat robertson said he would use the military to help stem the flow of illegal drugs into the united states and would order airplanes suspected of carrying drugs to be shot down
if one of those drug planes is flying without giving identification ... coming into this country, i wouldn't hesitate to give orders to shoot him down,'' the former television evangelist said at a rally tuesday
i believe we have played games long enough with drugs,'' robertson said. ``i don't think we are being as aggressive as we should.''
robertson, who has tapped a vein of anti-communist sentiment among cuban-americans as he campaigns around florida, also accused cuban president fidel castro of involvement in drug trafficking
earlier, robertson cited 21-year-old, second-hand testimony before a senate subcommittee as evidence that the soviet union has intermediate-range missiles based in cuba
he called for closing what he calls a ``cuban loophole'' in the u.s.-soviet intermediate-range nuclear forces treaty, which now is awaiting ratification by the senate
if the inf treaty is ratified without addressing this matter then i think it will be virtually treasonous,'' robertson said at a news conference. ``i do not feel there is any way that they can sweep this thing under the rug. i am not going to permit them to do it.''
several u.s. officials said tuesday the cuban military has some surface-to-surface missiles in its inventory, but none has a nuclear warhead and none could reach the united states even if it did
robertson quoted 1967 testimony by paul bethel, a state department official from miami, who said cuban refugees had told him of seeing missiles, and one of the refugees, identified only as mr. apud, who swore cuban soldiers let him know about missiles aimed at washington before he left in 1966
neither man testified he had personally seen the missiles, the transcript indicates
the testimony was given to the judiciary subcommittee to investigate the administration of the internal security act and other internal security laws. robertson read portions of it to supporters tuesday at a breakfast in fort lauderdale and during a rally the night before in miami
i've been accused of bringing funny facts,'' robertson told the fort lauderdale gathering. ``ladies and gentlemen, the clear eyewitness, sworn testimony of witnesses before a senate judiciary committee is not funny facts. ... this is documented evidence.''
robertson's assertion that there are missiles based in cuba has been denied by the white house, congressional defense experts and castro, who told nbc on monday that robertson should ``go and see a doctor, really, or a psychiatrist, because this is pure madness.''
several defense and administration officials were asked tuesday about robertson's claim. the officials, speaking on condition of anonymity because they did not want to become involved in the presidential race, said cuba has about five dozen frog-4 and frog-7 battlefield missiles, dating from the 1960s
the frog-7, when originally introduced by the soviets, could carry either a conventional or nuclear warhead, ``but we're confident no nuclear warheads ever went to cuba for that missile and it doesn't have any range anyway,'' said one source who requested anonymity
according to the reference book ``jane's weapon systems,'' the frog-7 has a range of only about 43 miles _ or half the distance between cuba and florida. moreover, the rocket has no guidance system to direct it to a specific target
white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said last month that cuba has been under extensive surveillance since the 1962 missile crisis and there is ``no evidence'' any other nuclear weaponry had ever been deployed there by the soviet union
in the subcommittee transcript, apud said he was told by cuban soldiers he had known for many years that the missiles were nicknamed ``washington left,'' ``washington right,'' and ``washington central.''
a congressional study is painting a dismal environmental picture of vital streamside areas on federal property across the west
tens of thousands of miles of these riparian areas have been degraded by poor livestock grazing practices on land leased to ranchers by the bureau of land management, according to the general accounting office, the investigative wing of congress
james duffus, a gao official, says the damaged land would start repairing itself if the bureau either would ban cattle from degraded streamsides or limit the amount of grazing there
but that solution is being made difficult because bureau leaders appear to be siding with opposition from many ranchers who pay below-market rates to graze cattle on the taxpayers' land, he told a house hearing tuesday
streamside areas are important in the arid west because they help raise water tables, collect sediment, increase the availability of forage, dissipate the energy of flood waters and serve as fish and wildlife habitats, said duffus, the gao's associate director for resources, community and economic development
it has taken decades of abuse to produce the level of riparian area degradation that currently exists,'' he told the interior national parks and public lands subcommittee. ``most riparian areas managed by the bureau are in degraded condition largely as a result of poorly managed livestock grazing.''
duffus said that while the bureau does not know the extent of the damage, ``tens of thousands of stream miles on federal rangelands remain in degraded condition.''
duffus said two bureau assessments found that 80 percent of the 12,000 miles of streamside areas in idaho need better management and that 90 percent of 5,000 miles in colorado were rated in poor or fair condition
not only has the bureau reduced its ranks of wildlife and fisheries biologists since 1981, many remaining personnel responsible for riparian areas don't believe the bureau is serious about improving the condition of the streamside areas, according to duffus
these staff widely believe that if their proposed actions for restoring riparian areas are opposed by the permitted ranchers, their managers will not support them,'' he said
many bureau staff ... recounted specific instances where their riparian management efforts were specifically undercut by bureau headquarters or local management direction after permitted ranches raised objections,'' duffus said
subcommittee chairman bruce vento, d-minn., distributed copies of a 1986 bureau headquarters memo telling field personnel that streamside area management ``requires the full support and cooperation of the permittee or lessee.''
pointing to the memo, vento asked whether ranchers using bureau land for cattle grazing are experts in environmental restoration
i wouldn't look to them for any expertise,'' duffus replied
tim locke, a bureau spokesman, gave no immediate response when asked by the associated press to comment on duffus' report
the music industry promises to find a new way to thwart home taping with digital recorders now that its proposed electronic anti-taping device has been declared ineffective by the national bureau of standards
the bureau's report, released tuesday, dealt a blow to the recording industry's campaign to prevent digital audio tape, or dat, recorders from reaching the domestic market
the recorders, now manufactured by japan and other foreign makers, can copy compact disc recordings with virtually no loss in sound quality. the u.s. recording industry fears that the machines will lead to mass copying that would devastate the compact disc and record markets, and so far has managed to keep the devices off the u.s. market
but rep. robert w. kastenmeier, d-wis., chairman of a house judiciary subcommittee that handles copyright issues, said the results of the bureau's study _ which he requested last year _ shows that congress should stop trying to prevent u.s. sales of dat recorders
kastenmeier said the report appears to doom an industry-backed bill that would require equipping dat recorders with scanning devices intended to prevent copying of specially coded recordings
the bill, sponsored by rep. henry waxman, d-calif., also would prohibit the manufacture or sale of any device designed to bypass the scanner
the bureau, an agency of the commerce department, said that the scanning device was unreliable and easily bypassed, and that it damaged the sound quality of recordings
because the report was conclusive about the ineffectiveness of blocking devices, it is even more desirable that the dat controversy be resolved by the industries involved, rather than by congressional imposition of a solution,'' kastenmeier said
kastenmeier said in an interview that as a result of the bureau of standards report, ``i think it highly unlikely that the waxman bill will succeed.''
u.s. manufacturers voluntarily blocked introduction of dat units on the domestic market until congress resolved the home taping issue, but the self-imposed ban has recently shown signs of crumbling under pressure from foreign manufacturers and demand from u.s. recording enthusiasts
kastenmeier said an alternative to a congressional solution might be payment of recording artists out of proceeds from sales of dat units, or from an endowment fund created by the recording industry
jason berman, president of the recording industry association of america, said the industry accepts the study results but intends to find a new technological solution to home taping, which he said costs the recording companies $1.5 billion in lost sales annually
working together with the hardware manufacturers, we are certain to find an acceptable technological solution,'' berman said
meanwhile, recording industry officials promised to sue any manufacturer that tries to sell the machines in the united states before the copying issue is resolved, either legislatively or through industry negotiations
but gary shapiro of the home recording rights coalition said ``there is no reason at this point why manufacturers should not be selling'' digital recorders in the united states
the coalition has been fighting anti-taping efforts as an infringement on the rights of consumers to make home recordings of records, tapes and compact discs for their private use
the scanning device was designed to detect ``notches,'' or tiny bands of frequencies removed from the audio signal of protected recordings, and interrupt taping of copies with intervals of silence
the bureau said its series of laboratory tests showed that notched material was recorded anyway in about half of the sound tracks studied
advocates of the anti-taping device claimed that the notches did not affect sound quality. but the bureau said its study showed that ``the system's encoder alters the original electrical signal,'' resulting in ``a discernible difference'' between notched and unnotched recordings
also, the bureau said, ``the copy prevention system can be bypassed easily.'' it said its engineers designed and built several electronic circuits to circumvent the system in five different ways
the circuits are simple and easy to construct'' and cost about $100, the bureau said
attorney general edwin meese iii's investment manager turned a $40,000 profit for him under an arrangement that may have involved financial favors or gifts to the attorney general, says a senator
the investment manager, w. franklyn chinn, ``wasn't investing mr. meese's money, so much as he was assigning profits and losses to the accounts of mr. meese and his other clients at his own discretion,'' sen. carl levin, d-mich., said tuesday
chinn, now under indictment in the wedtech scandal, turned a profit of nearly $40,000 for meese on a $50,000 investment in just 23 one-day trades of brand-new stock issues over an 18-month span. meese established a limited blind partnership with chinn's company and the attorney general says that under the arrangement he knew nothing about chinn's stock trading activity
the democratic majority staff of the senate subcommittee on oversight of government management found that stock purchases by chinn which later appeared in meese's account were initially made without identifying the customer in whose name the stock would eventually be recorded. the purchases were assigned by chinn to the accounts he managed, after the profit or loss was known
the report said that in one instance, chinn bought and sold 5,000 shares of a new stock issue in oliver stores inc. worth $30,000 on feb. 11, 1986. it wasn't until the next day, however, that chinn instructed imperial trust co. that 2,000 of the shares were to be recorded for meese's account. the transaction gave meese a profit of more than $1,700
in seven of the 23 stock trades, chinn spent substantially more money on behalf of his corporation's limited blind partnership with meese than meese had invested in the account, the subcommittee staff found. the sums ranged from $5,000 to $140,000
chinn exceeded the account balances for his other customers as well, said the subcommittee staff. he avoided the appearance that he had exceeded the account balance by directing that his stock purchases be recorded as if they had been made in smaller lots, any one of which would not exceed the account balance
because he did not allocate winners and losers to his clients' accounts until after the fact, he was effectively able to assign greater benefits to some _ including apparently mr. meese on numerous occasions,'' levin said in a statement. ``this procedure again raises questions about possible financial favors or gifts.''
levin asked the office of government ethics in a letter for a formal finding on whether meese complied with federal regulations governing gifts and loans to public officials
levin also sent a copy of the letter to the securities and exchange commission to investigate possible violations of regulations prohibiting brokers from exceeding account balances and regulations governing the conduct by investment advisers
meese ``had no knowledge of chinn's stock trading activity and i don't think meese should be held responsible,'' said one of the attorney general's lawyers, nathan lewin
this blind partnership was set up to be sure that he had no knowledge of how things were being done.''
lewin dismissed suggestions that meese should have reported the amount over the account balances as gifts, saying ``there were a number of losing transactions as well as profitable transactions.''
meese made a profit on 18 of the trades and lost money on five
according to the majority subcommittee staff, on sept. 4, 1986, chinn had $730,000 in five of his customers' accounts at imperial trust co., but on that day bought $6.6 million in sears, roebuck stock for them, which subsequently was reflected as 34 separate transactions and sales
chinn, a former director of scandal-plagued wedtech corp., was introduced to the attorney general in 1985 by longtime meese friend e. robert wallach. chinn and wallach are now under indictment for racketeering, fraud and conspiracy in an alleged scheme to extract payments from the bronx, n.y., defense contractor in order to influence meese and other federal officials. wallach and chinn have pleaded innocent
meese has been under criminal investigation by independent counsel james mckay since last may 11 for his involvement with wedtech. meese acknowledges interceding on behalf of the company when he was white house counselor to ensure that the firm got a fair hearing from the army in its effort to win a $32 million no-bid engine-building contract. the company eventually got the work
sources familiar with mckay's probe say one aspect of the investigation has been an examination of chinn's stock trading to determine whether chinn may have given meese preferential treatment over other customers
meese may be found to have benefited from a ``very subtle bribe'' if preferential treatment were found and were determined to be a reward for official action, one knowledgeable law enforcement source said in december
one of chinn's lawyers, penny cooper, said the questions addressed by levin's subcommittee are ``exactly the same material the independent counsel went over for months and they found no wrongdoing. there was no wrongdoing.'' she said that chinn ``did no better for meese than any other client.''
the subcommittee staff didn't reach any conclusions on whether meese received preferential treatment
inamullah khan of pakistan today won the 1988 templeton prize for promoting interreligious cooperation. he is the first moslem to win the $390,000 international award
it is biggest prize given in the world, about $40,000 more than the nobel prizes in science and literature
announcement of this year's winner was to be made at a news conference at manhattan's church center of the united nations
khan, 73, a founder and secretary-general of the world moslem congress, was cited for his ``tireless work as a coordinator for peace between moslems, christians and jews.''
khan, of karachi, also is chairman of the executive committee of the interreligious world conference on religion and peace, presiding at meetings around the world
he has been keenly supportive of united nations concerns, including disarmament, human rights, education and welfare, and twice has chaired meetings of the world federation of united nations associations in geneva, switzerland
the annual prize, established in 1972 by american financeer john templeton, is given to recognize those ``who through original and pioneering ways advanced the knowledge and love of god.''
the 1988 prize is to presented may 10 by england's princess alexandra at london's guild hall
of the previous 15 winners, 13 have been christians, one hindu and one buddhist
the first winner was mother teresa of calcutta, india, founder of the roman catholic missionaries of charity, while last year's winner was physicist stanley l. jaki, a roman catholic, of seton hall university in south orange, n.j
other winners have included:
southern baptist evangelist billy graham, russian orthodox expatriate alexander solzhenitsyn, belgium's cardinal joseph suenens, u.s. presbyterian educator james i. mccord and france's brother roger, founder of the taize ecumenical community
an international, interreligious panel of judges picks the winners
khan, born in burma and a graduate in arts and law from rangoon university, was a high school principal in rangoon and editor of burma's moslem daily until 1942 when burma was occupied by japan
he then settled in india, where he headed the all-india burmese evacuees association and the islamic brotherhood society. on establishment of pakistan in 1948, he became a citizen, settling in karachi
there, he founded the world moslem congress, its offices initially in his home, but which now has an imposing new headquarters there
as secretary-general, he has traveled throughout the moslem world, including both sides of the protracted iran-iraq war, and has stood with banned christian leaders in south africa
the rev. wilbert forker, vice president of the templeton foundation, said khan has given ``much energy and imagination to building bridges between the moslem world and neighbors from other religions and cultures.''
he ``has lived in a generation when religion has often come in for attack from secular sources'' and has challenged ``atheistic teachings and practices'' and pressed religion to correct its failings, forker said
he is clearly a man sustained by his faith in god and in human values and by his sense of solidarity with his community and with humanity,'' forker said. ``religion for him is not simply a private matter but an essential motivation for society.''
many motorists who wear seat belts are still exposing themselves to serious injury by wearing them improperly, according to a federal study that says women, children and motorists over 50 are most likely to put themselves at risk
the national transportation safety board raised questions tuesday about the way some belt users wear the safety devices after examining 167 accidents in which at least one occupant was belted
twenty-one percent of the motorists wearing belts had too much slack in the shoulder harnesses, and 7 percent of the occupants, often children, wore belts that were improperly routed behind the back or under an arm
thirty-one states have laws requiring use of safety belts. but ntsb chairman jim burnett said, ``we have a lot of misuse and that problem has to be tackled.''
overall, the safety board said, lap-shoulder belts provide excellent protection with 80 percent of the belted occupants suffering minor or no injuries. but the study suggested the results could have been even better were it not for improper wearing of belts
the ntsb study was not a random sample and, therefore, does not necessarily translate into similar percentages for all motorists, said lynne smith, who was involved in writing of the report. but, she added, the data are consistent with previous findings of widespread misuse
for example, the report cited an earlier insurance industry study of maryland motorists indicating that belts are worn too loosely about one-fourth of the time
examples of misuse with tragic consequences included a head-on collision and an accident in which a car struck a tree, according to the safety board
in the head-on crash, a passenger who had loosened her shoulder belt significantly died of massive injuries, while the driver who had worn his belt snugly ``walked away from the crash with moderate injuries,'' said suzanne stack, an ntsb staff researcher
in the other crash, the driver, who had worn his belt properly, escaped with minor injuries when his car struck a tree, but the passenger, whose shoulder belt was routed under her arm, was killed from extensive injuries
the board also cited examples of people suffering extensive injuries _ fatal ones in a case involving a 7-year-old boy _ when belts were used while seats were in the reclining position. in some cases the combination of the belt and the reclining seat may create new dangers, the report suggested
the four-member safety board urged the national highway traffic safety administration to require that safety belts meet standards for the maximum amount of slack allowed or require that the belt systems be equipped with a ``pre-tension'' device that automatically pulls a belt tight a split second before a crash
the safety board questioned the widespread use among u.s. carmakers of a belt design that allows a person to pull the belt out to its full length without it automatically retracting. most foreign manufacturers use another design which automatically keeps the belt snug against the occupant, but which has been criticized as being less comfortable and, therefore, less likely to be used
the safety board said there is evidence indicating drivers aged 50 years or older and female occupants are the most likely to misuse belts, especially wearing them too loosely. ms. smith said that, generally, slack equal to no more than the width of a fist should be allowed in the shoulder belt
a particularly high misuse of belts was found among children. one-third had part of the belts behind the back or under an arm
such misuse ... seriously degrades the protective capabilities of the lap-shoulder belt, reducing it to a lap-only belt with inferior crash protection,'' the safety board said
a number of auto safety pamphlets, including two distributed by the nhtsa and one by the american automobile association, have advised parents to place the shoulder belt behind a child if the harness crosses the neck or face
the safety board does not agree,'' the ntsb report said. ``there is little evidence that small children or short adults are likely to be harmed by the shoulder portion of a belt.''
the board called for the highway safety agency to revise its brochures
nhtsa, which issues auto safety regulations, was reviewing the ntsb report, said spokeswoman betsy tyson
the united states might not have fared that well in the winter olympics, but abc was a big winner
the high-rated two weeks of prime-time olympics, pre-empting abc's entire schedule, have given the network a february sweeps win that breaks nbc's 11-sweeps streak. abc is now second on the season
the olympics averaged a prime-time rating of 19.3 and a 30 share, up 5 percent over the 1984 winter olympics, according to the a.c. nielsen co. abc estimates that more than 150 million viewers saw some of this year's games
saturday night's figure-skating finale was last week's no. 1 show, earning a rating of 26.4 and a 43 share, and included the highest-rated half hour of saturday viewing since ``roots'' in 1977
olympics coverage on monday, tuesday and thursday also made it into the top 10. wednesday's was 12th, sunday's 17th, and friday's 30th. abc had no other prime-time programming
the olympics also apparently helped abc continue its three-week win streak over cbs in news. for the week that ended feb. 26, abc's ``world news tonight'' had an average rating of 11.7 and a 21 share. ``cbs evening news'' had an 11.2 and 20 and ``nbc nightly news'' had 9.9 and 18
the rating is the percentage of the nation's 88.6 million households with televisions. the share is a percentage of sets in use
abc won the week that ended feb. 28 with an average rating of 20.5. nbc was second with 15.6 and cbs third with 13.5. it was the highest weekly rating for any network since october 1986, and abc's highest since october 1985
february is one of four months a year when local ratings are measured for use in negotiating advertising rates. with only days left uncounted in the february sweeps, abc led nbc by about 1.5 rating points. cbs is third
nbc has an average 16.3 after 23 weeks of the television season. abc is second with 14.1, and cbs third with 13.6
the top 10 prime-time shows last week were: saturday olympics, abc; ``the cosby show,'' nbc; tuesday olympics, abc; ``a different world,'' nbc; monday olympics, abc; ``60 minutes,'' cbs; ``cheers,'' nbc; thursday olympics, abc; ``murder, she wrote,'' cbs; and ``matlock,'' nbc
the four-part miniseries ``noble house'' ended disappointingly for nbc. the final installment wednesday night took a slight upturn, but was only 20th
the first part of cbs' two-part ``bluegrass'' did better, coming in 15th with a 17.6 rating and 27 share
the annual rerun of the classic movie ``the wizard of oz'' on cbs last wednesday had its lowest rating yet, but still placed 25th with a 15.3 and 22
the lowest-rated shows of the week _ the rankings were abbreviated due to the olympics taking up abc's schedule, were: ``wiseguy,'' ``cagney &amp; lacey,'' ``sonny spoon,'' ``charlie brown,'' ``our house,'' ``garfield,'' ``equalizer,'' ``high mountain rangers'' and ``west 57th,'' which was against the olympics saturday night and got a dismal 5.5 rating and 9 share
here are the prime-time television ratings as compiled by the a.c. nielsen co. for the week of feb. 22-28. top 20 listings include the week's ranking, with full season-to-date ranking in parentheses, rating for the week, and total homes
an ``x'' in parentheses denotes one-time-only presentation. a rating measures the percentage of the nation's 88.6 million tv homes
1. (x) ``winter olympics-saturday,'' abc, 26.4 rating, 23.4 million homes
2. (1) ``the cosby show,'' nbc, 24.8, 22.0 million homes
3. (x) ``winter olympics-tuesday,'' abc, 23.5, 20.8 million homes
