an agriculture department labor expert says farmers probably will begin feeling the impact of a new federal immigration law next year
robert coltrane of the department's economic research service said the immigration reform and control act of 1986 exempts many agricultural employers from penalties for knowingly hiring illegal aliens, but that exemption will expire dec. 1
the real test is likely to come after that time, when penalties can be imposed and immigration investigators may take a more aggressive approach to agriculture,'' coltrane said
coltrane, whose analysis is scheduled for the march issue of farmline magazine, said farm employers may be relying heavily on the special agricultural worker program, or saw, which allows temporary legal resident status for foreign workers who formerly helped in the u.s. production of designated perishable crops
producers of those crops are exempted from the law's penalties until dec. 1. as defined by usda regulations, those crops include not only fruits and vegetables, but also wheat, sugarbeets and a number of other commodities
coltrane said the main crops not qualifying as saw commodities are cotton, sugarcane, hay, sod, forage and silage, seed intended solely for seed use, flax, millet and sorghum. livestock producers also are not covered by the saw provision
the pool of saw workers has been growing, although it is still relatively small compared with total agricultural labor needs, coltrane said. in the first eight months of signup, june 1987 through january, around 240,000 workers filed saw applications, the first step to temporary legal residency and, under certain conditions, eventual u.s. citizenship
but only about 2 percent of the saw applications through december were filed from outside the united states. coltrane said this means that temporary rules relaxing border restrictions to bring in farm workers have not had much of an impact. moreover, there is no requirement that saw workers stay with farm jobs
once farm workers receive their work authorization card, they can work wherever they want, and in whatever industry they want,'' he said. ``agricultural employers have no assurance that the workers will stay in agriculture.''
the soviet union has used up virtually all of its authorization to buy u.s. wheat at subsidized prices with additional purchases totaling 500,000 metric tons for delivery this year
agriculture department officials said tuesday that the latest sales, equal to about 18.3 million bushels, were handled by continental grain co., 100,000 tons; cargill inc., 375,000 tons; and mitsui grain corp., 25,000 tons
at recent prices averaging $2.75 per bushel, the wheat would have a farm value of about $50 million
more than 6.8 million tons of subsidized wheat has been sold to the soviet union under the department's export enhancement program, or eep, for delivery in the year that began last oct. 1
george j. pope, acting general sales manager for the department's foreign agricultural service, said that only 200 tons of wheat are still available to the soviet union under current eep authorization. there has been no official indication that a new line of subsidy may be approved
under eep, private exporters are given surplus commodities owned by the department's commodity credit corp. so they can sell a foreign buyer wheat or other authorized commodity at competitive world prices
pope said the subsidies, or bonuses, averaged $27 per ton on the latest sales, or about 74 cents per bushel. the subsidies for the soviet union have been available only for wheat
the sales also are part of the grain the soviet union is committed to buy during the fifth and final year of a long-term agreement, which calls for the annual purchase of at least 9 million tons of u.s. grain. the pact expires sept. 30
according to the agreement, the annual purchases include a minimum of 4 million tons each of wheat and corn. the soviets have the option of buying the remaining 1 million tons as wheat, corn or soybeans, with every ton of beans counting as two tons of grain _ up to a maximum of 1 million tons of grain equivalent
a metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 36.7 bushels of wheat or soybeans, or 39. bushels of corn
in addition, 2.62 million tons of u.s. corn, 813,300 tons of soybeans and 1.3 million tons of soybean meal have been bought by the soviets for delivery this year
interest rates charged by the agriculture department for price support crop loans made to farmers in march will be 6} percent, down from 7[ percent previously
milton hertz, executive vice president of the department's commodity credit corp., said tuesday that the decline reflects the interest rate charged ccc by the u.s. treasury this month
when the first musher charges north in the 16th annual iditarod trail sled dog race on saturday, organizers already will have their own victory, over alaska's economic bust and the race's $773,000 debt
fifty-five mushers have signed up for the rugged 1,100-mile contest billed as ``the last great race on earth.'' last year, 63 teams signed up; the year before, 73
this year's field includes four-time champion rick swenson; two-time winner susan butcher, whose $50,000 winner's check last year bounced; 1983 champion rick mackey; and 16 rookies. mushers from austria, canada, france and great britain also have signed up
the race is named after the iditarod trail, an old gold rush and mail route to nome. this year's race takes mushers over the tougher northern route, where temperatures, although moderate of late, can reach minus 50 degrees
starting in downtown anchorage on trucked-in snow, racers must cross over the alaska range, traverse frozen tundra and climb the timbered kuskokwim mountains to reach the yukon river at ruby, an old gold mining community
the mushers trek south on the yukon and turn toward the coast at kaltag. at unalakleet, the teams turn north and run along the windblown coast and sea ice to nome's front street
the trail became part of alaska's legends in 1925, when 20 mushers pushed for 127{ hours to relay diphtheria serum 674 miles from nenana to nome to save the city from an epidemic
after the check issued butcher bounced, a special audit in april found the race was $773,000 in debt, said rosemary phillips, the race's executive director
i suppose the economy had a lot to do with it,'' she said. ``the iditarod was caught up in the collapse. more was spent than was taken in.''
oil prices peaked at about $30 a barrel in 1985 but plunged to less than $10 by july 1986. about 85 percent of the state's revenues come from royalties and taxes paid by the oil industry. when oil prices fell, the state's economy, heavily dependent on state expenditures, went into the abyss
bankruptcies and foreclosures soared. property values tumbled, jobs dried up and businesses closed, but the iditarod, which relies on private contributions, did not get the message
we had a hard time seeing our problem,'' said iditarod trail committee president lavon barve. ``there was a budget, and the money was spent for that budget, but the money didn't come in.''
joe redington, an iditarod board member and race founder, said the race was spending money for things it did not need. ``we spent a lot of money and didn't pay no bills,'' he said. ``it was spent unwisely. we had too many employees. we had top salaries and all the benefits. we had better insurance than general motors.''
when the race's financial problems became known, officials cut the staff by two-thirds. ``we had 34 to start with. the rest took pay cuts. we cut all benefits,'' phillips said
joanne potts, race coordinator since 1983, said about 700 volunteers, such as pilots and ham radio operators, worked for the race last year. she expected about 1,200 this year
while cutting expenses, the race also has found new sponsors. a footwear manufacturer's four-year sponsorship could bring in more than $500,000, phillips said. a dog food manufacturer agreed to a one-year contract worth more than $25,000. a television network has offered $15,000 for coverage rights
merchandising the iditarod name on everything from beer steins to buttons makes up as much as 40 percent of the race's revenues, she said
as of right now, our outstanding debts are about $220,000. i think it's fantastic,'' phillips said. this year's purse will be at least $125,000, still the largest purse in sled dog racing, she said
potts said she never doubted the race would continue
there were people last june who didn't think we were going to have a race this year,'' she said. ``we fooled them. we're going to have one. it's just bigger than all the little problems we had last year.''
and the winner is ..
michael jackson? u2? prince? whitney houston?
the answer could be any and all of the above tonight at the 30th annual grammy awards, which return to new york city after a seven-year absence and promise a number of special performances and possible surprises
jackson, who has four nominations, will perform his most recent hit, ``man in the mirror,'' with an all-star backing cast including andrae crouch, the winans and siedah garrett. it is the superstar's first televised live appearance in five years
the grammys will be broadcast on cbs-tv from radio city music hall beginning at 8 p.m. est
not performing but likely to spend plenty of time on stage are the irish rockers u2, who garnered four major nominations and go head-to-head with jackson for album of the year
u2, whose album ``the joshua tree'' vaulted them to prominence last year, also is up for record of the year, song of the year and best rock vocal performance by a group or duo
jackson has additional nominations for best male pop vocal performance, best male rhythm and blues vocal performance and producer of the year with quincy jones
prince (``sign o' the times'') and houston (``whitney'') are also up for album of the year, along with dolly parton, linda ronstadt and emmylou harris for their ``trio'' album
prince also has been nominated for best rhythm and blues vocal performance by a group or duo with sheena easton for ``u got the look,'' which also garnered him a nomination for best rhythm and blues song _ a songwriter's award
houston, who will perform the nominated ``i wanna dance with somebody,'' is a potential winner in the categories best female pop vocal performance and best female rhythm and blues vocal performance
but there are lesser-known nominees with good chances at capturing one of the tiny phonograph trophys handed out by the national academy of recording arts and sciences
new york's own suzanne vega, a cult favorite who broke into the top 10 with her song ``luka,'' is up for record of the year, song of the year and best female pop vocal performance. los angeles' favorite sons, los lobos, are nominated both for their inspired remake of ritchie valens' ``la bamba'' and their brilliant second album, ``by the light of the moon.''
los lobos will perform their version of ``la bamba,'' a mexican folk tune adapted by the late valens, at the awards show and vega is slated to do ``luka.'' the only other nominee scheduled to perform is best new artist hopeful terence trent d'arby
d'arby's competition includes breakfast club, cutting crew, swing out sister and jody watley
the nikkei stock average closed at 25,682.82 points, up 246.92 points, on the tokyo stock exchange on wednesday
a treaty to eliminate most tariff barriers between the united states and canada leaves disputes in the auto industry unresolved, witnesses at a house hearing said
lee kadrich, director of governmental affairs and international trade with the automotive parts and accessories association, said tuesday the treaty was ``a lopsided agreement that sanctions long-standing canadian protectionism.''
he told the trade subcommittee of the house ways and means committee that the treaty would put u.s. parts makers at the mercy of foreign competitors
automotive products, which account for about one-third of the trade between the united states and canada, have been governed for more than 20 years by the auto pact, which gives duty-free treatment to some parts and vehicles moving between the two countries
critics of the free-trade agreement, however, charge that canadian efforts to attract manufacturing have given their makers an unfair advantage under the auto pact, and the agreement leaves that advantage in place
our current bilateral auto trade is skewed, to canada's benefit, by a number of trade-distorting practices,'' resulting in part from canada's domestic-content requirements and duty rebates on some auto parts, said rep. sander levin, a southfield, mich., democrat
steve beckman, international economist for the united auto workers union, said that the treaty, by retaining canadian production incentives for honda, toyota and hyundai, provides ``a subsidy of canadian production, much of which will be sold in the u.s.''
an exception to that overall assessment was given by thomas hanna of the motor vehicle manufacturers association, which represents auto manufacturers
hanna said the treaty would create the world's largest free-trade zone and ``takes on and resolves most of the trouble spots which were developing in the bilateral auto trade.''
he said concerns that the treaty would provide expanded entry for japanese and korean manufacturers were unfounded because the north american auto industry already has excess manufacturing capacity
it makes no sense for the canadian government to lure more foreign auto investment, especially when much of the production would be headed for the u.s. market,'' he said
the national transportation safety board says it was unable to determine what caused the crash in 1986 of a helicopter scheduled to carry the entourage of jordan's king hussein in which four people died
investigators concluded that poor flying conditions, including fog that caused limited visibility, were factors in the june 6, 1986, crash in sutton, mass. but the official probable cause was listed as ``undetermined.''
dennis jones, the lead investigator, said tuesday the massive disintegration of the helicopter hindered the inquiry. ``we're only as good as the evidence,'' he said
there's no evidence to point to anything that we can concretely say'' triggered the crash, ntsb spokesman michael benson said
investigators originally concentrated on a mysterious piece of wire that raised questions of sabotage, but that turned out to be part of an electrical testing instrument
the investigation later focused on what looked like a frayed cable that controlled the tail rotor, which provides stability to the craft. but the final report, issued monday, said ``no pre-impact part failure (or) malfunction was found.''
four employees of sikorsky aircraft were killed when the seven-seat, sikorsky-built s-76b helicopter went down on a trip from hanscom field in bedford, mass., back to sikorsky headquarters in stratford, conn
the helicopter was one of four sikorsky had provided to hussein during his new england visit, but the king, his family and aides drove from massachusetts to the westover school in middlebury, conn., for the graduation of his daughter, princess zeim, because of the bad weather. her twin sister, princess aisha, graduated from the dana hall school in wellesley, mass., later that weekend
sikorsky spokesman marty moore said the company supports the board's findings
benson said the crash illustrates the need for smaller aircraft to carry ``black boxes,'' devices that would tape the crew's conversations and possibly provide clues
the safety board has been pushing the federal aviation administration to require cockpit voice recorders in smaller craft, including helicopters that seat at least six passengers. the faa is considering the proposed rules change
scientists in two laboratories say they have confirmed a report from researchers that a new kind of superconducting material loses all resistance to electricity at a record high temperature
researchers at the university of arkansas say the material showed zero resistance at about minus 269 degrees fahrenheit, more than 20 degrees above previous widely accepted reports for stable superconducting compounds
paul chu of the university of houston said he had confirmed the arkansas results, finding zero resistance at minus 272 degrees. he said his sample also expelled an applied magnetic field, a hallmark of superconductivity called the meissner effect
the results also have been confirmed by researchers at international business machines corp., said ibm spokesman jerry present. he said he could not release details
superconductivity is the ability to carry current without resistance. scientists are trying to make materials that become superconducting at as high a temperature as possible, to make them practical for uses in high-speed computers, bullet trains and other applications
higher temperatures than the arkansas mark have been reported in the press. but some have not been confirmed in other laboratories, and others refer to the temperature at which a sample shows initial signs of isolated pockets of superconductivity, rather than superconducting pathways along its entire length
the new compound showed initial signs of superconductivity at minus 238 degrees, said university of arkansas researcher allen hermann, who did the research with zhenghi sheng
that is slightly higher than the mark of about minus 243 degrees recently reported for superconductors that include the element bismuth rather than a so-called ``rare earth.''
the arkansas compound uses the element thallium rather than bismuth or rare earth. other ingredients are calcium, barium, copper and oxygen
the results were announced to the press and at a scientific meeting last month, but were not widely reported. they have been accepted for publication in the british journal nature, hermann said in a telephone interview
chu said lessons from the thallium and bismuth compounds will help in developing materials with still higher temperatures. he also noted that the thallium compound showed zero resistance above 100 degrees on the kelvin scale, giving a psychological boost for hopes of higher temperatures
the 100-degree kelvin mark corresponds to about minus 280 degrees fahrenheit
thallium is ``not quite practical'' for applications outside the laboratory because it is toxic and in limited supply, he said
hermann said he thinks thallium and bismuth eventually will be abandoned in favor of new materials with higher temperatures and better characteristics for applications
brian schwartz, physics professor at brooklyn college, said the arkansas work is encouraging because it shows that substituting elements in superconducting materials may lead to higher temperatures
a federal court ruling expected today in boston could determine whether new regulations will go into effect this week that cut off funds to family planning centers which advocate or perform abortions
the months of debate continued tuesday as nabers cabaniss, deputy assistant secretary at the department of health and human services, defended the administration proposals before members of a family planning group challenging the regulations in court
cabaniss told the gathering that the new title x regulations were not an attack on the family planning industry but a reaffirmation of the administration's anti-abortion policy
addressing the annual meeting of the national family planning and reproductive health association, cabaniss said the new regulations, due to go into effect tomorrow, would withhold funding to centers in which ``abortion is a method of family planning.''
we support family planning but not abortion on demand,'' she said, urging the group to ``work together to separate family planning from abortion.''
cabaniss said the regulations require so-called ``non-directive'' counseling, which offers pregnant women information about their medical options with the exception of abortion
if the facility also performs abortions, to keep title x funding for its other programs the clinic must maintain separate personnel, separate accounting procedures, and provide different and clearly defined waiting and treatment rooms for each type of patient
among participants speaking out against the new title x rules was dorothy p. mann, executive director of the family planning council of southeast pennsylvania in philadelphia. she told cabaniss: ``we are not fools. women won't come to programs that can't help them
these regulations will destroy the family planning programs and in doing so the lives of millions of poor women.''
since the regulations were published in the federal register last month, two injunctions have been granted in courts in denver and new york. the denver suit was brought by planned parenthood federation of america, while the new york court action was brought by the american civil liberties union
the denver ruling covers all planned parenthood centers, and the new york ruling covers clinics in that state
a third suit, filed by nfprha in u.s. district court in boston, seeks an injunction to protect its publicly funded member clinics and other family planning centers not covered by the other injunctions
scott swirling, the association's executive director, said the suit was filed to eliminate regulations he asserted ``are illegal, violate the intent of congress, violate medical ethics and could harm the health care of almost 5 million poor women we serve.''
if the boston court agrees, the three preliminary injunctions would stop the regulations from going into effect and give the court time to look at the regulations and issue or deny a permanent injunction, cabaniss said
in this case we would expect some permanent ruling in march,'' she said, adding that the cases will end up in the supreme court
if the u.s. district court in boston denies the injunction, hhs must decide whether to wait or implement the regulations affecting those clinics not covered in the planned parenthood or new york state suits
as head of the office of population affairs, cabaniss administers the $140 million title x program, which funds about 4,000 family planning centers. according to hhs statistics, 85 percent of the patients served by these centers are low-income and one-third of them are adolescents
work could begin this week on a $2.3 million elevator that will allow visitors to view what is believed to be the perch from which president john f. kennedy was shot
the contract to build the elevator was awarded monday by the dallas county commission
the dallas county historical foundation struggled to fund the exhibit for the past 11 years, and plans to raise $1.5 million more from private sources for additional renovations on the sixth floor of the former texas schoolbook depository
as sad as it is, it is the most important historical site in dallas,'' said lindalyn adams, president of foundation
the project includes construction of a six-story access tower that will house the elevator and a one-story, ground-level exhibit hall adjacent to the building
the exhibit, to be called ``the sixth floor,'' is expected to attract an estimated 300,000 to 500,000 visitors annually
the warren commission determined that on nov. 22, 1963, lee harvey oswald fired a high-powered rifle at kennedy's motorcade from the sixth floor of what is now the dallas county administration building, where he worked
tony callaway, a partner in the architectural firm of hendrick callaway, said construction could be completed by november. but foundation officials say they are unlikely to schedule the exhibit's opening for nov. 22, the 25th anniversary of kennedy's assassination
we think it would be inappropriate,'' ms. adams said
about 30 of israel's leading entertainers staged a sing-in to protest the government's handling of 12 weeks of arab riots in the west bank and gaza strip
shalom, shalom, we are making peace. there will be peace. we are together beyond fear,'' they sang, swaying together on a stage in front of tel aviv's city hall
about 3,000 israelis sang along in hebrew to the tune of ``we are the world.''
the protesters also heard newly released peace songs and carried placards that said ``we won't be a nation of bullies'' and ``enough of occupation.''
the demonstration was held in kings of israel plaza, site of a protest by more than 100,000 israelis in 1982 that helped lead to israel's pullout from lebanon
tuesday's protest was sponsored by red line, peace activists who are staging a four-day march from rosh haniqra on the lebanon border to jerusalem, where about 1,500 marchers are expected today
three months of arab rioting against the 20-year israeli occupation of their homelands has produced a crop of new protest songs, the first since the end of israel's three-year occupation of lebanon in 1985
among the stars was rita fayrouz, the iranian-born singer who recently released ``a song for children.'' the lyrics say, ``he was born of mother war, but deep in his heart, he just wanted to be a poet.''
a number of participants expressed disappointment at the relatively small turnout. but rami kleinstein, a rock musician and ms. fayrouz's husband, predicted ``change is going to happen.''
one of the most critical songs was by si hyman, 26, who wrote ``shooting and crying'' to protest an incident last month in which israeli soldiers buried alive four arabs in kfar salem. the victims were rescued by relatives
ms. hyman sang:
shooting and crying, burning and laughing
when did we learn to bury alive?
shooting and crying, burning and laughing
when did we forget that we also had children killed?''
in an interview after the performance, she said she was shocked that ``this was done by the jewish people who lived through the holocaust. i said to myself we've got to stop it.''
japan and western europe were rebuilt with america's help after world war ii and should now repay the united states by picking up a larger share of nato and japanese defense costs, according to a well-known historian
the comments tuesday by yale historian paul kennedy echoed other calls by legislators and former government officials as president reagan flew to europe for a two-day meeting of the 16-nation north atlantic treaty organization
kennedy, author of ``the rise and fall of great nations,'' told the senate budget committee that calls for increased ``burden sharing'' are part of the effort to find a way out of ever-growing defense expenditures
some american allies ``are now richer per capita than the usa,'' kennedy said, adding that japan and western europe ``ought to bear a larger share of the defense burden.''
sen. lawton chiles, d-fla., chairman of the panel, agreed, saying: ``it seems to me we are draining our power trying to do too much. our adversaries are happy to see us try. our allies haven't done as much as they can to help.''
defense secretary frank c. carlucci also agreed at least in part with kennedy. at a house budget committee hearing earlier tuesday, he said, ``i quite agree with the thesis that our allies need to do more.'' but he added that ``i don't think it is very useful to simply berate the europeans on this.''
carlucci told the house panel that he doesn't think nato will increase spending in response to complaints by congress
rep. william gray, d-pa., chairman of the committee, complained about what he called ``unequal sharing'' by nato countries. ``our allies in nato are not doing, in my estimation, enough for their own defense,'' he said
the united states is spending about 6 percent of its gross national product on defense while no other countries in nato are above 3 percent, gray said
rep. richard durbin, r-ill., said the average japanese citizen spends about $100 a year in taxes for defense, while the average american spends $1,200
we need to make every effort to get our allies to do more,'' carlucci agreed, but he added that they do more than is ``generally recognized.'' he cited a statistic that nato would supply 90 percent of the ground troops that would be used to halt a soviet non-nuclear attack
carlucci said america's defense budget is 5.7 percent of the nation's gnp, not 6 percent and he added that u.s. defense budgets generally have stayed even or declined in recent years
nato has long set a target for each member to increase spending by 3 percent a year after inflation, and most nations don't meet that target, carlucci said. the united states hasn't met the 3 percent target for at least four years, he added
carlucci and adm. william crowe jr., chairman of the joint chiefs of staff, said nato needs to improve its conventional defenses in the wake of the treaty banning medium-range atomic missiles from europe
crowe detailed nato's shortcomings in non-nuclear weapons, but added, ``surely the prospect of having to fight 16 nations at once remains a sobering one for the kremlin.''
when congress convened last july for the first time in 15 years, it vowed to build democracy from the ruins of authoritarian rule. seven months later, critics say it has been slow to address fundamental issues
the new constitution, drafted under president corazon aquino, reestablished the bicameral, u.s.-style congress. former president ferdinand marcos abolished congress in 1972 and replaced it with a single-chamber, rubber-stamp assembly
members of the senate and house of representatives were elected in may 1987, and congress convened last july 27. since then, more than 6,000 bills have been submitted in the 23-member senate and the 202-member house
as of the end of february, only 13 had been enacted into law
the bills are not an indication of quality at all,'' said rep. bonifacio gillego. he said most were for local projects such as roads, schools and hospitals
meanwhile, legislation on major national issues, such as land reform, has been bogged down by special interests and organizational problems in the two chambers
commentators and congressional sources disagree on why congress has not been more productive
some complain that traditional politicians spend too much time on ``peripheral'' topics or delivering lengthy speeches while ignoring complex issues
it's part of the turmoil of transition, part of growing up,'' said opposition leader wilson gamboa, who was defeated for the senate last may. ``vital issues of legislation that should have far-reaching effects on the condition of the people have not been addressed.''
some congressmen defend the slow pace, saying it is better to take time with complicated issues than rush legislation which members may later regret
we cannot afford to hurry that much and regret it later,'' said sen. juan ponce enrile. ``we're not just talking about our few interests but a complex situation.''
sen. ernesto maceda, chairman of the senate defense committee, also defended the slow pace
is that what they want, faster laws but probably imperfect laws?'' maceda said in an interview. ``we're slower, but probably all sides are heard.''
last month, eight senators formed a ``conscience bloc'' and publicly criticized senate president jovito salonga for delays in bringing legislation to the floor
one of the eight, sen. alberto romulo, said economic and social issues ``have not been given the importance they deserve.'' he added, ``our performance will be assessed by how much we have done to improve the quality of life of our people.''
salonga promised to speed up senate proceedings and reduce the time allotted for speeches
some congressmen also complain that the two chambers lack sufficient staff and resources to provide members with detailed information and advice on legislation
many commentators view the current debate on land reform as a test case of congress' ability to legislate controversial issues with far-reaching impact on national life
last july, mrs. aquino decreed a nationwide land redistribution program but left virtually all the difficult decisions, such as compensation and retention limits, to congress
she gave the lawmakers 90 days to approve the legislation, and house speaker ramon mitra boasted his chamber would meet the deadline within 30 days. but neither the house nor the senate has approved a land reform bill, in part because of opposition by landlord members
there has been considerable delay, almost intentional on the part of the landlords to avoid the passage of an agrarian reform bill,'' said gillego, chairman of the house's land reform committee
the justice department should appeal a pair of conflicting rulings on random drug testing for civilian government employees in order to resolve the issue, says a judge responsible for one of the decisions
u.s. district judge thomas f. hogan on tuesday ordered the army to stop random checks of 9,400 of its civilian employees for drug use because the tests are an unreasonable search prohibited by the constitution
it is with some regret that the court removes what might be a powerful weapon from the nation's arsenal in the campaign against illegal drug use, but the values represented by the constitution and fourth amendment are transcendent,'' hogan ruled
hogan said random checks could not be justified by safety concerns because the urine test used by the army did not indicate whether an employee was using drugs on the job
the ruling was made on three challenges brought by public employees unions to the army's 1986 order directing random drug tests of civilians in sensitive jobs. the cases involved unions representing civilians at ft. stewart, ga., the sharp army depot in lathrop, calif. and guards at aberdeen proving ground, md
noting that another federal judge in washington last year upheld random drug testing of nearly 30,000 transportation department employees, hogan invited the justice department to appeal his decision
he also suggested that the u.s. circuit court of appeals here consolidate the two cases for a single review of ``a question of exceptional importance.''
based on hogan's invitation, ``we are reviewing the opinion and are considering an appeal,'' said amy brown, a justice department spokeswoman
on monday, the supreme court agreed to review a ruling by a federal appeals court in new orleans, which had upheld drug testing of u.s. customs service employees who seek promotions
a federal appeals court in san francisco last month ruled unconstitutional the mandatory drug testing of railway workers involved in accidents
sen. edward m. kennedy says increases in the government's food stamp program are needed to make up for reagan administration cuts that have helped create hunger in america through the 1980s
the cold statistics only begin to measure the toll in terms of the human lives damaged, disabled and destroyed by our shameful abdication of responsibility in recent years,'' the massachusetts democrat told a group of nutrition activists tuesday
we have financed the greatest arms buildup in human history, but once again we are losing the war on hunger,'' he said
kennedy, chairman of the senate labor and human resources committee, planned to introduce legislation today with sen. patrick j. leahy, d-vt., and rep. leon e. panetta, d-calif., that would help ``right those wrongs.''
i do not intend to accept proposals that seek to balance the federal budget on the backs of poor children,'' he said. ``survival of the fittest may be the law of the jungle, but it is not the law of america, and it is time for america to help.''
kennedy said his anti-hunger legislation would raise food stamp benefits ``so that no americans are forced to go hungry for the last part of every month.''
it also would ease food stamp eligibility requirements and provide more public information about the program
kennedy said hunger in america was largely eradicated by the late 1970s, but ``misguided'' budget cuts under president reagan have ``rubbed salt in the wounds'' created by the recession of the early 1980s, triggering the re-emergence of hunger
earlier, boston mayor raymond l. flynn told the food research and action center's annual conference that the nation needs a ``compassionate urban agenda.''
flynn, chairman of the u.s. conference of mayors' task force on hunger and homelessness, said both problems are growing, especially among families with children
the sad truth is that hunger is now more prevalent in our nation than at any time since the great depression,'' he said
the underdog hero of the winter olympics, british ski-jumper eddie ``the eagle'' edwards, has been offered a recording contract and may soon appear in commercials endorsing a brand of vodka
edwards, who became the olympics' favorite loser, flew home to a hero's welcome tuesday. he was the last man off the plane
a plasterer from cheltenham, in southwest england, edwards won the hearts of this nation of underdog-lovers by finishing last in ski-jumping events in calgary. he arrived at heathrow airport with the 100-member british team, some of whom wore ``eddie the eagle'' t-shirts
edwards, 24, trooped into the airport to be greeted by flower-throwing fans and an army of photographers, reporters and television crews
i've made it, i've made it to the olympics,'' the eagle said. ``that's all i cared about.''
alfred and catherine heath, a retired couple from wimbledon, were among the well-wishers. ``we saw him on tv,'' said heath. ``he was just wonderful.''
he's got guts,'' said john ward, a transport executive. ``he's captured the imagination of people.''
edwards was britain's first ski-jumper in the games for more than 50 years
he finished last in both the 70-meter and 90-meter events, but endeared himself to millions of armchair athletes with his gangly, bemused clumsiness, enhanced by the thick glasses that gave him a bird-like look
his hometown is planning a parade for him on thursday
edwards said he was suprised by all the publicity he received, but said: ``i'm going to try not to let it get in the way. nothing's going to change. i'm still a jumper. i'm still training.''
when he was asked if fame might go to his head, edwards replied: ``i'll try not to let it.'' he confirmed, however, he intends to cut a record titled ``fly, eddie, fly.''
edwards signed up an agent, london music promoter simon platz, who told a british tv interviewer the eagle would cut the record today. ``he says he can sing, and that's good enough for me,'' said platz
edwards also was negotiating a deal to endorse vladivar, a brand of vodka
it's great to actually have somebody who's prepared to have a smile at themselves _ and keep on coming last. that's very important,'' phil staniforth, the vodka company representative, told the interviewer
critics had said edwards should not have entered the olympic events because of the danger, but he said, ``i proved them wrong.''
i've only been jumping two years, and the trainers i've talked to say there's no reason i can't get into the top five. hopefully, i'll be a force to reckon with next year.''
but in the meantime, edwards said he wanted to get back to his job as plasterer. ``it's a nice rest, plastering,'' he said
a stamp cancellation such as the british one proclaiming that ``jesus is alive'' could not be issued in the united states, a postal service official says
the postal service's 74 division managers can approve special cancellations for events of general public interest, said dick rustin, manager of the stamp information branch
the special cancellations may not deal with things only of local interest or for political, religious, fraternal, trade or commercial purposes, he said tuesday
the british post office on tuesday began postmarking nearly all letters mailed in that country with the words ``jesus is alive!'' as part of a private arrangement financed by an evangelist
jewish leaders criticized the christian cancellation as potentially offensive
the special postmark, which also contains a small cross, will last six weeks and was paid for by paul slennet, who sells religious literature at two bookstores in southend-on-sea, east of london. he said god told him to buy the postmark
the state-owned post office said slennet paid the equivalent of $88,500 for the privilege of having every letter mailed through 68 of britain's 69 sorting offices with the jesus message
rustin said groups seeking the special cancellations have to pay $900 for the engraving of the cancellation plus about $100 for each canceling die to be used. for a large post office many dies can be required, rustin said. us</head>
the state department says it approves of efforts by opponents of panamanian strongman manuel antonio noriega to freeze panamanian assets in the united states and choke off payments to the government
it's their action to take,'' state department spokeswoman phyllis oakley said tuesday, calling it ``the legitimate action of the constitutional government in panama.''
panamanian opposition leader gabriel lewis, a former ambassador to washington, said legal steps were being taken to freeze the assets but he gave few details
lewis said disclosing specifics of the plan could enable panamanian officials loyal to noriega to take countermeasures
juan b. sosa, u.s. ambassador for panama's president in hiding, eric arturo delvalle, released a proclamation from delvalle calling on all panamanians not to engage in any financial transactions with the authorities who seized power from him last week
the proclamation states that payment of debts, taxes and other obligations should be withheld until constitutional government is restored in panama
the legal efforts in the united states were being handled by william d. rogers, a former assistant secretary of state for inter-american affairs and an undersecretary of state for economic affairs
the panamanian national assembly, dominated by forces loyal to noriega deposed delvalle last friday after the president had attempted to fire noriega as defense chief
pentagon officials are studying a reorganization plan for the ``stars &amp; stripes'' military newspapers that could change their printing schedules, introduce advertising and cut back on staff
the reorganization plan, proposed to the pentagon last fall by an advisory task force but only recently released publicly, is now being studied by the european and pacific commands, where the two newspapers are published
the top military leaders of those commands are to file comments with the pentagon within the next week or so, allowing defense department officials to make some final decisions on the fate of the two newspapers, said william caldwell, a pentagon spokesman
ultimately, dan howard, the assistant defense secretary for public affairs, will decide whether to change the newspapers' operation in consultation with defense secretary frank c. carlucci and congress
the internal review comes at a time when the general accounting office is conducting an independent investigation of alleged censorship by military commanders at the papers. congress, at the prodding of sen. william proxmire, d-wis., ordered that investigation last december and is likely to study closely any reorganization plan
the newspapers are published for american servicemen posted overseas and date back to publication in france during world war i. the papers' chief goal is to provide the same national and international news available in the united states to troops assigned to foreign countries
although frequently referred to as one newspaper, there are two separate editions of the stars and stripes, published by autonomous bureaus in west germany and japan
the papers are staffed by military as well as civilian journalists and report to the commanders of the european and pacific commands. they are partially supported by taxpayer funds _ roughly $9 million in fiscal 1986
the pentagon formed a seven-member ``stars &amp; stripes advisory task force'' in the fall of 1986, asking for ideas on how to make the operations more efficient. named as chairman was capt. robert a. rosen, a longtime communications executive in private life who is also a public affairs officer in the naval reserve
the 55-page report produced by the rosen panel concludes that the two newspapers are ``bringing to overseas dod personnel a balanced presentation of u.s. and international news along with relevant dod and unified command news, but at a high cost.''
the task force saw areas where improvement in newspaper quality and significant cost savings could be made.''
the panel said the pentagon should consider such things as shifting from a seven-day-a-week schedule to a six-day-a-week schedule; consolidation of management and procurement; paring expenses on wire services by subscribing to only one; investing in modern text-editing computers to improve staff efficiency; and closely reviewing staff levels in any event
the newspapers are published in a similar fashion, yet the editorial staff of the european edition is twice that of the pacific edition _ 87 to 41, the panel found
the task force came away with the distinct impression that the european stars &amp; stripes, and possibly the pacific stars &amp; stripes, editorial departments were overstaffed,'' the report states
most importantly, it is time to re-think the restrictions that prevent the newspapers from accepting most forms of advertising, the panel insisted. the two papers rely now primarily on their 25-cent subscription charge
the report said: ``the task force believes that the congress and the dod must come to grips with the practical reality of what a newspaper is _ namely a manufactured product that conveys news and other information, including advertising information. ..
congress and dod must apply that reality to the stars and stripes so that the papers may better serve their readers and become economically secure with a reduced need of appropriated funds.''
if the government is not willing to do that, ``it should either resign itself to continued appropriated fund support ... or get out of the daily newspaper business,'' the panel concluded
richard gephardt stood in the bright sunshine on the steps of the capitol building and delivered the message that has carried him to the front rank of the democratic presidential field
it was tough talk about trade and the problems of american workers
his critics call gephardt's message protectionist. they decry the undeniable fact that this washington insider is running against the establishment
but the missouri congressman appears to be getting a positive response. no other candidate has a message that has caught hold so effectively with a large portion of the democratic party electorate
gephardt may fall short in the race for the democratic presidential nomination. the party may turn to gov. michael dukakis' technocratic appeal, to sen. albert gore jr.'s tough defense and foreign policy message or to jesse jackson's anti-establishment platform
but gephardt's strong run for the nomination already has delivered a message to the the party, one that might outlive his candidacy
a strong tribute to the gephardt message came in the republican presidential debate in atlanta last sunday when rep. jack kemp of new york turned to kansas sen. bob dole and accused him of sounding ``just like dick gephardt.''
when dole campaigns in south carolina he unabashedly supports legislation to restrict textile imports. so does pat robertson
the reason is simple. over 45 percent of the jobs in south carolina are in the textile industry and the state has lost 126 plants
a staple of the gepardt message is reference to an editorial in the wall street journal that referred to the trade deficits as ``just a fact of life.''
then he said he'd like the editorial writer to come with him to bettendorff, iowa, where 6,000 workers in three different industries have recently lost their jobs because of foreign competition
sit across the table as i did from live human beings and have them tell you what it's like to lose their life insurance, lose their health insurance, lose their pension, what it's like to go home and tell their families that they've lost their jobs, that they're going to stand in an unemployment line or a welfare line, to tell them it's just a fact of life,'' he said
he referred to electronics workers in new hampshire and textile workers in south carolina and said, ``ladies and gentlemen, i don't like those facts of life.''
he said it was time for america to ``get control of our economic destiny,'' a powerful message to americans who feel uneasy over the nation's enormous trade deficits
four years ago, republicans derided as protectionist, walter mondale's call for legislation that would require a certain portion of foreign products to be manufactured in the united states, so-called domestic content legislation
the label stuck. it was special interest legislation, a bad thing for the country
but during the four years since that election, the situation has not improved and more and more people are feeling they are a part of that special interest
two former governors of south carolina _ robert mcnair and richard riley _ stood with gephardt on the capitol steps and endorsed his candidacy
both felt compelled to defend the congressman against charges he is protectionist
mcnair said gephardt has ``faced up to putting america first with a fair, sound and sensible trade bill. ... it is not a piece of protectionist legislation as some have tried to portray it, but it is what is best for this country.''
dick gephardt has spoken out during this campaign on trade and some have referred to him as a protectionist,'' said riley. ``he's not a protectionist at all, he's a pragmatist.''
republican bob dole received more money from political action committees than all the other presidential candidates, while democrat richard gephardt, who has portrayed himself as anti-establishment, leads in pac contributions among his party's hopefuls
gephardt, a missouri congressman, accepted $337,698 in contributions from pacs, including those representing first republican bank fund, prudential-bache securities and e.f. hutton &amp; co., now a part of shearson lehman hutton inc
dole, a senator from kansas, has received $645,190 in contributions from pacs representing banking institutions, utility companies and other groups, according to a report issued tuesday by congress watch
vice president bush has received the second-highest amount with $559,895; rep. jack kemp has gotten $57,766, and the other republican candidate, former television evangelist pat robertson, has not accepted any pac contributions, the report said
tennessee sen. albert gore jr. was second among the democrats with $174,934 in pac money, and illinois sen. paul simon was third with $152,250. jesse jackson accepted $47,925 in pac contributions, the report said
massachusetts gov. michael dukakis and former colorado sen. gary hart have said they do not accept pac money
gephardt was roundly criticized on the subject by several of his rivals in a debate monday night in williamsburg, va
and the dukakis campaign has prepared anti-gephardt ads that communications director leslie dach described this way: ``he says he is leading the little guy's fight, but his campaign is financed and supported by the big guys. his biggest contributors are america's biggest corporations.''
congress watch, which issued the report, is the legislative arm of public citizen, the liberal organization founded in 1971 by consumer advocate ralph nader. the group based its report on federal election commission documents from october 1987 and campaign contributions through jan. 31 of this year
monday night, dukakis took gephardt to task for accepting pac contributions while ``racing around the country beating up on the establishment.''
gephardt said he had often voted against the policies advocated by his contributors and ``to suggest that people have voted according to the wishes of people who have given them money, i just think is out of touch with reality. i haven't done that and i know you haven't done that.''
but jackson said gephardt's contention that he ignored the wishes of his contributors was unrealistic
lobbyists would lose their jobs if they gave money continuously against the interests of who they were working for,'' jackson said
among contributors to gephardt's campaign were the builders pac association, $5,000; first republican bank fund, $5,000; prudential-bache securities, $2,500; mercantile bank corp., $1,000, and e.f. hutton, $1,500
election law limits each pac to contributions of no more than $5,000 to any one candidate, in contrast to the limit for individual contributions of $1,000
gore received contributions from pacs representing coca-cola bottling co., $2,500; lockheed corp., $1,000; the sheet metal workers, $5,000, and pacific telesis, $1,500
dole's pac contributors included american telephone &amp; telegraph co., $5,000; h &amp; r block, $1,000; shell oil, $5,000; union oil, $5,000, and federal express, $2,000
according to fec documents released last year, dole led his senate colleagues with a total of $3.3 million received from pacs since he entered congress in 1968
of that, about $1 million was raised from pacs for the kansas senator's re-election campaign in 1986
bush accepted contributions from pacs representing citicorp, $2,250; csx transportation, $1,000, and manufacturers hanover, $2,000
bill greene of the boston globe and anthony suau of black star were chosen the top newspaper and magazine photographers of the year in the 45th annual pictures of the year competition at the university of missouri
the top photo essayist award went to herman leroy emmet, a new york city free-lancer who won for a seven-year documentary focusing on migrant workers
bill kuykendall, director of the pictures of the year competition, said tuesday that a record 1,995 photographers entered more than 37,000 photographs in what he called ``the world's largest and most significant photojournalism competition.''
the contest is cosponsored by the national press photographers association and the university of missouri school of journalism. eight experts in photography worked for two weeks narrowing the field of more than 37,000 entries in 38 categories
the winners by categories:
