the tokyo stock exchange surged closer to pre-crash levels today, setting a new 1988 record for volume, while the dollar fell slightly
foreign buying and a bullish economy in the united states have convinced domestic investors to join in,'' said a market analyst who requested anonymity, adding that the strength of the market has been surprising
latecomers have been trying to catch the bus. i would be concerned if turnover like today's continued, though, because it could show that the market is overheating,'' he said
the nikkei stock average of 225 selected issues closed at 25,682.82 points, up 246.92 points, or 0.97 percent from tuesday's close. volume in the first section was 1.7 billion shares, a record high for this year
on the foreign exchange market, the dollar closed at 128.47 yen, down 0.16 yen from tuesday's close of 128.63 yen. the dollar opened today at 128.43 yen
a currency dealer at a major commercial bank in tokyo, who also spoke on condition of anonymity, said the dollar was trading in a narrow range in the absence of major market-moving news
trading on the first section of the exchange totaled 900 million shares at the end of the morning session, before closing the day 100 million shares higher than the previous 1988 record, set tuesday
prior to the october crash, the nikkei index stood at 25,746.56
institutional investors are responding positively to the favorable outlook for the economic performance of japanese firms in this fiscal year,'' said hiromi yoneyama, a dealer with wako securities
yoneyama said corporate earnings of major firms were expected to show better-than-expected results in fiscal 1987, which ends march 31
the league of women voters called off democratic and republican debates scheduled for sunday after presidential candidates in both parties showed little or no interest in attending
in essence, the candidates are snubbing nearly half the country two days before this critical election,'' said carole bucy, president of the league of women voters of nashville
the debates, which were to have been telecast from nashville by cable news network, would have come only two days before the 20-state round of caucuses and primaries on march 8, or super tuesday
league spokeswoman janice kaplan had said earlier in the day the democratic debate was definitely on and the republican debate would proceed even if there were only two candidates
the cancellation followed indications by republican bob dole that he was unlikely to join jack kemp for a two-man debate
in knoxville, where dole spoke to a downtown rally, press secretary walt riker said he doubted seriously that dole would participate in the rally without vice president george bush
bush and pat robertson, a former television evangelist, both advised the league they would not show up
ms. kaplan said rep. richard gephardt ``told us this week he did not want to debate in (tennessee sen.) albert gore's back yard, even though he has known all along the debate was in nashville.''
ms. bucy said massachusetts gov. michael dukakis had decided not to participate
gore's chief campaign spokesman, mike kopp, chided gephardt and dukakis passing up the debates here. both of them also skipped a debate last sunday in houston
kopp said gephardt and dukakis ``participated fully in the debates that preceded the iowa caucuses. now these same candidates are dodging these (nashville and houston) debates where they have to talk about the issues.''
sen. paul simon, who has said he would not campaign actively in southern-dominated super tuesday states, was apparently planning on taking part in the nashville debate
other democrats in the running are jesse jackson and former colorado sen. gary hart. delegates</head>
sen. bob dole picked up a delegate and another was slated uncommitted as wyoming's gop presidential delegation selection process got under way
republicans in two counties met tuesday to select two of the state's 18 delegates to the republican national convention
most of the rest of the gop delegates and 13 of the state's 18 democratic delegates will be selected saturday, three days before super tuesday
despite the emphasis on campaigning in the south, wyoming was getting some attention from the candidates
sen. albert gore jr. of tennessee and massachusetts gov. michael dukakis both planned stops in the state before saturday's county conventions. gary hart, who is from neighboring colorado, has visited
rep. richard gephardt bought radio ads in wyoming, the first time a candidate has advertised his candidacy over the airwaves
none of the republican candidates were expected in the state, where vice president bush and sen. bob dole were considered the frontrunners
natrona and platte counties were the first to allocate presidential delegates tuesday, with eight other counties ready to select their gop delegates on saturday
the natrona county delegate, judy catchpole, said she was committed to dole; the platte county pick, natty dodge, was uncommitted
weston county republicans planned to choose their delegate friday and niobrara county party members were to do the same on march 12
the final six presidential delegates will be selected at the state republican convention on may 7 in cheyenne. all 23 democratic presidential delegates will be selected saturday at county conventions throughout the state
gore already received the support of former gov. ed herschler and another of the state's five ``super delegates,'' who can remain uncommitted going into the democratic national convention in july. unlikely</head> bgng ``carter made ...''; to delete nunn's first name, sub 8th graf, bgng ``he said ...''</note>
former president jimmy carter said there's an even chance that none of the democratic presidential candidates will have a lock on the party's nomination before the national convention in july
carter, who has not endorsed any of the candidates, received a visit tuesday from one of the hopefuls, rep. richard gephardt of missouri, who characterized the meeting as a non-political call on ``an old friend.''
my hope is that out of the primary and caucus season will come a clear winner,'' carter said just one week before 20 states, most of them south of the mason-dixon line, hold primaries and caucuses with 1,307 delegates at stake
i'm not sure that's a likelihood now,'' he said
carter made it clear he is not one of those waiting for some other candidate to enter the race _ a mario cuomo, bill bradley or even georgia sen. sam nunn
i would not personally favor turning to someone outside the active candidate group for the nomination,'' said the former president
carter explained his decision not to endorse any of the party's contenders, saying ``it is better for us not to take a preferential position among the democratic candidates.''
he said the only democrat he might have thrown his support behind was nunn, who decided against entering the race
carter talked about the democratic race and super tuesday after meeting at his rambling brick home with gephardt, one of six democratic aspirants for the presidency
gephardt denied he had any political motive for his trip to this tiny georgia town carter put on the map
i didn't come here to try to be helped on super tuesday,'' said gephardt, who stopped in georgia on a trip from williamsburg, va., to columbia, s.c
i came here today not to enhance my prospects, but to greet an old friend,'' he said
gephardt, carter and his wife, rosalynn, stood on the front walk of the former president's home at 1 woodland road. his hair much whiter than when he left the white house in january 1981, carter wore an open-necked checked shirt, a tweed jacket and khaki pants
asked if he missed all the attention of a political campaign, carter laughed and said he and his wife had just returned from skiing in colorado
but he was also willing to answer questions as long as reporters had any to ask
carter was careful to say something nice about all the democratic candidates, and suggested that any one of them could do well in the south
i'm sure sen. (albert) gore (of tennessee) will have an advantage among some voters because he's a southerner,'' said carter. the former president's daughter, amy, has endorsed jesse jackson
amy doesn't ask me for counsel,'' he said, when asked if she had discussed her position with him
texas women extended their reign over the miss usa pageant to a fourth consecutive year as a beaming courtney gibbs took the crown in a contest marred by arrests, an assault and protests
pageant spokeswoman stacy sacco said she was stunned by the texas victory record and felt compelled to assure reporters tuesday night that the contest televised nationally by cbs was not rigged
the woman who started the winning streak in 1985, laura martinez-herring of el paso, did a little jig after ms. gibbs was crowned, and echoed the sentiments of many pageant-watchers: ``i just feel sorry for the next miss texas.''
ms. gibbs, a 21-year-old junior at texas christian university, smiled broadly when outgoing miss usa michelle royer of keller put the crown on her head
it feels fabulous,'' the blue-eyed brunette said calmly, seemingly unsurprised by her victory
one of the gifts michelle (royer) gave me was a dictionary with the word `impossible' whited out. so of course it was possible,'' she said
the pageant made the news weeks before the coronation: bob barker ended his 21-year reign as host to protest the awarding of furs to the winner and use of furs during the show. the first two miss minnesotas bowed out after it was disclosed they had been arrested. animal-rights protesters picketed the el paso convention center. and co-host tracy scoggins fought off an attacker in a hotel elevator
ms. gibbs of fort worth beat diana magana, 22, of rancho palos verdes, calif., who was first runner-up. it was one of two best possible results for guyrex associates of el paso, the company that produces the miss texas-usa and miss california-usa contests and hones those winners' pageant skills for the miss usa contest
ms. gibbs, who won about $200,000 worth of prizes, including a mink coat and jacket, will represent the united states in the miss universe pageant may 23 in taipei, taiwan. ms. magana, a brown-eyed brunette, will represent the united states in the miss world pageant
second runner-up tuesday was donna rampy, 24, of riverdale, ga.; followed by monica farrell, 23, of jacksonville, fla.; and dana michele, 20, of richmond, miss
officials did not rank the other five semifinalists: gina zordani, 23, of illinois; rowann brewer, 23, of maryland; tamara walker, 18, of oklahoma; april abel, 20, of south carolina; and stephanie potts, 23, of tennessee
the 11 judges scored each semifinalist on interviews and on the swimsuit and evening gown competitions. the five highest scorers became finalists
miss minnesota, julie nelson, was the second runner-up in her state's contest, but the first two finishers, sue bolich and jolene stavrakis, quit the miss usa pageant after it was disclosed they had been arrested in separate shoplifting incidents
about 25 animal-rights activists peacefully picketed the pageant to protest the mink awards. members of sangre de cristo animal rights contend that fur ranching and trapping are cruel to animals
bob young, director of the group's las cruces, n.m., chapter, asked co-host alan thicke to resign as barker did to protest the awarding of the fur coats. but thicke refused, saying the furs were taken from ranch-raised minks that were treated humanely
in the pre-pageant incident, the man accused of attempted sexual assault in the attack on miss scoggins last week was released on $100 bail. prosecutors usually ask for $15,000 bail for such third-degree felonies
a state judge ordered pedro concepcion padill, 35, of el paso, re-arrested and imposed $100,000 bail, which he posted
the associate municipal magistrate who imposed the original bail was suspended and is under investigation, police said. showing</head> to correct spelling of ``pronounced'' subs 4th graf, bgng ``still, the ...''; to correct spelling of ``candidates'' subs penultimate graf, bgng ``but the ... .''</note>
republican george bush and democrat michael dukakis, on new england home ground, triumphed in vermont's ``beauty contest'' primary, but jesse jackson and bob dole had reason to celebrate as well as the presidential pack headed into the final days of the super tuesday campaign
our message continues to win,'' jackson exulted after finishing a strong second in vermont, which has only a tiny black population. jackson garnered 26 percent to dukakis' 57 percent
dole, outspent and out-organized, nonetheless made an impressive showing, gaining 39 percent to bush's 49 percent in what his campaign called the vice president's ``back yard.'' bush has a summer home in maine
still, the vice president pronounced himself pleased
this win gives us three out of three in new england, and i'm hopeful we can be as successful this saturday in south carolina and on super tuesday,'' said bush, who was campaigning in florida
no delegates were at stake in the tuesday primary. delegate selection begins at local caucuses next month and representatives of the dole campaign said they would work now on organizing for the caucuses
dukakis, fresh from a weekend win in maine's democratic caucus, was buoyant about his victory
it's terrific, we're rolling 'em up,'' said the massachusetts governor, who was campaigning in baltimore. with a strong organization and the endorsement of gov. madeleine kunin, dukakis had been expected to do well here
rep. richard gephardt, who has been dukakis' chief opponent in some recent contests, trailed with 8 percent. gephardt backers said his poor showing was caused by a lack of spendng in the state by his national campaign
dukakis and jackson both made a decision to compete,'' said lt. gov. howard dean, gephardt's state chairman. ``you can't overcome national organizations with just a vermont organization.''
some political observers had predicted a tight race between jackson and gephardt for second place, but jackson stole the show. he ran a strong second in the state's largest city of burlington and actually beat dukakis in 27 communities and tied him in two
we have found the common chord that is linking the american people,'' said jackson from his mother's home in greenville, s.c
it's putting to rest once and for all that he is candidate for black people,'' said burlington mayor bernard sanders, a jackson backer. ``we are the whitest state in america. i think it's an extraordinary showing.''
in unofficial results, with 100 percent of the state's 262 precincts reporting, dukakis had 28,244 votes or 57 percent; jackson 13,030 votes or 26 percent; gephardt 3,968 votes or 8 percent; simon 2,596 votes or 5 percent and hart 2,052 votes or 4 percent
bush received 23,550 or 49 percent; dole got 18,636 or 39 percent; former television evangelist pat robertson 2,447 votes or 5 percent; rep. jack kemp 1,866 votes or 4 percent. dropouts pete du pont and alexander haig received 794 votes, or 2 percent and 327 votes or 1 percent respectively
the robertson and kemp campaigns put up little effort in the state, although robertson plans to compete in the caucuses
i really didn't contest it,'' said robertson, in orlando, fla. ``we had virtually no organization in vermont.''
in years past, vermont's primary won national media attention because of its timing. candidates could use a victory in the state to build momentum following a victories in new hampshire or iowa. or, they could try to repair an image wounded by a loss in either of those two states
but the timing element worked against the state this year. because no delegates were being allocated, the candidates practically ignored the state to concentrate on the mega-delegate race in the south
the primary was part of the state's annual ritual, town meeting day, when vermont's voters decided town budgets, road repairs and a host of other local issues. turnout was lower than expected, with just under 100,000 venturing to the polls
vermont residents used their annual town meetings to bolster efforts to save family farms and grapple with growth
one town voted to exempt silos from property taxes and another declared its population growth rate too high
the votes tuesday reflected concern that vermont's rural heritage is being gobbled up by condominiums, resort developments and vacation homes. that issue was the focus of a special commission created by gov. madeleine kunin that recommended a comprehensive package of legislation to control growth and save open land
the town meetings, a mainstay of local government in which residents vote on town budgets and perennial issues such as road repairs, took up the growth controversy during debates of zoning regulations, expansions of planning staffs and other proposals
pawlet residents voted 249-178 to exempt farm silos from the property tax, though proponents ackowledged it would mean a savings of only $200 a year for each of the town's 17 farms
it's going to be a combination of these little things that keep the farmers going,'' said state rep. perry waite
in wallingford, residents tried to go even further, approving a proposal to exempt local farms from paying any property tax on farm land or buildings
for technical reasons the vote was not binding, said board chairman robert barker
we determined, though, the selectmen have the authority to institute this program,'' he said. ``and i think there's support for it. i'm for it.''
in woodstock, residents were asked to recommend a preferred population growth rate for the community, ranging from 0.66 percent, the highest annual growth rate the town had between 1890 and 1970, to 2.5 percent, the average so far this decade
they opted for the middle range of 0.9 percent, far below the present growth rate
if the populace makes it loud and clear it doesn't want rapid growth, perhaps the town could control growth by setting up certain conservation areas, or by steering patterns of development and population densities,'' said john wiggin, a member of a group studying growth in the community
growth wasn't the only issue on the minds of voters at town meetings. in corinth, the question of the day was whether the tiny hamlet at the town center is called cookville or cookeville
town clerk jack learmonth had asked for the vote because of disagreements throughout history. ``henceforth, it will be cookeville,'' he said following the vote
jesse jackon returned to his boyhood hometown as he headed down the home stretch to the super tuesday showdown, buoyed by another strong showing in a northern state
our message continues to win,'' the democratic presidential candidate said when he learned tuesday night that he had finished second in vermont's ``beauty contest'' primary
jackson was surrounded by family, staff and reporters enjoying a home-cooked southern style meal when word of his showing reached him
we have found the common chord that is linking the american people where they are in iowa or maine or new hampshire of minnesota or south carolina,'' he said
jackson is hoping that the inroads he has made among white voters in iowa, new hampshire, minnesota and maine _ all states with 1 percent or less black voting age population _ will continue in the march 8 series of primaries across 20 states, most of them in the south
jackson is expected to run well on super tuesday, especially in the deep south with its heavy black population. but the campaign also is targeting the working class, students, gays and other minorities
jackson acknowledged upon arriving in south carolina, which holds its primary saturday, that the south is different than the states that have voted so far. but he said, ``i'm a son of the south ... i know the south and its ways.''
he said his message _ attacking multinational corporations and appealing to the economically oppressed _ would remain the same as he campaigns in the south
arriving at the greenville airport, jackson highlighted the plight of textile workers who have been hurt by u.s. industry taking its operations overseas
he said that when he was a youth, greenville was the textile capital of the world and was filled with mills, now closed down
jackson said the customs laws must be enforced to keep foreign products from entering the country illegally, and he called for adjustment of the exchange rates by south korea and taiwan so those nations cannot receive inflated prices on their goods
jackson also defended his leadership qualifications which have come under attack from democratic rival tennessee sen. al gore jr. because jackson has never held an elected or appointive government post
speaking to a baptist convention at the springfield baptist church where his mother sang in the choir when he was a boy, jackson repeated his oft-stated claim that he knows the american people better than any other candidate. he also gave a litany of foreign leaders he has met, labor strikes he has mediated and civil rights causes he has championed
i'm not propped up by aides,'' he said, adding that he can speak to the poor because ``i was born in the underclass.''
earlier, in washington, jackson met with the south african ambassador to protest pretoria's new clampdown of anti-apartheid factions and arrest of dissident religious leaders, including archbishop desmond tutu
jackson told a news conference later that the ambassador, piet g.j. koornhof, asked for a follow-up meeting with rep. ronald dellums, d-calif., who attended the meeting and who is sponsoring legislation on sanctions against south africa because of its apartheid policy of racial separation
the ambassador did not join jackson and dellums at the news conference
jackson said u.s. corporations and banks should be ordered to leave south africa. and he called on the reagan administration to convene special united nations security council session international support for full sanctions against pretoria
he also called for suupport of the frontline states around south africa and aid in constructing trade corridors so zimbabwe and zambia would not be dependent on south african trade routes
he said he had phoned national security adviser colin powell and urged that the issue be raised with north atlantic treaty organization allies
jackson said powell told him there was ``a sense of outrage'' in the administration about the recent crackdown in south africa and that reagan would so state if the matter was brought up at the nato meeting
george bush had a nearly 3-to-1 lead over rival bob dole among republicans likely to vote in super tuesday's 16 primaries, while michael dukakis and jesse jackson were battling for the lead in the democratic contests, according to poll results published today
the vice president held a strong lead in virtually all the 16 states holding primaries next tuesday, according to the washington post-abc news poll. he had the support of nearly 60 percent of the 946 likely republican voters surveyed, while the kansas senator had just over 20 percent
former television evangelist pat robertson trailed with slightly more than 10 percent and rep. jack kemp of new york had 5 percent
in a survey of 1,121 likely democratic voters in the 16 primary states, jackson had an edge in mississippi, georgia, alabama and north carolina and was roughly tied with dukakis in arkansas, florida, texas and virginia
dukakis, the massachusetts governor, held a strong lead in his home state, rhode island and maryland. tennessee sen. albert gore jr. led in tennessee and kentucky, and missouri rep. richard gephardt was ahead in his home state
louisiana voters appeared to be split among jackson, dukakis and gore, and oklahoma was a three-way contest among dukakis, gore and gephardt
when the survey was conducted feb. 17-28, dole was running even with bush only in missouri and maryland. in the next-closest states of arkansas and rhode island, he was a little more than 10 percentage points behind bush
the newspaper said the poll results had ``varying margins of error,'' but did not provide them
a pop-up scarecrow and a snowplow-proof mailbox were just some of the gizmos displayed at the second-annual north dakota inventors congress
peter konzak of devils lake rummaged through the clutter of his briefcase and found a letter to prove his scarecrow has already earned him some attention
i am still invited to the johnny carson show. it is a standing invitation,'' the 66-year-old retired farmer said
forty inventors and manufacturers, most of them from north dakota, showed off their gadgets and thingamajigs at the show, which ended tuesday
the hinged mailbox was devised by a minot man after a neighbor complained about his mailbox getting knocked down by snowplows each winter
konzak's pride and joy stood at one side of his booth on the floor of the jamestown civic center. it's a steel contraption wearing fluorescent work gloves that sports a dummy's head adorned with a cowboy hat. a battery and propane tank give it life
in a sunflower field, the clumsy-looking ``pest-scaring device'' jumps up, twirls and whistles to keep blackbirds from feasting on the seeds, konzak said monday
all you need is one on 40 acres,'' he said. ``with the buzzer in here and all the stuff, it can pay for itself in one year.''
since receiving a patent for his mechanical scarecrow in april 1986, konzak has made about 30 of them and sold them all at about $500 apiece, he said
but he said he hasn't made any money yet. ``i've just made my expenses. i put $20,000 into patenting this thing.''
when guam gov. joseph f. ada checked out of a washington hotel earlier this week, the hotel declined to take a guam government check for payment of room charges
the hotel management said it couldn't accept the check because guam is a foreign country,'' ada said tuesday during a stop in honolulu on the way home
we told them that guam is a u.s. territory where america's day begins.''
guam long has been an unincorporated u.s. territory in the western pacific, about 3,800 miles west of hawaii
they said they would give me credit because i was attending the national governors association meeting,'' he said. ``what the hotel didn't realize is that they will receive the same government check for payment.''
the president of connecticut's third-largest bank is trading his pin stripes for dancing tights to help promote corporate support of the arts
david carson, 53, president and chief executive officer of people's bank in bridgeport, will play the role of the duke of courland in the ballet ``giselle,'' to be performed march 11-12 by the connecticut ballet theater in stamford
the production also will feature stephanie saland, principal dancer with the new york city ballet
the bank has supported the theater, but i think you can support the arts with not just money, but with your presence, too,'' said carson
the ballet was looking for ``a very regal type of person,'' and it decided to approach carson, said brett raphael, the company's artistic director
it occurred to me that this was natural casting if possible, however far-fetched,'' raphael said. ``it's not every day a corporate personality takes time out of his schedule to dabble in a very different art form.''
said carson, ``it appealed to my sense of humor, and if it helps give the ballet some recognition, that's great.''
carson will do some mime and walk to music, rather than dance. but, he asked, ``when does walking in time become dancing?''
the post office today began delivering mail bearing the postmark ``jesus is alive!'' throughout britain, a move that jews, humanists, the national secular society and others called offensive to other beliefs
it is absolutely outrageous,'' said martin horwood, spokesman for the british humanist association, a national organization for the non-religious
imagine the furor if we had asked to have `jesus is dead' printed on hundreds of millions of letters. we might think these things privately, but they should not be forced on everybody else in such an insensitive way,'' he said
horwood said he is writing to post office chairman sir brian nicholson asking for the postmark to be withdrawn
christian evangelist paul slennet privately financed the arrangement with the post office. slennet, 41, sells christian literature at two bookstores in southend-on-sea, east of london. he said god told him to buy the postmark
the six-week arrangement runs through good friday, april 1, when christians mourn the crucifixion of jesus christ and easter sunday, april 3, when they celebrate his resurrection
slennet was quoted by the daily telegraph as saying he was convinced ``the lord will speak to the nation'' through the scheme, which he said was designed to mark easter
we are not trying to offend people in any way,'' the paper quoted slennet as saying
but shimon cohen, spokesman for lord jakobovits, the chief rabbi of britain, said: ``it could well cause offense and resentment. we've made our feelings known to the post office.''
the state-run post office began using the postmark on mail tuesday and the first deliveries of mail bearing it began today
barbara smoker, president of the national secular society, said she was enraged by the slogan, which she condemned as insensitive ``propaganda.''
press reports quoted ms. smoker, 64, as saying that 26 percent of britain's 56 million population are atheists or agnostics and that the society exists to defend their rights
ms. smoker was quoted as saying she plans to retaliate by stamping her own slogan ``jesus is a myth'' on every envelope she mails
post office spokesman duncan marshall said: ``the printing of this slogan in no way confirms post office approval of its contents. the slogan is not considered to be contentious but a fair and reasonable message generally acceptable to the public.''
the post office said slennet, who belongs to an evangelical group called intercessors for britain, paid $88,500 for the privilege of having every letter mailed through 68 of britain's 69 sorting offices stamped postmark ``jesus is alive!''
the 69th office, in plymouth, is already booked for a slogan celebrating england's defeat of the spanish armada in 1588
the deal includes mail sent abroad but excludes parcels, periodicals and mail stamped by businesses that do their own franking. nearly 52 million letters are mailed daily in britain
the post office said it considers each private application for a postmark slogan on its merits. revenue-boosting private-slogan postmarks usually urge support for health-research charities and other worthy causes. the postmark before the ``jesus is alive!'' slogan was a post office message reading ``pass on your postcode.''
cohen said the chief rabbi's office was ``flooded with phone calls'' after news of the slogan appeared tuesday
we recognize that this is a christian country and we have the utmost respect for the primacy for the church,'' cohen told the associated press. but he added: ``we do fear that the slogan ... is by implication addressed to non-christians and could well cause offense and resentment.''
rabbi charles emmanuel, chairman of the assembly of rabbis of the reform movement of great britain, told the ap: ``to me it is simply a question of not only an infringement of my personal rights but of my religious rights.''
but the united kingdom islamic mission, a group representing moslems, was quoted by the guardian newspaper as saying of the ``jesus is alive!'' postmark: ``there is no problem for us.''
cocaine now is the most visible target in the war on drugs, a battle that a congressional report says is costing society tens of billions of dollars a year in lost wages, law enforcement outlays and treatment programs
a study of recent changes in the drug trade by the general accounting office, the investigative arm of congress, said, ``cocaine has emerged as the widely abused drug of greatest concern.''
marijuana use has been declining, the report said, while various substances known as designer drugs have emerged as a significant phenomenon
some highlights of ``controlling drug abuse: a status report,'' include:
_in 1983 alone, drugs cost american society some $59.7 billion in crime, lost employment, criminal justice spending, prisons, reduced productivity and treatment programs
_the number of cocaine-related emergencies reported by hospitals jumped 167 percent from 1983 to 1986
_the share of high school seniors who admitted ever having used cocaine fell from 16.9 percent in 1986 to 15.2 percent in 1987. however, some experts fear this may not include all those using the newly popular ``crack'' form of cocaine, which is smoked and is highly popular among young people
_heroin seems to be widely available across the country. the number of heroin-related hospital emergencies rose 24 percent from 1983 to 1986
_marijuana use has declined, although it remains the most widely used illegal drug in the country. an estimated 61.9 million people over age 12 have used this drug at least once
_los angeles is the cocaine consumption capital of the nation, although pcp and heroin are also popular and it's a transshipment point for mexican heroin
_miami is the cocaine importation center, with many homicides related to the drug trade. the spread of the disease aids is being added to by the use of drug needles
_new york has become a center for the importation of heroin and has the nation's largest heroin addict population with the spread of aids also a major problem. the new york heroin trade is dominated by chinese immigrants
_san francisco faces a major problem with lsd and methamphetamines, with growing use of heroin and cocaine
_cocaine availability has increased sharply in washington, d.c., where pcp also is used heavily. a high per capita overdose rate is reported in the nation's capital
_chicago too is facing rising cocaine use
mayor thomas vezzetti, the badly dressed bootlegger's son who took to the streets with a bullhorn to win elections and fight the gentrification of this hudson river city, died early today. he was 59
vezzetti died of a heart attack at st. mary hospital shortly after midnight, police said
vezzetti, a lifelong bachelor, was said to have been angry tuesday night by the outcome of a special election in the 5th ward. a councilman who frequently criticized vezzetti's policies won a special election over a candidate supported by the mayor
officials said that at about 11 p.m. tuesday neighbors heard vezzetti fall in his apartment and they called for an ambulance
city business administrator edwin chius said city council would meet later today to choose a successor to head this city of 42,000
before vezzetti's election to public office, he had developed a reputation as an eccentric, sometimes wearing mismatched shoes, orange pants and a hawaiian shirt. his face was often unshaven and he sometimes carried his belongings in two paper bags
he also was a political gadfly, showing up at school board and city council meetings, complaining about the waste of taxpayers' money
he took a bullhorn in 1982 and walked up and down washington street, the city's main artery, to announce he was challenging the city council president in the next election
he won, and then used the tactic against mayor steve cappiello in 1985, hitting on the theme of stopping yuppies from sweeping the working and middle class out of the city across the hudson from manhattan
if you want to stay in hoboken, vote for me,'' he often said
he forced cappiello into a runoff, and the mayor questioned vezzetti's mental competence and wardrobe
clothes do not make the man,'' vezzetti said at a campaign debate
and he beat the three-term mayor in a major upset. supporters literally carried him to city hall
his longtime motto was ``it's not that i'm so good. it's just that they're so bad.''
thomas jefferson vezzetti and his twin sister, louise, were born in 1928
he once described his father as a ``bootlegger'' who owned five saloons. the mayor's mother was an heiress to a peanuts and dried fruits fortune
that's where i get my campaign money from,'' vezzetti once told new jersey monthly
he was one of a kind,'' said police chief george crimmins. ``it'll be a long time before he can be replaced.''
caroline kennedy schlossberg, daughter of the late president john f. kennedy, is expecting a baby, the daily news reported today
a photograph of an obviously pregnant ms. schlossberg, who married artist-author edwin schlossberg in july 1986, appeared in today's editions
the news did not say when the baby is due
ms. schlossberg, 30, was photographed monday arriving at the equitable building in manhattan to give a speech in place of her uncle, sen. edward kennedy, d-mass., who had been sidelined by a bad back
the baby would be the first grandchild for jacqueline kennedy onassis, who is 58. mrs. onassis' son, 27-year-old john kennedy, is unmarried
a condominium association rejected an attempt by a blind man to move in because of his disability, the man says
i was offended, insulted and hurt,'' larry tomacek, 35, said from his parents' home in nearby delray beach. ``i'm still trying to understand this. i'm a responsible adult and generally a good neighbor
if i was some scum off the street, i'd understand,'' said tomacek, adding that he is mobile
but the kenwick ``b'' condominium association of century village sent a letter to apartment owner donald finck saying members voted unanimously to reject tomacek ``because the applicant ... unfortunately is blind.''
his presence here would pose some very serious problems to all the owners here,'' the letter said
tomacek, who supports himself on social security and disability benefits, suffers from retinitis pigmentosa, a degenerative disease that destroys the retina of the eye cell by cell
i was very distressed,'' finck said. ``you can't do that. it's discrimination. (tomacek) is entitled to live wherever he wants.''
jim green, legal director for the american civil liberties union in florida, and harry mcgee, regional manager for the state division of the blind services, agreed that the association's letter indeed was discriminatory
florida law prohibits discrimination in housing on the basis of physical impairment, green said
should charges be filed, a conviction on the second-degree misdemeanor carries a maximum 60-day jail sentence and $500 fine
condo association president david cohen declined to comment on the matter
tomacek said he no longer wanted to rent the apartment
with neighbors like that, who would need enemies?'' he said
bands of teen-agers taunted police and erected barricades in the capital's streets today as a 36-hour nationwide general strike protesting parliamentary elections got under way
police and paramilitary troops patrolled the city's streets, which were nearly empty of traffic, and guarded main intersections
shops and businesses were shuttered and most bus, train and ferry service was canceled. government offices were closed because authorities had declared today and thursday, the day of the elections, holidays
major opposition parties called the strike in an attempt to disrupt the balloting, which they are boycotting and claim will be rife with fraud. voters are to choose bangladesh's fourth parliament in 17 years of independence
president hussain muhammad ershad announced the elections in december when he dissolved parliament in an effort to end an opposition campaign seeking his ouster that began nov. 10
ershad, a 58-year-old former army general, seized power in this nation of 105 million people in a 1982 bloodless coup. he was elected president in 1986 in balloting the opposition said was rigged
dhaka was generally calm this morning, but small groups of youths briefly stoned police in some parts of the city during the afternoon
four people were reported admitted to dhaka medical college hospital suffering minor injuries from homemade bombs
youths stopped a municipal garbage truck, smashed it with sticks and clubs and set it ablaze. downtown, protesters threw up barricades of broken bricks, which riot police later removed
on a street across from police headquarters, a police van was briefly stoned, but there was no confrontation between attackers and police
near the city's main bus station, a band of about 70 youths marched through the streets chanting ``strike, strike.''
police in riot helmets watched from trucks. the government also called in 9,000 soldiers to guard against election-day violence
the mainstream opposition of 21 parties is boycotting the balloting, but between eight and 102 political parties are vying for parliament's 300 seats
the two main opposition leaders, sheik hasina of the awami league and khaleda zia, warned that thursday's vote would trigger more bloodshed
pre-election violence has claimed at least eight lives, including that of a candidate who was gunned down by suspected anti-government protesters
during feb. 10 local elections, more than 100 people were killed, by government count. the unofficial estimate is as high as 500
since the campaign seeking ershad's ouster began, at least 25 people have been killed in police clashes with mobs
a moderate earthquake hit the south flank of kilauea but was unrelated to the volcano's continuing eruption that began five years ago, scientists said
there were no reports of injuries or damage from tuesday night's quake, according to police
the temblor measured 4.5 on the richter scale, said paul delaney, a geologist at the u.s. geological survey's hawaiian volcano observatory,
the earthquake, which struck at 10:42 p.m. (3:42 a.m. est today), was centered six miles below the surface of the volcano to the southwest of where lava has been pouring from the earth since the summer of 1986, delaney said
the quake was not strong enough to generate a pacific-wide tsunami, or tidal wave, according to the pacific tsunami warning center in honolulu
it didn't even rattle the china,'' delaney said
the volcano on hawaii island began erupting jan. 3, 1983, although some early phases were marked by the underground movement of lava
the richter scale is a measure of ground motion as recorded on seismographs
an earthquake of 3.5 on the richter scale can cause slight damage in the local area, 4 moderate damage, 5 considerable damage, 6 severe damage
vietnam has begun urging the united states to play a larger role in southeast asia and to work for a settlement of the conflict in cambodia, four u.s. scholars said after returning from two weeks in vietnam
three said the push indicated that vietnam was changing and wanted to improve relations with the united states
the fourth said vietnam was just putting into practice the old chinese proverb: ``using barbarians to control barbarians.''
the four china specialists spoke at a briefing tuesday sponsored by the henry luce foundation, which supported their trip from dec. 29 to jan. 11
in all, seven american ``china hands'' took part in the trip, which included stays in hanoi and ho chi minh city, once known as saigon, and talks with high-ranking vietnamese officials
helen chauncey, a professor of history at georgetown university, said america's preoccupation with its loss of the vietnam war and with the pow-mia issue was hampering its ability to respond to a changing vietnam
we have to stop letting the past determine our actions in the region,'' agreed brantly womack, a professor of political science at northern illinois university
jonathan pollack, of the rand corporation, was not as optimistic about the changes in vietnam or about the prospects for peace in indochina
pollack contended that the fighting in cambodia was still a ``sideshow'' in a larger struggle between the soviet union and its ally vietnam against china. it will remain the scene of violence until the larger powers can sort out their problems, he said
frederic wakeman jr., a history professor at the university of california, berkeley, said he was impressed by changing vietnamese society, citing beatles songs played on a flight from hanoi and the raffish tilt of berets on the heads of communist party officials
we were astonished again and again by the candor of the vietnamese,'' wakeman said. ``intellectuals, officials, party members were all very open.''
as a china scholar, wakeman said, he was particularly interested in the entrepreneurial spirit of the ethnic chinese in ho chi minh city
we had the sense in saigon of a commercial economy waiting to break loose,'' he said
chauncey and womack said a combination of circumstances has given america a chance for a new beginning in vietnam
for the first time, womack said, vietnamese officials, including foreign minister and vice premier nguyen co thach, are talking with eagerness about leaving cambodia
vietnam invaded cambodia in december 1978, kicked out the chinese-backed khmer rouge and installed a puppet government in phnom penh
about 140,000 vietnamese troops remain in cambodia fighting a resistance coalition headed by prince norodom sihanouk that is backed by china, the united states and the free-market countries of southeast asia
but last year, sihanouk split with the coalition and began direct negotiations with hun sen, prime minister of the vietnamese-backed government
chauncey said the negotiations, supported by vietnam, were a sign that vietnam wants to end the conflict
vietnamese officials told me they want the united states to play an active role in negotiations to bring peace to cambodia,'' she said
vietnam also is trying to boost its economy, in which the average annual income is about $125. as such, it has recognized the need for foreign exchange and investment from the west
wakeman said he believed vietnam wants an increased u.s. presence to counterbalance chinese interests in southeast asia
in part, it's a very old diplomatic tactic of using the barbarians to control the barbarians,'' he said
chauncey said the united states must reassert itself in southeast asia
if it doesn't, we will be left behind in what will be a realignment of political and economic forces,'' she said
prices were mixed on the london stock exchange early today
the financial times-stock exchange 100-share index was 7.5 points, or 0.42 percent, higher at 1,789.4 by midmorning. the index opened at 1,783.2, up 1.3 points from tuesday's close
the rise was mainly due to gains by insurance shares, which were marked up after commercial union, a major british insurer, announced a better-than-expected 43 percent rise in pre-tax profits for 1987, brokers said
west coast members of the writers guild of america almost certainly voted to authorize a strike against movie and television producers, a former guild president said
the vote was taken tuesday night in hollywood by secret ballot, and results were not expected to be announced until thursday. the 9,000-member union also includes 2,500 east coast members who were scheduled to vote this afternoon
the guild's contract expired at 12:01 a.m. tuesday
union negotiators said a replacement contract offered by the alliance of motion picture and television producers was calculated to force a strike. the negotiators unanimously urged members to reject the offer and vote instead for a strike authorization, said cheryl rhoden, a guild spokeswoman
she said 2,400 ballots were cast tuesday night
the former guild president, mel shavelson, said that judging from the sentiments he heard expressed during the balloting, ``i don't think there was any doubt as to what the vote was.''
while a strike could begin as early as thursday, shavelson said it was unlikely a walkout would be called immediately
a strike could have an immediate impact on talk shows and soap operas, which use scripts daily and without much lead time. prime-time programs and feature films would be affected only by a longer strike
negotiators for the two sides met for just two hours before quitting tuesday afternoon
the brief meeting followed a 21-hour session that lasted until 7:15 a.m. tuesday and made progress on ``25 to 30 lesser issues,'' said herb steinberg, spokesman for the producers
steinberg and ms. rhoden said three major stumbling blocks remained. the writers are seeking more ``creative rights'' to control what happens to their scripts and higher payments when programs are distributed in foreign markets. the producers want to give writers reduced payments for domestic syndication of one-hour television programs, a shrinking market
the entertainment writers last went on strike three years ago. the walkout lasted two weeks before writers voted to accept a package offering them essentially the same terms as one they had earlier rejected
the median annual income for guild writers is $40,000, but about half of the members are unemployed at any given time, the union says
five thousand troops from half the nato countries were airlifted to the mountains and valleys of northern norway in a show of unity as leaders of the alliance gathered in brussels at a major strategy conference
u.s. transport planes on tuesday ferried in the combat units for the maneuvers, code-named ``arrowhead express,'' which climaxes in two weeks in a battle on snow-covered terrain against an ``enemy'' of 9,500 norwegian forces
the exercise mobilized the allied command europe mobile force, a brigade designed to rush to areas of potential conflict with the soviet-led warsaw pact
the maneuvers were clearly intended to serve political more than military aims, and to demonstrate the cohesion of the north atlantic treaty organization
our operational role is in peacetime, to show as many flags with as much visibility as possible in a threatened area to deter an aggressor,'' said british maj. don mclaren
if we reach the combat stage, we've failed,'' he said in a telephone interview tuesday from command headquarters in bardufoss, 1,000 miles north of oslo
although not officially tied to the summit, the exercise dovetails with president reagan's recent efforts to reassure u.s. allies of the american commitment to defend europe at the same time that it negotiates arms reductions with the soviet union
the war games also coincide with mounting norwegian concern that nato's flank in the north atlantic will become more active following the u.s.-soviet agreement to dismantle intermediate-range nuclear weapons
the inf agreement has made the norwegian and the barents seas more important,'' kaare willoch, chairman of the norwegian parliament's foreign affairs committee, said tuesday
the soviet union has built the world's greatest concentration of firepower on the kola peninsula adjacent to norway's northern border
willoch, a former conservative prime minister, said in an interview that the soviet buildup in the north had been going on for decades and had shown no signs of slackening since the disarmament accord was signed in december
the buildup proceeds. it necessitates nato countermeasures,'' while negotiations continue on further arms reduction accords, he said
the soviet northern fleet, armed with submarine-launched, long-range nuclear weapons, must pass norway to reach the atlantic fire zone, the closest point of deployment to the united states for soviet missiles
norway's northwestern coast, kept ice-free all year by the warmth of the gulf stream, also becomes more attractive to the soviets as naval warfare grows in importance in soviet military strategy, norwegian analysts say
one war scenario foresees the soviets slicing off norway's remote and nearly unpopulated northern province, challenging nato's willingness to respond. that is precisely the kind of action the allied command europe mobile force was formed in 1960 to deter, mclaren said
arrowhead express, commanded by norwegian vice admiral torolf rein, involves forces from eight of nato's 16 countries: the united states, canada, west germany, italy, luxembourg, the netherlands, britain and norway
the u.s. role in arrowhead express is limited to air support, since its units are not trained for arctic warfare. much of the maneuvering will be done on skis or snowmobiles, mclaren said
the force holds maneuvers twice a year, once in norway or denmark and once along an isolated region of nato's southern flank in turkey, greece or italy
neighbors and police worked frantically but failed to save an elderly man who was buried alive by cinder blocks when he tried to demolish a 5-foot-high wall in his yard
edward margrabia, 69, died tuesday of multiple trauma at pembroke pines hospital
he was just crushed, his kidneys and everything. oh, i tell you, it was awful,'' said neighbor ann adelson. ``poor man. he's a terrific guy. he helps everybody in the neighborhood.''
chris mccauley, whose home is behind margrabia's, said she heard the wall collapse as she fixed sandwiches for lunch
i just heard a sound like cement blocks hitting the ground ... i thought it was strange to hear a noise and see nobody there,'' she said. when she realized what had happened, she roused other neighbors to help extricate margrabia
by the time we had eight people there, we were trying to pry the wall up with pieces of wood. and as we were trying, the wall broke _ right on his back,'' ms. mccauley said
when police arrived to free margrabia with a hydraulic jack, he was unconscious, police spokesman ed plaisted said. margrabia, who was recovering from heart-bypass surgery, was trapped for about 30 minutes
a military court sentenced two polish journalists to prison after convicting them of selling information to western intelligence agencies, a government spokesman said
mariusz dastych, 46, and tadeusz podwysocki, 56, both formerly worked for the official government daily newspaper rzeczpospolita and were arrested last april on spying charges. both reported on poland's economy
a warsaw military court on monday sentenced dastych to eight years in prison after finding him guilty of selling information since 1973 to the cia on poland's ``socio-political situation,'' government spokesman jerzy urban said. the court also fined dastych $790 and ordered the confiscation of all his property, said urban, speaking at his weekly news conference tuesday
podwysocki received a 1{-year prison sentence because the court accepted his defense that he was ``unaware that information he had communicated was used for intelligence purposes,'' urban said
podwysocki, one of poland's best-known economic reporters, also was barred from working as a journalist for two years, fined $530 and ordered to pay back all the western currency he had received for the information. urban did not specify how much the journalists received for selling the information
urban said dastych and podwysocki had cooperated with ``representatives of another western intelligence service,'' which he would not name
he refused to confirm or deny reports that the second country involved was japan. according to western press reports, they were accused of passing trade secrets to japan
three boys held a gun to the head of a 9-year-old to rob her of the dollar bill her grandmother had given her to buy an ice cream cone, police and the child said
a 10-year-old boy pressed the gun to latarra william's temple and told her, ``put it down, put it down now or i'll blow you head off,'' the girl said tuesday, a day after the robbery
the 10-year-old and his two 12-year-old companions were apprehended tuesday and were carrying 12 rocks of crack cocaine, $4 and a starter's pistol, which doesn't fire bullets, said police spokeswoman connie ryan
the boys were held overnight in the broward county juvenile detention center, each charged with armed robbery and possession of cocaine, she said
after the robbery, the girl ran home to her grandmother, who called the police
