nuclear waste shipments from the crippled three mile island plant will be temporarily halted while the department of energy completes its investigation into a rail switching incident in the st. louis area, according to sen. john danforth
meanwhile, rep. jack buechner, r-mo., has introduced legislation that would require casks used by the doe to ship radioactive waste to meet safety standards set by the nuclear regulatory commission
danforth, r-mo., said tuesday the doe has agreed to stop the shipments from pennsylvania to a laboratory in idaho falls, idaho, until the investigation is completed. he said he didn't know how long the probe would take to complete
danforth, ranking minority member of the senate commerce, science and transportation committee, last week requested the investigation into whether there were violations of rail regulations feb. 9 when a mislabeled car was added to a conrail train carrying casks of radioactive wastes
the covered hopper car carried a placard stating it contained a flammable material, federal railroad administration spokesman bill loftus said last week. it was later discovered the car was not carrying the dangerous cargo
loftus said the investigation is looking at possible violations by the rail switching yard and the union pacific railroad, which operated the train after it left the yard, and a lime company that was shipping the car
danforth said tuesday the doe had agreed to allow the department of transportation to make a complete study of the routes used to transport the tmi material. the energy department has done such studies in the past but has always concluded that the route from pennsylvania to idaho was the best
a request by danforth not to move rail shipments in the st. louis area between the hours of 6:30 a.m. to 9:30 a.m. and 3:30 p.m. and 6:30 p.m. _ commuter rush hours _ also was agreed to by the doe
other agreements by the doe included a promise not to add cars to tmi trains along the route. the trains, which leave pennsylvania under conrail power, will continue to switch to union pacific when necessary but no cars will be added, danforth said
as a way to minimize the total number of shipments, all future shipments will be consolidated into three casks, danforth said
according to a statement by danforth's office, other agreements made by the doe include:
_ union pacific will assign a certified hazardous materials inspector at the east st. louis, ill., yard to assist with mechanical inspections and managers will be assigned at crew change points, inspection points and en route to monitor speed and times of day schedules through st. louis
_ the doe will post a health physicist on each tmi train
_ an fra official will accompany each tmi train to monitor speed, schedules and track and equipment. the energy department also will provide additional emergency response training to st. louis and state officials
buechner's legislation, introduced monday, would remove an exemption that allows the doe to make nuclear waste shipments without nrc safety inspections
the energy department has contended that casks it uses to ship radioactive waste and spent nuclear fuels, including the tmi shipments, will withstand even the most extraordinary transportion accident
a jetliner returned to kennedy airport after a passenger was found in a lavatory with crack and equipment to burn it for ``freebasing,'' authorities said
the man and a companion who was standing outside were arrested tuesday by federal agents who happened to be aboard, said robert stutman, head of the drug enforcement administration's new york office
a flight attendant who smelled ether discovered the man in the lavatory, along with about a quarter-ounce of crack, a torch, ether and butane, stutman said. the man outside also had crack in his possession, he said
this could have produced a real tragedy,'' stutman said. ``ether is an extremely volatile, explosive substance when it is near flames.''
richard moskowitz and jeff tofler were arrested on charges that included possession of cocaine and interference with a flight, stutman said. they were turned over to the fbi upon landing, he said
about 98 passengers were aboard eastern airlines flight 977, which left kennedy at 1:35 p.m. and was scheduled to arrive in miami at 4:24 p.m., said karen ceremsak, an airline spokeswoman
when the pilot learned about the alleged drug activity, he notified a dea agent and a u.s. customs agent who were on board to attend a trial in miami, stutman said
the ages and hometowns of the suspects were not immediately known
a powdered form of cocaine, not crack, a potent derivative, is usually used in freebasing, a process in which the powder is mixed with ether and then heated so the fumes can be inhaled, stutman said
he said there was no damage to the aircraft
a sri lankan soldier opened fire with a semi-automatic rifle and killed seven sleeping comrades before he was shot to death by his commander, military officials said today
nine other soldiers were wounded in the tuesday night attack at an army camp next to a steel mill 10 miles southeast of colombo, they said
the attacker was a member of the people's liberation front, an ultra-nationalist sinhalese group that has raided several military camps to steal weapons, the officials said
the officials, who by regulation cannot be identified, said the attack was designed to kill as many soldiers as possible and to steal weapons. they said all the victims were sinhalese, the majority ethnic group that controls the government and military in sri lanka
the officials were unable to explain why the assailant risked making so much noise by gunning down fellow soldiers if the purpose of the attack was to collect weapons and escape
a vehicle had arrived at the scene to enable the attacker to make his getaway, they said, but the escape was foiled when the commanding officer heard the shooting, rushed to the scene and killed the soldier
the driver escaped in the vehicle, the officials said
neither the soldier nor his commander was identified, but the officials said they both served in a signal corps unit
according to the officials, similar attacks have occurred in the past but this was the largest number of soldiers ever killed by a fellow soldier
the government has blamed the people's liberation front for the assassinations of at least 150 government officials and supporters since july 29, when sri lanka signed a peace accord designed to end a 4-year-old separatist war by tamil guerrillas
the front says the accord makes too many concessions to the minority tamils and has vowed to kill anyone who supports the pact
military officials said last winter that front had about 4,000 supporters in the 45,000-man army
india mediated the peace accord last summer and it now has 45,000 peackeeping troops in the island
tamils, who are mostly hindus and comprise 18 percent of sri lanka's 16 million people, want a separate homeland, claiming they are discriminated against by the majority sinhalese buddhists
experts have started conducting tests to determine how to repair the sphinx, the ancient monument that lost a chunk of stone from its right shoulder
the limestone slab fell from the sphinx feb. 7, six days after a sandstorm buffeted giza plateau
damage to the sphinx caused heated political and scientific debate over the future of the 4,600-year-old monument and egypt's other ancient treasures
the main casualty of the unrest was ahmed kadry, until early february chairman of the egyptian antiquities organization
kadry lost his job after accusing his boss, culture minister farouk hosni, of staging the rock fall to reflect badly on kadry's stewardship of the sphinx and, by extension, the other relics of egypt's rich past
restoration work began on the sphinx on monday
the monument was fitted with sandbags for support and scaffolding to help in the early stages of the effort
a committee of experts took rock samples to test for salt content and damage and to see whether the stone is strong enough to hold iron bars that will be inserted to strengthen it
tests also are being conducted to determine what kind of mortar should be used to cement the rock in place
we're not in a hurry. we want to do things right,'' said zahi hawass, general director of the pyramids area and director of the restoration
the sphinx has the head of a pharaoh and the body of a crouching lion. many egyptologists think the face belonged to chephren, son of cheops and builder of the second pyramid on giza plateau next to cheops' great pyramid
any damage to the pyramids or the sphinx _ symbols of the past with deep emotional overtones for modern egyptians _ brings instant outcries in cairo's national press. the rock fall proved no exception, to kadry's chagrin, and charges of incompetence and corruption flooded the newspapers. pickup.</note>
vietnam today repatriated what it believes are the remains of 17 american servicemen listed as missing in action from the vietnam war, a u.s. military official said
the vietnamese also turned over written reports on three other missing americans, said lt. col. paul mather, head of the u.s. military team that flew to hanoi to receive the remains
the remains were flown to the army's central identification laboratory in honolulu for analysis after a brief turnover ceremony at hanoi's noi bai airport
the repatriation was the fourth largest since the war ended in april 1975 with a communist victory over the u.s.-backed south vietnam government. the largest was in august 1985, involving 26 sets of remains
earlier reports that 20 remains were to be returned today resulted from a misunderstanding in communications from hanoi, said mather, the head of the bangkok office of the u.s. joint casualty resolution center
the center, based in hawaii, is entrusted with resolving the fates of nearly 1,800 americans listed as missing in action, or mia
mather said some of the 17 remains and three cases on which written reports were received were on a list of 70 high priority cases that u.s. presidential envoy and retired gen. john w. vessey jr. gave the vietnamese during his mission to hanoi last august
the united states says that in these so-called ``discrepancy cases,'' there is strong evidence the vietnamese know what happened to the missing men, including photographs of them taken after their capture
mather said each set of remains was accompanied by a written report containing such information as the area where the remains were found, and what people there said about them. he said the vietnamese also turned over identification cards and ``dog tags'' _ military identification tags which servicemen wear around their necks
mather said the remains were placed in metal transfer cases and loaded onto a c-141 transport plane for the flight to honolulu. a u.s. honor guard saluted as each case, draped with a folded u.s. flag, was loaded during the half-hour ceremony, he said
a high proportion of remains returned by vietnam after a preliminary analysis are later confirmed by the u.s. army laboratory as those of mias
mather also announced that the vietnamese have set march 12 as the starting date for the next round of ``technical talks'' on mias
during these talks, which hanoi has agreed to hold six times annually, experts on both sides discuss ways of retrieving remains, locating warplane crash sites and related issues
today's turnover was the third since hanoi agreed during vessey's visit to break a long deadlock and resume efforts to account for the missing men
the united states pledged then to look into vietnam's own humanitarian concerns, and an official u.s. medical team flew into hanoi today to continue that mission, said the spokesman of the u.s. embassy in bangkok, ross petzing
it was the fourth visit by a u.s. medical team. the teams have been studying the plight of disabled war veterans and other humanitarian cases and made recommendations on how private u.s. charitable organizations can aid rehabilitation programs
petzing said the team included dr. bruce van dam, an orthopedic surgeon at the walter reed army medical center in washington, d.c.; frederick downs, the director of the prosthetics and sensory aids service of the veterans administration; and laurence kerr, the state department's desk officer for vietnam
the vietnamese have said they prefer direct u.s. government aid, but washington has refused because of its embargo on aid to protest vietnam's occupation of cambodia. grafs to correct pleas of boesky and davidoff.</note>
a millionaire stock trader charged with intending to shoot financier ivan boesky has been ordered held without bail by a judge who rejected arguments that jail would harm the trader's mental health
john a. mulheren, 38, of rumson appeared tuesday before u.s. magistrate john c. manna to face two charges of attempting to tamper with a federal witness. he was transferred to a federal prison in new york city
the magistrate scheduled a friday bail hearing over the objections of mulheren's attorney, peter bennett, who said his client suffered manic-depression
a manic-depressive such as my client back on lithium for the last five days is not a risk to himself or others,'' bennett told the judge. ``jail is detrimental to his condition. he's far better off in a private care clinic.''
bennett said mulheren was on a ``manic-crash'' the day authorities allege he intended to shoot boesky
authorities contend mulheren pulled out of his riverfront estate feb. 18 with a high-powered assault rifle and army fatigues in the back seat of his car after police had confiscated three other weapons from him
he intended to shoot boesky, 50, of new york and boesky's former chief stock trader, michael davidoff, 43, of manalapan township, according to a new jersey complaint
before the federal hearing tuesday, state superior court judge alvin y. milberg released mulheren from the county jail where he was being held on the state charges
mulheren was arrested immediately afterward by four u.s. marshals, flanked by an investigator from the u.s. attorney's office in the southern district of new york and a federal attorney from new jersey, authorities said
mulheren had been held in the county jail in lieu of $17,500 bail on two weapons charges that carry a total maximum of 15 years in prison
bennett told the magistrate that mulheren was not bailed out of the county jail for 12 days because his manic-depressive condition precluded him from cooperating with attorneys on a defense. bennett asked that bail be set at tuesday's hearing
however, manna ruled in favor of terrence flynn, an assistant u.s. attorney who said he needed more time to prepare his case
boesky, once a close friend of mulheren's, and davidoff pleaded guilty last year to a single count of securities fraud and have cooperated with the government's continuing investigation of insider trading on wall street
boesky paid a fine of $100 million to the securities and exchange commission to settle civil charges of insider trading, and will begin serving a three-year prison term march 24. davidoff faces a five-year term when sentenced
mulheren is a friend of rock star bruce springsteen. the singer, also of rumson, visited mulheren in the county jail saturday during a break in his national concert tour, monmouth county sheriff william m. lanzaro confirmed monday. picks up pvs 10th graf bgng, fitzwater told; deletes last 5 grafs to tighten.</note>
president reagan and 15 other allied leaders today began their first summit talks since 1982 in a bid to underscore the unity of the western alliance despite differences over nuclear arms strategy
reagan, the last of the leaders to arrive at sprawling nato headquarters, made no comment as he passed a crowd of reporters and diplomats for the first summit session, but nato secretary general lord carrington stressed the cohesion of the alliance
carrington said the summit will provide nato ``with sustained impetus...in a way which will reflect the fundamental solidarity which unites us in trans-atlantic partnership.''
looking toward soviet-american arms talks, carrington said an improved soviet human rights record was fundamental to creating ``the confidence necessary to proceed with a radical arms control agenda.''
he added: ``for most of us in the west that cause (of tension) is the degree of mistrust created by the denial of basic human rights and freedom to the peoples of eastern europe and the soviet union.''
carrington reaffirmed nato's commitment supporting a proposed superpower agreement to reduce long-range nuclear weaponry by 50 percent on both sides. he said nato also looked forward to ``a more serious engagement'' with the soviet-led warsaw pact on a chemical weapons ban and reducing the eastern bloc's superiority in conventional arms
central to the summit talks here was the issue of how to fill the gap left by reagan's agreeement with soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev last december to eliminate ground-launched medium-range nuclear missiles from europe
while the allies agreed on the need to reduce east-west conventional forces, a dispute remained over whether nato members should quickly improve their stocks of short-range nuclear missiles
i don't look for any glossing over at all,'' said canadian prime minister brian mulroney as he arrived for the talks
as the meeting began, white house spokesman marlin fitzwater reported that ``progress is fine'' on drafting a statement of common alliance goals to be issued at the conclusion of the two-day summit
reagan, who reached brussels coughing and complaining of allergies, ws to spend 2 1-2 hours conferring with the 15 other heads of state or government. when he arrived tuesday, the president tried to allay concerns over the warsaw pact's advantage in conventional forces by promising to keep u.s. troops in europe ``as long as europeans want them to stay.''
before the summit talks began over lunch, reagan met privately with secretary of state george shultz on the secretary's recent efforts to get the peace process moving in the middle east
fitzwater told reporters that shultz has been doing ``yeoman's work'' and that united states has made clear it wants a more visible role in the middle east peace process
although fitzwater said no decision had been made, he and other officials indicated reagan is likely to send shultz back to the middle east after the summit
in his afternoon remarks to nato _ a session closed to reporters in the alliance's austere central meeting hall _ the president was to repeat his assurances of the u.s. commitment to the nato democracies and urge them to repel soviet attempts to split the pact
the heads of state and government will discuss ``overall policy and the direction of the alliance _ the big picture,'' fitzwater added
fitzwater said reagan also planned to listen to his colleagues' concerns, particularly about the new round of arms control talks and their worries that american budget restrictions might force cutbacks in the 326,000 u.s. troops stationed in western europe
we also expect them to voice support ... as the president prepares for the moscow summit,'' fitzwater said. a date hasn't been set, but the fourth meeting between reagan and soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev is expected to be held in late may or june
the spokesman said that while the nuts and bolts on issues such as troop strength would be left to lower-level aides, reagan would urge the members to push forward on talks with the east bloc on reducing its edge in conventional forces
now in a preliminary stage in vienna, the discussions over conventional force reductions are expected to begin in earnest this fall
planners on both sides of the atlantic have predicted that no major decisions will result from the nato summit. the leaders are expected to sidestep differences over such issues as modernizing their own short-range nuclear weapons arsenal, and concentrate instead on issuing final statements that emphasize the pact's cohesion and resolve. clouseau; also sent in advance as b0282.</note>
michael caine has just made his eighth film in three years and has a tv miniseries set to roll, but the oscar-winning star of ``sherlock and me'' says he still worries about being out of work
you feel uneasy if you haven't got something to do,'' caine said in an interview in north london's camden town, where the $8.5 million-movie was concluding its nine-week shoot
people say i work all the time, but i don't. what they (distributors) do is always put the bloody things out at the same time.''
the actor's on-screen good cheer has been one of the few constants in the ever-changing hollywood scene
last year, he played sally field's love interest in ``surrender'' and a british intelligence agent in ``the fourth protocol.'' he starred in films as quintessentially american as ``jaws iv _ the revenge,'' and as quintessentially english as ``the whistle blower,'' a political thriller
in 1986 he was a british diplomat romantically linked with call girl sigourney weaver in ``half moon street,'' and had vivid supporting roles in ``sweet liberty'' and ``mona lisa.''
then, too, there was his academy award last year for best supporting actor for his performance in ``hannah and her sisters.'' the erstwhile cockney, who was born maurice joseph micklewhite in 1933, the son of a porter at billingsgate fish market in london, had integrated himself into the bittersweet world of woody allen's manhattan neurotics
i'd known woody for years, and i knew new york so well,'' said caine. ``i don't have a voice which is posh british, anyway
my attitude is that i'm more like an american, coming from a working-class background. lots of americans think i'm australian, or something like that _ crocodile dundee's father.''
caine's previous oscar nominations were for ``alfie'' in 1966, ``sleuth'' in 1972 and ``educating rita'' in 1983
in his new film, he impersonates that celebrated sleuth, sherlock holmes. caine is a boozing, down-on-his-luck actor who is hired by dr. watson to play the famed fictional detective to prove him real
i get to play two parts and a particular hero of mine, which i like, because i've always been a great fan of holmes,'' he said
we have the pipe, the magnifying glass, everything,'' said caine, referring to the traditional holmes accoutrements. ``it's a chance to play a hero who i'm not really right for and to do it in an entirely different way, as a comedy.''
the film, due out in the fall from orion pictures, co-stars oscar winner ben kingsley (``gandhi'') as dr. watson, who is forced by public demand to find a real-life holmes to match the figure he has been writing about in a magazine
caine compared his creation to the part of the inimitable inspector clouseau,, created by the late peter sellers in the popular pink panther series. ``peter would have laughed at some of the physical humor i do. the character is such a putz,'' caine said. ``i'm having fun; i'll tell you that.''
on march 14, caine moves on to his next assignment: a cbs miniseries, ``jack the ripper,'' which marks his first tv work since he played horatio to christopher plummer's hamlet in a 1966 production of shakespeare's tragedy
caine will play the fictitious inspector frederick abberline of scotland yard in the $5 million show
said to be based on confidential police and government files, the show will be aired in the autumn to coincide with the 100th anniversary of the notorious mass murderer, who terrorized victorian london in the late 1880s
caine said he's made a conscious effort to vary his parts and his performances. ``it gives you cachet as someone who can play anything,'' he said
i've been a leading actor, not a movie star who comes on and does the michael caine personality performance like a cary grant or a john wayne, although i admire both of them very much.''
his salary, he joked, reflected this attitude: ``i know a lot of actors like dustin hoffman, jack nicholson, who don't do pictures for years, but they get $6 million, $7 million, $15 million a picture.''
i don't. i get $1.98 and a bollocking (a reprimand) for being late on monday morning,'' he joked. caine is one of the few british actors who reportedly commands around $1 million a movie
caine said the british had reacted oddly to his decision in june 1986 to return to his native country with his wife, the indian model shakira baksh, and their 14-year-old daughter, natasha, after living for nine years in los angeles
people here treat me as if i'd just come back from some fearsome jungle and survived,'' he said. ``americans are just like we are, except they work harder _ that's what frightens the british. you've got to get up at 8 o'clock monday morning and go out and do something; you can't just sit there.''
caine is glad to be home. he divides his time between an apartment in london's elegant knightsbridge and a 15th-century manor house in rural oxfordshire northwest of the capital city
as for the sometimes brutal english class system, caine said it's no problem
years ago, all the people who wouldn't have spoken to me are now people i wouldn't want to speak to because they're so boring,'' he said
i've gone beyond class. i go with anybody, from the queen down.''
police were searching for suspects in the cross burning near the home of a black couple in a racially integrated neighborhood
it was done so quietly that we did not hear a thing,'' mary lomax, 72, said tuesday. ``nothing like this has ever happened here in our lifetime.''
she said her 19-year-old granddaughter, who lives across the street, spotted the cross burning monday night in a lot next to the home mrs. lomax shares with her husband. the cross stood 4{ feet by 6 feet
police said tuesday they had no witnesses
it is an out-of-the way neighborhood and it suggests something local,'' said sgt. angus park. ``we know of no incident that could have triggered the cross burning.''
cross burning is a felony punishable by three years in jail and a $5,000 fine. according to the office of human rights, the last cross burning in howard county occurred in october 1984. four juveniles were arrested
the pilot of the delta airliner that crashed at dallas-fort worth international airport in 1985, killing 137 people, had a pattern of ``use and abuse'' of three tranquilizers, a government lawyer said
attorney roy krieger suggested during his opening statement at a trial to determine liability for the crash that delta capt. edward m. connors might have habitually piloted jetliners under the influence of drugs
krieger told u.s. district judge david o. belew jr., who is presiding over the non-jury trial, that prescription records will show connors took the tranquilizers dalmane in 1978, valium in 1982 and 1984 and stelazine from 1982 to 1985
the records will show ``a clear pattern of use and abuse of these tranquilizers'' over the eight years before the aug. 2, 1985, crash, krieger said
the conclusion is inescapable,'' krieger said. ``he must have been taking them on the days he was flying'' because the prescription quantities were too large to have been taken only when he was off duty
why should the day of the crash be any different than all the other days in the previous years that he was taking tranquilizers,'' krieger said
delta lawyer john martin said during a break in the trial that there is no evidence that connors was using stelazine at the time of the crash. he said too little tissue was recovered from the crash to run tests for drugs other than alcohol. those tests were negative
the medical experts will show (stelazine) is a prescription tranquilizer that would not affect a person's ability to fly anyway,'' martin said. ``there are pilots who fly taking stelazine.''
during his opening statement, martin said negligence on the part of federal aviation administration and national weather service employees caused delta flight 191 to crash
the crew of 191 found themselves in the wrong place at the wrong time'' because none of the government employees did their jobs,'' he said
martin claimed faa controllers and the weather service failed to warn the flight crew of the severity of weather at the airport
a report by the national transportation safety board concluded that the crash was caused, in part, by the pilot's decision to fly the l-1011 widebody jet into a wind shear, a violent downdraft
the trial will determine whether the government must pay part of $91.2 million in claims that delta's insurers have paid so far in the crash
in december, belew ruled that about 90 lawsuits filed by individuals against delta should be parceled out from federal court in fort worth to other federal courts. about half of those suits have been settled
joe besser, a rotund member of the three stooges for two years, was found dead of an undetermined illness at his home, his publicist said. he was 80
he had been ill for some time and wouldn't even see a doctor,'' said publicist jeff lenburg. besser's body was found tuesday by a relative, lenburg said
i go back 50 years with joe besser when i played vaudeville with him,'' said comedian milton berle. ``he was one of a kind. he was very innovative, very creative. he was a darling of a man, very congenial.''
besser joined moe howard and larry fine from 1956 to 1958 and was one of several actors to replace shemp howard as the third stooge
the three stooges specialized in head-knocking, eye-gouging slapstick, pratfalls and endless buffoonery. the trio made more than 190 short films and about 50 feature-length films until the '60s, lenburg said
besser embraced his role, bouncing off his fellow stooges in a schtick that distinguised his character
no matter how light the slap, besser's invariable response was a whining, ``not so h-a-a-a-a-a-r-d.'' the stooges' preposterousness elicited from besser an exasperated, ``ooooh, you crazy.''
the original three stooges, created in the vaudeville days of the 1920s, were morris ``moe'' horowitz, who changed his last name to howard; his brother samuel ``shemp'' horowitz and larry fineberg, who used the stage name fine
by the early 1930s, shemp had left in a pay dispute and was replaced by his brother, jerome howard, known as curly. curly left the team in 1946 after suffering a stroke, and brother shemp came back to replace him. after shemp's death in 1955, he was replaced by besser, who in turn was replaced in 1959 by joe de rita, who played ``curly joe,'' when the trio began making feature films
curly howard died in 1952. moe howard and fine died in 1975. de rita, the last surviving stooge, is 79 and retired, lenburg said
the character of joe became besser's trademark and he added to it in television's ``the abbott and costello show,'' where he played the mean, whining brat ``stinky'' who liked to slap lou around
he appeared on ``the abbott and costello show'' in the 1950s and '60s, along with regular appearances on ``the ken murray show'' and ``the joey bishop show.''
besser made 250 television appearances during his 67-year career, joking with such comics as berle and jerry lewis. he also appeared in more than 40 films
before becoming a stooge, besser worked as a comedian on broadway, on radio and in motion pictures
in the 1940s, his portrayal of an exasperated, whining child earned him a spot in olsen and johnson's long-running broadway show, ``sons o' fun,'' a sequel to their ``hellzapoppin.''
besser called his association with the stooges ``the happiest years of my life in show business.'' he was on hand in 1983 when the three stooges were awarded a star on the hollywood walk of fame
besser is survived by his wife of 56 years, ernie. funeral arrangements were pending
president augusto pinochet said a chain of bombs found at the end of an airport runway were planted by leftist extremists who planned to assassinate him by destroying his plane
authorities disclosed late monday that they had discovered six homemade bombs loaded with plastic explosives and shrapnel at the city airport of la serena on the pacific coast 300 miles north of santiago
attached to each bomb were about 300 sticks of dynamite, according to a communique issued by the civil aviation office
the bombs were buried at the western end of the runway and connected to a 2,000-foot-long detonating cable that ran to a ravine beside the airport
the explosives were discovered on saturday, the communique said
pinochet was to fly to la serena on jan. 29 to appear at an agricultural fair, but canceled the visit at the last minute
on tuesday, during a tour of southern chile, he told reporters there was evidence the bombs were planted in anticipation of his visit
they knew i was going to the north and prepared the explosive material that was found,'' he said during a stop in the town of maullin, 700 miles south of the capital. his remarks were carried by santiago radio stations
he said it was only by chance that he did not travel to la serena. ``there were a series of problems that obliged me to stay in santiago,'' he said
in september 1986, pinochet survived an ambush of his motorcade by a commando of the pro-communist manuel rodriguez front, the country's main lefitst guerrilla organization. five of his bodyguards were kiilled in the attack with machine-gun and rocket fire
pinochet, commander of the army, seized power in a 1973 coup that toppled the elected government of marxist president salvador allende
a molotov cocktail was dropped off a bridge today onto one tugboat and flares were fired at another in violence stemming from a 2-week-old longshoreman's strike, police said
the incendiary device bounced harmlessly off the tugboat, which was towing a gasoline barge, and fell into the east river at 4 a.m., said sgt. raymond o'donnell
about 5:30 a.m., several flares from a flare gun were fired from a pier at a tugboat towing two city sanitation department barges, but missed all three vessels, o'donnell said. the flares were fired from a pier at newtown creek, which empties into the east river and divides the boroughs of brooklyn and queens
late monday, a molotov cocktail was tossed from the queensboro bridge onto a barge unloading 500,000 gallons of gasoline at the amoco oil storage facility. it ignited a small fire that was extinguished quickly and caused only minor damage
police have recorded more than a dozen violent incidents since the strike began feb. 16, including the wounding a week ago of a tugboat captain when shots fired at his boat shattered the glass in the pilot house
negotiations between local 333 of the international longshoremen's association and five of the nine tugboat companies being struck are to resume thursday for the first time since the strike began
at issue are concessions the tugboat companies are demanding from the approximately 2,500 affected tugboat and barge workers
al cornette, local 333 president, said earlier that union members unanimously rejected the companies' demands for the elimination of 750 jobs and for wage and benefit givebacks of up to 62 percent
five companies had locked the workers out and four had not come to terms, cornette said. those firms have been using replacement workers, he said
the union has signed with nine other companies and 10 more had unexpired contracts
mary beth whitehead-gould and her former husband will reportedly receive up to $40,000 in a settlement with the agency that brokered her contract to act as a surrogate mother in the baby m case
the agreement, signed in manhattan by u.s. district judge pierre n. leval, dismisses the case without costs or attorneys' fees, but does not reveal terms of the settlement
however, it was reported early last month that the infertility center of new york and its founder, noel keane, agreed to pay the couple $30,000 to $40,000
keane, reached tuesday at his law office in dearborn, mich., said only that ``attorneys' fees would have been much more'' than his payment to the couple
the lawyer for mrs. whitehead-gould, joel d. siegal of newark, n.j., did not return a telephone call tuesday
mrs. whitehead-gould and richard whitehead, her husband at the time the contract was signed, had charged in a lawsuit that the infertility center and keane committed fraud in the baby m contract
the suit questioned whether mrs. whitehead-gould was properly counseled before becoming a surrogate mother
after being accepted by the center, mrs. whitehead-gould signed a contract with a tenafly, n.j., couple, william and elizabeth stern
under the arrangement, mrs. whitehead-gould was to accept $10,000 to become pregnant through artificial insemination with stern's sperm, and then relinquish the baby to the couple
however, after the baby was delivered, mrs. whitehead-gould launched a long, but ultimately unsuccessful, campaign to keep the baby girl, now nearly 2 years old and living with the sterns
foreign minister bill hayden today urged poland to allow lech walesa, leader of the outlawed solidarity labor federation, to visit australia
he said he cabled poland's foreign minister, urging him to approve walesa's application to travel to melbourne to attend a four-day world congress of the international confederation of free trade unions starting march 14
the polish government said tuesday it would bar walesa and three aides from attending the congress, citing the protection of poland's ``basic political interests.'' walesa and the three other solidarity leaders have been trying to obtain passports to allow them to attend the congress
they were invited by the australian council of trade unions
but jerzy urban, the government spokesman in poland, said the solidarity delegation would be prevented from going to the congress as representatives of ``a polish trade union which was dissolved and ceased to exist legally.''
walesa's and his colleagues' trip and their participation in the australian congress would be contradictory to the basic political interests (of poland) and would be a mockery of our legal order,'' urban told reporters
polish law regulating passport affairs orders denials of passports in such cases. poland has the sovereign right to protect its legal order.''
urban criticized some australian trade union activists for threatening to cut off water and electricity to the polish consulate in sydney and the polish embassy in canberra if walesa and his aides are refused passports, saying that such threats are only ``inflaming the atmosphere.''
he said poland would not yield to the ``pressure of hooligan threats'' toward its diplomatic missions, adding that it was australia's duty ``to guarantee the functioning of polish consular offices.''
walesa has not traveled abroad since the december 1981 imposition of martial law that crushed solidarity
also invited to australia were wroclaw solidarity leader wladyslaw frasyniuk, gdansk leader bogdan lis and senior adviser bronislaw geremek
walesa, contacted tuesday at his gdansk apartment, expressed surprise and disappointment. ``now i can see that as long as urban and company are in power i have no chance. please let me know as soon as you hear about urban's end,'' said walesa, the 1983 nobel peace prize winner
i have no further comment,'' he said. ``we have to wait for the reaction of trade unions and other organizations.''
in australia, trade unionists reacted angrily to urban's comments
we have a moral duty to protest against the polish authorities' actions and to back up our verbal condemnation with a bit of action,'' said michael easson, assistant secretary of the trades and labor council of new south wales
we reject the accusation by polish authorities that australian unions were behaving like hooligans for insisting that mr. walesa by granted permission to visit australia,'' he added
charles weyman, ethnic affairs director for the federated iron workers, told his members to boycott polish ships and cut off water, gas and electricity supplies to the consul in sydney and the embassy in canberra
authorities today acknowledged ``manifestations of anti-semitism'' in a 1968 purge of intellectuals and liberals that forced thousands of jews out of the communist party, government and academia
an article in the communist party daily trybuna ludu said innocent people were harmed merely for advocating reform, but it added that ``the predominant majority of party and state activists had no part in anti-semitism.''
addressing the 20th anniversary of the march 1968 event, the 1{-page article said some conservative, nationalist party factions ``took advantage of the jewish ancestry'' of some of their political rivals
injustice was done to many people of jewish descent as they were removed from political and professional positions, irrespective of their views and conduct,'' the paper said
but, it added, all the people in the conservative faction in the intra-party struggle were not anti-semitic, and some actively disassociated themselves from anti-semitism
about 9,000 jews lost positions in the party, government, academia and other official institutions in the purge. an estimated 12,000 to 20,000 jews emigrated, the majority of the jewish population that remained after the nazi holocaust
the first word that the party was going to issue a revised history of the 1968 ``anti-zionist'' purges came at the end of january in a speech by a polish historian in jerusalem
two weeks ago, the party weekly polityka printed a chronology of the events with a critical introduction. but the trybuna ludu article, which was reported by the state-run news agency pap and television, has the authority of an official party statement
speaking more generally about the persecution of liberals at the time, the party paper said, ``identification of the pro-reformatory movement with revisionist and anti-socialist movements was a mistake on the part of the leadership.''
it said the party leadership failed to make contact with the leading intellectuals who made ``rational proposals of democratization and who sought a dialogue with the authorities'' while recognizing the authority of the party
discrimination against jews, in the guise ``anti-zionism,'' began after israel's victory in the june 1967 middle east war. but it accelerated sharply in 1968
before world war ii, poland was home to more than 3.5 million jews _ more than half the world's jewry. there are now believed to be between 7,000 and 15,000 jews, with not a rabbi among them
all the obscenities of the march (1968) propaganda campaign have been repeated, all of them,'' said adam michnik, a prominent opposition activist and historian who was a student leader in 1968 and a chief target of anti-semitic attacks
what has been done is nothing but cosmetics,'' he said in a telephone interview
a leading party theoretician and journalist, ludwik krasucki, said on polish television tuesday that the party's attempts to reconsider the history of the period were vital
he expressed hope that with a thorough re-examination of the period, in all its aspects, ``this chapter, which nevertheless can't be forgotten, shall once and for all be closed.''
less than a week ago, eric arturo delvalle was reviled in much of the hemisphere as a figurehead president of panama, a tool of the country's military establishment, a man who gave panama's political system a constitutional facade
but, in a single stroke, delvalle has carried out a remarkable political rehabilitation. he has been transformed from delvalle the meek to delvalle the martyr
much of the reagan administration's strategy toward panama over the past few days has been built around delvalle and his claim to be panama's constitutional president
he is an integral part of the administration's ``chipmunk strategy'' toward panama _ keep gnawing away at panama's economy, at military strongman manuel antonio noriega's claim to legitimacy and his reputation and base of support at home and abroad
in time, the administration hopes, noriega will wake up, find his hold on power has evaporated and depart his homeland quietly. the administration wanted a democratic symbol around whom panamanians could rally, and found one in delvalle, the man who defied noriega, the armed forces chieftain, political heavyweight and, according to a federal indictment, cocaine smuggler. for now, at least, delvalle has the earmarks of a panamanian version of corazon aquino, a democratic symbol around whom opposition to philippine president ferdinand marcos coalesced
delvalle's image as a powerless front man dates back to when he took office in the fall of 1985. noriega was unhappy with the president at the time, nicolas ardito barletta, because of an independent streak, and he forced barletta from office
delvalle was sworn in as president under the most unpromising of circumstances. in effect, he had to behave according to noriega's wishes or he would end up like barletta. he carried that burden for two years
the image he projects nowadays is quite different. a certain mystique has developed around delvalle since he tried to fire noriega and wound up out of office himself. rather than flee the country after his dismissal, he has gone into hiding, issuing proclamations to his countrymen, making videotaped messages and frustrating efforts by noriega's forces to locate him
one of his chief allies these days is gabriel lewis, a former ambassador to washington who is now a captain of the anti-noriega campaign in exile
to hear lewis tell it, delvalle had wanted to break with noriega for five months but was reluctant to do so because of ``confusing'' signals from washington
lewis said tuesday that noriega has been suspicious of delvalle's intentions for some time and kept telling the president, ``don't act against me because the gringos are behind me.''
this was based on what noriega felt were reassuring visits by emissaries from washington, including assistant defense secretary richard armitage
one turning point occurred in early january, lewis said, when a gathering of panamanian opposition leaders met in miami and delvalle sent an envoy
the emissary told us that if we gave him (delvalle) assurances that we would support him, he was ready to act and dismiss noriega,'' lewis said
we sent him back a message,'' lewis said. ``we have heard that many times. we want deeds and not words. if you fire noriega and his cronies, we will give you support.''
contacts with lewis and other noriega opponents continued, with some messages being passed by delvalle's dentist in florida. another turning point took place in early february when two florida grand juries charged that noriega was a key figure in an international drug smuggling ring
with an end to the ambiguity in washington's position, the opposition front suggested that delvalle come here to announce his break with noriega before the organization of american states. delvalle agreed and arrangements were made
but then delvalle had second thoughts, reasoning that firing noriega at oas headquarters in washington might be seen ``as acting on instructions from the united states,'' lewis said. but was delvalle getting cold feet?
at lewis' instigation, sen. edward m. kennedy, d-mass., called delvalle to give him encouragement. on feb. 17, delvalle was in miami and invited assistant secretary of state elliott abrams to visit him
if delvalle was ousted for trying to fire noriega, abrams assured him, the united states would support him as panama's constitutional president, lewis said. eight days later, in an important moment in panama's tumultuous history, delvalle fired noriega only to be dismissed himself hours later by noriega's allies in the national assembly
lewis said the turn of events was foreseen in an 18-point anti-noriega conspiracy crafted by the opposition coalition
he said the program is up to point six. twelve to go
george gedda has covered foreign affairs for the associated press since 1968
police have been guarding the offices of a conservative weekly newspaper that has revived stinging attacks on a black professor and reawakened charges of racism at dartmouth college
a march through the school's fraternity row and continued picketing of several businesses that advertise in the dartmouth review were planned today, and a larger rally was scheduled for thursday
four review staff members face college disciplinary charges and possible expulsion stemming from a confrontation last week with william cole, a music professor who once sued the paper for libel
the staffers say they are being persecuted for taking strong stands on the quality of dartmouth life and education, and deny that race has anything to do with it
the independent newspaper also was at the center of controversy two years ago when 12 students, mostly review staffers, took sledgehammers to symbolic anti-apartheid shanties on the campus green. that raid sparked a semester of sit-ins, disciplinary hearings and other unrest that caused a leadership crisis for dartmouth president david mclaughlin
mclaughlin resigned in june 1987, though he said the disturbances didn't contribute directly to his decision
as tensions rise again, mclaughlin's successor, james freedman, said tuesday he would ``urge everyone in the dartmouth community to take the high road to civility of expression.''
freedman had a similar message monday when he spoke to 250 students at a rally protesting the review's attacks on cole. he defended cole's qualifications, as well as the right to freedom of speech, ``however unpopular, provocative and offensive that speech may sometimes be.''
cole sued the paper in 1983 for libel over an article that said he ``looks like a used brillo pad.'' he dropped the suit in 1985. he received no damages and both sides claimed vindication
two weeks ago the review published a cover story calling cole's teaching performance ``academically deficient'' and including excerpts from a transcript from one of his recent classes
on thursday four review staffers approached cole after a class. editor-in-chief chris baldwin said the staffers wanted to give cole a chance to rebut their article, and to demand that he apologize for allegedly calling them ``white-boy racists'' during a class
shouting ensued, and the incident ended with the professor allegedly breaking the camera flash of review photographer john quilhot. the review published a photograph of an agitated cole on its cover in its next issue with the headline, ``the truth hurts. cole explodes over review criticism.''
cole has not commented publicly on the incidents
three police officers stood guard tuesday outside the review's office above a hardware store a block from the dartmouth campus
nearby, hoisting signs that urged motorists to ``honk if you don't support the review,'' about 25 people picketed the dartmouth bookstore and other stores that advertise in the review
the four review staffers face punishment ranging from a fine to expulsion if they are found guilty of disorderly conduct, harassment, or violating cole's right to privacy. they are baldwin, a junior from hinsdale, ill.; quilhot, a sophomore from fort wayne, ind.; executive editor john sutter, a senior from st. louis; and staff writer sean nolan, a freshman from lexington, mass
the foreign ministry said today that many aspects of soviet president andrei gromyko's memoirs dealing with chinese-soviet relations are false
many of the recollections and descriptions in gromyko's memoirs relating to the history and present state of chinese-soviet relations do not square with the facts,'' ministry spokeswoman li jinghua told a weekly news briefing
she refused to elaborate on what elements in the memoirs china disputed
the new york times, quoting an advance copy of gromyko's two-volume book ``memoir,'' said gromyko claimed chinese leader mao tse-tung proposed in 1958 that the soviet union help lure u.s. troops into china and attack them there with nuclear weapons
gromyko wrote that mao was expecting a u.s. attack on mainland china because of washington's support for the nationalist chinese government on taiwan and tensions over the tiny islands of quemoy and matsu in the taiwan strait
gromyko said in ``memoir'' that he rejected the plan, proposed while he was on a secret august 1958 visit to china, according to the times
ms. li confirmed that gromyko, then soviet foreign minister, visited china in 1958. she refused to comment on the purpose of the trip or the content of his talks with mao
at the time, the soviet union had close ties with the younger communist state and provided it with economic and military aid. the two countries split bitterly a few years later over ideological and strategic differences
memoir'' is due to be distributed soon to soviet bookstores. it covers nearly 50 years of soviet diplomacy, including relations with nine u.s. presidents from franklin d. roosevelt to ronald reagan, the times said. conference set for 2:30 p.m. est; lead planned</note>
a former congressman who has accused gop presidential contender pat robertson of ducking combat duty in korea said today the candidate is ``chickening out'' by trying to drop his libel suit
he's chickening out of the trial just like he chickened out 37 years ago,'' said former rep. paul n. mccloskey jr., r-calif. ``the courtroom's a great place to learn the truth. ... now that he's up with the truth to be told and testimony under oath, he's backing off.''
robertson, who faced a trial date on super tuesday _ the day 20 states hold primaries and caucuses, said tuesday he wants to drop his $35 million libel suit against mccloskey
in order to compete in that trial, i would have to break off my campaign today and run the risk of losing florida, texas, south carolina and other parts of the south,'' robertson told reporters in sarasota, fla
that was an impossible decision for me to make and an unfair one,'' he added
but mccloskey, who insists robertson invoked his late father's political influence to avoid combat in the korean war, said he will oppose the former television evangelist's request to drop the case
i think the truth ought to be told,'' mccloskey said on ``cbs this morning.'' ``i don't know any better place to get the truth than in the courtroom. he invoked the process, he ought to go through with it.''
mccloskey said he fears that an individual who avoided combat in his youth may try to make amends in the white house
you know when you get a president in office who has evaded combat in his youth and all his advisers are saying look tough against the soviets ... i think there is a tendency to try to prove your manhood late in life,'' mccloskey said
robertson's lawyers called a news conference at their washington offices today to discuss their decision to ask u.s. district judge joyce hens green to dismiss the lawsuit
she can't force a plaintiff to continue the suit,'' robertson said
but under the civil rules of procedure, the judge could force robertson to go to trial unless he pays mccloskey's legal expenses of nearly $400,000
we are prepared to go to trial,'' said mccloskey's lawyer, george lehner, adding that the former congressman has long insisted that robertson pay his legal fees as a condition for any settlement
the case involves a 1986 letter that mccloskey wrote to rep. andrew jacobs jr., d-ind., alleging that robertson used the political influence of his father, the late sen. a. willis robertson, d-va., to get out of combat duty in the korean war
mccloskey, a decorated marine, was aboard a troop ship from which robertson was removed during a stop in japan before the ship proceeded to korea. he quoted robertson as telling fellow marines that his father had helped him get out of combat
in the letter that was published by two syndicated newspaper columns, mccloskey also said the former television evangelist was later assigned to be a ``booze officer'' to a rear-echelon unit in korea
robertson called mccloskey ``a patent liar.''
but mccloskey, a liberal republican who once sought the republican presidential nomination as an opponent of president nixon's vietnam war policies, has found a number of ex-marines who served in korea who support his story
the former congressman also said today that a. willis robertson, in letters written during the war, thanked the marine corps for assuring that his son would not be involved in combat. mccloskey's lawyers subpoenad the letters, which had been left to william &amp; mary college
a trial, as scheduled, would have resulted in extensive publicity about the allegations as robertson is trying to win votes in the presidential race. as early as last fall, robertson expressed regrets over filing the politically troublesome lawsuit, telling time magazine: ``in all candor, i think it was a bad idea.''
robertson, who had earlier called judge green ``patently unfair'' for refusing to postpone the trial, said tuesday that she ``had done everything she can to get us to drop the case.''
robertson proposed that he and mccloskey submit their case to the iowa libel dispute program run by the university of iowa's law school and the american arbitration association
if mccloskey refuses, robertson says he will seek to drop the lawsuit anyway and put the facts of the case to an unspecified panel of experts
we will prove to the american people that he truly doesn't want the truth to come out,'' robertson said
lehner called the proposal for arbitration ``a red herring,'' and noted that the idea had been rejected by robertson's own lawyers nine months ago
a 19-year-old woman could be sentenced to up to four years in jail and fined $10,000 in the deaths of her two children last summer in a locked, sun-baked car
lisa shields, of white township, pleaded guilty tuesday to reduced charges in the deaths of kristle, 3, and calvin shields, 1
washington county judge john bell accepted pleas to two counts of endangering the welfare of children, and indiana county district attorney william martin agreed to drop two counts of involuntary manslaughter. no sentencing date was set
mrs. shields' 24-year-old husband, john shields, goes on trial march 14 on charges of involuntary manslaughter and endangering the welfare of children
mrs. shields stopped her trial, which began monday, and pleaded guilty after her husband testified that he had agreed to care for the children and had locked them in the car while his wife slept
shields said he hid the car in which the children were sleeping in a sunny area at the rear of a farmhouse after a friend told him a warrant had been issued for his arrest because the car had no license plates and was not registered
he said he closed the car windows ``because it was supposed to rain'' and locked the doors because ``i didn't want anyone taking my kids.''
shields said he left the children in the car because the house was unheated and had broken windows
earlier tuesday, dr. william kenney, a penn state university assistant professor of physiology, said the temperature in the car probably reached 150 degrees, which the children could have withstood for 17 minutes
both parents have been in jail since their arrests shortly after the children's deaths in august. fifth</head>
a lawyer seeking lt. col. oliver north's testimony in a drug trial says the ex-national security council aide will refuse to answer questions by invoking his constitutional right against self-incrimination
ronald c. dresnick, who obtained subpoenas last week against north and two other figures in the iran-contra affair, said tuesday he had not decided whether to pursue his bid to compel north to appear march 15 in u.s. district court in detroit
however, the attorney said he believed north could provide information to support his claim that his client, frank ivan turek correa, of colombia, was a victim of entrapment or other government misconduct
dresnick said he wanted to question north about michael palmer, a former airline pilot whom dresnick claimed was being protected from prosecution
palmer accompanied correa and other defendants on an airplane that allegedly carried drugs from south america to michigan, the attorney said. but dresnick said he believed palmer was allowed to go free because the government wanted to conceal his alternate role in shipping food and clothing to the contra rebels trying to topple the government of nicaragua
dresnick, in court papers seeking to subpoena north, said the dc-6 airplane allegedly used to ship the drugs to michigan was once owned by vortex air international. palmer is a former executive with both vortex and southern air transport, which dresnick called a cia-backed operation
i believe the government knows about palmer and ... must be aware that palmer was involved in drug smuggling,'' dresnick said
palmer also has been subpoenaed to testify in detroit, but his whereabouts are unknown, dresnick said. the attorney said he was forced to subpoena north because of the government's refusal to produce palmer
assistant u.s. attorney robert donaldson acknowledged tuesday that palmer was not included in a sept. 24, 1987, indictment naming correa and seven other defendants. he said the government had no interest in north's testimony and declined further comment
dresnick said barry simon, a washington attorney representing north, told him by telephone monday that his client ``indicated he will take the fifth amendment.''
if that's all that's going to happen, it's a little pointless to drag him out (to detroit) to say that,'' dresnick said
simon, contacted monday night, had declined to say whether north would appear in detroit and would not answer any other questions
more than 2,000 libyan soldiers have entered northwestern sudan to launch an offensive against chad, the government radio of chad said
n'djamena radio said the troops joined thousands of other soldiers already stationed in sudan's darfour province ``with the complicity of the khartoum authorities.'' the report tuesday night was monitored in abidjan
the column included regular soldiers from the libyan army as well as mercenaries, the radio said. it added that libyan leader col. moammar gadhafi was planning an attack
chad and libya have been observing a cease-fire in their war over the disputed anzou strip, a mineral-rich area that lies between the two countries. the cease-fire was arranged by the organization of african states last september
chad frequently has accused libya of using sudan to launch attacks against it
as for khartoum and its government, chad reiterates its appeal for a sense of responsibility to avoid turning the sudanese territory into a powder keg and an aggression base against a neighboring and brotherly country. otherwise, chad will assume its responsibility,'' the radio said
a special organization of african unity committee is to meet in dakar, senegal, on april 10 to negotiate a settlement in the chad-libya conflict
deposed president ferdinand marcos said his doctors once suspected he had cancer but surgery proved the diagnosis wrong, an uncle of president corazon aquino reported today
rep. francisco sumulong said through a spokesman that marcos told him of the preliminary diagnosis when the two men met in hawaii in early february. he said marcos had thyroid surgery in october, after which doctors ruled out cancer
on tuesday, the peoples journal tonight quoted sumulong as saying that marcos was in declining health and may be suffering from cancer. a marcos spokesman in honolulu denied the report in the manila newspaper
sumulong and mrs. aquino's cousin, rep. egmidio tanjuatco, met separately with marcos earlier this year in hawaii, where the former president has lived since he was ousted in a military-civilian revolt in february 1986
marcos spokesman leonie tan confirmed the meetings but denied that the former president had used his health to strike any deals with the aquino government for his return
he's in excellent health,'' tan said. ``he has regular medical check-ups and definitely does not have cancer.''
mrs. aquino said in manila on tuesday that before marcos would be allowed to return he must return billions of dollars he allegedly took from the country he ruled for 20 years
marcos repeatedly has denied stealing money from the philippines, and tan said he had not offered to pay any money back
no deal has been struck, indeed, not a single item on the agenda has been decided,'' tan said
it is not known when negotiations for marcos return will start, ``but the desire from both sides is that talks begin immediately,'' tan said
marcos lives with his wife, imelda, in a mansion in the makiki heights section of honolulu. both have frequently expressed their desire to return to the philippines, but cannot because mrs. aquino revoked their passports shortly after assuming the presidency
the coach of the romanian bobsled team refused to return home after the winter olympic games and has asked for asylum in canada, police and olympic sources said
city police supt. len esler said tuesday a man approached two police officers at the athletes' village at the university of calgary on monday night and ``requested political asylum.''
he was taken to a police station, where immigration officers picked him up and placed him in protective custody. esler refused to say who the team official was or give his nationality ``for his safety and the safety of his family.''
but police and olympic sources identified him as dumitru focseneanu, who was listed as the romanian bobsled coach staying at the olympic village
focseneanu was in calgary last december as the 22-member team's coach during world cup competition
the romanian embassy in ottawa refused comment
wilf lindner, manager of the calgary immigration center, said the man had not yet formally applied for refugee status and would be given two or three days ``to reflect on his position without undue pressure.''
his refugee status is to be decided at a later date,'' lindner said. ``all decisions are made on a case-to-case basis. we have his request to remain in canada, nothing else.''
lindner said no other olympic-related requests to remain in canada had been received by the calgary office. but during the first week of the games, three romanian speed skaters and their coach abruptly departed amid speculation they were planning to defect
a federal judge rebuked shiloh true light church of christ for exploiting children and cited church members for contempt of court for violating federal child labor laws
u.s. district judge robert potter also ordered two companies owned and operated by church members to pay $203,272 to cover a federal investigation and litigation expenses and to pay employees back wages and interest
the actions tuesday further set back the church's campaign to stop what it calls government interference with its religious beliefs
potter ruled that church members and the two companies _ mcgee brothers co. inc. of union county and wendell's woodwork inc. of mint hill _ violated his october 1987 order to obey federal child labor laws
true light families educate their children at home. the church also sponsors a job-training program that gives youths the opportunity to earn money while learning such trades as bricklaying, woodworking and sewing
church members acknowledged during the trial they used their children, some as young as 9, at construction sites and in workshops where they carried bricks, laid foundations and more recently, operated forklifts and power saws. they said they had been doing that for at least 100 years
in october, potter ordered children to stop working for the companies. when the owners of the companies continued the program for the church, the labor department asked they be found in contempt
in separate judgments, potter ordered both companies again to obey the laws and warned that mcgee brothers would be fined $10,000 and wendell's woodwork $5,000 for each day the companies remain in contempt of his order
in addition, potter said wendell's two owners _ wendell long and herbert long _ would be fined $500 each per day that they remained in contempt of his order. the five brothers who own mcgee brothers face fines of $1,000 per day each if they remain in contempt
potter also ordered mcgee brothers to pay $133,890 in back wages and interest to employees who had not been paid minimum wages and for overtime work
calls to both companies' offices and the offices of their attorneys for comment were not returned
we feel like our freedom of religion and freedom of worship has been violated,'' said rommie purser, the church's minister. ``we just plan to go on to the supreme court and see if we aren't being denied freedom of worship.''
in a january trial, the labor department charged the owners of the two companies _ all of whom are members of the church _ with violating the federal statute against child labor
the judge wrote in his 58-page opinion that the children employed ``are children doing adult's work, and regardless of the label defendants have attached to them, i.e. `trainees in shiloh vocational training program,' they are manifestly being exploited by defendants in this case, whether or not they proclaim their purpose to be in furtherance of their religious beliefs.'' cyprus for zurich; picks up 9th graf pvs: `stening said...'</note>
two scandinavian u.n. relief workers freed from 25 days in captivity said today that their moslem abductors moved them often, did not reveal their identities and treated them well
swede jan stening, 44, and norwegian william jorgensen, 58, who were freed by their abductors tuesday night, made the comments at a packed news conference at a hotel in christian east beirut
we were very well treated during the whole period of captivity,'' said stening. jorgensen said stening was speaking for ``both of us.''
stening said neither of them had any idea about the identity of their captors, their motives or their demands
all our guards were masked,'' stening said. ``we changed locations seven or eight times. we never knew where we were held at any time.''
we were held together ... both of us were blindfolded at the beginning for an hour or so but then the blindfolds were removed and we were allowed to talk freely to each other,'' stening said. ``we were moved from one location to another at night and in the trunks of the cars,'' stening added
he said their captors ``interrogated us in a polite manner, asking such questions as the names of countries we worked at and the kind of jobs we had.''
after the news conference, the former hostages left lebanon in a u.n. helicopter from christian east beirut for larnaca, cyprus. they then departed larnaca for zurich, switzerland, aboard a regular swissair flight for their journey home
stening said four gunmen kidnapped them near south lebanon's provincial capital of sidon as they were driving in a u.n. car from their base in the southern port of tyre to beirut on feb. 5
asked whether either one could tell if the kidnappers were palestinians or lebanese, judging by their accent, stening said in english: ``no. we haven't the slightest idea. i don't know arabic.''
the two worked for the u.n. relief and works agency, which cares for 280,000 palestinian refugees in lebanon
jorgensen said ``yes'' when asked whether he would be willing to return to work for the agency in sidon after their ordeal
john fennessey of ireland,the agency's acting director, told reporters at the news conference that the two former captives ``wish to join their families as soon as possible and we're going to fulfill that'' request
the first word about the release came in a handwritten arabic statement delivered to a western news agency in beirut late tuesday
it was accompanied by a picture showing the two men. it said after they were ``proved innocent, they were released.''
the statement did not say what they had been accused of, but in earlier statements the group claimed the men were involved with the intelligence service of an unidentified foreign power. u.n. officials blamed the abductions on palestinians acting individually for personal, not political, motives
the kidnappers of u.s. marine lt. col. william r. higgins, who was abducted in south lebanon feb. 17, said in a statement released tuesday they would put him on trial. they accused higgins of working for the u.s. central intelligence agency
the organization of the oppressed on earth, which claimed higgins' abduction, said israel's crackdown on anti-occupation palestinian riots in the west bank and gaza strip and the middle east trip of u.s. secretary of state george p. shultz ``make us more determined to try this criminal, higgins.''
both the united nations and the united states have denied that higgins, who served with the u.n. peacekeeping force in south lebanon, was a cia spy
reporters in sidon, 25 miles south of beirut, said the two scandinavians were turned over by their abductors at 8 p.m. tuesday to palestine liberation organization representative salah salah
they were then driven to beirut by the militia of leftist sunni moslem leader mustafa saad, who controlled the city since the 1975 outbreak of the lebanese civil war
higgins, 43, was abducted near south lebanon's ancient port of tyre. he heads a 76-man u.n. observer group that monitors truce violations on the lebanon-israel border under a 1949 armistice agreement
the organization of the oppressed on earth is believed to be made up of pro-iranian shiite moslems. it previously claimed responsibility for kidnapping 12 lebanese jews in west beirut and said it killed eight of them
in all, 23 foreigners are missing after being kidnapped in lebanon since march 1985. they are nine americans, four frenchmen, three britons, two west germans, an italian, an irishman, an indian and two unidentified men
held longest is terry a. anderson, chief middle east correspondent of the associated press, kidnapped march 16, 1985. word; sub final item to restore ap logo</note> ministers</head>
a newspaper poll of baptist ministers in south carolina shows former television evangelist pat robertson with a plurality of support in the influential group, despite its theological differences with the republican presidential candidate
robertson has said he has to win south carolina's republican primary saturday, three days before the super tuesday primaries in other mostly southern states. about 700,000 of south carolina's 3 million people are southern baptists, with about 2,000 ministers
a poll conducted last weekend by the atlanta journal and the atlanta constitution showed robertson with the support of 31 percent of the ministers who plan to vote saturday
vice president george bush was second at 24 percent, followed by 17 percent for kansas sen. bob dole and 10 percent for new york rep. jack kemp
although robertson is a former southern baptist minister _ he stepped down as he began his presidential campaign _ he comes from a charismatic branch of the denomination, believing, among other things, in faith-healing and speaking in tongues. most of the fundamentalist members of the denomination reject such teachings
state republican party officials say the large turnout expected for saturday's presidential primary is stretching their manpower to the limits
the party still is looking for volunteers to help man the polls and will probably have to combine some precincts, officials said
any time you try to man 1,800 precincts with volunteers, it's a lot of work,'' said state republican party executive director tony denny. ``some counties have got it licked and are in good shape, others are struggling and trying to find volunteers during the last minute
but i think we'll get the precincts open.''
the largest primary race the gop has held in the state came in the 1980 presidential campaign, which drew about 145,000 voters, denny said
he is anticipating a turnout of about 175,000 saturday. denny said regular june primary elections never have drawn more than approximately 60,000 voters statewide
the texas state teachers association has dropped its endorsement of illinois sen. paul simon, dealing another blow to a presidential campaign that a simon official said has been misconstrued as dead in the south
the tsta, tuesday switched to massachusetts gov. michael dukakis as its candidate in next tuesday's texas democratic presidential primary. tsta, with 95,000 members is the state's largest teacher organization
while sen. simon's strong national record on education prompted our endorsement, his decision not to campaign in texas forced us to reassess our position,'' tsta president charles beard said at a news conference
simon announced last week he does not have sufficient money to mount full campaigns in the super tuesday states, including texas. but bob krueger, simon's texas chairman, said tuesday that simon is running in texas and expects to earn some delegates
simon will campaign in texas on monday and tuesday, according to krueger
pat robertson apparently will be the only one of the four republican presidential candidates to hit the legal spending limit for saturday's south carolina primary, campaign officials say
about 25 percent of the money robertson is spending in south carolina will go into television advertising, which includes a 30 minute television ad expected to air thursday or friday night in greenville, charleston and columbia markets, said kerry moody, robertson's national deputy press secretary
the bulk of the money has gone into field organization efforts, including distribution of 200,000 tapes titled ``pat robertson: what i will do as president.''
in new hampshire, robertson sent more than 200,000 tapes, and in last week's south dakota race, he sent 206,585 tapes
robertson also spent the legal limits in iowa and new hampshire. the limit set by the federal election commission for south carolina is $916,099
jesse jackson has qualified to be on the ballot for indiana's may 3 democratic presidential primary
jackson supporters tuesday submitted the required ballot petitions to the secretary of state's office. at least 500 signatures from each of the state's 10 congressional districts are required to qualify for the statewide ballot
jackson became the fifth democrat to earn a spot on the ballot. also competing for the 79 delegate votes available through the primary are rep. richard gephardt of missouri, sen. albert gore of tennessee, gov. michael dukakis of massachusetts and sen. paul simon of illinois
jackson finished third in the 1984 primary behind then colorado sen. gary hart and former vice president walter mondale
senate minority leader bob dole of kansas and rep. jack kemp of new york have filed for the republican primary
