vice president george bush, buoyed by polls showing him with a comfortable lead in the south, said today no candidate can win the nomination without winning on super tuesday
you cannot design a strategy to be president of the united states without doing well in the super tuesday states,'' bush said at a breakfast with supporters here at the start of a campaign day that will take him to alabama, mississippi, louisiana and south carolina
bush said tuesday he wants to keep ``a rather high plane'' in the closing days of the super tuesday campaign
but when asked about a television advertisement in which dole attacks him on the iran-contra affair, bush told reporters: ``we'll see whether it helps him, but i think i have every right to set the record straight. you ought not to be surprised if you see some comparative ads
you know, we're not going to sit out there unprotected,'' he added
after a swing through south florida on tuesday, bush planned to breakfast today with senior citizens in pinellas county, then head on to mississippi and louisiana campaign events
bush said that he is confident but not cocky about the campaign for the march 8 super tuesday of 20 primaries and caucuses, most in the south. a washington post-abc poll released today gave him a 3-1 lead over dole
two weeks ago yesterday, the polls (in new hampshire, where he won the primary) showed me on the canvas; and the voters said different. i'm not going to get overconfident (because polls show him leading in the south),'' said bush
the vice president campaigned tuesday with former sen. barry goldwater, the 1964 republican presidential nominee from arizona, and florida gov. bob martinez
in recent days, dole has made a point of saying he is the only candidate ``tough enough'' to deal with the problems a president faces
bush replied with an appearance that played up his combat record. when he arrived at the tampa airport, a grumman avenger plane, the same model he flew during world war ii, had been brought from a nearby air museum. he climbed into the cockpit
later, bush drove a paving machine at the construction site of a north miami beach development
bush's mother, who lives in palm beach, briefly joined him. also campaigning with bush in tampa was his son jeb, who is florida's secretary of commerce. comments. picks up 11th graf pvs, `otherwise, he ...; one word cq for najib.</note>
the mediator through nearly six years of peace talks on afghanistan opened a crucial and perhaps final round today and said he was sure it would lead to the withdrawal of soviet troops
u.n. mediator diego cordovez said ``difficult'' problems remained but that he believed both sides were determined to overcome them and reach a settlement as soon as possible
cordovez said the negotiations would last as long as was necessary to forge that settlement
perhaps it will be signed earlier than you think,'' he added
i have the impression that the afghan people are tired of this conflict, that they will want peace,'' cordovez said. he did not specify what problems remained, citing a need of confidentiality that allowed the parties to be ``flexible''
cordovez spoke to reporters shortly before beginning his shuttle between the pakistani and afghan delegations, seated in separate rooms in the geneva office of the united nations
the indirect format was adopted because pakistan, representing the anti-marxist afghan guerrillas, does not recognize the soviet-backed afghan government of president najib
cordovez said he had been in contact with representatives of several countries, including the united states, the soviet union, the european community and australia, to discuss humanitarian aid to afghanistan after a settlement
i have the feeling that there will be a broad international effort,'' he said
pakistan has insisted that pullout of the 115,000 soviet troops from afghanistan be accompanied by formation of a broad-based transitional government to replace the afghan regime
the soviets intervened in 1979 to back the kabul government against moslem insurgents
pakistan's chief negotiator, minister of state zain noorani, said pakistan came to geneva with a ``constructive attitude to finalize the text of the peace package.''
the head of the afghan delegation, foreign minister abdul wakil, did not renew charges that pakistan's demand for an interim government threatens to thwart a settlement
both held separate news conferences on tuesday
wakil said he approached the talks with a ``sense of full optimism.''
asked whether pakistan would sign the peace package with the najib government, noorani said that would be decided after consultations in islamabad on sunday with ``national leaders,'' including opposition leaders
the geneva talks will recess to allow noorani to take part in those talks
noorani said pakistan would continue to press for an interim government acceptable to all afghans to be created in conjunction with a soviet withdrawal
otherwise, he said, there is a threat of new bloodshed preventing the return to afghanistan of more than 3 million refuges from pakistan and another 2 million from iran
we also seek cooperation of the soviet union,'' said noorani. ``we feel that after 8{ years of occupation, the soviets owe it to the people of afghanistan to give them a durable peace.''
wakil said afghanistan has no preconditions for the makeup of the future government
but seven pakistan-based resistance movements that claim to speak for the about 200,000 moslem guerrillas have ruled out any power-sharing with najib. last week, they presented their own plan for an ``islamic government.''
kabul immediately rejected the plan, which noorani described as a ``positive proposal.''
the talks have moved rapidly since soviet leader mikhail gorbachev's feb. 8 announcement that moscow would bring its troops home within 10 months starting may 15, provided a geneva settlement is signed by march 15
noorani said the march 15 date ``is not all that important'' and that he is sure soviet withdrawal plans would not be upset if the signing came later
he said the timetable for the pullout is now within ``negotiable range,'' but he indicated there are still considerable differences
pakistan wants at least half the soviet troops to leave during the first three months of a pullout, noorani said. gorbachev has been vague on the subject, which is directly related to the question of a cutoff in western aid to the guerrillas
the united states is reported to have given the guerrillas $700 million last year
wakil said agreements already drawn up provide for the cutoff to coincide with the start of the soviet pullout
the afghan monarchy was overthrown in 1978 and a communist government was installed. the soviets intervened at the request of the embattled new marxist government
the doctor for three aids-exposed brothers who were ostracized in their hometown has retracted his diagnosis of aids-related complex for the oldest boy
jerry barbosa testified at a hearing tuesday that he earlier made the diagnosis for 11-year-old ricky ray because he felt compelled to under a judge's order
aids-related complex, or arc, often is a precursor to acquired immune deficiency syndrome. there is no known cure for aids
the way i interpreted the order, i had no choice but to label this patient as having arc against my clinical judgment,'' barbosa told u.s. magistrate elizabeth a. jenkins
the purpose of tuesday's hearing was to clarify earlier reports that the physician had diagnosed arc in the youth weeks before reporting it to the court
on jan. 29, u.s. district judge elizabeth kovachevich modified an earlier order and required barbosa to report the progress of ``any aids, aids symptomology, or other aids-related syndrome.''
her wording prompted him to say in his feb. 2 report that ricky had developed arc, barbosa said
but ricky has not exhibited physical symptoms necessary for such a finding, although the boy's blood tests might support an arc diagnosis, the doctor said. he also cited april 1987 guidelines issued by the federal centers for disease control in atlanta that prohibit labeling any child under age 13 as having arc
it doesn't mean much to the court that somebody has or doesn't have arc,'' ms. jenkins said. ``when material changes in the boys' health occurs, it is not up to the court to try to look behind the medical reports to see what is there.''
when ms. kovachevich ruled aug. 5, 1987, that the desoto county school system had to readmit the ray brothers to regular classes, she ordered aids testing of the boys every six months and said any changes in their condition had to be reported to her
ms. jenkins told attorneys for the rays and the school board to devise an improved way to keep the court informed about the hemophiliac brothers' medical conditions. the attorneys must submit the plan by monday
ricky, robert, 10, and randy, 8, were banned from regular classes after they tested positive for the aids antibody in august 1986. doctors say the children were apparently exposed to the aids virus through infusions of blood products that aim to promote clotting
soon after the boys began school in arcadia last fall, amid a boycott and protests by other students' parents, an arsonist torched the ray home. since then, the family has moved to sarasota, where the ray children have attended public school without incident. waldheim ordering lawsuit. picks up 5th graf pvs, `a spokesman....' minor editing to conform.</note>
a group of 300 austrians has asked state prosecutors to investigate whether president kurt waldheim can be prosecuted on suspicion of murder, a spokesman for the group said today
a petition asking that waldheim be prosecuted in connection with his world war ii service as an officer in the nazi army has been circulating among intellectuals and at anti-waldheim demonstrations for the past three weeks
the left-wing vienna magazine falter today published the text of the complaint, which it said was signed by 300 people, including two prominent writers _ robert jungk and erich fried
walter oswalt, a journalist and spokesman for the group, said the complaint was sent to the vienna state prosecutor's office by registered mail and was delivered this morning
later, waldheim asked state prosecutors to sue falter on grounds of defamation and asked that it be removed from newsstands, the president's spokesman, gerold christian, said
waldheim has initiated four other similar suits, including one against the west german news magazine der spiegel, which published a document last month purportedly linking waldheim to the deportation of civilians to prison camps in 1944. the magazine later said the document was a forgery and apologized for publishing it
a spokesman for the state prosecutor's office said privacy laws prevent the office confirming the receipt of the austrian group's complaint
the complaint quoted extensively from a historians' report on waldheim's wartime service, published feb. 9, and from other material to back its request for an investigation of waldheim on suspicion of murder
it cited an article in austria's criminal code saying that ``not only the direct perpetrator commits the punishable act, but also a person who persuades another person to commit it, or who otherwise contributes to its perpetration.''
the historians' report concluded that waldheim had concealed his record as a german army lieutenant in the balkans during world war ii. it also said he was in ``close proximity'' to some nazi atrocities, knew about them and did nothing to prevent them
christian, asked for a reaction to the complaint, said only that legal proceedings were constitutionally impossible
under article 63 of the austrian constitution, a president can be prosecuted only if both houses of austria's parliament agree to it
waldheim has said the report exonerates him from accusations linking him to war crimes, but the historians left open the question of guilt
waldheim has consistently denied any links with alleged war crimes and has insisted he will stay in office despite increasing pressure to resign. he was elected to a six-year term in june 1986, three months after his service in the balkans was first disclosed
the u.s. justice department has barred waldheim from the united states as an undesirable alien
the israeli member of the historians' commission, yehuda l. wallach, has said the report could serve as a basis for an investigation of whether waldheim could be prosecuted
the west german historian on the panel, manfred messerschmidt said in an interview published feb. 25 in the munich daily sueddeutsche zeitung that legal steps could be considered over waldheim's role in the fate of british commandos executed in greece in 1944
last month, british prime minister margaret thatcher ordered a renewed investigation into that episode by british authorities
parts of messerschmidt's interview were quoted in the text of the complaint against waldheim
messerschmidt said in connection with the 1944 episode, ``i think that from the point of view of penal law, one could think about whether this was not assistance'' in murder
justice ministry spokesman gerhard litzka said that, under austrian law, the state prosecutors' office is bound to examine such a complaint and to deliver a recommendation to the justice ministry on whether or not to open legal proceedings. baghdad. other editing. no pickup.</note>
iraq said it pounded tehran with surface-to-surface missiles today for a third straight day and fired two rockets at iran's holy city of qom, seat of ayatollah ruhollah khomeini's religious hierarchy
iran said it launched three long-range missiles against the iraqi capital of baghdad early today in retaliation
one iranian missile hit baghdad at daybreak, killing or wounding several civilians, including women and children, and destroying houses, shops and cars, the official iraqi news agency said without elaborating on the casualties
iraq said it had sent 19 missiles into the iranian capital since monday, including two today that iran's official islamic republic news agency said wounded 15 civilians, among them eight women and five children
iraq's news agency reported a third missile was fired into tehran in the afternoon
khomeini said iran will not bow to pressure, and that missile attacks ``make our nation stronger,'' tehran radio reported
it was the first time iraq has used surface-to-surface missiles on tehran, a city of 6 million, since the iran-iraq war began in september 1980. it marks the worst escalation of the 3-year-old ``war of the cities'' that has killed thousands of civilians
the attack on qom was iraq's first with surface-to-surface missiles on the city 80 miles south of tehran. the last time iraqi warplanes bombed qom was january 1987
iraq said the missiles used against tehran were of its own design and production, but iran said they were soviet-supplied
western military analysts believe the iraqis are using soviet-made scud-b surface-to-surface missiles with ``strap-on'' booster rockets to give them extra range to reach tehran, which is 290 miles from the iraqi border. qom is about the same distance from the border
iran also uses scud-bs to attack baghdad, but has an advantage because the iraqi capital is only 80 miles from the border
the iraqi news agency said the missiles on qom were fired just before noon, but gave no other details of the attack on the city, which it called ``the center of charlatans and hypocrites.''
the agency reported a second attack on qom in the early afternoon
the iranian news agency said no casualties were reported in the strike on qom before noon, but did not mention the later attack. irna said 15 civilians suffered wounds in the latest attacks on tehran
qom, a city of 250,000 people, is home to iran's main theological center and tomb of a shiite moslem saint. ayatollah hussein ali montazeri, khomeini's designated successor, lives in qom
although the city is khomeini's seat, the 87-year-old supreme leader of iran's fundamentalist revolution lives in suburban tehran. he told families of war victims at his residence today: ``we fear nothing. for a martyrdom-lover it makes no difference to be martyred by a missile, a bomb or anything else,'' tehran radio reported
irna said iranian artillery gunners, in retaliation for today's attacks on tehran, shelled military and economic installations in the iraqi cities of basra, ammara, badra, zorbatiya, ali sharqi and ali gharbi
iraq said it began the missile barrage of tehran to retaliate for two pre-dawn iranian rockets on baghdad on monday. iran said the missiles were in retaliation for iraqi air raids on the tehran oil refinery last week
the iraqi and iranian dispatches were monitored in nicosia
a water stoppage that took place about 30 minutes earlier than announced left a man with a burned scalp
at 7:30 a.m. monday, keith dennis, of ventnor, applied a caustic hair relaxer to his scalp. fifteen minutes later, he ducked his head under the shower, only to discover there was no water
dennis knew a new water main was being connected as part of a road reconstruction, but residents had been notified that water would be turned off about 8:15 a.m
faced with a scalp that was beginning to burn, dennis and his wife, melissa, first tried to bail some water out of the bottom of the bathtub. then they tried melting ice cubes on his head
it started burning more and more,'' dennis said
dennis considered rinsing his hair with any liquid in the refrigerator, but was worried about chemical reactions, he said
he shouted for workers on the street to turn his water back on, but said they laughed
the couple then called a poison hot line, asking for an ambulance to bring water
but the message got garbled by the time it got to emergency officials: ``the dispatcher said this guy had shampoo in his hair, and could we send a bucket of water over,'' is how fire capt. bert sabo recalls it
an ambulance was deemed unnecessary. the dennises wound up driving to a hospital, where dennis was treated for first-degree burns
a spokesman says shrimpers will defy a federal regulation requiring the use of devices designed to save endangered sea turtles, despite a federal judge's decision to enforce the regulation
to further complicate matters, louisiana wildlife and fisheries agents are prohibited by state law from enforcing the federal regulation requiring use of turtle excluder devices, which shrimpers claim could ruin their business
federal enforcement of the regulations began tuesday after u.s. district judge patrick carr threw out a suit by shrimpers that claimed that the devices cut down on their shrimp catches and aren't effective
but louisiana's department of wildlife and fisheries is bound by a state law forbidding enforcement of the federal law, said phil bowman, assistant chief of the seafood division
we'll have to consult with legal counsel before we know what to do,'' he said
tee john mialjevich, spokesman for concerned shrimpers of louisiana, vowed defiance despite carr's ruling
i don't care if he upheld it. it's a bad law, and the shrimpers ain't going to live by it,'' he said
the law also went into effect tuesday in texas, mississippi and alabama waters, and has been in effect in florida since jan. 1. louisiana waters won't open to shrimping for two months, but big boats work year-round in federal waters beyond the three-mile limit
coast guard patrols caught six shrimp boats working without the devices since the law went into effect in florida, suzanne montero of the national marine fisheries service said by telephone from st. petersburg, fla
there were no reports of violations tuesday, she said
the maximum civil penalty is $10,000, but first-time offenders will probably be fined $5,000 to $7,500, she said
under the law, most shrimpers will be required to use the cage-like devices to save turtles protected under the endangered species act. the devices, which fit in shrimp nets, have slats to force a trapped turtle out of a flap, but critics say they don't always work that way
critics said sometimes shrimp escape and debris gets caught in the frame and ruins the net
mialjevich said florida shrimpers experienced catch reductions of 35 percent to 50 percent
i'm telling you myself _ personally _ i'm not going to pull a ted (turtle exclusion device), because i can't make a living. i'll lose everything i've accumulated in 45 years. ... i can't take a 1 percent shrimp loss. how am i going to take a 35 percent loss?'' said mialjevich
carr had said in advance that his ruling would not determine the effectiveness of the devices, but would address only whether the government had followed proper procedures
the leader of the social democrats, one of five parties in the government coalition, resigned after accusations that he was involved in a kickback scandal
franco nicolazzi, 63, submitted his resignation as party secretary on monday to preserve party unity, he said. he denied wrongdoing, saying ``these hands are clean.''
the scandal involved millions of dollars allegedly paid to prominent politicans by companies in exchange for prison construction contracts. nicolazzi is under investigation but hasn't been charged
nicolazzi was public works minister in several governments from 1980 through june. during his tenure, he helped pass a decree authorizing $629 million for new prison construction
pressure to resign built last week when gabriele di palma, a close associate of nicolazzi and former head of the ministry's public construction department, was detained by swiss authorities while allegedly trying to sneak into switzerland
nicolazzi was secretary of the social democrats since october 1985
the party received 3.4 percent of the vote in elections to the chamber of deputies last june. only the liberals, with 2.1 percent, had fewer votes among the five coalition parties. the others are the dominant christian democrats, the socialists and the republicans
pier luigi romita, a senior social democrat deputy, is considered the favorite to become the new leader of the party
fire broke out today on the roof of the 26-floor london stock exchange, but officials said it was quickly brought under control and no one was injured
police closed nearby streets and scores of spectators gathered as smoke billowed from the skyscraper in london's financial district
press association, the british domestic news agency, said a few people were evacuated from upper floors, but work continued elsewhere in the building
the fire broke out in a cooling tower and appeared to have been started by a workman's blowtorch igniting trash in the area, the news agency said
the stock exchange said none of its financial services were affected
since the switch to computers on oct. 27, 1986, most trading on the london stock exchange has been done by telephone rather than on the floor of the exchange
police today searched more than 80 homes of suspected neo-nazis and made some arrests in a crackdown on extreme rightist groups, officials said
the searches were conducted in about 60 towns and cities across the country, said police in the state of baden-wuerttemburg
a police official in stuttgart, where federal authorities coordinated the searches with state and local police, said there had been ``some arrests,'' but he declined to be more specific
the official, citing department policy, spoke on condition he not be identified
the searches apparently were carried out in conjunction with the release from prison of michael kuehnen, a prominent neo-nazi
kuehnen was was freed today from butzbach prison near frankfurt after completing a 3{-year sentence for distributing banned right-wing extremist propaganda, a spokesman for the frankfurt prosecutors office said
he was kept in prison up to the last minute possible,'' the spokesman, jochen schroers, said in a telephone interview
kuehnen, a former west german army lieutenant, headed an illegal right-wing extremist group called ``action front of national socialists-national activists.''
the group was banned by the west german interior ministry on dec. 7, 1983 for advocating violence against leftists and foreigners and for promoting nazi ideology
the launch of a scout rocket from an italian facility in kenya is being delayed by one week from its scheduled march 18 date because of a defective gyro, nasa announced today
the gyro helps maintain directional control
the spacecraft, called the san marco d@l, is to carry five scientific instruments, three from the united states and one each from germany and italy. it is expected to be launched on march 25 from italy's san marco equatorial range in kenya
a powerful bomb exploded in the doorway of a downtown apartment building today, damaging property but causing no injuries, federal police said
police said the 1:50 a.m. blast at a four-story apartment building blew a heavy wooden door into the street and shattered windows in adjacent buildings
police said the objective of the attack was not immediately clear and that no political or military figures lived in the building
police said they found several leaflets at the scene bearing the initials ``o.a.s.,'' ``m.r.p,'' and the phrase ``for national liberation,'' as well as drawings of argentine independence hero gen. jose de san martin and a condor
the significance of the initials was not immediately known. no known terrorist or extremist group has used those initials in recent years. church spokeswoman; picks up graf 7, `the louisiana...'</note>
assemblies of god leaders in louisiana have rejected a request by national church officials to toughen their recommended sanctions against evangelist jimmy swaggart, a church official says
juleen turnage, spokeswoman at church headquarters in springfield, mo., said today that national church officers have not been informed of any decision by the louisiana district
the louisiana official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said tuesday the 19-member state presbytery decided at a nine-hour meeting monday in alexandria to resubmit its original recommeendation that swaggart be barred from preaching for three months as part of a two-year program of rehabilitation
the official said it would now be up to national assemblies of god officials to decide whether to accept the state panel's recommendation
the assemblies' general presbytery has a regular session scheduled march 29, but an emergency session could be convened sooner
mrs. turnage said at least three of the officers must attend any meeting of the executive presbytery. she said it would be at least thursday before three of the officials will be back in springfield
mrs. turnage said she talked by telephone tuesday night with the rev. g. raymond carlson, the general superintendent of the church, who said he believes it would be unprecedented for a state presbytery to reject the national church's recommendations
asked about reports last week from from friends of swaggart that he might leave the church if he feels the punishment is too harsh, mrs. turnage said national officers have heard nothing directly from swaggart
we're not dealing with a radical or a rebel here. if he does leave the church, it will be because his ministry can't survive without him. it will be a pragmatic decision,'' she said
i think he is very committed to the church,'' mrs. turnage said
the louisiana presbytery's original sanction was a two-year rehabilitation program that also included counseling for swaggart, who heads a ministry that reportedly takes in $150 million a year
swaggart stepped down from the pulpit feb. 21, telling the congregation at his baton rouge worship center in a tearful confession that he had sinned against his wife and god. swaggart reportedly paid a prostitute to pose nude for him and then tried to make a deal with a minister who confronted him about it
the national presbytery reportedly recommended barring swaggart from the pulpit and television for a year, with an additional year of regulation of his ministry afterward
a louisiana assemblies of god official contacted tuesday night by the associated press confirmed that the state panel stood by its previous punishment for the evangelist. the decision originally was reported by katc-tv of layfayette
when asked if louisiana officials had sent back their original censure to the church's national leaders, the source said, ``it would be correct to say that.''
cecil janway, the assemblies of god district superintendent for louisiana, had said any actions made monday by the state board would not be made public
there was no indication whether swaggart attended that meeting. the rev. jim rentz, who is substituting for swaggart at his family worship center, did attend
forrest hall, secretary-treasurer of the louisiana district council, acknowledged monday that national assemblies of god representatives also were at the meeting. killed</head>
four sheriff's deputies today forcibly evicted the last resident of the lorraine motel, where martin luther king jr. was assassinated 20 years ago
jacqueline smith, who has lived at the motel for 11 years, refused to obey an eviction order, in protest of attempts to build an $8.8 million museum at the site. she has said the project would force poor people out of the neighborhood
king was shot by an assassin april 4, 1968, while in memphis to help organize a strike by sanitation workers
you people are making a mistake. you people are making a mistake,'' miss smith said, sobbing, as four shelby county deputies carried her in a kneeling position from the balcony outside her second-floor room to the sidewalk in front of the motel
i refuse to stand up,'' she said as the deputies walked away. ``i'm trying to help the people who live in this area. we're being forced out. you people are wrong.''
miss smith has been holed up at the motel since jan. 11, when it was closed by state officials directing the museum project
she ignored a state deadline feb. 8 to move out and likened her protest to civil rights battles staged by king
before the deputies arrived, miss smith talked to reporters and about 10 other spectators through an eight-foot chain link fence that was put up around the site jan. 11
my family is here and i have a home, but that's not what i want,'' she said. ``if i can't live at the lorraine, i'll camp out on the sidewalk out front.''
randy wade, an administrative assistant for the shelby county sheriff's office, said deputies used a tire iron to force open the door to miss smith's room, just three doors down from the room where king was killed
the federal aviation administration will require the boeing co. to install 10 exit doors in its new 747 passenger jetliners, rather than the eight the company prefers, the agency's chief said today
faa administrator allan mcartor told a house subcommittee that for safety reasons, he had decided to issue a final rule that would require the additional doors and expected it to be ready by late summer
a boeing official, however, told the lawmakers that having eight doors would be safe
prudence,'' mcartor said when asked during a break in the hearing about why he had made his decision. ``just a concern of safety.''
boeing plans to soon begin building a new line of the wide-body 747s, whose first generation went into service in 1970. the aircraft, which can carry more than 500 passengers, are the most frequently used jetliners for international travel and are also commonly used for coast-to-coast flights within the united states
there are currently eight-exit versions of the 747s used by foreign airlines, but they carry only 440 passengers
mcartor told the house public works investigations subcommittee that the new rule would require a maximum of 60 feet between exit doors for aircraft flown by u.s. airlines. this would, in effect, require 10 doors in the 747s
in testimony prepared for delivery to the subcommittee, boeing vice president orvil m. roetman contested mcartor's decision
data, tests, in-service experience and analysis all show that the 747 distances between exit doors, with either eight or 10 doors on the main deck, are more than adequate for providing safe evacuation,'' he said
a businessman was accused of diverting more than $8,000 in surplus government food intended for school lunch programs to his catering business and restaurants
siinto wessman, 70, was cited tuesday in a criminal complaint in state district court with two counts of fraud
from 1981 through june 1986, wessman's catering firm, the neal bort co., had contracts with the mountain iron-buhl, biwabik and gilbert school districts to provide hot lunches under the federal child nutrition program
the contracts allowed the catering firm to obtain surplus government commodites, including cheese, hamburger and butter, for use in the school programs
the criminal complaint alleges wessman diverted the food to two restaurants, which have since closed, and to his catering business
the charges are absolutely false,'' wessman said tuesday. ``i don't know anything about it.''
the charges each carry penalties of up to 10 years in prison and a $20,000 fine. pvs, ``the spokesman</note>
president reagan, stepping up american peace efforts in the middle east, today directed secretary of state george p. shultz to return to the region for further talks with arab and israeli leaders
reagan acted after receiving a report from shultz on his four days of diplomatic shuttling in the area and a critical session tuesday in london with king hussein of jordan
all countries in the region believe it is useful for the united states to remain engaged in this process,'' reagan said. ``we will spare no effort in our search for a comprehensive settlement.''
shultz will leave from brussels after the windup of a nato summit meeting thursday. he is expected to make stops in israel, jordan and egypt before returning to washington next weekend
marlin fitzwater, the white house spokesman, told reporters earlier today, ``the president has said on a number of occasions the united states wants a more visible role in the middle east in terms of trying to be helpful, that we were willing and eager to participate in any way that could move the peace process forward.''
the u.s. spokesman said shultz was doing ``yeoman's work'' in trying to promote negotiations
a u.s. official, who demanded anonymity, said hussein had not ``thrown cold water'' on the u.s. initiative but also had not endorsed it
israeli prime minister yitzhak shamir had a similar reaction
if i had to describe the situation, i would say that nobody has signed up to our proposals, but everybody wants us to keep working,'' shultz said tuesday in tel aviv
yossi ben-aharon, director-general of shamir's office, said both jordan and israel had asked shultz to continue his mediation effort, however
shultz saw reagan briefly tuesday night on the president's arrival from washingtoon, but `they really didn't get a chance'' to talk about the middle east, fitzwater said
we will see where it goes from here,'' the u.s. spokesman said. ``there is no decision at this point.''
hussein is demanding an active soviet role in peace talks and participation by the palestine liberation organization as he sole representative of the 1.5 million palestinian arabs who live under israeli control in the west bank and in gaza
shamir, menawhile, refuses to deal with the plo, which is considered to be a terrorist group both by israel and the united states, and wants also to block participation by the soviets, who have backed arab positions in the past and do not have diplomatic relations with israel
shultz has made a point of emphasizing a need for u.s. communications with the palestinians, despite a ban on plo contacts. ``there's not a substitute for directly sitting down with people,'' he said tuesday. ``and that's in a sense what we've been calling for all along.''
the nation's largest dredging company will plead guilty to a charge of rigging bids on army corps of engineers' dredging projects in the gulf of mexico in 1983-84, a company officer confirmed today
great lakes dredging company of oak brook, ill., will pay $4.26 million in fines as part of a plea bargain covering bid-rigging charges filed tuesday against the company in federal courts in new orleans, philadelphia, san francisco and cleveland, said u.s. attorney john volz
as part of the agreement, a subsidiary of great lakes, north american trailing co., also will plead guilty in new orleans to 1986 charges of bid-rigging and submitting false statements to the government, volz said
north american's charges relate to bids submitted on dredging projects let for bid by the corps from 1982-84
itel corp. acquired great lakes in 1985, and with it the legal problems
gary hill, vice president for finances, said today that the plea bargain is the final step in clearing up the problems
the company has been on a `good behavior' program, so to speak, for over a year. that includes a lot of internal safeguards to make sure that never happens again,'' hill said from his illinois office. ``we set them up to establish ourselves once again as a responsible contractor.''
no company officials were named in the charges tuesday, but at least three have entered guilty pleas in the case over the last 18 months
anglican archbishop desmond tutu said today he would try to persuade western governments to break all diplomatic ties with south africa until it eased restrictions on anti-apartheid groups
we want to tell the south african government that they do not deserve to be part of a decent society,'' he said at a news conference
tutu said western nations should cut any diplomatic links with south africa and expel south african diplomats from their countries
britain and america and west germany have kept saying that sanctions hurt blacks and sanctions are not effective,'' he said. ``while not withdrawing my support for economic sanctions, i am saying to britain, west germany and other western countries, `here is your chance.'''
tutu was in the kenyan capital for a meeting of the all-african conference of churches, which he heads
he said he has called in the past for western governments to break relations with pretoria. but he said this time he intended to actively campaign for such a move
my own intention now is to challenge the west to break off diplomatic relations with south africa, to expel south african diplomats from their countries until certain conditions are met,'' the churchman said
those conditions are a lifting of the state of emergency, reversal of a feb. 25 ruling that outlawed political activity by 18 opposition groups, and the release of political detainees, especially children
tutu, winner of the 1984 nobel peace prize, and other churchmen were arrested monday when they attempted to march on the south african parliament at cape town to protest the crackdown on black opposition groups
the rev. allan boesak, president of the world alliance of reformed churches, also was arrested. in an interview with ``cbs this morning'' from harare, zimbabwe, he said it is clear that the government now is outlawing ``all legitimate peaceful activity,'' and that apartheid opponents have no choice but to resist
and if that means confrontation, if that means disobedience to your unjust laws then i think that is exactly what we mean,'' he said. ``we are talking about the possibility of civil disobedience.''
he said non-violent protests have ended in deaths in the past but won't be a deterrent to civil disobedience
we will have to take the risks that go with it and we will have to take the consequences that follow these actions of ours,'' he said. parade</head>
an irish republican army member convicted of killing a british army officer has been selected honorary grand marshal of philadelphia's st. patrick's day parade
after initially rejecting joseph patrick thomas doherty last week, the board of the st. patrick's day observance association reconsidered this week after some members ``vociferously voiced their feelings,'' city councilman and board member francis w. rafferty said tuesday
thomas j. gibson, this year's grand marshal and a charter member of the st. patrick's day association, and other board members had questioned whether any honorary grand marshal should be selected this year for the march 13 parade
i think it takes away from what the parade was organized for,'' said gibson, a southwest philadelphia tavern owner. ``it's a religious parade, a catholic religious parade ... and there's nothing in there (the association constitution) that says we should go in for these kinds of politics.''
doherty, 33, has been held in new york city's metropolitan correctional center since 1983 on charges he illegally entered the country using a false passport after he escaped from a belfast prison
requests by the british government to have doherty extradited have been rejected. he faces a life sentence in northern ireland
the u.s. attorney general began reviewing the case last year, according to doherty's attorney, stephen somerstein
doherty has been named honorary grand marshal in st. patrick's day parades in hartford, conn., and bergen county, n.j., in past years, said somerstein. irish solidarity day in new york was dedicated to him last year, he said
doherty's mother, maureen, is expected to attend the parade, according to vincent scully, doherty's champion in the irish community and the state vice president of the ancient order of hibernians. parade participants will be asked to wear yellow arm bands to show their solidarity with doherty, scully said
we consider him a hostage,'' said scully. ``i don't know him and he doesn't know me, but i can't tolerate another irishman treated like dirt.''
new york city subway gunman bernhard goetz jr. will inherit $140,550 from his father's estate, but the sum will hardly cover legal bills stemming from his 1984 shooting of four teen-agers, a lawyer said
besides four years worth of unpaid legal fees for the shooting in a subway train, goetz is being sued for $63 million by three of the four black teen-agers he shot
the inheritance ``won't go very far in defending him on anything,'' said joseph kelner, who has defended goetz free of charge in the civil cases
kelner also said tuesday that he planned to drop goetz as a client, saying goetz has been ``uncooperative.''
goetz last october was sentenced to six months in jail and five years probation for carrying an unlicensed gun, which he used to shoot the young men. a jury acquitted him of more serious charges, including attempted murder
he is free on $5,000 bond pending appeal
goetz, his brother and two sisters are to share the $562,200.92 remaining in the estate of their father, bernhard willard goetz sr. of orlando, orange county probate court records show
goetz sr., 78, died sept. 4, 1984, the day goetz paid $400 for two 9mm pistols at ken's firearms inc., giving his father's address as his. goetz's father had moved to orlando in 1963 from rhinebeck, n.y., where the family owned a dairy, a bookbinding company and several real estate parcels
a lawyer for one of the shooting victims, james ramseur, welcomed news of goetz's inheritance
i'm surprised,'' said ron kliegerman. ``his attorneys have been telling us all along that he doesn't have a dime. now we know there's something there.''
ramseur's suit seeks $8.5 million, paraplegic darrell cabey is suing goetz for $50 million and troy canty has brought two suits for $2.5 million _ one for negligent injury, the other for intentional injury
the amount of time that will be involved in this case and damages involved obviously will far exceed $150,000,'' kliegerman said. case</head>
the supreme court today gave cities, at least for now, additional protection from lawsuits that accuse lower-ranking city officials of violating the rights of employees
by a 7-1 vote, the justices threw out a $15,000 award st. louis was ordered to pay james j. praprotnik, a fired city architect
but the seven justices voting to overturn the award were sharply split in their reasoning. only four justices joined in the court's main opinion, leaving open the possibility that a future case could prompt a different result
today's ruling, therefore, may leave local officials confused over what standards apply in determining when cities can be held legally responsible for violating individual rights
justice sandra day o'connor, who wrote the court's main opinion, said cities may not be held liable unless those who claim their rights were violated prove the ``existence of an unconstitutional municipal policy.''
she said praprotnik cannot win his case by claiming that high-ranking city officials _ such as the mayor and city aldermen _ failed to override decisions by subordinates who may have violated praprotnik's rights
simply going along with discretionary decisions made by one's subordinates ... is not a delegation to them of the authority to make policy,'' o'connor said
praprotnik was a manager in st. louis' community development agency when in 1980 he became embroiled with his superiors over the proposed installation by the city of a controversial sculpture
praprotnik was suspended for 15 days but the city civil service commission reinstated him with back pay
then in 1982 he was transferred to another city agency, the heritage and urban design division, and his job responsibilities were reduced. the transfer also meant a loss in seniority that exposed him to being laid off
he was fired dec. 30, 1983, a day after he was released from a hospital where he had undergone surgery. the layoff cost him his income, more than 500 hours of accumulated sick leave and other pension and vacation benefits
city officials said he was fired for budgetary reasons
praprotnik then sued under a federal civil rights law, charging he was shunted to a dead-end job and then kicked out because of his appeal to the civil service commission for his suspension back in 1980
a jury awarded him $30,000. the 8th u.s. circuit court of appeals reduced the amount to $15,000
the appeals court said there was sufficient evidence to support praprotnik's claim that he was fired for exercising his constitutional rights
the appeals court said the city was liable, even though the jury exonerated the individual officials sued by praprotnik
o'connor said the appeals court's ruling was too broad in allowing the city to be sued based on decisions made by those who lacked policy-making authority
federal courts are not ``justified in assuming that municipal policy-making authority lies somewhere other than where the applicable (state) law purports to put it,'' she said
in praprotnik's case, she said, that authority rests with the mayor, the city aldermen and the civil service commission
the justices ordered further lower court hearings in the case to determine whether praprotnik still has a viable case
o'connor was joined by chief justice william h. rehnquist and justices byron r. white and antonin scalia
justice william j. brennan, in a separate opinion, said he was worried that the court's main opinion embraces ``a theory of municipal liability that is both unduly narrow and unrealistic and one that ultimately would permit municipalities to insulate themselves from liability for the acts of all but a small minority of actual city policymakers.''
he was joined by justices thurgood marshall and harry a. blackmun
justice john paul stevens dissented, voting to uphold praprotnik's lower court victory. justice anthony m. kennedy, who only recently joined the court, did not take part in the decision
the case is st. louis vs. praprotnik, 86-772
conductor henry sopkin, who started with 100 high school musicians and gradually created the atlanta symphony orchestra, has died. he was 84
sopkin, who lived in palo alto for three years, died of heart failure tuesday after entering stanford university medical center last week
before his retirement in 1966, he was musical director of the symphony for two decades, overseeing more than 1,000 performances and artists including jascha heifetz and benny goodman
a native of the new york city borough of brooklyn, he studied violin as a youth and entered the american conservatory of music in chicago, where he grew up, earning bachelor's and master's degrees in music. in the 1920s and '30s, he taught at the conservatory, at high schools and at woodrow wilson college before he was hired in 1944 to direct the atlanta youth symphony orchestra
with a budget of $5,000, he developed the youth symphony into an adult professional organization with a $300,000 budget 21 years later
after he retired, sopkin was an instructor with the california institute for the arts in the los angeles area, where he lived for 19 years before moving to palo alto
sylvia, his wife of nearly 60 years, died in 1986. survivors include two sons, a brother, two sisters and a grandson. inspection results.</note>
a ship carrying incinerator ash from philadelphia won't be allowed to return to tie up here until there is an agreement about cleaning up 2,000 to 4,000 tons of ash reportedly left in haiti, a lawyer says
bruce phillips, attorney for joseph paolino &amp; sons inc., which has a contract with the city to dispose of the ash, said the khian sea would be allowed to dock at paolino's pier only after there is an agreement on cleaning up the ash in gonaives, haiti
we want an enforceable covenant that the material will be removed from haiti or disposed of in an environmentally sound manner,'' phillips said
robert cordes, president of the ship's operator, amalgamated shipping co. of freeport, bahamas, declined to comment when reached at his office by the philadelphia inquirer
phillips said paolino will not be paid unless it can show the ash has been disposed of legally
the ship had been turned away from six countries while wandering the caribbean and the atlantic seeking a dumping spot. it anchored at the mouth of delaware bay, north of lewes, del., on tuesday
in addition to the question about the ash in haiti, the ship's 80-mile voyage up the delaware river to philadelphia was delayed by inspections and a pier fire
the coast guard refused to allow the ship to proceed until it passed an inpsection by the american bureau of shipping
the coast guard said this morning that the ship passed an inspection conducted tuesday, and that the captain of the port has determined the ship is ``safe to transit u.s. waters,'' the coast guard said
no time was set for the khian sea to travel upriver. its radar system still didn't work and the coast guard said the ship is restricted to daytime traveling
the environmental group greenpeace has labeled the khian sea's cargo toxic. state tests conducted when the ash was loaded found no dangerous levels of toxins, and recent federal tests from the same incinerator came to the same conclusions
the fire department, meanwhile, is investigating a rubbish fire at the paolini pier this morning. the fire damaged a transfer station, a company official said
coast guard spokesman scott miller said the city will appoint an independent engineering firm to determine the safety of the pier and whether the khian sea will be able to dock there
paolino is expected to send the residue to an ohio landfill, where the bulk of the city's ash has been dumped for the past two years, said phillips. considers bill</head>
former first lady rosalynn carter said wednesday that mental illness was america's no. 1 health problem as a house panel opened hearings on a plan to increase spending on care and services for mentally ill senior citizens
the ``elderly mental health initiative'' advanced by rep. edward roybal, d-calif., would increase outlays for community-based services for the elderly and their families, on research into prevention, treatment and services, and on training for health care professionals
it also would lift the lifetime limit on inpatient psychiatric care paid by medicare and expand medicare to cover more outpatient and community-based mental health services. and it would require medicaid to cover community-based services as well
in addition, the roybal bill would create a consumer bill of rights and set up a national mental health education program
now is the time for federal action,'' roybal said in opening a hearing on the subject. ``for far too long, mental health care has been a neglected priority.''
the roybal bill would authorize $161 million in new spending in its first year, most of it to expand mental health grants to states. the money does not include added expenditures under the medicare and medicaid programs, for which roybal did not provide an estimate
according to a report compiled by roybal's house select committee on aging, between 15 percent and 25 percent of americans over 65, about 7 million people, have significant mental health problems. very few receive appropriate care, the report said
mrs. carter and ohio gov. richard celeste told roybal's committee the federal government needs to pay more attention to mental health needs and spend more on them
she called mental health ``america's no. 1 health problem.'' she recommended substantially higher spending channeled through states, improvements in medicare and medicaid coverage, and strengthening of patient advocacy services such as the nursing home ombudsman program
one of my most urgent pleas is for adequate insurance coverage for mental illnesses,'' mrs. carter said. ``i think the congress should do everything possible to assure this coverage. it is is another of our sadly neglected needs.''
celeste stressed the need for community-based services for the elderly and the relatives who take care of them
it is a family and community issue. it impacts on all of us at one time or another,'' he said. ``many of us here today know firsthand the responsibility of caring for an elderly family member.''
rep. claude pepper, d-fla., said more than 25 percent of all suicides are committed by the elderly, ``indicating in many cases the desperation that they feel.'' he also said more than half the patients in nursing homes have alzheimer's disease
it might have sounded corny if said by someone else, someplace else. but this was elizabeth dole, and the praise of her presidential candidate husband struck a pleasing chord with her fellow north carolinians
he kind of reminds me of a laser beam,'' mrs. dole said. ``i'm in awe of the way he can cut through the complexities of a tough issue and come up with an answer.''
the crowd responded with applause and approving smiles
standing atop a platform in the parking lot of a suburban office complex, the former transportation secretary spoke with feeling about the decision she had made days before to relinquish her cabinet post and become a full-time campaigner
this is where my roots are,'' said the one-time debutante and beauty queen from salisbury, n.c. ``this is home. this is where i draw my strength.''
george bush boasts a superior organization and pat robertson has his ``invisible army,'' but bob dole has had his own not-so-secret weapon in the battle for southern votes next week on super tuesday
the weapon, he says, is elizabeth dole _ known as liddy _ whose old-south charm and ivy league credentials propelled her from small-town north carolina to the reagan cabinet. she has shown a talent for holding crowds in the palm of her hand
she's a vivacious, bright, enthusiastic campaigner,'' said haley barbour, a mississippi consultant and former political adviser in the reagan white house. ``i think other southerners will feel a kinship to her.''
mrs. dole agreed last fall to step down as transportation secretary and hit the campaign trail, making what she said was one of the toughest decisions of her life. some feminists complained, saying she had squandered on opportunity to debunk the traditional image of the candidate's wife
but mrs. dole, 51, said there was nothing demeaning about her change of course
i mean, this is a challenging assignment to be discussing national and international issues with the press and the public,'' she said then. ``i will be lucky if i get to see bob very much at all. it is not just standing at his side and smiling.''
she spent the fall crisscrossing the south, speaking at rallies, giving interviews, lining up commitments among gop activists and raising money for the kansas senator
observers say the final vote counts on tuesday may well show vice president bush, not senate republican leader dole, the big winner in the south. but that wouldn't mean mrs. dole failed, they say
she's a charmer, but there's only so much you can do,'' said ted arrington, a republican activist and political scientist at the university of north carolina at charlotte
tim archie, the dole campaign's deputy press secretary, said, ``she laid the groundwork for our presence in the south. she represents the region, can pull in a crowd, and her experience in the administration is useful.''
she's also been credited with helping dole change the image as a slashing campaigner acquired in his 1976 quest for the vice presidency. she speaks of his compassion and courage, qualities she says are most evident close-up
campaign strategists considered mrs. dole's vote-getting potential important enough to hustle her to iowa in the weeks leading up to that state's caucuses _ which dole won
mrs. dole grew up in a small, conservative town in the north carolina piedmont, the only daughter of well-to-do parents. she was a debutante at age 18 and two years later was student body president of the women's college at duke university. she graduated from harvard law school and went to washington, where she spent two decades in various government posts including the federal trade commission
in 1976, shortly after her marriage to dole, she took a leave of absence to help him run for vice president. in 1979, she quit the ftc to join dole's presidential campaign. from outside hospital compound. pick up 5th pvs, `two physicians...'</note>
israeli troops hunting for arab protesters today fired tear gas into the reception area of a hospital emergency room, driving out dozens of elderly patients, doctors said
palestinians hurled firebombs and troops fired tear gas in scattered clashes throughout the night in the occupied west bank and gaza strip, where violent protests have occurred daily since dec. 8
violence erupted for the second consecutive day at the government-run ramallah hospital about eight miles north of jersusalem, the latest in a recent series of intense clashes at medical facilities in the occupied territories
about a dozen israeli troops outside the hospital compound were confronted by rock-hurling palestinian protesters who blocked a nearby street. one smoking canister landed in the reception area of the emergency room and another landed in a hospital courtyard, doctors said
two physicians donned gas masks and others held onions to their noses to blunt the effects of the tear gas, one doctor said. about 30 patients, including elderly people, were driven outside
even the doctors couldn't breathe, so imagine the effects on the patients inside, many of whom are seriously ill,'' said a doctor who spoke on condition of anonymity
arab doctors say injured palestinians often are reluctant to come to hospitals for fear of being arrested by israeli authorities while under treatment
but hospitals also have often become refuges for arab demonstrators fleeing arrest after violent confrontations with soldiers
soldiers detained three youths outside the hospital, including one with a gash on his forehead and bleeding from the shoulder. he was seen being dragged by a soldier
on tuesday, three soldiers had burst into the same hospital, fired tear gas and rubber bullets and struck two doctors with their rifles as they looked for demonstrators, doctors there said
an army spokesman denied soldiers entered the hospital or beat doctors. he said soldiers detained two palestinians, but that the youths were taken into custody at the entrance to the hospital
in the occupied gaza strip, officials at the shifa hospital said israeli sodliers entered the facility overnight and arrested two arab demonstrators accused by israel of trying to run over a soldier with their car
at least 76 palestinians have been killed, mostly by israeli gunfire, and hundreds wounded since dec. 8 in the territories israel seized in the 1967 middle east war
also today, three italian legislators chained themselves to electric poles near ramallah to protest the israeli crackdown. one legislator held a sign saying: ``stop the killing _ yes, to palestinian self-determination.''
israel's right- and left-wing politicians disagreed today about the future of secretary of state george p. shultz's peace initiative after hearing reports of his meeting tuesday with jordan's king hussein in london
shultz had just finished a four-day diplomatic shuttle in the middle east trying to gain acceptance of a formula for talks to deal with palestinian unrest in the occupied lands and an overall arab-israeli settlement
likud legislator dan meridor, a close aide to right-wing prime minister yitzhak shamir, today said israel ``was unhappy because of the positions we are hearing from jordan'' following talks between hussein and shultz in london
king hussein says the plo must be involved in the peace process and he wants a full-scale international conference,'' meridor said on israel television. ``if that's progress, i don't know what going backwards is.''
but former foreign minister abba eban, a legislator from the centrist labor party, said the differences between jordan and israel could be bridged
a deaf man mistaken for an auto theft suspect was clubbed with a nightstick, sparking complaints from his sister and an internal police investigation
we made a mistake, no doubt about it. i don't know what went wrong,'' police spokesman steve cole said tuesday. ``sometimes in the heat of trying to catch somebody, it's going to happen and it's unfortunate that it did
i think (the officer's) main concern was he thought he had somebody that was going to get away from him,'' cole said
jeffery johnson, 21, suffered shoulder bruises monday night
the main thing is he doesn't understand why he was struck. he keeps asking why,'' said his sister, betty matthews, who shares her home with johnson. she filed a complaint with police
the incident began when officer delier diaz gave chase to a car that had refused to pull over. the chase led to an apartment complex, where the car's two occupants parked the vehicle and fled
johnson had just helped two maintenance workers at the complex free a tractor from a ditch when diaz arrived
the officer approached johnson, who raised his hand to his ear _ the signal used by the deaf to indicate they can't hear. diaz ordered him to the ground, said apartment resident elizabeth borreo
jeff put up his hand and the cop just started hitting him,'' mrs. borreo said. ``he hit him with his stick on the leg. jeff bent down to grab his leg, and he hit him again on the left shoulder. then the cop pushed him down.''
she and her husband said diaz held johnson's hands behind his back while another officer handcuffed him and put him in a patrol car
i said, `you got the wrong guy. he lives here and i saw him not five minutes ago,''' apartment manager iris cox said. within 30 minutes, the officers released johnson
later monday, two people were arrested on charges of grand theft auto and resisting arrest without violence
after those arrests, diaz filed a report saying he mistakenly tried to apprenhend johnson, who he thought was ignored his order to lay down
president felix houphouet-boigny says his family is paying for a huge new basilica whose construction has attracted attention during the west african nation's economic crisis
houphouet-boigny told a visiting french boy's choir the government would never pay for construction of a church building because the nation was made up of many religious faiths
the government daily fraternite matin on wednesday quoted the president as saying that ``on the streets, some people are amusing themselves by saying the basilica is financed by the ivorian government.''
it will be a gift from my family to the holy see,'' houphouet-boigny said
the basilica, which will be the second-largest in the world, will be built on land donated by houphouet-boigny to the state in his native yamoussoukro, fraternite matin said
pope john paul ii is scheduled to open the church sept. 10, 1989. it will have 120 arches and a row of columns about 275 yards long. figures on its cost have not been released
the ivory coast has a budget shortfall of more than $600 million, and last year it suspended payments on its international debt
thieves stole five rare paintings from the hometown mansion of ousted president ferdinand marcos, police said wednesday
benjamin guittab, caretaker of the house in batac, northern luzon, said he noticed while cleaning on wednesday that only the frames remained
the burglars apparently climbed a tree and crawled in an open window of a second-floor bedroom during the weekend, police said. there were no suspects
the 4-foot-by-6-foot paintings by 19th century painter juan luna, a national hero, had adorned the marcoses' living room. antique collectors and the curator of the luna shrine near here say the works are priceless
batac mayor jesus nalupta said he visited marcos early this year in honolulu and the former president asked him to look after the house. marcos fled to exile in hawaii following a popular revolt in february 1986 that ended his 20-year authoritarian rule
