leaders of the western alliance today endorsed president reagan's efforts to negotiate new reductions in nuclear arms and demanded sweeping cutbacks in the soviet union's vastly superior conventional forces in europe to rule out a surprise attack
within hours of opening their first summit talks in six years, reagan and leaders of 15 other nato nations declared that soviet conventional forces ``cast a shadow over the whole of europe'' and must be reduced sharply to ease the imbalance in east-west military strength
these proposed cutbacks, they said, ``will entail, for example, the elimination from europe of tens of thousands of warsaw pact weapons relevant to surprise attack, among them tanks and artillery pieces.''
the overall aim of the talks was to demonstrate allied unity in advance of reagan's planned moscow summit meeting with soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev in late may or june. but there were nagging differences among the nato leaders over other nuclear arms issues
reagan, his voice hoarse and rasping from allergies, summoned reporters to the steps of his 19th century palace residence, the chateau stuyvenberg, to read his own statement on the nato declaration. the president called the massive soviet conventional forces ``the most direct threat to our security and to stability in europe.''
he added: ``but arms reductions are not enough. ... we also look for greater respect for human rights and fundamental freedoms on which lasting security and stability in europe ultimately depend.''
reagan seemed undisturbed by frictions among nato leaders about the future of the u.s.-supplied force of short-range nuclear weapons, most of them based in west germany
i have never seen such harmony as we have,'' the president said. he called the statement on european conventional forces ``a major step'' forward for the allies
reagan also announced he was sending secretary of state george shultz back to the middle east after the nato summit ends thursday to press his talks with arab and israeli leaders
all countries in the region believe it is useful for the united states to remain engaged in this process,'' reagan said. ``we will spare no effort in our search for a comprehensive peace settlement.''
at the opening summit session earlier today, reagan sat next to british prime minister margaret thatcher and listened intently as nato secretary general lord carrington pledged the allies' ``full support'' for reagan's drive to reach agreement with the soviets on drastic cuts in strategic nuclear weapons
but, carrington declared, ``the alliance will not rest on its laurels.''
in a six-page statement on conventional forces, the nato leaders said:
the soviet union's military presence in europe, at a level far in excess of its needs for self-defense, directly challenges our security as well as our hopes for change in the political situation in europe
thus, the conventional imbalance in europe remains at the core of europe's security concerns.''
the allied leaders spelled out demands for far bigger cutbacks in soviet conventional forces than in the west's military levels, during negotiations to begin in earnest this fall in vienna, austria, with representatives of the warsaw pact consisting of the soviet union and six east european allies
our aim will be to establish a situation in europe in which force postures as well as the numbers of deployments and weapons systems no longer make surprise attack and large-scale offensive action a feasible option,'' the nato statement said
carrington said the alliance leaders had gathered to celebrate the new u.s.-soviet ban on edium-range missiles, and for ``charting the way ahead'' as gorbachev pursues a peace offensive
one agreement which reduces some weapons, and indeed one new soviet leader who is ready to reduce some tensions, however significant, do not in themselves remove the military capability and potential of the soviet union,'' carrington said
he added that nato's ``collective determination to deploy and maintain a military capacity where necessary were what convinced the soviet union of the better route of arms control and disarmament.''
we wish president reagan and his negotiators well in the effort to secure an agreement on strategic arms reduction, which has the alliance's full support,'' carrington said
reagan was the last of the leaders to arrive at sprawling nato headquarters today for the opening session of two days of summit talks that are expected to stress alliance unity despite differences over nuclear arms strategy
at the first closed meeting, reagan reportedly underlined the u.s. commitment to europe and urged his fellow leaders to guard against soviet attempts to divide the western alliance
it was west german chancellor helmut kohl who touched on a simmering dispute over whether nato members should quickly improve their stocks of short-range nuclear missiles, most of which are deployed in west germany
the load, the risks and the responsibilities of our defense must be equally shared by all members,'' kohl said
kohl's remarks, made public by bonn officials, alluded to the fundamental issue of how the alliance can fill the gap left by the reagan-gorbachev agreement last december to eliminate ground-launched, intermediate-range nuclear misiles from europe
senior nato officials drafting a final communique to be published thursday sought to bridge differences ranging from west germany's reluctance to britain's enthusiasm for a swift decision on modernization to internal divisions over the issue within the french government
looking toward soviet-american arms talks, carrington said an improved soviet human rights record was fundamental to creating ``the confidence necessary to proceed with a radical arms control agenda.''
he added: ``for most of us in the west that cause (of tension) is the degree of mistrust created by the denial of basic human rights and freedom to the peoples of eastern europe and the soviet union.''
carrington reaffirmed nato's commitment supporting a proposed superpower agreement to reduce long-range nuclear weaponry by 50 percent on both sides. he said nato also looked forward to ``a more serious engagement'' with the soviet-led warsaw pact on a chemical weapons ban and reducing the eastern bloc's superiority in conventional arms
as the meeting began, white house spokesman marlin fitzwater reported that ``progress is fine'' on drafting a statement of common alliance goals to be issued at the conclusion of the two-day summit
reagan, who reached brussels coughing and complaining of allergies, ws to spend 2 1-2 hours conferring with the 15 other heads of state or government. when he arrived tuesday, the president tried to allay concerns over the warsaw pact's advantage in conventional forces by promising to keep u.s. troops in europe ``as long as europeans want them to stay.''
police arrested people involved in ethnic rioting in a southern republic, the official media said today, and the government acknowledged that others may have been killed during the massive unrest
a radio station and newspaper in baku, the capital of azerbaidzhan, reported also that the republic's premier, gasan n. seidov, had traveled to the affected area
the unrest has been stopped. businesses and establishments of trade and public eating are working in a normal rhythm and classes are taking place in schools and other educational establishments,'' the baku worker newspaper reported
the newspaper's article, referring to the azerbaidzhan city of sumgait, was read to the associated press by soviet foreign ministry spokesman gennady i. gerasimov
order and peace have been ensured by law enforcement organs. people caught in the unrest have been detained,'' the baku worker newspaper reported
gerasimov said in a telephone interview that he could not confirm rumors circulated by armenian activists that as many as 20 people had been killed in sumgait. but he added, ``there was hooliganism and there can be deaths in such cases.''
on tuesday, gerasimov told a news briefing that authorities clamped a curfew on sumgait. he suggested the unrest in sumgait, and demonstrations and violence elsewhere in the caucasus region in which at least two people died, were due to a ``mistake'' made 65 years ago when a territory composed largely of armenians was made part of neighboring azerbaidzhan
he said ``there were certain injuries'' in sumgait, an industrial city of more than 160,000 people in azerbaidzhan where hooligans were blamed for touching off the sunday riot
the situation is calm there today, but it is tense,'' gerasimov said at the tuesday briefing
moscow-based foreign journalists have been barred from the region, and only sporadic reports from witnesses, activists and the official media have reached the soviet capital. most telephone calls placed to baku and sumgait today did not go through
a man answering the telephone at the ministry of internal affairs in baku said ``everything is over'' when asked about the unrest in sumgait. the conversation was cut off before a reporter could ask the person's name and position
baku radio, monitored by the london-based british broadcasting corp., reported today that two non-voting members of the national ruling politburo, georgy p. razumovsky and pyotr n. demichev, had visited businesses and other establishments in baku to speak to the ``working people of these multinational collectives.''
it did not say when the tour occurred or say whether the two officials also went to sumgait. they had visited the armenian capital, yerevan, last week during demonstrations there
asked about reports that soviet tanks are patrolling the streets of sumgait, that ethnic azeris are attacking armenians in the streets and that there have been at least two deaths in the city, gerasimov told the briefing,``there is a curfew,'' but that he had not heard anything about tanks being sent into the city
asked if troops remained in the city tuesday, gerasimov said: ``i don't know, but i guess so. presumably.''
the violence in sumgait, reported monday by tass, the official soviet news agency, followed earlier outbreaks 150 miles away in nagorno-karabakh, the contested region in azerbaidzhan, and massive but apparently peaceful demonstrations in yerevan, the capital of armenia
hovik vassilian said in a telephone interview today that he and other armenian activists were angry that the official media reported that the unrest had been quelled. he said he heard from travelers and from telephone calls to residents of the region that demonstrations were continuing in nagorno-karabakh and that food was in short supply
the demonstrators demanded that nagorno-karabakh, part of azerbaidzhan since 1923, be made part of armenia. more than three-quarters of the region's population of 157,000 are ethnic armenians
on saturday, a soviet prosecutor reported that two people living in a region of azerbaidzhan that borders on nagorno-karabakh had been slain in unrest caused by the territorial dispute
on friday, soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev appealed for restraint in azerbaidzhan and armenia and promised that the communist party central committee would review relations among the soviet union's more than 100 nationalities
predominantly moslem azerbaidzhan is the largest of three soviet republics in the caucasus. it is bordered on the west by largely christian armenia and georgia and on the north by the russian republic. the caspian sea runs for nearly 800 miles along its eastern edge
a federal safety agency filed a civil complaint wednesday seeking to force the recall of a device intended to help fishermen collect worms, but which it says could wind up electrocuting the anglers instead
the consumer product safety commission said it wants to halt sales of the worm gett'r made by p&amp;m enterprises of caldwell, idaho
directory information showed no listing for p&amp;m enterprises in caldwell
the device uses metal probes on wooden handles and is tied together by an electric wire, the commission said. when the probes are inserted into the ground, electric current passed through the wire drives worms to the surface
but the commission said the design exposes users to the bare metal charged with electricity and thus could lead to a dangerous shock
no injuries have been reported involving the device, but there have been 23 deaths since 1971 involving other brands of similarly designed worm probes, the agency reported
about 30,000 worm gett'r devices were sold nationally over the past five years at prices ranging from $8 to $30, the commission said
the commission asked that consumers who have been injured, or know of others who have had mishaps involving any type of worm probe, to call it at 1-800-638-2772. for two others.</note>
a man armed with two guns leaped out of a taxicab and opened fire on a crowded street today, wounding four people before being shot moments later, police said
witnesses said the gunman got out of a taxicab after arguing with the driver of another vehicle and began firing repeatedly about a half-block from the hyatt regency hotel, which is about five blocks from the alamo
i saw there was a confrontation with the man in another vehicle. he pulled out a gun and started firing,'' said tod tarble, 20, who witnessed the 9 a.m. incident from a bus stop about 90 feet away
there were people all around the street who were trying to get up there when everybody was being shot, but i tried to keep them back,'' he said
a 55-year-old man believed to be the gunman was being treated at medical center hospital for a gunshot wound to his left thigh, spokeswoman inez eisazadeh said. his condition was not known, she said
another victim was being treated at medical center hospital for a wound to her right knee, and another was treated at brooke army medical center for multiple gunshot wounds. a third was taken to baptist memorial hospital with a leg wound, and the fourth to nix hospital, also with a leg wound
after the initial shots, the gunman ``heard the sirens and began running. a downtown foot patrolman and a park ranger confronted him,'' police sgt. paul buske said
the man apparently was out of shells in one of his guns, and was trying to reload while attempting to shoot with the other one,'' he said. ``the officers returned fire, and the man was struck in the upper leg.''
buske said he didn't know whether bullets from the officers' guns or from the gunman's struck the man
tarble said that when the gunman, who was a passenger in the taxi, began firing, the taxi driver and the driver with whom the gunman had argued both tried run away
the gunman got out of the car, shot a passer-by in the leg, fired two shots at a woman trying to hunker down in her car's front seat and fired again at a passing station wagon, hitting the driver
he then went around a corner, shot at another person and was then felled by gunfire, buske said. third day</head> add details of zuniga's arrest. pick up 8th graf pvs: `he was...' edits thereafter to conform</note>
doctors stopped treating patients and industry and construction halted today as a strike protesting the rule of gen. manuel noreiga picked up support despite a violent crackdown on tuesday
most stores in the downtown commercial zone were open, but many outside the area closed
in washington, a lawyer for a panamanian opposition group said the state department was preparing to notify all u.s. banks where the panamanian government has deposits not to engage in any transactions with the regime that seized power last week
william d. rogers said the state department action would require the banks to make payments only to the ambassador who represented the deposed government of president eric arturo delvalle. the state department did not immediately confirm rogers' statement
on tuesday, security agents armed with shotguns ransacked a radio station that defied censors by broadcasting news and backing the strike. a former presidential candidate also was roughed up
the raid by a score of state security agents shattered the uneasy calm that had marked the organized protest strike that began monday to seek the ouster of noriega, panama's military strongman
the station was totally destroyed,'' said the owner, carlos ivan zuniga, who ran unsuccessfully for president in 1984. ``it will return to the air when there is democracy in panama.''
many doctors appeared to have joined the strike today. most of the main hospitals were staffing only their emergency rooms, a check of major hospitals and clinics showed
zuniga was seen being arrested with his son, carlos, and two other people
security agents pulled zuniga by the hair, forced his head down and shoved him hard into a vehicle. his shirt was almost torn off as he struggled against the agents
the car was blocked by another vehicle and zuniga, a white-haired man of about 60, fled down the street with his torn shirt fluttering and security men in pursuit
he was captured and later released and said he was unhurt. the other three were kicked, punched and beaten with truncheons
at least three people were wounded by birdshot, none seriously
security agents confiscated the exposed film of several news photographers, including the tampa tribune's allyn divito, who had a pistol held to his head until he surrendered his film
at a news conference following his release, zuniga called the attack an ``act of official state gangsterism.'' he estimated damage to his station, radio mundial, at $100,000. the station is also known as radio 10-fm
shortly before the attack, zuniga said, the station broadcast an appeal to residents of the capital to demonstrate peacefully against the government by waving white hankerchiefs, honking their car horns and banging on pots and pans each day at noon and 6 p.m
that was in defiance of government censors' orders that the station only play music
about 15 people were handing out anti-government leaflets outside the station when the security agents arrived suddenly in four four-wheel drive vehicles with darkly tinted windows
the agents bolted from the vehicles, firing shotguns and revolvers in the air, quickly dispersed the leaflet distributors and charged into the station, smashing equipment and furniture
the station is housed in the offices of the popular action party, which zuniga heads, and is in a middle-class neighborhood. at the first sounds of gunfire, about 150 neighbors poured into the street, many of them waving white banners and taunting the agents
young men threw rocks at the security men and set up barricades of burning trash on the street outside the station and several sidestreets. order was not restored for several hours
as word of the attack on radio mundial spread, barricades went up on streets elsewhere in the city, but there was no further violence
leaders of the national civic crusade, a wide coalition of business, professional, labor and political groups that organized the nationwide strike, claimed tuesday night that the action halted 85 percent of the country's economic activity
crusade leaders said they would meet today to decide whether to continue the action
after noriega's former second-in-command went public last june with charges the general was involved in vote fraud, corruption and political assassination, the crusade organized several large demonstrations
noriega, chief of panama's 17,000-member defense forces, sent troops into the streets with guns, billy clubs and tear gas to break up last summer's protests. three people were killed and scores injured
crusade leaders deny their goal is to restore delvalle to the presidency. national assembly ousted delvalle on friday for trying to fire noriega
noriega, who has run the country since 1983, was indicted in the united states last month for trafficking in colombian cocaine. delvalle had said last thursday that the general should step down while the charges were investigated
until he tried to fire noriega, delvalle was widely seen as the general's puppet. the reagan administration says it still recognizes delvalle's presidency
hours after he was dismissed, delvalle went into hiding. he has not been seen publicly, but has issued statements calling for an international trade embargo against panama to stop the cash flow. up 6th graf pvs: this by-election ...</note>
an extreme right-wing party opposing all concessions to blacks was favored today as voters began the process of filling two vacant seats in the white chamber of parliament
the conservative party was expected to win the seats in the districts of standerton and schweizer-reneke, despite an aggressive campaign waged by president p.w. botha's governing national party
the turnout was expected to exceed 70 percent in both districts. more than 15,000 people were eligible to vote in schweizer-reneke and more than 22,000 in standerton
the conservative party seeks to reinstate all rescinded apartheid laws and charges that botha is capitulating to the country's 26 million black majority through his limited reforms in recent years
the conservatives have been gaining ground in standerton and schweizer-reneke, rural districts in transvaal province, at the expense of the national party. in parliament's white chamber, the national party has firm control with 133 seats to 20 for the conservatives
in last may's whites-only general election, the conservative party captured both the standerton and schweizer-reneke seats, but they became vacant when the incumbents resigned
this by-election campaign illustrates the degree to which white politics has become a struggle on the right. the anti-apartheid progressive federal party did not field candidates and demands of black activists and foreign critics are dismissed as irrelevant
the choice is between bad and worse,'' said business day, the leading financial daily. ``it may be an appalling thought, but the growing power of the extreme right is so serious a threat that we believe the conservative party has to be opposed at every turn, even if it means voting for nationalists.''
the star of johannesburg described schweizer-reneke as an area ``where blacks are seen and not heard. when they are seen it is largely in terms of service to whites.''
both parties campaigned aggressively, revealing the widening rift among right-wing afrikaners
last year, the conservative party drew 26 percent of the vote nationwide and its support is growing, particularly in rural areas. it is favored to win another special election in transvaal later this month
the conservative party has close links to the afrikaner resistance movement, a paramilitary, white-supremacist group which is taking an increasingly confrontational stance against the government
last saturday, 5,000 movement members, many armed and wearing khaki uniforms, staged a boisterous rally in pretoria and then marched to government buildings with a petition demanding creation of a whites-only state
conservative party leader andries treurnicht, in a televised debate monday, refused to repudiate the movement
treurnicht told f.w. de klerk, a cabinet minister who heads the national party in transvaal: ``i defend the right of an organization to join me in resisting the dangerous course you are taking.''
the national party, in power since 1948, says the conservative party's goal of returning to strict apartheid is unrealistic. botha advocates limited power-sharing, with blacks gaining a say in national politics while whites retain control. under apartheid, the white minority controls the country and keeps blacks in separate districts, schools and health services
speaking last week in standerton, botha called for unity among afrikaners _ who comprise 3 million of the country's 5 million whites _ and said the national party would protect white interests
we are not prepared to sell out south africa to marxist revolutionaries,'' botha said. ``we are prepared to fight for our country
why are we (afrikaners) cutting each others' throats when our enemy is waiting?'' he asked
in an hour-long speech before about 1,000 people, botha did not mention the government bans imposed last week that forbid political activity by 18 black opposition groups. nor did he speak of any future race reforms
the star said in an editorial tuesday: ``to pacify right-wingers, the government has cracked down on black activists .... the nationalists have abandoned any commitment to reform.''
treurnicht spoke in standerton the same night as botha, drawing a crowd of about 1,400. he said the national party was capitulating to the 26 million black majority
when you share power you are no longer in control,'' treurnicht said. ``we don't want blacks in our parliament and we don't want to sit with them in theirs.''
south africa's parliament has separate chambers for whites, asians and people of mixed race. blacks are excluded
treurnicht dismissed the recent crackdown as an election gimmick, saying it was too little, too late
botha, meanwhile, said he was not a ``bad afrikaner'' simply because he was willing to meet with ``reasonable'' black leaders
one has to be realistic,'' he said. ``this country consists not only of whites ... is there a farmer who can produce without black labor? is there an industrialist who can produce without black workers?''
federal reserve board chairman alan greenspan said today that deep cuts in ``entitlement'' programs, which include social security and medicare, may be the most realistic way for cutting the federal budget deficit
greenspan, testifying before the senate budget committee, also called for a 15-cent-a-gallon increase in the federal gasoline tax
but he said that, in general, tax increases do not appear to be a feasible way for trimming the budget shortfall, which was $150 billion last year
there are upside limits to the share of income that can be taxed,'' greenspan said
he also said he saw little opportunity for further major cuts in military spending, or in crucial federal programs such as the prison and air control system
that leaves little left for budget cuts beyond entitlement programs, which now make up about half of the federal budget
entitlement programs are automatic-benefit social programs, in which increases are tied to the rate of inflation
simple arithmetic points clearly to those areas where the scope for action is greatest,'' greenspan testified
even though trimming social security and other benefit programs would be politically difficult, greenspan told the panel that ``entitlement programs offer substantial opportunities for long-term budgetary savings.''
all the alternatives are known. the choices are political, not economic,'' greenspan testified. he appeared as the panel considered president reagan's $1.09 trillion budget for the fiscal year that begins next oct
in other testimony, greenspan said:
_ trade deficit improvements, led by higher import prices and surging exports, would continue even at current exchange-rate levels of the dollar
_ there was some danger of increased inflation in the coming months from higher prices, but that these increases do ``not appear to be on the order of a magnitude that should cause concern.''
_ that ``there are no secret agreements'' among industrial nations involving interest rate levels in the united states that might be needed to support the goal of stabilizing the u.s. dollar at its current exchange-rate value
an aids-stricken prostitute was acquitted today of two counts of attempted poisoning for selling his tainted blood to a blood bank
as the verdict was announced, joseph markowski, a 29-year-old transient, rolled his eyes upward and nodded to his attorney, guy o'brien
jurors, who deliberated seven hours over two days, came to a decision tuesday, but the verdict was sealed until today because o'brien was unable to be in court
markowski was charged with two counts of attempted poisoning for selling his blood for $10 to plasma production associates on june 22 and for trying to do so again june 25
he was arrested june 23 after screaming, ``kill me! kill me! i have aids!'' in a hollywood bank while trying to grab a security guard's gun. when police arrested markowski, they found the receipt for the plasma center
deputy district attorney antonio barreto jr. said markowski knew his blood could infect others but didn't care
but the defense said he had no intention of harming anyone
he made these donations for one reason and one reason only. he was broke and he was destitute and he was homeless and he was desperate,'' o'brien said
district attorney ira reiner originally charged markowski with attempted murder. but superior court judge ronald coen dismissed those counts, saying the law required a specific intent to kill that was not present in the case
markowski, who has acknowledged being a homosexual prostitute, was tested positive for the presence of the deadly aids virus. he has appeared pale and emaciated during his trial
