like many of his fellow cuban-americans, agustin aguero is republican and staunchly anti-communist
the vice president and manager at florida national bank's little havana branch calls himself a moderate conservative and voted for president reagan in 1980 and again in 1984
but aguero is among the growing ranks of well-educated and politically sophisticated cuban-americans who will require more from presidential candidates than fierce anti-communist rhetoric
we cubans are anti-communist, but that isn't our only goal,'' said aguero, who left behind cuba and fidel castro 17 years ago
in the waning days before super tuesday, when 20 states including florida will hold presidential primaries and caucuses, cuban-americans are weighing their options with a heavy tilt toward vice president george bush
more than two-thirds of the 165,274 cuban-american voters registered in dade county are republicans, according to the dade county elections department
since the 1984 presidential elections, the republican party in dade has added more than 42,000 cuban-americans to its rolls
in tampa, the cuban-american community, made up mostly of second-and third-generation cubans and some who have been around since the turn of the century, tends to vote democratic, according to the hillsborough county elections department, which keeps no record of the ethnic breakdown among parties
but the much larger and politically mobilized cuban-american community in miami is clearly dominated by republican fervor
here, bush appears to be the ticket for most cuban-americans. he has made regular forays here and has a strong organization headed by gov. bob martinez and his son, jeb, who is the state secretary of commerce
bush could conceivably capture about 70 percent of the cuban vote, said dade county republican party chairman carlos salman. a recent poll of south florida hispanics showed bush the choice of 81 percent, with the other gop candidates far back in single digits
pat robertson cannot be counted out, however. he has made a serious pitch for the cuban-american vote, criticized castro as a ``butcher'' and his claim that there are soviet nuclear weapons in cuba fell on receptive ears here
but the former television evangelist's recent anti-communist appeals apparently aren't being taken very seriously, and some say his impact on the cuban vote will be negligible
i think the cubans are very sophisticated ... they can see when people are saying things just to cater to them,'' said jaime suchlicki, director of the institute of inter-american studies at the university of miami. ``they prefer truth and candor, not political sloganism.''
bush's ties to the reagan administration could hold negatives, suchlicki said
there has been an enormous amount of disillusionment vis-a-vis nicaragua,'' he said
as well, immigration policy also has been a sore point, with a reversal in the special treatment once accorded cubans by the immigration and naturalization service
there is definitely a great deal of disappointment,'' said eddie levy rodriguez, former president and founder of the cuban american democrats association, ``with the way immigration (officials) and the state department are treating the cubans from mariel and ... the fact that (cuba and the united states) are talking constantly, even though reagan promised he would never deal with castro.''
foreign policy remains a top concern of cuban-americans, but increasingly they say their other interests are not being addressed, including but not limited to, issues such as the economy, housing and unemployment
aguero said the new generation of cubans, who don't harbor notions of ever going back to cuba, simply have different ideals. they consider themselves americans first and cubans second, he said
levy said the number of cuban-american democrats is growing, and he said massachusetts gov. michael dukakis should fare well among them
but most of the cuban-american population still votes republican
we feel the republicans have done more for the things we like,'' salman said. ``since ronald reagan is president of the united states we have not lost one country to communism. we also are interested in being able to have better lives, better jobs, low interest, low inflation and high employment. republicans do this more often and better than the democrats.''
a mutiny broke out on among usually meek and patient london commuters, with passengers refusing orders to leave their delay-plagued subway train until its driver took them to their destination
only about a dozen rebellious passengers were involved in the tuesday night incident on the ``tube,'' as the subway system is known, but london regional transport said it was unprecedented, given the meek and humble nature of the british commuter
to the london evening standard newspaper, it was ``the great tube revolt,'' and the mutineers' unidentified leader was ``a superhero in the clark kent mold _ quiet, mild-mannered and unassuming.''
the excitement generated by the incident reflected not only the frustrations of riding the system's aging northern line, but the amazement of londoners at the prospect of british commuters abandoning their fabled reserve and making a public fuss
a similar incident occurred in new york city's subway system in april 1985, when about a dozen commuters refused to leave a disabled train until they were taken from it by transit police
london regional transport accused the tube mutineers of being selfish
spokesman david morris said the problem began with delays caused by a signal failure. passengers bound for high barnet, at the end of the northern line, were told to disembark five stations before their destination and wait for the next train
they started filing off, but then, according to the standard, a ``mild-looking and well-dressed'' passenger declared: ``i've had enough. i'm staying put. if we all do it, they'll have to take the train on.''
about a dozen passengers got back into the train, it said. more passengers followed, and after hurried consultations the staff bowed to the pressure and sent the train on
morris said that had the passengers done as they were told, the next train would have taken them to high barnet, while the first train could have turned back to collect passengers in central london who had been delayed by the earlier signal failure
we had an overall picture of what was happening,'' he told the associated press. ``those passengers had only a narrow and selfish view and put their needs above others.''
passenger sheila golding of high barnet was quoted by the standard as saying the mutineers were cheering and laughing, because ``we knew that if everyone did it _ and stayed put _ there wasn't anything they could do about it.''
another passenger, maria gama, was quoted as saying: ``everybody was just totally fed up. the waiting room was freezing and nobody could tell us why the train was stopping where it did. but when everybody climbed back on, it was a marvelous moment.''
the northern line, parts of which are more than a century old, carries 700,000 passengers a day and serves 50 stations between south and north london
dubbed ``the misery line'' by newspapers, it is attacked for defective trains and equipment, last-minute schedule changes, signal failures and dirty stations. it is to have a major modernization in the 1990s
morris denied the line was worse than others but conceded that some employees can be rude. ``they know what they're up against and they probably don't look forward to coming to work any more than passengers look forward to using the line,'' he said
by putting new emphasis on the threat to europe from soviet tanks and troops, western leaders hope to blunt moscow's drive to capitalize on splits within nato on nuclear arms strategy
in a joint statement wednesday, leaders of the western alliance called on the soviet union and its allies to begin negotiations aimed at eliminating the east's capability for launching a surprise attack in europe
they said soviet non-nuclear forces facing nato are far in excess of moscow's needs for self defense and ``cast a shadow over the whole of europe.''
president reagan called the declaration ``a major step forward for the alliance.''
the idea is to portray the north atlantic treaty organization as united in calling for fewer non-nuclear weapons at a time when the alliance members cannot agree how far to go in scrapping atomic arms
the nato initiative also shifts the public spotlight away from west germany's dispute within the alliance over whether and when to replace very short-range nuclear weapons with new, more effective ones. most of these weapons, if used, would strike german soil, east or west
the main nato theme is that the soviet-led warsaw pact's numerical superiority in conventional weapons and troops _ not the existence of nuclear arms in europe _ is the greatest danger to western security
according to western estimates, the warsaw pact holds about a 3-to-1 advantage in tanks and artillery and nearly a 2-to-1 edge in combat aircraft and troops, including reserves in the soviet union. moscow contends that east-west conventional forces are roughly equivalent
the stress on conventional arms, nato hopes, will steal some of the momentum from soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev's campaign to woo the european public with calls for ridding their continent of all nuclear weapons
nato leaders agree that some nuclear arms are needed in europe to deter attack
gorbachev appears to have significantly improved his public image in western europe by agreeing last year to a longstanding u.s. proposal to eliminate all intermediate-range nuclear weapons, based mostly in europe
the 16 nato nations have strongly endorsed this deal, known as the inf treaty. the senate is expected to ratify the treaty this spring
but in the aftermath of the inf deal, the alliance has fallen into disagreement over whether to press immediately for east-west negotiations to reduce a large soviet edge in short-range nuclear missiles. west germany, which is most directly threatened by these weapons, wants such talks to start soon; most of the other nato allies do not
the brussels nato summit was not expected to discuss this quandry in detail, much less find a solution. instead, a key aim of the meeting was to turn the public's attention to other aspects of east-west relations, including human rights and non-nuclear arms talks
the nato members and the seven warsaw pact nations have been working for a year to agree on the framework for a new set of negotiations to establish a more stable balance of conventional forces in europe
these talks, likely to begin this fall, would replace a narrower set of east-west negotiations on cutting troop levels, which began in 1973. after 15 years, these talks have not produced a single agreement
nato members hope the new negotiations would focus more directly on warfighting equipment as well as troops. these talks also would encompass the full european area, from the atlantic to the ural mountains. the old troop talks were limited to the central front
even though the western allies acknowledge that it may take years to reach a meaningful agreement on conventional forces, they hope the drive to reach the bargaining table will put nato back on the diplomatic offensive
organization for the associated press. abuse</head>
children at a hare krishna commune have been subjected to sexual abuse and forced into communal marriages, according a court petition filed by a former sect member seeking custody of her children
the petition was filed with the state supreme court, which gave no immediate answer tuesday to the appeal by christina mills, a former hare krishna member who claims her children are in danger at the religious sect's west virginia commune
mills alleges that new vrindaban, the nation's largest krishna community, is fraught with polygamy, child molestation and sexual abuse, her lawyer told the court tuesday
mills, now a legal secretary in san antonio, texas, is asking the high court to remove her three children, ages 2, 3 and 6, from their father's care at new vrindaban
these children have no protection today but in this court,'' lawyer david gold told justices
the northern west virginia community is the target of several federal and state investigations
a family law master had ruled that the children were in jeopardy at the commune, but a circuit judge stayed that order at the request of the children's father, dennis gorrick. mills is appealing that stay
gorrick's attorney, james lees, said the family law master has issued a gag order on the case and he could not discuss it
members of the commune have faced criminal charges, including murder and manslaughter charges against fringe members of the commune, and child molestation charges against two former commune teachers. the sect's leader, kirtanananda swami bhaktipada, recently was found innocent of arson charges, although another commune member was convicted in the case
the krishnas have denied any wrongdoing and have accused authorities of harassment
mills' petitions make a broad range of allegations against the krishna community
gorrick ``has been simultaneously `married' to the petitioner and other women, said marriages being ordered by the swami,'' according to the petition
children at new vrindaban ``have been subject to sexual abuse by the very teachers entrusted with their safety and well-being. said abuse includes the repeated and systematic oral and anal homosexual rape of school children at said school by the headmaster,'' according to the court petition
parents who have confronted the swami about said sexual abuse have been advised by said swami that, `sex is sex,''' the petition states
authorities at (new vrindaban) regularly contribute to the delinquency of minors, by forcing girls ... to drop out of school and marry ... as young as the age of 12 years,'' the petition states
gorrick, whom mills calls the commune's chief fund-raiser, ``has directly caused or contributed'' to the alleged practice of using commune children as young as 11 to solicit donations, according to the petition
a juvenile court judge ordered a psychiatric evaluation for a 13-year-old boy who chopped off his uncle's hand at the uncle's request
juvenile judge kenneth turner said tuesday that the youth was charged with mayhem, the crime of cutting off a body part of another, after he chopped off his uncle's hand sunday at the man's home in lakeland, near memphis
shelby county sheriff's department inspector buck wood said the uncle, james veazey, 33, had a history of treatment for mental problems. wood said the man told his nephew he had rabies in the hand and asked him to chop it off
sgt. travis taylor said the youth had said veazey had repeatedly asked him to cut off the hand. ``i got tired of listening to it and got on with it,'' taylor quoted the youth as saying
the boy used a single-blade ax to cut off the hand and then threw it into a garbage can, retrieving the hand only when a neighbor doubted his tale of cutting it off
veazey had prepared a bucket of hydrogen peroxide and water to treat the stump of his arm, taylor said
neighbors called an ambulance and the sheriff's department after they were shown the hand
veazey was taken to the regional medical center for surgery, then transferred to memphis veterans medical center
taylor said relatives told him veazey had himself chopped off a finger of the hand in the shelby county jail last year
the severed hand could not be reattached, taylor said
vietnam on wednesday returned to the united states what are believed to be remains of 17 american servicemen missing in action in the vietnam war, a u.s. official said
the vietnamese also turned over written reports on three other missing americans, said lt. col. paul mather, leader of a u.s. military team that received the remains in a ceremony at hanoi's noi bai airport
the return was the largest in two years and the fourth largest since the war ended in april 1975 with a communist victory over the u.s.-backed south vietnam government
the largest return was in august 1985, when 26 sets of remains were returned
mather said some of the remains received wednesday involved cases of highest priority to the united states
mather said a u.s. honor guard saluted under chilly, overcast skies as the metal caskets of remains, each draped with a folded american flag, were loaded onto a c-141 transport plane for the flight to hawaii. the names attached to the remains were not released
they will be analyzed there by the army central identification laboratory to see if they belong to any of the nearly 1,800 americans listed as missing in action from the vietnam war
mather said some of the names that the vietnamese provided, along with the remains and written reports, are among a list of 70 that the united states considers of highest priority
retired gen. john w. vessey, acting as a u.s. presidential emissary, handed over the list of names during a mission to hanoi in august
the united states says that in these ``discrepancy cases,'' there is compelling evidence that vietnamese authorities at some level know what happened to the missing men. evidence includes photographs of captured americans who never emerged from prisoner of war camps
mather said the remains were mostly of airmen. most missing airmen were shot down during bombing missions in north vietnam
the vietnamese told mather they would start the next round of ``technical talks'' on mias on march 12. during these talks, which hanoi has agreed to hold six times annually, experts of both sides discuss ways of retreiving remains, locating warplane crash sites and related issues
wednesday's turnover was the third since hanoi agreed during vessey's visit to break a deadlock and resume efforts to account for american mias
the united states pledged then to look into vietnam's own humanitarian problems. an official u.s. medical team flew to hanoi on wednesday to continue that mission, said the spokesman of the u.s. embassy in bangkok, ross petzing
three previous medical teams have studied the plight of disabled war veterans and other humanitarian cases and made recommendations on how private u.s. charitable organizations can aid rehabilitation programs
washington has encouraged private assistance but refused vietnamese requests for direct u.s. government aid. the united states has withheld diplomatic recognition and official aid to protest vietnam's military occupation of cambodia
the 3{-year-old girl who received five organs in a landmark transplant operation is progressing ``with no major bumps'' in her recovery four months after the surgery, hospital officials said wednesday
tabatha foster, from madisonville, ky., was reported still in serious condition in a private room of children's hospital of pittsburgh
tabatha underwent surgery ending nov. 1 to replace her liver, pancreas, small intestine and parts of her stomach and colon. she suffered from short gut syndrome, a congenital defect, and would have died without the transplant, according to doctors
her recovery has really been somewhat uneventful,'' said hospital spokeswoman lynn mcmahon. ``she is really progressing fine. there have been no major bumps along the way.''
tabatha is still being fed intravenously, through a special pump to her stomach, and by mouth with a special baby food formula, according to miss mcmahon. the girl has never eaten solid food
tabatha's surgeons said they have no precedent for feeding such a patient. two other patients underwent similar operations in the united states in recent years, but they died within a few days
her mother, sandra, is at her bedside daily, miss mcmahon said
president reagan appealed for donations and prayers for the girl in his weekly radio address jan. 23. reagan also contributed $1,000 to a special fund for her medical bills
eds: tabatha foster fund, heritage national bank, 401 smithfield st., pittsburgh, pa 15222
a judge who orders some juvenile offenders to go to the library and read as a condition of probation says he harbors no illusions that it will help everyone. he'd settle for one out of four
i understand that a good number of young people will laugh at this,'' baltimore circuit judge john carroll byrnes said in a recent interview. ``some will try, but will fall by the wayside when they get back in with their buddies in their environment. and others simply won't be able, intellectually
but i'm convinced that a significant minority, once coerced into reading, will be so attracted by the experience that it will change their lives. i'm optimistic that we can do it. if we can reach 25 percent of the youthful offenders we see, i'd call this plan a roaring success.''
the judge, who splits his time between juvenile court and the city's circuit court, said he has made reading a part of probation since he came on the bench about five years ago. an ad hoc committee of librarians, educators and parole and probation officers was formed a year ago and hopes to have a formal list of suitable titles, basically from the junior high school level, by the end of the year
some of the suggested titles include ``i am the darker brother'' by arnold adoff, ``westmark'' by lloyd alexander, ``anna to the infinite power'' by mildred ames, ``curse of the blue figurine'' by john bellairs, ``sounder'' by william a. armstrong, and ``are you there god? it's me, margaret'' by judy blum
byrnes also said he has restricted television viewing as a condition of probation in some cases. ``it's interesting _ no matter what you say before that, they shudder when i come to the one about television,'' he said
police on wednesday arrested a bricklayer in connection with a mafia-linked shooting that left two men dead and two injured in a coffee bar, italian media reported
police said they weren't sure how many attackers burst into the bar, in a central square, on tuesday night and began shooting, first at giuseppe postorino, 43, who fell mortally wounded, then at three others, the ansa news agency reported
investigators speculated that the target was postorino, who police linked to the 'ndrangheta, the version of the mafia here in calabria, a region at the ``toe'' of the boot-shaped italian peninsula
the other dead man was identified in news reports as francesco cosma, 27
felix the ferret was scheduled for execution this week, but a public outcry resulted in a pardon from the mayor
we are going to ferret out a solution,'' said farmers branch mayor john dodd, who spared the animal monday
the fuzzy, pink-eyed ferret was caged at the city's animal shelter
farmers branch police officer rodney wallace spotted the animal friday during patrol. when he opened the door of his car and whistled, the ferret jumped into his lap and snuggled against him
wallace took the ferret to the animal shelter in the dallas suburb and attached a note to his cage that said, ``please do not destroy. if no one claims it, i want it back.''
because of a city ordinance prohibiting exotic animals, officials said the ferret would be destroyed if his owner was not found. as news spread of the ferret's plight, the animal shelter was deluged with requests to adopt the creature
animal control officer mike worsham said his department could not take responsibility for placing felix for adoption because there is no approved vaccine for ferrets and the animals sometimes bite
but dodd promised monday to ``cut through the red tape.'' the mayor said he spoke to the owner of an animal rehabilitation center about taking the animal. the center has a state license to keep wild animals, which will prevent the ferret's death
he's got a reprieve,'' dodd said. offer</head> tender offer; picks up 15th graf pvs, `they can...' version moved financial wires.</note>
federated department stores inc. announced today its board had accepted a multibillion-dollar acquisition bid by r.h. macy &amp; co. inc. over a competing offer from campeau corp
but campeau refused to give up its quest for federated, the nation's fifth-largest retailer
federated and macy signed a definitive agreement to create a new company, macy's-federated inc., said jim fingeroth, a spokesman for macy, which has nearly 100 department and specialty stores
the agreement provides for macy to begin a cash tender offer of $74.50 a share for about 80 percent of federated's 89.6 million outstanding shares, or a total of $5.25 billion, fingeroth said. the remaining federated shares would be exchanged for stock in the new company
campeau had offered $68 a share in cash for all federated shares, or $6.1 billion
after the agreement was announced, campeau said it would proceed with a $66 cash tender offer for federated
macy's bid is not competitive and we intend to prevail in the marketplace,'' a campeau statement said. ``it is now up to federated's shareholders to decide.''
trading in federated stock was halted on the new york stock exchange prior to the federated announcement. after trading resumed, its stock rose 50 cents per share to $67.50
macy's bid came to light monday as federated directors met to consider whether to accept the campeau offer
campeau began its bid jan. 25, offering $47 a share. the bid was rejected as inadequate, and campeau sweetened the offer several times before arriving at the $68 bid
late last week, federated officials decided to negotiate an agreement with campeau, and the toronto-based developer's offer was still on the table as the macy bid was considered
macy originally offered $73.80 per share and then increased its bid before the agreement was signed
wall street analysts said tuesday the rival bids were attractive for different reasons
campeau is sitting there with cash, and macy's walked in the door with some cash but the opportunity for the company to enjoy future growth _ as opposed to campeau's potential breaking up or dismantling of the company,'' said thomas tashjian, an analyst with seidler amdec securities inc. in los angeles
he referred to the fact that campeau sold off most of allied stores corp.'s divisions after he bought the company in december 1986
new york-based macy, which is privately held, is the nation's 10-largest retailer
a federated acquisition represents for macy's a chance to control some of its major competitors, such as bloomingdale's, and to increase its market share at the same time, said michele davis, of the investment firm oppenheimer &amp; co
they can position bloomingdale's at one price point and macy's at another price point such that they don't compete head on with each other,'' she said
the deal also would give macy more outlets for its extensive line of private label merchandise, said monroe greenstein, of the investment firm bear stearns &amp; co. inc
campeau was fighting for federated because it does not want to lose the opportunity to gain the foothold into major u.s. shopping centers that federated stores would provide, greenstein said
moreover, that entree could go instead to macy board member a. alfred taubman, himself a shopping mall developer, greenstein said
the agreement between macy and federated called for the new company's board to include significant representation from the existing federated board
macy, one of the nation's biggest and best-known retailers, was taken private by a management group in a $3.6 billion leveraged buyout in 1986. its stores rang up $5.21 billion in sales during the fiscal year ended aug. 1
federated took in $11 billion last year from its more than 650 department stores, supermarkets and other outlets nationwide, including bloomingdale's, abraham &amp; straus, filene's, burdine's, lazarus, bullock's and rich's department stores; gold circle discount stores and ralphs supermarkets
in december 1986, campeau acquired giant allied stores, whose operations still include the jordan marsh, stern's and ann taylor chains
a judge today ruled the confession by a man to the slayings of seven women in his apartment could be admitted at trial and rejected a claim of illegal arrest
common pleas judge robert latrone denied a defense motion to suppress the confession and all physical evidence seized by police in harrison graham's home last august. defense attorney joel moldovsky also had sought to have graham's arrest declared illegal
latrone said the validity of the statement will be up to the jury
moldovsky and assistant district attorney roger king then met with latrone to discuss the start of jury selection. no date was immediately set
the ruling ended a 14-day pretrial hearing for graham, accused of killing seven women after luring them to his apartment with liquor and drugs. police found human remains in and near graham's apartment
moldovsky is mounting an insanity defense for his client. he claims graham has three personalities: frank, a foul-mouthed junkie who kills women during sex; marty, an easy-going, mother-worshiping guy who confessed to the murders; and junior, a mute, bad-mannered 2-year-old who and likes cartoon characters
graham's full name is harrison frank graham jr
moldovsky last week asked for new psychiatric evaluations of graham when the suspect described how he punched another inmate during a fight at the detention center
frank did it,'' said graham, describing to latrone how he responded to an inmate who had kicked him
king has dismissed the multiple-personality claim as ``just smoke.'' he says graham is a shrewd, street-smart faker who deserves the electric chair
king fahd on wednesday inaugurated the king fahd international stadium, the largest free-span structure in the world
the official opening of the stadium coincided with the ninth gulf cup soccer championships in which seven teams from arab countries are participating
in a ceremonial message, king fahd said ``this is eloquent proof of the progress which this country has made in all fields.''
there have been hints in the pro-government media that the kingdom would like to be a host for the olympic games
the multimillion-dollar stadium can accommodate 75,000 spectators, with the design owing something to the traditional shape of a bedouin tent but merged with the most advanced engineering technology
the exterior of the stadium is in the shape of a circle with a diamater of 290 yards. the bowl contains the playing field with natural grass, imported from kenya, the 400-yard running track, the long jump pits, pole vaulting area and javelin throw run
the roof membrane is stretched between 24 tent-shaped peaks, each supported by a 60-yard vertical mast. the covering is a teflon-coated fabric
the royal and vip pavilion, with six floors of exclusively furnished rooms for royal receptions, seats 750
the grass is watered from a 15-inch-deep water underground reservoir
bands of youths hurled bombs, burned cars and trucks, and shouted anti-government slogans wednesday during a general strike called to disrupt parliamentary elections. at least eight people were injured
teen-agers and children, several appearing younger than 10 years old, stopped a city garbage truck in downtown dhaka, smashed it with clubs and set it ablaze
we set fire to ershad's throne!'' the youngsters chanted, referring to president hussain muhammad ershad
demonstrators stoned and taunted police burned election banners, along with at least one scooter and a taxi
the opposition called the strike to protest thursday's parliamentary elections. many here believe the elections have more potential for violence than for halting the stalemate between ershad and his foes
eight people were reported hospitalized with injuries from small bombs, and two were in serious condition, police and hospital officials said
but no major confrontations erupted between police and protestors, and the city was calm overall
in the southern port city of chittagong, witnesses said at least 50 people were injured in clashes between protestors and police. the witnesses, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said protestors threw bombs at the office of the local municipal corporation and damaged several vehicles
in the capital, the strike appeared successful, shutting down shops and businesses and chasing from the streets the bicycle rickshaws that make dhaka traffic a nightmare
but the strike appeared to have little effect outside dhaka other than stopping trucks and buses from running
it was the 24th strike called by the opposition since nov. 10, when it began its campaign to oust ershad
in a move to compromise with his opponents, ershad dissolved the 330-seat parliament last december, 3{ years before its term was to expire, and scheduled new elections. but opposition leaders have said no election conducted under ershad can be fair, and they are urging a voter boycott
at least 33 people have been died since nov. 10, either in clashes, by police gunfire, or in campaign-related violence
sheik hasina of the opposition awami league said wednesday that she expected only 5 percent or 10 percent of the 47.8 million voters to cast ballots
more than 900 candidates from 102 political parties are running for parliament. eighteen candidates, all from ershad's jatiya party, have already been declared elected for lack of opposition, and voting in one district was canceled because of the slaying of a candidate
in addition to the parliamentary election, municipal elections will be held in the cities of dhaka, chittagong, khulna, and rajshahi
in similar polling for town and village councils across the country three weeks ago, more than 100 people were killed in battles between supporters of candidates
ershad seized power in a bloodless coup in 1982 and won election in 1986. he ordered 9,000 army troops and about 290,000 local police and paramilitary troops deployed to ensure security for the elections
the state department is preparing to notify all u.s. banks where the panamanian government has deposits not to engage in any transactions with the regime that seized power in panama last week, a lawyer for a panamanian opposition group said today
william d. rogers, an attorney for the arnold &amp; porter law firm, said the panamanian government is believed to have deposits in five u.s. banks and that law suits are being drawn up to ensure bank compliance with the measure
rogers told a news conference the state department action would require the banks to make disbursements only to the ambassador who represented the deposed government of president eric arturo delvalle
later, state department deputy spokeswoman phyllis oakley said the department was preparing documentation certifying that persons designated by delvalle are the legitimate representatives of the panamanian government
but she did not say what the legal consequences of the certification were or why it was being prepared
ambassador juan b. sosa, who has maintained that delvalle's ouster was unconstitutional, said he had no precise figures on the amounts of money in the panamanian accounts but estimated the number to be $50 million
in new york, lawyers for delvalle sued in federal court today to block a new york bank from turning over millions of dollars to new government in panama
a federal judge issued a temporary restraining order, blocking the republic national bank of new york from transferring an estimated $10 million
a hearing on the matter is slated for monday before u.s. district judge lloyd f. mcmahon
the lawsuit seeks to establish title to the funds held in the republic national bank account and ``to prevent their transfer into the hands of a military dictatorship ... which has attempted to seize power and overthrow the lawful authorities of the republic of panama,'' according to court papers
in washington, sosa said the state department is seriously considering withholding from panama the next payment on the fees the united states gives panama for use of the panama canal. he estimated that figure at $8 million
ms. oakley confirmed that a request from the delvalle government to put the funds in escrow had been received and that the state department was consulting with other agencies on how to proceed
delvalle fired military strongman manuel antonio noriega last thursday but the defense chief ignored the order and rallied his allies in the national assembly against the president. on friday, the assembly voted to oust delvalle and installed education minister manuel solis palma in his place
noriega has been indicted on drug smuggling charges by two florida grand juries and has been under heavy diplomatic, economic and political pressure by the reagan administration to step aside and open the way for civilian-led constitutional rule
among the banks listed by rogers which would be affected by the order are marine midland, irving trust, bankers trust and the republic national bank. he said all have headquarters in new york
every dime we can find is in those banks,'' rogers said. he added that any bank which ignores the order could be liable for whatever payments it makes to the current panamanian government
the coalition of opposition leaders believes that the panamanian government is facing a grave cash flow problem and is extremely vulnerable to economic pressure from the united states
unlike other countries, panama cannot cover its cash shortages by printing new money because the dollar is the national currency
sosa said international opposition to the new government was evident earlier this week when, he claimed, only eight ambassadors showed up for a state of the union address. from the western hemisphere, he said, only cuba and nicaragua attended
three people have been arrested in a roadside robbery in which a deputy minister was shot, it was reported wednesday
aggrey suit, deputy minister for energy and technology, was driving tuesday with his 6-year-old daughter through a suburb of kampala when three gunmen drove from the roadside, blocked his vehicle and demanded the keys, the government-owned radio uganda said
during a scuffle, one of the gunmen opened fire hitting suit in the leg. the girl was not injured
the gunmen fled with suit's four-wheel drive vehicle, which was found abandoned at jinja, 50 miles east of kampala
driving through the streets of this diplomatic capital, one would never guess that the leaders of the western world are in town to chart the future course of the nat0 alliance
but then, brussels tends to take its summits in stride
there are no banners, no curious onlookers and few flags to bear witness to the presence of president reagan and 15 other government leaders for the two-day nato summit that began wednesday
except for occasional motorcycle escorts leading official limousines on a weaving course through traffic, the city's normal routine has not been disrupted noticeably
security is tightest for reagan, who is staying in the 19th century chateau stuyvenberg on the outskirts of the city, next to the royal palace. the chateau's wooded grounds are patrolled by guard dogs and mounted police
it is a fortress,'' said one police official, who spoke only on condition that he not be identified. ``everything is tiptop in order.''
brussels is a stolid, middle-class city that for decades has played host to the european economic community, the north atlantic treaty organization, several offices of the european parliament and numerous international lobbying groups
strict security for highly placed officials is a routine and unobtrusive element in this city of about 1 million people. brussels handled its last summit, for the eec, only three weeks ago
the pace of the city is geared toward international meetings. taxi drivers ask their customers whether they prefer a normal or a fast trip out to the sprawling nato headquarters in the quiet suburb of evere
the only sign of summit-induced chaos was seen wednesday at the nato press center, where an estimated 2,000 journalists jostled each other for copies of official statements, draft beer and interviews with the few official sources willing to brave the crush
reflecting the belgian taste for good living, beer began to flow from the press center taps at about 11 a.m
a minor incident occurred when a nato security agent tried to grab a microphone from an american television network crew member while the nato leaders posed for a group photograph
a u.s. security agent accompanying reagan stepped in with the admonition, ``do not manhandle journalists,'' and the nato agent backed off
police spokesman jacques devaux said 500 uniformed belgian policemen were working around the clock ``with uncommon vigilance'' to protect every nato leader. a brussels newspaper said they were being reinforced by about 500 state security force personnel
days before the summit opened wednesday, police guards were reinforced and additional metal detectors were installed at zaventem international airport. areas where summit leaders were to arrive were swept repeatedly for explosives, but none was found
the summiteers, who brought their own security forces along, were staying in hotels and embassies scattered throughout the city. overall security was being coordinated at a command center in the interior ministry
police detained 20 anti-nuclear protesters for identity checks after they tried to demonstrate outside nato headquarters without a police permit
the government said wednesday it won't release a recording of the conversation between a control tower and a south african airways jumbo jet that crashed nov. 28 in the indian ocean, killing all 159 people aboard
the announcement was made by supreme court justice cecil margo, head of an international board that began meeting monday to investigate the cause of the crash on a flight from taipei, taiwan to johannesburg
the boeing 747 went down minutes before it was due to refuel in mauritius
reports at the time had quoted mauritian officials as saying the pilot reported fire or smoke in the cockpit
south african officials took over the investigation from mauritian aviation authorities, and no further information was released. the south african officials said at the time that quotes from the recording would not be released because they might be misunderstood and some people might believe they were being accused or blamed
margo said the recorded conversation was indistinct in parts and experts had disagreed about what was said, so no official transcript or sound from the recording would be released
margo said the board had decided wednesday that the cockpit voice recorder, flight data recorder and other pieces of the jet must be recovered ``at all costs'' from the crash site 14,520 feet under the ocean north of mauritius
aboard the jet were 71 south africans, 47 japanese, 30 taiwanese, and one or two passengers from australia, mauritius, hong kong, the united states, holland, britain, germany, denmark and south korea. only 11 bodies were recovered
here are excerpts from recent editorials in newspapers throughout the nation
feb. 29
the albuquerque (n.m.) tribune on gen. manuel antonio noriega of panama:
gen. manuel noriega, panama's drug-running strongman, seems still to be in control of his troubled nation
washington has been trying for months to figure out a way to depose noriega, who recently was indicted in miami on charges of drug trafficking. obviously, the u.s. government was involved in president eric arturo delvalle's attempt to dismiss noriega from command of panama's defense force
the maneuver may eventually contribute to an erosion of support for noriega among the country's military officer corps. but so far, most of those in the echelons below noriega either are in cahoots with the general or too afraid to buck him
noriega also faces strong opposition from the public, many of whom rioted last summer because of the country's declining economy and reports of corruption at the top
noriega has got to go, and the united states should do all it can to hasten that event. this should include an economic squeeze, by washington and other capitals, that could cause increased resentment against the general
feb. 29
baltimore sun on military spending:
when a secretary of the navy jumps ship or walks the plank, it is fitting that he made a big splash
james e. webb has done just that by unleashing a petulant attack on defense secretary frank c. carlucci, a veteran public servant who has taken on the tough, thankless job of bringing pentagon spending and planning into the realm of reality. ..
in the end, carlucci ordered the scrapping of 16 aging frigates as part of a $12 billion cut in fiscal 1989 navy spending. this was a sensible decision, in keeping with plans for a lean but tough defense establishment. ..
webb's spectacular manner of departure may have one beneficial effect. it could trigger a defense debate that most washington politicians would prefer to put off until the november elections
the next president and the next congress need to avoid sharp peaks and valleys in military spending and to devise a defense strategy that is compatible with the nation's resources, commitments and priorities
feb. 24
salem (ore.) statesman-journal on jimmy swaggart:
a repentant jimmy swaggart has confessed and apologized publicly for sins of sexual misconduct. ..
with this latest scandal, the tendency among much of the public may be to condemn all radio and television religious ministries
that would be understandable, but it also would be a mistake. some of these programs, a few dating back for 40 years or more, have a clean record of service and financial accountability. nevertheless, they often are smeared with the same broad brush
swaggart, (jim) bakker and other dimming stars of the glitzy world of television evangelism need our compassion, but they also need to clean up their lives and their organizations
feb. 26
the mcpherson (kan.) sentinel on the arrest of an absentee senator:
we had thought that house speaker jim wright had sunk to the bottom depths in congressional decorum a couple of months ago when he had the effrontery to make time stand still in order to gain passage of a bill he wanted
but after senate majority leader robert byrd's actions (last) week, wright is barely running a close second
we have often thought that congress resembled a circus more than it resembles the world's greatest deliberative body, but byrd made it complete with keystone kops ... when he ordered the arrest of republican bob packwood in order to get a quorum
we hope, of course, that byrd's tactic ... was worth such despicable conduct, because byrd has certainly degraded both himself and the senate
somehow we can't help but doubt that it was
feb. 25
the times of trenton, n.j., on the new tax laws:
there's a variation of the popular tv game show ``jeopardy!'' that you can play by calling your local internal revenue service offices. ask them a technical question about the 1986 tax law changes that go into effect this year
what's the ``jeopardy'' part? well, one fourth of the time the answer will be wrong. ..
but if you rely on that answer when you file your return, and underpay your tax as a result, you're still subject to a penalty and interest for underpaying
a year ago ... the new tax witholding forms ... turned out to be so arcane that the (irs) had to waive deadlines and develop new forms
it's hard to figure out how a law that was so widely understood and welcomed _ as an effort to make the tax code more fair, logical and efficient _ could have spawned such confusion
feb. 24
the new ulm (minn.) journal on pat robertson:
republican presidential hopeful pat robertson has a problem with making outrageous statements that he can't back up with facts
he labeled planned parenthood supporters as people trying to create a master race just because birth control pioneer margaret sanger dabbled in eugenics back around the turn of the century
he warned us that there are nuclear missiles in cuba and offered as proof that ``no one can prove there aren't missiles there.''
now he has the gall to suggest, though he admits he has no proof, that the george bush campaign is behind tv preacher jimmy swaggart's fall from grace in an attempt to discredit robertson, a former tv evangelist trying hard to distance himself from that past
robertson doesn't need anyone to discredit him. he appears to be doing a fine job of it himself
feb. 24
the knoxville (tenn.) news-sentinel on playing politics with appointments:
ohio's democratic sen. howard metzenbaum has gotten himself all twisted out of shape over the justice department's refusal to release certain of its files to the senate judiciary committee
the files relate to the department's investigation of reports that former u.s. ambassador to switzerland faith ryan whittlesey mishandled some entertainment funds
she was said to have entertained american friends with privately donated money that was intended to be used to fete foreign officials. the justice department said there was no evidence to produce a ``viable criminal case.''
that wasn't good enough for metzenbaum. he wants to come up with something politically damaging to the reagan administration
metzenbaum is holding up senate confirmation of four reagan appointees to federal court judgeships
this isn't just playing politics. it's hostage-taking, and it ill becomes a senator of the united states
feb. 29
sioux falls (s.d.) argus leader on president reagan's budget:
however else he is remembered, ronald reagan will go down as the biggest spender in the history of the presidency
the $1.1 trillion national budget he proposed recently would only increase military spending about 2 percent
in addition, reagan has an agreement with congress to run up only $136 billion more debt during the next budget year. in fiscal 1987, they accumulated $148 billion in debt
minor concessions like that will not erase the fact that reagan, more than any other president, has led the nation into what seems like a bottomless pit of overdue bills
of course, reagan is not entirely to blame. every democratic and republican representative and senator who has served in congress since reagan took office in 1981 must shoulder part of the blame for the nation's spending problems
reagan, the candidate who promised to balance the budget, has failed financially. he has less than a year remaining in his term _ not enough time to balance the budget
the good news is that this is an election year. taxpayers and voters have the opportunity _ and an obligation _ to hold presidential candidates accountable on that issue
feb. 28
the orange county (calif.) register on the supreme court parody decision:
when the u.s. supreme court hands down a unanimous decision, you might figure it was a cut-and-dried case. not so with last week's decision upholding hustler magazine's disgusting parody of the rev. jerry falwell
while the court seemed to grant almost absolute protection to speech that is intended as satire, it left blurred the line that distinguishes fact from fiction, parody from portrayal
at issue was a 1983 takeoff of a well-known liquor advertisement in which famous people describe the ``first time'' they tasted the product. in hustler's version, falwell was depicted as having sex with his mother in an outhouse
outraged, the televangelist and founder of the moral majority sued publisher larry flynt for $45 million for libel, invasion of privacy and infliction of emotional distress
a lower court had no trouble discerning that the parody was fiction. thus falwell did not have a case for libel. ... but it awarded him $200,000 for emotional distress
it took the supreme court to rule that awards for emotional distress require ... (proof of) factual falsehood, the standard for libel. ... and now the court rules draw a distinction between satire, which is absolutely free, and seriousness, which is not
free speech should mean just that. ... in the marketplace of ideas and public opinion, truth almost always will win out
feb. 27
charleston (w.va.) daily mail on foreign-held patents:
the u.s. patent and trademark office issued 89,385 patents last year. a stunning 46.6 percent of them went to people who are not u.s. citizens
americans are inventing more things than they used to, say officials at the patent office. but non-americans are inventing at a faster pace
in the past two decades, the share of u.s. patents awarded to foreigners has more than doubled. from the patent office's figures, the chief competitors of the future will be the japanese, who claimed 17,288 patents, and the west germans, who registered 8,030
it seems likely that more of the next generation of americans will be paying license fees, and more inventors in other nations will be sitting back collecting royalties
feb. 24
the asheville (n.c.) citizen on jimmy swaggart:
so one more television evangelist falls. jimmy swaggart is one of the biggest, but the country has become accustomed to seeing tv ministers stumble because of worldly pleasures
the only remarkable thing about the swaggart case is the extent to which everyone is focusing on his physical sin, that of consorting with a prostitute. in the eyes of his church and his followers, that was his greatest offense, and they already have begun forgiving him
give swaggart credit _ he knew what he had to do. he prostrated himself before the elders of the assemblies of god denomination, his congregation, his tv audience and god himself. swaggart blamed no one else
he admitted sinning, took full responsibility and begged forgiveness. most of his sympathizers were not just touched, they were overwhelmed
amid all this glorious healing, it seems almost unkind to note that swaggart did not admit his sin until he had no choice _ until it was reported by a fellow tv evangelist and competitor whom swaggart had helped discredit and drive out of business
he did not confess until his worldly empire was at stake. where were swaggart's humility and repentance during all those months or years before he was found out?
feb. 29
palm beach (fla.) post on the supreme court's parody decision:
the supreme court decision in the case of falwell vs. flynt is a reassuring vote of confidence in the principle of freedom of speech
in a decision significant for its unanimity, the justices said the rev. jerry falwell may not collect $200,000 in damages from publisher larry flynt and hustler magazine for a parody. ..
there is no question the parody was putrid. it also was painful for moral majority founder falwell
still, to condemn it because it breaks all boundaries for sleaze is one thing. to rule it is libelous is another
if a public figure cannot prove he has been libeled, he can't recover damages for even the most extreme embarrassment
in this case, that would have meant proving the parody contained statements known by the author to be false, which could be considered true. it's impossible to imagine that anyone considered the parody true
feb. 25
honolulu star-bulletin on the supreme court parody decision:
the american democratic system requires that the fullest possible leeway for comment, even comment that is unfair and in the worst taste
that description applies to the hustler spoof. because it could not have been reasonably interpreted as stating facts about (jerry) falwell, his claim of libel failed. at that point the first amendment took over
many of us committed to the first amendment would feel more comfortable rallying behind a worthier champion than hustler magazine. but great principles of justice can sprout from unseemly roots
the supreme court, by extending constitutional protection for parody and satire, has advanced the cause of freedom
feb. 25
the sun, westerly, r.i., on the long supreme court vacancy:
two-thirds of a year have gone by from the time a supreme court vacany occurred until judge anthony kennedy was sworn in ... as the ninth justice
the question whether it was worth the wait will be variously answered, depending on one's opinion of kennedy and the prior nominees who were rejected
no one, however, can dispute the assertions that kennedy was a compromise candidate after the administration had failed with judge robert bork and douglas ginsburg
the senate deemed bork too controversial for his narrow constitutional stance, ginsburg not only flawed in character but of inadequate judicial stature. ..
kennedy, in contrast to his predecessors before the senate in its process of advice and consent, was readily approved _ perhaps in part out of relief that a conservative yet not rigidly doctrinaire nominee was at least offered; but in any case, approved
some liberals, especially women's rights advocates, still have their doubts about how justice kennedy will perform. on the whole, however, he appears to be an excellent choice. and it is good to have a full court again after a long hiatus
feb. 28
the oshkosh (wis.) northwestern on educational testing:
while it is edifying that wisconsin leads the rest of the nation on american college testing (act) scores, ... wisconsin ranks near the bottom in the percentage of students taking that or the scholastic aptitude test (sat)
that does not mean that the high score is somehow invalid. but it does suggest that it may be artificially high in comparison to other states where the average is lower but the percentage of students taking the test is higher
as ratings experts have long counseled: do not read too much into the test scores data. it can't be used to prove the quality of a state's educational product
it may point to some extra efforts if the average fluctuates greatly from one year to the next. but it is not universally taken and thus there are too many other factors involved in assessing the quality of education which those tests can not depict. in miami</head>
billions of dollars in bank deposits are being taken out of panama for safer havens in the wake of the political turmoil following the drug indictment of military strongman gen. manuel antonio noriega, financial experts say
some of that money has wound up in miami, where federal regulations adopted earlier this decade allow ``offshore'' banks to escape the scrutiny that domestic banks undergo
panama in the 1980s had come to be known as the switzerland of latin america, offering banking secrecy and stability to the region's investors and depositors. banks there are unfettered by high taxes or cumbersome rules, providing a safe haven for both legitimately and illegitimately earned money
but a deposit flight began last year when street demonstrations broke out in panama, accelerating after noriega's indictment last month
this certainly has destabilized panama as a banking center,'' said gonzalo valdes-fauli, senior vice president and manager of the miami office of london-based barclay's bank
valdes-fauli said some foreign banks are moving their operations to other caribbean or central american nations
credit suisse, the third-biggest u.s. bank, announced tuesday that it was closing its panama office at the end of april, and said its offshore business has already been transferred to branches in miami and the bahamas
one unidentified top banking expert told the miami herald that from june to october panamanian banks lost $7 billion of the $36 billion they held
some of that money began trickling back, but since noriega's indictment and the subsequent political upheaval, panama banks are losing the funds once more, the herald reported wednesday
foreign deposits in miami increased 39 percent in 1987 to $6.2 billion, although it was not known how much of that represented deposits from panama banks
the deposit flight from panama could be accelerated by an expected state department notification to u.s. banks not to transact business with the central american nation's current government
a judge has given postal inspectors the go-ahead to seize mail orders for ``fat magnet,'' a pill nationally advertised as the ``lazy way'' to lose weight
u.s. district judge terry hatter jr. issued a preliminary injunction tuesday against the company after assistant u.s. attorney george wu argued it may be fraudulently promoting the pill, which it claims absorbs fat and flushes it out of the body
the pill does not have federal drug administration approval
the u.s. postal service had requested the injunction, which allows the postal inspectors to continue seizures they began three weeks ago. a decision on the charges will be made at an administrative hearing in washington, d.c., within 60 days
postal inspector jim harbin said the postal service already has seized between 8,000 and 10,000 pieces of mail addressed to the company in beverly hills and will keep the mail, including checks for purchase of the product, until a fraud hearing is held
attorneys for fat magnet said the product not only works, but is a food for special dietary use, a category recognized as between food and drugs that does not require fda approval
we certainly agree that this product has not been approved by the fda,'' said kirkpatrick dilling, a company attorney. ``it's not necessary.''
dilling said the pill's two main ingredients, fiber and purified bile, do not qualify fat magnet as a new, unapproved drug
but wu responded that there are questions about how well fat magnet works, if it works at all, and serious consumer safety concerns about its use
like rip van winkle, north tarrytown has been asleep to its heritage for years, and will awaken to a new and better life if its name is changed to sleepy hollow, some residents say
it's a part of history that we're sleepy hollow,'' said chris skelly, a member of the village of sleepy hollow committee. ``it's not a made-up name. it gives us the potential to be famous because everyone's heard of sleepy hollow.''
in the washington irving story, sleepy hollow was the town where the headless horseman rode. rip van winkle, another irving character, slept for 20 years in the catskills
skelly said irving, for whom nearby irvington was named, didn't make up the name, but reached back to 17th century dutch descriptions of the area as ``slaeperingh haven'' and ``slaeperingh hol,'' or sleeping harbor and sleepy hollow. the names meant it was easy to dock there and spend the night
now, skelly and others want to bring the dutch name back to distinguish north tarrytown from neighboring tarrytown and try to revitalize the village of 8,000 beset by financial and social woes
residents will decide the matter during village elections march 15
opponents of the measure, such as edna belanich, a founder of concerned citizens against changing the name of north tarrytown, say it would be confusing and costly and wouldn't accomplish anything
it'll be a panacea, not a cure,'' she said. ``history will not pay the bills or solve the problems. we can keep history in our hearts.''
skelly says history can go a long way to attracting new business, particularly tourism, to the village, which boasts the sleepy hollow cemetery, an old dutch graveyard, and philipsburg manor, the home of an early english settler
we are not a suburb of tarrytown,'' he said. ``we're in different towns. we have different histories. we are the older, more historic village and the name should reflect that.''
a report done by mayor janet gandolfo estimated the cost of the name change to range as high as almost $40,000, including a new seal, new badges for police and firefighters and new administrative costs
but mrs. belanich said the cost would be higher because it was difficult to determine hidden expenses
and it's not necessary,'' she said. ``they think changing the name will solve our financial problems and the social problems. they just don't want to be associated with them.''
the village suffered a major racial disturbance in 1986 when problems in the hispanic community brought in officers from several neighboring communities and led to a countywide evaluation of hispanic problems
financially, the village has been running in the red since it agreed to lower the property tax assessment for the general motors plant, which had threatened to sue
originally called beekmantown, the village became north tarrytown in 1874, three years after tarrytown was incorporated
skelly said north tarrytown felt threatened by the town of mount pleasant, so it aligned itself with tarrytown
now we're just tarrytown's poor relation. we don't get enough attention and we deserve it because we're world-famous,'' said skelly. ``it's a very powerful name and image. it's a potential gold mine.''
new home sales fell 9 percent in january, pushing sales activity to its slowest pace since the end of the last recession, the government said wednesday as the housing industry continued to stagger following the october stock market collapse
a downturn in housing has often been the harbinger of the onset of a recession, but analysts said they believed falling mortgage rates offered the hope of a rebound in home sales in coming months
in january, the commerce department said that sales of new single-family homes fell for the third consecutive month, dropping to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 535,000 units, 26 percent below a year ago and the slowest pace since the last recession was ending in december 1982
in a second lackluster economic report, the commerce department said orders for manufactured goods fell 0.6 percent in january to a seasonally adjusted $212.6 billion
while this was the first decline in five months, analysts noted that it followed an unusually large 2 percent december increase, a gain which reflected a big jump in demand for jet airplanes
analysts said the one-month setback did nothing to change their view that american manufacturers are continuing to enjoy a sales boom led by increased demand for exports
analysts said they were surprised by the sharpness of the decline in home sales, especially since sales had already fallen by 6.8 percent in december and 3.4 percent in november
the decline in new home sales followed other reports showing a big decline in construction starts for new homes in january and the third consecutive monthly decrease in sales of existing homes
it looks like housing is bearing the brunt of the stock market decline, but i believe lower interest rates can solve a lot of problems in this industry,'' said bob villanueva, director of economic forecasting for the national association of home builders
analysts noted that fixed-rate mortgages have fallen into the single-digit range again, averaging 9.87 percent last week, compared to 10.6 percent when the year began
james christian, chief economist for the u.s. league of savings institutions, said with ``mortgage rates moving in the right direction'' sales for all of 1988 should rebound to around 650,000 units, only 3 percent below the 1987 sales pace
but other analysts said it remained to be seen whether the drop in mortgage rates will be enough to attract new buyers. they noted that sales have been strong for the past three years and a lot of pent-up demand has been exhausted
we simply don't have the demand for housing that we had in the first part of the recovery,'' said michael sumichrast, an economist and publisher of a construction industry newsletter. ``the south, which accounts for almost half of all new homes sold, is still weak and you won't see any significant improvement until that area turns around.''
analysts, however, said they were not ready to forecast an end to the current economic recovery
we are seeing a shift away from economic growth driven by housing and other domestic sectors and toward growth in manufacturing and other export sectors,'' said warren lasko, executive director of the mortgage bankers association
the 9 percent decline in new home sales in january was the steepest decline since a 10.9 percent drop last may. the big decline in sales was accompanied by a sharp rise in prices
the median, or mid-point, price of a home shot up 9.7 percent to $120,000 while the average home price rose to $149,000, an increase of 10.5 percent
economists said that while home prices have been outpacing rises in overall inflation in recent months, the january surge was skewed upward by the fact that sales rose in the northeast, a high-priced section of the country, while they were down sharply in the less-expensive south
sales dropped 24.4 percent in the south to an annual rate of 177,000 units. sales were off 13.7 percent in the midwest to a rate of 88,000 units
sales rose 23 percent in the northeast to an annual rate of 91,000 units, but this big increase followed a much larger 53 percent december decline. sales edged up 0.6 percent in the west to an annual rate of 179,000 units
the falling of a piece of rock from the crumbling body of the sphinx has caused an avalanche of debate over the future of the 4,600-year-old monument and egypt's other ancient treasures
the principal casualty of the uproar has been ahmed kadry, formerly chairman of the egyptian antiquities organization
kadry lost his job after accusing his boss, culture minister farouk hosni, of staging the falling rock incident to reflect badly on kadry's stewardship of the sphinx and the other relics of egypt's rich past. hosni did not reply to the accusation
the limestone slab fell from the sphinx's right shoulder on feb. 7, six days after a sandstorm buffeted giza plateau
a restoration plan is in the works. the sphinx has been fitted with sandbags for support and scaffolding to help in the early stages of the effort, and a committee of experts has taken rock samples for analysis to help decide what steps to take
the sphinx, which is 66 feet high and 160 feet long, has the head of a pharaoh and the body of a crouching lion. many egyptologists think the face is that of chephren, son of cheops and builder of the second pyramid on giza plateau next to cheops' great pyramid
a similiar accident six years ago brought down kadry's predecessor, fouad oraby, and a sphinx-restoration project that kadry began as antiquities chairman remained unfinished when the latest rock fell
zahi hawass, general director of the pyramids area and archaeology adviser to hosni, will direct the latest restoraton and conservation efforts
the earliest restoration of the sphinx began 3,600 years ago
two hundred years from now all our monuments will be finished,'' hawass told the associated press
in the past the monuments were safe from many factors that destroy them because they were buried in the sand. the monuments were not subjected to pollution, the environment, tourists, the things that are ruining them now.''
the emergency work on the sphinx should be finished by late march, with fallen pieces of limestone replaced and weak places beneath the neck and shoulders treated, hawass said. made of weaker limestone than other parts, the neck long has been considered a chronic problem
after the emergency work, experts will draw up an overall restoration plan, hawass said
a major problem, said omar el-arini, cairo representative of the washington-based national science foundation, is that previous restorers have not learned why the sphinx continues to decay
in a nutshell, we have been looking at symptoms of the problems, not the problems themselves,'' he said
we have been treating it as a rock carved 4,600 years ago, but the limestone is 40 million years old. our approach should be to look at an object of 40 million years.''
one of the problems facing the team will be how to rid the monument of salt, which is visible on many portions of the body
shawky nakhla, chief restorer for the antiquity organization, said restoration efforts in the 1940s and 1950s added to the sphinx's salt problem
they used cement, and a lot of salt started appearing,'' he said. ``we don't know if a high water table level below the sphinx is a real cause of the salt problems, or whether the salt is coming out of the limestone itself.''
pat robertson won a one-sided preference poll victory in alaska's republican caucuses, nearly doubling the support given vice president george bush, party officials said today
robertson, the former television evangelist, claimed 47 percent of the votes compared with bush's 24 percent in a poll of 2,020 precinct delegates. sen. bob dole took third with 20 percent
the preference poll was not binding, though it gave an indication of the feelings of the delegates who will attend 27 gop district conventions march 18-26. at those meetings, 400 delegates will be chosen to attend the state convention in late april, when the state's 19 gop delegates will be named to attend the national convention
a hint of robertson's strength was suggested tuesday when party spokesman linda shafer noted that republican regulars had noticed new faces in the precinct caucuses that began saturday
in other early-contest states, robertson supporters have signed up thousands of new party members to participate in caucuses
there were people new to the political process,'' said shafer. ``you could tell by their political platforms _ things like anti-marijuana and anti-abortion _ that they were church folks.''
many of the delegates had been expected to back robertson, shafer said. but robertson had competition on the religious front. a baptist preacher, the rev. jerry prevo, organized members of his anchorage church to attend the caucuses and support bush
the caucuses were open to any registered republican
precinct and district delegates have been known to shift allegiances, but the gop delegates to the national conventions never have abandoned their chosen candidates, state republican chairman jim crawford said
crawford said the alaska gop is trying to link up with other western states in hopes of gaining clout, especially in selecting a vice presidential candidate
the democratic party's delegate selection, similar to that of the republican party, is scheduled to begin in alaska with precinct caucuses in 10 days
here are capsule profiles of some of the major figures in gov. evan mecham's impeachment trial:

frank x. gordon jr. _ chief justice of the arizona supreme court and presiding officer in the senate trial. democrat, a self-styled moderate, 59; described as the epitome of a small town lawyer and judge, friendly, open, straight-forward. scored 100 percent for integrity in a poll of 300 arizona attorneys in 1986. arizona's youngest superior court judge when he was appointed to that bench in may 1962. born in chicago in 1929, came to arizona with his parents as a child. graduate of stanford university in 1951, received law degree from the university of arizona in 1954. kingman city attorney in 1955-56. appointed to the state supreme court in 1975 by then-gov. raul castro. became chief justice in 1987

william p. french _ lead prosecution attorney. hired by the house in october to investigate mecham's $350,000 campaign loan and other allegations. french, 56, presented a report on jan. 15 outlining possible grounds of impeachment and conducted the subsequent hearings that led to the feb. 5 impeachment. former presiding judge of the maricopa county superior court's criminal division. worked for the u.s. justice department as a prosecutor in the organized crime section

jerris leonard _ hired one week before the impeachment trial began to head mecham's defense team. accustomed to defending controversial people, but forced to resign from his washington, d.c., law firm because it didn't want to be involved in representing mecham. former head of the law enforcement assistance administration and the justice department's civil rights division under president nixon. former wisconsin senate majority leader. leonard, 57, headed united sciences of america, a company accused by the new york state attorney general of engaging in an illegal pyramid-type scheme to sell vitamins. the company agreed to a financial settlement in october

fred craft _ a mecham friend and the subject of two major disputes between mecham and the legislature in 1987. mecham wanted to hire him as the governor's washington, d.c., lobbyist, but the legislature refused to appropriate the money. mecham eventually decided to hire craft anyway and paid his salary and expenses from the governor's office budget. mecham also was accused of pressuring a state panel to choose craft as its lobbyist for arizona's bid for the federal superconducting super collider. the panel eventually chose another lobbyist. craft resigned as arizona's washington lobbyist shortly after impeachment turned the governorship over to arizona's secretary and state and forced mecham to step aside as governor at least temporarily. craft ad leonard are longtime friends, and craft brought leonard into the impeachment trial

ralph milstead _ the man mecham is accused of ordering not to cooperate with the state attorney general's investigation of a death threat allegation. director of the department of public safety since 1980. given a new five-year contract in 1985. previously spent 20 years in the phoenix police department, reaching the rank of major. mecham has been rumored at various times to have wanted to replace milstead, 48, but by law he cannot be fired at will by the governor

donna carlson _ mecham's former special assistant and liaison to the legislature. a former state senator and unsuccessful congressional candidate. she resigned in october 1987, saying the controversy surrounding mecham's administration had made it impossible for her to do her job. ms. carlson, 50, was scheduled to testify before the state grand jury regarding mecham's failure to report a $350,000 campaign loan when she allegedl became the subject of a death threat by then-state official lee watkins

peggy griffith _ the woman who reported then-state official watkins had voiced threats to the life of carlson. mrs. griffith is director of the governor's office of women's services. she told the department of public safety on nov. 13 that watkins had told her her friend, ms. carlson, had better keep quiet or ms. carlson might go on a ``long boat ride'' and not come back. mrs. griffith earlier had been close friends with ms. carlson, but ms. carlson said the two had become somewhat distant at the time the alleged death threat was made
a state health department study indicated about one in every 116 women giving birth in new york state carried the aids virus, far higher than the 1 in 476 results in a similar massachusetts study
the new york study, conducted in november, showed 161 positive tests from 18,700 infants examined in the state. in new york city, there were 148 positive test results from 9,000 infants examined _ a rate of one in 61. the figure was even higher in the city's poorer neighborhoods, with a figure of one in 43 in the bronx
an infant's immune system reflects its mother's system. an infant testing positive for the presence of aids antibodies almost always got the virus through an infected mother
the massachusetts study found that one of every 476 women giving birth, or 2.1 for each 1,000, were infected with the aids virus. at three inner-city boston hospitals, eight per 1,000 were infected _ a rate of one per 125 births
a week ago eric arturo delvalle was reviled as a figurehead president of panama whose chief purpose was to provide a democratic fig leaf to the military forces who ran the country
now delvalle the meek has become delvalle the martyr. in the reagan administration's view, he could become a panamanian version of philippines president corazon aquino, the lightning rod for democratic opposition to former philippines president ferdinand marcos
much of the reagan administration's strategy toward panama over the past few days has been built around delvalle and his claim to be panama's constitutional president
he is an integral part of the u.s. ``chipmunk strategy'' toward panama. the state department wants to keep gnawing at panama's economy, at military strongman manuel antonio noriega's claim to legitimacy and his support at home and abroad
noriega is the chieftain of panama's armed forces, and, according to a federal indictment handed up in miami, a cocaine smuggler
eventually, in the administration's hopes, noriega will find his hold on power has evaporated and pack up
in defying noriega and ordering him stripped of power, devalle provided a democratic symbol around whom panamanians could rally
delvalle's image as a powerless front man dates back to when he took office in the fall of 1985. noriega was unhappy with the president at the time, nicolas ardito barletta, because of an independent streak, and he forced barletta from office
delvalle was sworn in as president under the most unpromising of circumstances. in effect, he had to behave according to noriega's wishes or he would end up like barletta. he carried that burden for two years
a mystique has developed around delvalle since he tried to fire noriega and wound up out of office himself. rather than flee the country after his dismissal, he went into hiding, issuing proclamations to his countrymen, making videotaped messages and frustrating efforts by noriega's forces to locate him
one of his chief allies these days is gabriel lewis, a former ambassador to washington who is now a captain of the anti-noriega campaign in exile
to hear lewis tell it, delvalle had wanted to break with noriega for five months but was reluctant to do so because of ``confusing'' signals from washington
lewis says noriega has been suspicious of delvalle's intentions for some time and kept telling the president, ``don't act against me because the gringos are behind me.''
this was based on what noriega felt were reassuring visits by emissaries from washington, including assistant defense secretary richard armitage
a turning point occurred in early january, lewis said, when panamanian opposition leaders gathered in miami and delvalle sent an envoy
the emissary told us that if we gave him (delvalle) assurances that we would support him, he was ready to act and dismiss noriega,'' lewis said
we sent him back a message,'' lewis said. he said the message was: ``we have heard that many times. we want deeds and not words. if you fire noriega and his cronies, we will give you support.''
contacts with lewis and other noriega opponents continued, with some messages being passed by delvalle's dentist in florida. another turning point took place in early february when two florida grand juries charged that noriega was a key figure in an international drug smuggling ring
with an end to the ambiguity in washington's position, the opposition front suggested that delvalle travel to washington to announce his break with noriega before the organization of american states
delvalle agreed, but had second thoughts. he reasoned that firing noriega at oas headquarters in washington might be seen ``as acting on instructions from the united states,'' lewis said
but was delvalle getting cold feet?
at lewis' instigation, sen. edward m. kennedy, d-mass., called delvalle to give him encouragement. on feb. 17, delvalle was in miami and invited assistant secretary of state elliott abrams to visit him
if delvalle was ousted for trying to fire noriega, abrams assured him, the united states would support him as panama's constitutional president, lewis said
eight days later, in an important moment in panama's tumultuous history, delvalle acted
editor's note: george gedda has covered foreign affairs for the associated press since 1968
director oliver stone and producer edward pressman have agreed to trim a slur against puerto ricans from the home video version of ``wall street'' following complaints from the hispanic community
state sen. olga mendez said wednesday the comment during dialogue between actors charlie sheen and sylvia miles will be missing when the movie is released on video
it took just a week for negotiations to remove it,'' said mendez. ``it shows very clearly they are very sensitive to people's feelings.''
according to mendez, ex-deputy mayor kenneth lipper acted as mediator in the negotiations to remove the line in question. lipper, who also served as a technical advisor to the film, said the line was included to demonstrate the greed and bigotry of the miles' character, a real estate agent
in the box office hit, sheen is trying to sell his new york apartment. miles, explaining that will be no easy task, tells him, ``the only things moving in new york are puerto ricans and cockroaches.''
pressman, in a letter to mendez, agreed to trim the comment
as you know, oliver stone and i are identified with such progressive films as `the revolutionary,' `walker,' `salvador' and `platoon,''' he wrote
a man who has been on the lam for nearly four years with a pair of 3{-ton elephants says he'll come in from the cold if he is assured that tory and duchess will not be returned to two men he alleges brutalized them
arlan seidon raised the indian elephants from infancy and then sold them to edward drake. in may 1984, he and the 7-foot-high beasts disappeared in a tractor-trailer
he surfaced last week when he called a newspaper from an undisclosed location to say he'd surrender if guaranteed that the elephants will not be returned to drake and his father, richard
i want to make sure where they are going to. i don't feel that i'm going to spend this much time trying to protect them so they end up back with the drakes,'' seidon told the star-ledger of newark
i know i sound like a crazy old man but i'm not,'' he said
the elephants' owners and the president of a national animal trainers group say the animals were not harmed, and both sides accuse each other of lacking an elephant-like memory about the incident
edward drake says seidon sold him the elephants for $80,000 in 1981, when the drakes owned an exotic animal ranch in tehachapi, calif., about 200 miles north of los angeles
drake said tuesday that seidon acted as his booking agent for animal shows after the sale but began cheating, taking money and finally the elephants while a circus was in new jersey
seidon told the star-ledger he exercised the terms of the sale contract by repossessing the elephants when the drakes fell behind in their payments
while waiting for money at a colts neck township farm, seidon said, he discovered the animals had wounds caused by hooks piercing their skin during training. on may 4, 1984, after a superior court judge in monmouth county ordered the elephants returned, he fled with them
his attorney, estelle strauss, said tuesday her client never stole money and that he only wanted to help tory and duchess
the elephants' condition was never aired at the trial,'' said ms. strauss. ``he had an agreement that he could repossess the animals if they were abused. his position has not changed.''
but edward drake, who like his father is now out of the animal business, said seidon's story about the elephants' treatment is ``so far-fetched it's unbelievable.''
john cuneo, president of the illinois-based national congress of animal trainers and breeders, said the drakes did not abuse their animals. ``they had beautiful elephants. i even wanted to buy one,'' he said
cuneo said anyone concerned about an animal's condition can alert state, federal and private monitoring authorities
seidon has forsaken his fordland, mo., farm and his career preparing animals for circus and television appearances to care for his 25-year-old elephants, who eat about 200 pounds of hay a day
ms. strauss said she does not know where or how seidon conceals the elephants. he calls her periodically to check on his case, she said
she said he would come forward to face criminal charges _ third-degree theft carrying a sentence of up to five years in prison, a $100,000 fine or both _ if he wins a safe haven for the elephants. the attorney filed a court motion last week to overturn the judgment awarding the animals to the drakes
county assistant prosecutor alton kenney said he was not ready to discuss any deals for seidon and had not heard from ms. strauss
the communist party said wednesday a sweeping political purge of two decades ago showed ``manifestations of anti-semitism,'' but it added that most party members took no part in the religious bias
more than 9,000 jews lost official positions in the 1968 ``anti-zionist'' purge, and an estimated 12,000-20,000 emigrated, more than half the jews then living in poland
the acknowledgement of anti-semitism by the party newspaper trybuna ludu carried the authority of an official statement. it also was repeated by the state-run news agency pap and reported prominently on state tv and radio
but one leader of the 1968 student protests which sparked the purge said the newspaper's article did not go far enough in its condemnation of anti-semitism and that it repeated past slanders against jews
it ``amounts to drawing wool over people's eyes,'' said adam michnik, a writer and prominent leader of poland's anti-government opposition
the article in trybuna ludu, the official daily of the polish united workers (communist) party, was timed to coincide with the 20th anniversary of the 1968 ``events.''
discrimination against jews, in the guise of ``anti-zionism'' which had begun after the june 1967 israeli victory in the middle east war, accelerated sharply after march 1968 student demonstrations around the country against censorship
the purge, which began within the party, soon spread to the government, army, academia, press and other official institutions,
the newspaper said some conservative, nationalist party factions at the time ``took advantage of the jewish ancestry'' of their political rivals
they did not realize then that they were being manipulated by various political factions which in different ways made use of their actions.''
some western histories have charged that students were provoked by conservative factions using them to provide a pretext for a purge
poland was home to about 3.5 million jews before the war, who represented about 10 percent of the population. estimates vary, but the number of jews in the country now is believed to be between 7,000 and 15,000
explaining the origins of the anti-semitism, trybuna ludu referred to support of israel expressed by some polish jews after the 1967 war and prominent roles held by jews during the stalinist period of the late 1940s to early 1950s
polish people preserved the memory of unlawful conduct, of violation of law and order, and of the perpetrators of those offenses. it was easy in 1968 to use that memory as a background for presenting the `alien ... group' as the source of all evil,'' it said
but the article added that these explanations ``by no means'' could excuse anti-semitic acts in poland
michnik, referring to the explanations, said, ``all the obscenities of the march (1968) propaganda campaign have been repeated, all of them. what has been done is nothing but cosmetics.''
a leading party theoretician and journalist, ludwik krasucki, said tuesday on polish tv that the party's attempts to reconsider the history of the period were vital
he expressed hope that by thoroughly reexamining the 1968 events, ``this chapter, which nevertheless can't be forgotten, shall once and for all be closed.''
negotiators on wednesday launched their latest and possibly last round of afghanistan peace talks, and the u.n. mediator said he was confident of forging a settlement to end soviet involvement in the country
this was a good session,'' pakistan's acting foreign minister, zain noorani, said as he emerged from the first closed-door meeting late wednesday. ``we are cautiously optimistic.''
pakistan is representing the afghan guerrillas in the talks
afghanistan's foreign minister, abdul wakil, told reporters that his meeting with mediator diego cordovez was ``very nice.''
cordovez has been the go-between since the indirect negotiations began nearly six years ago. because pakistan refuses to recognize afghanistan's soviet-backed government, the delegations sit in separate rooms, with cordovez shuttling back and forth
before the talks opened, cordovez told reporters he believed both sides had the ``political will'' to work out an agreement
soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev announced last month that if a settlement were signed by march 15, the withdrawal of an estimated 115,000 red army troops from afghanistan could begin by may 15
the soviets intervened in 1979 to back the kabul government in its war with moslem guerrillas
pakistan wants any settlement to be accompanied by formation of a transitional government, replacing the present one headed by president najib
it argues that only a broad-based government could prevent new bloodshed in a country where war has already claimed more than a million lives
cordovez said the new talks would ``last as long as necessary'' to reach an agreement and added, ``perhaps it will be signed earlier than you think.''
he said some ``difficult'' problems remained but said he was sure they could be resolved soon
cordovez didn't say what those problems were, but reports have suggested they focus on the timetable for the soviet withdrawal and the timing of the cutoff of military aid to the warring sides
the united states last year gave an estimated $700 million worth of military assistance to the 200,000 insurgents fighting the soviets and the smaller afghan forces
noorani said pakistan will decide next week whether it is prepared to sign a settlement with the present afghan leadership. the decision will come after consultations sunday between prime minister mohammed khan junejo and political leaders, including those from opposition groups
pakistan has argued that under current conditions, the more than 3 million afghan refugees in pakistan and another 2 million in iran could not return home
cordovez said, ``civil strife is part of the way of life there,'' and he said there was a ``posibility'' that it would continue. but he added that he believed that the ``people of afghanistan are tired of this conflict, that they want peace.''
cordovez said he had been in contact with representatives of several countries, including the united states, the soviet union, the european community and australia, to discuss humanitarian aid to afghanistan after a settlement
i have the feeling that there will be a broad international effort,'' he said
the sense of optimism was not shared by iran, which is not participating in the talks. tehran has refused to participate as long as the moslem resistance is not invited
iranian ambassador sirous nasseri told reporters that iran attaches ``no significance to the settlement as it is being forumulated here.'' he said the main problems were related to formation of a government acceptable to all afghans and the phasing of the soviet pullout
i doubt very much that this could be solved here,'' he said
gov.-elect buddy roemer is testing his influence by backing a candidate to take his old seat in the u.s. house of representatives, but so far his favorite is running no better than second
state sen. foster campbell, the front-runner in the field of 10, says he has not worried about roemer's endorsement of stan tiner, former editor of the shreveport journal
i'm just trying to see folks and i'm taking it day by day,'' said campbell, a democrat
if no candidate wins a majority of the non-partisan vote on march 8, a runoff between the top two would be held on april 16
the winner will fill roemer's unexpired term and faces re-election this fall. roemer resigned the seat effective march 14, the day he takes office as governor, replacing edwin edwards
the field also includes state rep. claude ``buddy'' leach, who lost the seat to roemer in 1980 after one term during which he was acquitted of charges in a vote-buying scandal. leach later returned to the state house but lost a race last year for state treasurer
the other candidates include jim mccrery, the lone republican and formerly roemer's top aide; june phillips, an administrator at southern university-shreveport and the only black in the race; mayor gene byars of minden; shreveport lawyers troy bain and marshall jones; charles martin, a retired shreveport businessman; and mitchell e. marsh, a fencing contractor from mansfield
recent polls by the journal and joint polls by the shreveport times and ksla-tv have shown campbell ahead. in the journal poll published feb. 19, campbell had the support of 26 percent, followed by tiner with 16 percent and mccrery and leach close behind
the times-ksla poll released on feb. 26 had tiner running third, five points behind leach
campbell, a state senator since 1976, would not predict who would be in the runoff with him
whoever i'm in a runoff with, i can beat,'' he said
roemer, who insists he hasn't formally endorsed anyone, recently appeared at a fundraiser for tiner and gave him a campaign contribution
that's it,'' roemer said of his efforts. ``i said publicly, the truth. `who am i going to vote for?' i said stan tiner. we're 20-year friends
but frankly, i've got other friends in that race. june phillips, great person. jim mccrery, great person. i'm leaving five people out and i shouldn't have gotten into this.''
a harvard student who contends she is being excluded from the breeding grounds of power is challenging the membership policies of nine exclusive all-male student clubs
in her complaint before massachusetts commission against discrimination, lisa j. schkolnick argues that the fly and eight other ``final clubs'' may be violating state laws prohibiting sexual discrimination in public institutions by refusing to admit women
schkolnick said in a recent interview that she picked the fly at random as the target of her suit, and considers it representative of the other clubs. the commission, a quasi-legal entity, has the power to investigate cases, award damages, and seek injuctions
the clubhouses are located in some of the most expensive real estate holdings in and around harvard square, discreetly shielded by tall hedges and unmarked doors. some have separate entraces for women visitors
they were originally called final clubs to distinguish them from waiting clubs _ less exclusive, now extinct organizations. evolving from fraternities to eating clubs in the past century, they became social meeting places by the 1950s. past members have included both franklin and theodore roosevelt and several members of the kennedy clan
harvard formally severed ties to the clubs in 1984, after members refused a university demand to admit women. but schkolnick's case rests on the argument that the clubs remain an integral part of student life and cannot be considered private
the issue has become a major topic of debate on campus
the undergraduate student council last week narrowly rejected a proposal to endorse schkolnik's cause, but voted to reimburse $250 in office costs to a lawyer who offered to help her without a fee
harvard law professor alan dershowitz expressed moral support, urging council members to back schkolnick
i think it's the first major challenge to what have been very entrenched institutions at harvard,'' dershowitz said in an interview. ``these finals clubs are the minor leagues for the power clubs in the major cities, the all-male ones.''
dershowitz, a former yale student, compared the clubs to yale groups ``so secret i didn't even know about them until i graduated,'' and to princeton university's two remaining all-male eating clubs, now appealing a state order to admit women
barbara bolten, vice president of public relations in the boston chapter of the national organization for women said, ``we support the philosophy of what she's doing totally, and i hope she wins.''
schkolnick, a 21-year-old philosophy senior from princeton, n.j., said she was the target of a rash of crank calls, ``some obscene, others frightening,'' for several weeks after she filed her complaint dec. 14
she suggested that the clubs serve as old-boy networks to the detriment of women
these are power centers, and these people are being fed into powerful positions, and women are being excluded,'' she said. ``i'm going to be a lawyer one day, and i could have used some of these positions that members are exposed to.''
the clubs, in turn, deny that their members gain undue advantage through networking and argue they are strictly private organizations which should be allowed to decide on membership
there are some people in the clubs established in business, but it's definitely not an institutionalized process through which you secure interviews through alumni,'' said stan novak, former president of the fox final club
novak, who graduated last year, was the only one of several final club members polled on the controversy willing to go on the record. judith malone, a lawyer retained by the fly, declined comment
the clubs do not publicize their membership rolls. but several students estimated that more than 10 percent of harvard's undergraduate males belong. total undergraduate enrollment is about 6,400
novak said membership didn't help him in his job search
the fact that after being president for a year, i was still sitting around from june till jan. 1, that will give you an idea about ... how effective alumni ties are,'' said novak, of barrington, r.i
the supreme court was urged on wednesday to block states from recouping the costs of keeping criminals behind bars by seizing money which prison inmates receive in federal benefits
lawyers representing the reagan administration and a former prison inmate attacked an arkansas law that let authorities seize for state use an inmate's social security or veterans administration benefits
they said the law, similar to those enacted in four other states, conflicts with federal laws specificially barring any legal action aimed at diverting benefits away from designated recipients
congress could have made an exception for state institutional care,'' argued justice department lawyer richard j. lazarus. ``but congress has not done so here. in our view, that is simply the end of the issue.''
thomas m. carpenter, a little rock lawyer representing former state prison inmate george bennett, also contended that the arkansas law ``must fall.''
the issue before the high court is not whether those inmates with available money may be charged for their imprisonment but whether states may get at money the inmates receive in federal benefits
the impact of the justices' decision, expected by july, has been blunted somewhat by laws passed by congress in 1980 and 1983 withholding or limiting benefits otherwise due imprisoned felons
the justices asked few questions, and what had been scheduled as a hour-long argument session was over in 35 minutes
bennett had served 11 years of a 21-year sentence at a pine bluff prison for second-degree murder when he turned 62. he started receiving $275 a month in social security retirement benefits. bennett was released from prison in late 1984 but is seeking to recover $3,600 in benefits confiscated by the state
the arkansas legislature in 1981 had passed an inmate care and custody reimbursement act. under it, state authorities may seek court approval to seize an inmate's estate _ income from any source
similar laws have been enacted in michigan, ohio, oklahoma and tennessee
reagan administration lawyers had told the justices in briefs submitted previously that the rationale used by the arkansas supreme court in upholding the 1981 state law ``would seem to validate the attachment of social security and va benefits paid to persons confined in state mental hospitals or in other institutions where they are provided care by the state.''
they said it is important for the arkansas law to be invalidated so the growing number of states asking prison inmates to help foot the bill of their imprisonment will not seize federal benefits
arkansas attorney general steve clark told the justices wednesday that arkansas merely was trying to prevent ``windfall benefits'' for prison inmates who receive their food, clothing and medical care at state expense
clark said congress' intent of protecting people ``from the rigors of poverty'' was ``not frustrated by the arkansas statute at all.''
responding to clark's contention that the state had not ``created any kind of hardship,'' carpenter said his client could make good use of the money wrongly withheld from him
carpenter described bennett as ``a 69-year-old man who can't get a job'' and who would be destitute if he had not been cared for by relatives
the case is bennett vs. arkansas, 86-6124
a nine-day sit-in by minority students at hampshire college ended wednesday with the signing of a 16-point agreement designed to encourage racial harmony at the small private school
the acceptance of our demands by the administration is both an acknowledgment of institutional indifference and neglect and of the immediate need for redress,'' anita fearman, a spokeswoman for the protesters, told a gathering of 150 students
the group watched as college president adele simmons and two other administrators signed the document outside the dormitory office occupied by an estimated 40 protesters since feb. 23
the six-page settlement provided for a dean of multicultural affairs, an adviser for the group that occupied dakin house office and at least $4,500 in yearly funding for the group
the adminstration also agreed to take no disciplinary action against the students and to allow them to make up work they missed during the sit-in
i think the institution won,'' simmons said after the signing. ``for the last several years we've been working to improve student life and this represents a finishing of the old agenda
a number of the things they asked for were already in place, but i think the occupation strengthened the institution,'' she said
dean of students trey williams said the occupation had taken a toll on many at the liberal arts school, where about 100 of the 1,100 students are minorities
the students are exhausted, the president is sick. but it's better that it took us only one week than forever,'' he said
the occupation was prompted by what students described as the school's longstanding indifference to their concerns
they were claiming this is a multiculturally diverse community, which isn't true,'' said protester penny predmas
college officials said the allegation was a surprise, given the school's image as a progressive alternative to the sort of traditional liberal arts education offered at nearby amherst, mount holyoke and smith colleges. hampshire students design their own courses of study and graduate after passing three divisional examinations requiring them to complete individual research projects and some classwork
we're way in front in transforming curriculum to be much more global,'' said faculty dean penina glazer, ``but we're lagging in recruiting of minority students and we're trying as hard as we can.''
the agreement came two weeks after the end of an occupation at nearby university of massachusetts that was sparked by campus racial violence. that takeover ended when chancellor joseph duffey agreed to increase funding of minority student programs and other demands
a university disciplinary hearing began tuesday into allegations that five white male students assaulted two black male students on feb. 7, said spokeswoman jeanne hopkins
protesters at hampshire said racial violence is rare on their campus, but said there have been several instances of harassment and discrimination since a cross was found burning on a building lawn 11 years ago
the protesters said, however, that the sympathy shown them by students and faculty during the occupation had changed their minds about warning minorities away from the school
i really would tell them to come here,'' said predmas
a few white students watching the signing ceremony said they supported the protesters' aims, but disagreed over the wisdom of occupying the dormitory office
there basically was a lot of friction,'' said paul trunnell. ``the feeling was, `either you're in or out. either you support us or you don't.' well, no two of us agreed on this campus, but it's important that we band together to solve these sorts of problems.''
vice president george bush called himself ``the most stable'' candidate wednesday, crediting himself with good judgment that sets him apart in the presidential race
you want steadiness. you want judgment. you want even temperament,'' bush said. he added that a president ``can't make these outrageous claims.''
bush didn't elaborate, but in recent days he has disputed rival gop candidate pat robertson's contentions concerning soviet missiles in cuba, robertson's knowledge of u.s. hostage whereabouts in lebanon and the possibility the bush campaign tried to hurt robertson by manipulating the timing of allegations against tv evangelist jimmy swaggart
in a much-publicized iowa flap one month ago, a bush aide questioned dole's temperament, calling him ``mean-spirited.''
bush commented wednesday after seeing u.s. navy warships in drydock at the ingalls shipyard here. he was accompanied by former navy secretary john lehman
the vice president told the shipyard workers that democratic candidate michael dukakis wanted to reduce the number of navy battleships. bush called that ``a dumb idea.''
beginning his day in clearwater, fla., bush talked of his five children _ including florida secretary of commerce jeb bush _ and 10 grandchildren, and also said his support of prayer in the schools is of long standing
they ought to take a look at my family and what i epitomize in this regard,'' bush told reporters
bush also served boiled crawfish at a small rally in biloxi, miss., spoke briefly to supporters at the mobile, ala., airport and planned to participate in a cajun feast in baton rouge, la., before heading to greenville, s.c
at the shipyard here, bush saw the uss stark, the navy ship damaged last year by iraqi missiles in the persian gulf. it is being overhauled and repaired. he also toured the first of a new class of amphibious assault ships called the lhd class
he spoke of the expansion of the navy under the reagan administration and lehman
on tuesday, bush was accompanied through florida by former sen. barry goldwater of arizona
goldwater is right when he says george bush will be the best president,'' bush said in mobile. ``i can think of no single endorsement more helpful than that of barry goldwater.''
the bush campaign plans to use a goldwater endorsement commercial in some of the southern states voting in the march 8 super tuesday primary
democrat jesse jackson didn't have a paid staff, much money or very high hopes in overwhelmingly white vermont, but his campaign pulled off a strong second-place finish in tuesday's presidential primary
it has a tremendous significance on a symbolic level,'' garrison nelson, a university of vermont political science professor, said wednesday. ``this is exactly what jackson hoped for. he can now say he appealed to more than just blacks going into super tuesday.''
jackson finished with 26 percent, behind massachusetts gov. michael dukakis, whose 15-person paid staff and 60-plus volunteers helped him capture 57 percent of the vote. vice president george bush won the gop primary
this is a home-grown campaign where people have worked all the time, constantly on the issues,'' said chris wood of the jackson campaign. ``we're working on issues that jackson is talking about.''
wood said many of those who worked for jackson also were active in grass roots organizations supporting low-income vermonters and the state's financially distressed dairy farmers. many also have protested apartheid in south africa
jackson raked in three times as many votes tuesday as he did in 1984, when he won 7.8 percent of the vote
according to unofficial results, with 100 percent of the state's 262 precincts reporting, dukakis had 57 percent, jackson 26 percent, rep. richard gephardt 8 percent; sen. paul simon 5 percent and former sen. gary hart, who won vermont in 1984, 4 percent. sen. albert gore jr. was not on the ballot here
on the republican side, bush received 49 percent, sen. bob dole 39 percent, former television evangelist pat robertson 5 percent and rep. jack kemp 4 percent
political observers had predicted a tight race between jackson and gephardt for second place, but jackson stole the show
he ran a strong second in the state's largest city of burlington and actually beat dukakis in 27 smaller communities and tied him in two
it depended really on volunteers,'' said eric davis, a political science professor at middlebury college. ``they weren't putting up lawn signs _ they weren't doing mailings. to get almost 30 percent of the vote just on grass roots says something about jackson's appeal.''
jackson's campaign was propelled by the alliance of the rainbow coalition of vermont and the progressive coalition and its most prominent member, burlington mayor bernard sanders
sanders, a socialist, endorsed jackson during one of his recent visits to the state. jackson was one of the few candidates to actively campaign in vermont in the last days before the election
the fight for vermont's delegates to the national convention begins in april with local party caucuses. marjabelle young stewart, which moved in am-brites for wednesday ams.</note>
