hart, 2,052 - 4 percent
jackson, 13,030 - 26 percent
simon, 2,596 - 6 percent
construction workers stayed off the job throughout nicaragua for the third day wednesday to demand higher wages and to protest the sandinista government's new economic measures
the opposition general workers confederation said 4,000 workers had been on strike since monday, paralyzing 53 construction projects nationwide. the labor ministry said the strikes involved 600 workers at 12 work sites
the workers are demanding a 200 percent salary increase and an end to wage scales that are fixed for almost all jobs. construction workers earn the equivalent of $412 a month. apprentices make $266
these salaries don't meet the basic food needs,'' said carlos salgado, secretary-general of the general workers confederation, in an interview
citing runaway inflation, the government announced a series of economic measures feb. 14. a new version of the currency, the cordoba, was issued and valued at 10 to the dollar. prices set by the leftist government for most products soared
the old currency was fetching 20,000 to $1 on the legal exchange and more than 50,000 to the dollar on the black market
president daniel ortega said the measures were intended to fight inflation, which he said was running at 1,300 percent. unofficial estimates put the figure at 7,000 percent
under a new wage scale, salaries range from the equivalent of $50 a month to $753. the price of a pound of meat rose from about $1 per pound to $3.50. eggs went from just over $1 a dozen to $2.50
angel reyes palma, regional director of work inspection for the labor ministry, called the construction workers' strike illegal
he said a legal strike requires a petition and naming of a special judge to determine the merits of the case
they want to boycott the economic measures, and while they stay on strike there is no negotiation,'' reyes said
strikes were illegal in nicaragua under a state of emergency the government imposed in 1982, shortly after the war with the u.s.-backed contras heated up. the restrictive measures were withdrawn in january as part of the government's compliance with a regional peace plan
threats against tawana brawley may soon motivate the family to end a stalemate and begin cooperating with state prosecutors, according to a report published wednesday
the family of the black wappingers falls teen-ager who claims she was kidnapped and sexually assaulted by six white men in november is increasingly concerned about her safety, the poughkeepsie journal, said, quoting an anonymous source said to be close to the family
on the advice of her lawyers, c. vernon mason and alton maddox jr., the family has thus far refused to cooperate with attorney general robert abrams, whom gov. mario cuomo appointed as a special prosecutor
the lawyers want abrams ousted and a permanent special prosecutor named to investigate race-related crimes
mason and maddox did not immediately return telephone calls to their office wednesday
the rev. al sharpton, a new york city minister who has been advising the brawleys, denied that the family was on the verge of cooperating with authorities and refused to comment on reports there had been threats against miss brawley
sharpton confirmed that he had taken miss brawley from the home of matthew strong, the uncle with whom she had been staying since the attack. he would not say where miss brawley was staying
a woman who answered the phone at the brawley's house wednesday said neither glenda brawley, miss brawley's mother, nor juanita brawley, the girl's aunt, were available. she said the family had no comment
miss brawley, 16, was found wrapped in a garbage bag after being missing for four days last november. excrement was smeared on her body and ``kkk'' and ``nigger'' were written in charcoal or black ink on her body
strong had vowed to ``march tawana down to abrams' office'' if the stalemate did not end in the next few days, the journal quoted the source as saying. strong has been critical of the lawyers' handling of the case, according to several published reports
a 23-member grand jury was empaneled monday to investigate the case, and jurors heard an opening statement from abrams. sharpton called the attorney general's participation monday ``a good sign.''
the panel is not expected to hear evidence this week
the centrist social democrats and liberals will unite on thursday after a stormy courtship during which they ran as the alliance in two elections but were proccupied with their own quarrels
the new social and liberal democrats party hopes to end the dominance of the governing conservatives and the socialist labor party, the main opposition
in a mail referendum, social democrats voted 18,722 to merge and 9,929 against, or slightly under 2-1. liberals approved the union 46,376 to 6,365, or more than 7-1, said to the london-based electoral reform society, which counted the votes
separate party conventions approved the merger last month
only 55.5 percent of the 52,000 social democrats and 52.3 percent of the 90,000 liberals voted. protracted infighting over the merger had split both parties
liberal leader david steel and robert maclennan, the social democrat leader, toasted each other with champagne
steel, who is expected to be elected leader of the new party, said he looked forward to ``success and the future.'' maclennan described the vote as ``clinching.'' the party is to be officially launched thursday
david owen, who resigned as social democrat leader in opposition to the union, had urged members to boycott the vote and called it a ``fiasco.'' he plans to continue the social democrats as a separate party
the two parties began the merger process after placing a distant third in last june's general election, won by prime minister margaret thatcher's conservatives
jody powell is volunteering the public relations skills he practiced in the white house to fight plans for a shopping mall near fields where his confederate ancestors fought
powell, who was president carter's press secretary, is putting the resources of his firm, ogilvy &amp; mather public affairs of washington at the disposal of groups joined in the save the battlefield coalition
powell said tuesday the fight to preserve the site near the manassas battlefield national park is worthwhile because encroaching development is a problem at many other battlefields and historic sites as well
goodness, if you can't stop something this bad, then what hopes do you have of fending off more creeping sorts of problems, where a park gets nibbled to death?'' powell said
ten of his family members fought at the battle of second manassas in 1862, part of which was waged on land where the hazel-peterson cos. of fairfax plan to break ground for william center
one of powell's ancestors was mortally wounded just before the battle, as confederate maj. gen. thomas ``stonewall'' jackson raided the union supply depot at manassas junction
on the site where gen. robert e. lee built his headquarters during second manassas, hazel-peterson and the edward j. debartolo corp. of ohio plan to build a 1.2 million-square-foot shopping mall. delegates</head>
republican presidential candidate george bush picked up 24 delegates in new york this week by virtue of his opponents' failure to file delegate slates in eight of the state's congressional districts
and successful challenges to non-bush delegate slates in other districts, if upheld by the courts, could leave the vice president with at least two dozen other delegates running unopposed
the board of elections on tuesday wiped two slates of delegates supporting bob dole off the the april 19 primary ballot, one day after stripping the kansas senator's slate and one backing new york rep. jack kemp from the ballot
the petitions were rejected mainly because they did not contain the required 1,250 signatures of registered republicans, or were signed by republicans living outside the congressional district the petitions were filed for
while bush slates remain on the ballot in 33 of the state's 34 congressional districts, kemp will be able to field delegate slates in only 12 districts, dole in 11 and robertson in nine
having delegate slates on the ballot is all-important in new york where registered republicans will not vote for any of the candidates, but for the delegates who pledge to support them at the national convention in new orleans
the candidates that the delegates back will be listed next to the delegates' names on this year's ballot
at stake in new york are 102 delegates, three from each congressional district. the republican state committee will designate 34 other delegates after the primary
the vice president's campaign has managed to get 10 dole slates knocked off the ballot, as well as six slates supporting pat robertson and five backing kemp
decisions disqualifying nominating petitions can be appealed to state courts, and bush opponents say they will pursue that course in most cases
meanwhile, in the early round of the wyoming caucuses, dole gained one delegate while another remains uncommitted. caucuses in the state continue through saturday
a mentally ill prostitute who sold his blood even though he is infected with aids was acquitted wednesday of charges of attempted poisoning
jurors said they had decided that joseph markowski lacked the intent required for a conviction under state law, frustrating prosecutors who said the 29-year-old drifter ``can go out and do this again.''
what this has told us here today is that the law in the state of california does not make it a crime to sell aids-contaminated blood. and that's unfortunate,'' said los angeles county district attorney ira reiner
markowski, a homosexual prostitute who has tested positive for the aids virus, nodded to his attorney, guy o'brien, as the jury found him innocent of two counts of attempted poisoning
he had been accused of selling his tainted blood for $10 to plasma production associates last june 22 and of trying to do so again june 25. one of the ways aids can be spread is by transfusion of infected blood or blood products. he would have faced up to seven years in prison if convicted
i'm delighted and i'm a little surprised'' by the verdict, said o'brien, who had argued that markowski, homeless and destitute, had sold his blood in desperation
i was afraid the jury wouldn't have the courage to follow the letter of the law. i thought the fear of aids ... would preoccupy the jury.''
markowski, originally from michigan, was first arrested june 23 after screaming, ``kill me! kill me! i have aids!'' in a hollywood bank while attempting to grab a security guard's gun. police found on him a receipt for the plasma center
deputy district attorney antonio barreto jr. argued at trial that markowski knew his blood was tainted. he said the drifter sold it knowing it might contaminate the plasma pool but didn't care
juror bill ferguson of echo park said that even though markowski knew what he was doing, he was doing it for money, not to poison
right now you have to prove specific intent. you have to be able to prove that a person went down there willfully to poison the supply. that was not the case in this case,'' ferguson said
the legislature has been sitting on their duff in this area for some time,'' said barreto. ``we need legislation on this. he can go out and do this again today, as long as he said `i just did it for the money.'''
prosecutors tried last year to have a law passed that would make it a felony to knowingly sell or donate aids-contaminated blood. the assembly failed to approve it, and reiner said he will push for it again this year
mr. markowski is today free to do what he did when he was arrested for the crime,'' reiner said. ``will he do it again? perhaps. all he needs to do now is adopt an alias.''
markowski had allegedly admitted to police that he sold his blood because he needed money and didn't care about the public, but superior court judge ronald coen ruled the statement inadmissible because police had not read markowski his rights to remain silent and wait for an attorney
the detective who interrogated markowski said he committed the error because he was so shocked by what markowski had done
deliberations began monday after a 10-day trial before coen. jurors returned the verdict tuesday after deliberating for seven hours, but it was sealed until wednesday because o'brien was unable to make it to court
reiner originally charged markowski with attempted murder. but coen dismissed those counts, saying the law required a specific intent to kill that was not present
o'brien said markowski suffers from mental illness and carries the aids virus but has not developed the disease. the attorney said markowski will be placed in a halfway house
the long-term prognosis at this point is not good. i'd say the outlook is guarded,'' he said
boys playing in an abandoned railroad station discovered a dog hanged by its neck from a pipe, the latest of several such incidents in the area, authorities said wednesday
the dog, a german shepherd mix, had been dead for five or six months, animal control officer john holmes said
it would have to be some type of nut that would take an animal like that and hang him from a pipe,'' holmes said
the schoolboys told holmes on tuesday that they had discovered several dead dogs in the crumbling pawtucket-central falls station
three years ago, holmes said, he found a hanged dog in the same place in the depot. similar cases have been reported in cumberland, lincoln, and attleboro, mass
in 1986, a 26-year-old pawtucket man was charged in connection with a rash of dog hangings in cumberland, but he skipped bail before trial
here, at a glance, are developments in the economic picture wednesday:
new home sales fell 9 percent in january. sales activity was the slowest since the last recession ended in december 1982
analysts were surprised by the decline, since sales had already fallen 6.8 percent in december and 3.4 percent in november
the sales downturn was accompanied by a sharp rise in prices. the median price of a home shot up 9.7 percent to $120,000
orders to u.s. factories for manufactured goods fell 0.6 percent in january, the first decline in five months
orders for both durable and non-durable goods dropped to a seasonally adjusted $212.6 billion following a big 2 percent increase in december
it was the first setback in orders since a 1.4 percent drop in august, but economists said it showed a return to more normal demand following the placement of several large orders for jet aircraft in december
the stock market settled for a small gain after a broad early advance faded. the dow jones average, up about 15 points at its best level of the day, finished with a .83 gain at 2,071.29
the tokyo stock exchange surged closer to pre-crash levels. the nikkei stock average closed at 25,682.82 points, up 246.92 points, or 0.97 percent from tuesday's close. before the october crash, the index stood at 25,746.56. volume in the first period of trading was 1.7 billion shares, a record high for this year
in london, the dollar gained against the british pound when the bank of england sold pounds to keep the british currency below 3.0 west german marks as the mark fell against the dollar. at the end of the day, one pound cost $1.7680, cheaper than $1.7775 late tuesday
in tokyo, the dollar closed at 128.47 japanese yen, up from 128.30 tuesday
alan greenspan, federal reserve board chairman, said deep cuts in ``entitlement'' programs, which include social security and medicare, may be the most realistic way for cutting the federal budget deficit
greenspan, testifying before the senate budget committee, also called for a 15-cent-a-gallon increase in the federal gasoline tax
but he said that, in general, tax increases do not appear to be a feasible way for trimming the budget shortfall, which was $150 billion last year. woman; inserts 4 grafs after graf 7, ``michael,'' with statement from company's lawyers, picks up graf 8, ``richard''; subs 2nd graf to clarify that pacoima is a district of los angeles.</note>
convinced they had won a $2 million sweepstakes offered by a california mail-order company, kathy and dale work bought a pickup truck and a new car and were about to quit their jobs. then they learned they hadn't won a thing
i guess it seems like we're a couple of country hicks,'' said mrs. work. ``we'd made all kinds of plans. i don't know what we're going to do now.''
the united states purchasing exchange, a company based in the pacoima district of los angeles that sponsored the sweepstakes, said mrs. work has not won anything _ at least not yet
the u.s. postal service said wednesday it had received complaints about the company and had forwarded them to the federal trade commission for investigation
a man who answered the telephone at a uspe telephone number said the sweepstakes is still in progress and that mrs. work is one of thousands with a chance at the top prize, said to be more than $2 million. the man would not give his name and would not respond to other questions
mrs. work is not the first person to be confused by the sweepstakes. debra long of pearl city, mich., woman told reporters she recently quit her job and vacationed in las vagas before learning she had not won $1.7 million, as she thought
michael flitcraft, a chardon, ohio, truck driver, said he thought he had won the contest after receiving a letter from the company on monday
david carlin of loeb &amp; loeb, a new york law firm representing uspe, issued a statement that disputed the michigan woman's claim but did not comment on mrs. work's claims
it is been reported that a prize in excess of $1 million was won by miss debra long of pearl city, mich., in a sweepstakes sponsored by united states purchasing exchange,'' carlin's statement said. ``miss long reported that she was notified by a certified letter from the company and she subsequently confirmed her winnings in a telephone conversation to the company on feb. 15, president's day
it appears that miss long is involved in a trick or hoax perpetrated by unknown parties, because the company does not notify winners by certified mail, the company's offices were closed on president's day, the company does not request bank account numbers from winners nor does it require the other information miss long claims was requested of her.''
mrs. work said the company also had requested her bank account numbers
richard eppstein, president of the toledo chapter of the better business bureau, said the bureau has received at least 20 complaints about uspe's contest over the last few years
the mail is just chock-full of these kinds of sweepstakes,'' eppstein said. ``and they are so ... worded that some people think they have won something when they have not.''
we have received a lot of complaints about the company, mostly from people who had not received merchandise they ordered from the company,'' said linda russo, occupational support specialist with the u.s. postal service in california
dave plottner of the regional office of the federal trade commission in cleveland declined comment on whether the agency is investigating uspe
mrs. work, who lives in stony ridge, 10 miles southeast of toledo, said she she received a letter from the company in october that read: ``we are pleased to inform you that you have been designated to receive certified bank checks from the united states purchasing exchange for $1,894,876 ... your winnings in our multimillion dollar sweepstakes when you are the grand prize winner.''
a few weeks later, another said her winnings stood at $2,024,464
then she received what she thought were two checks: one for $2 million and one for $24,000. she was asked to endorse them and send them back to the company along with her social security and bank account numbers
at that point, the works thought they were millionaires
however, the company's mailing said, ``certified bank check for this amount ... will be drawn and issued to kathy work upon verification that the kathy work entry has been selected by the independent judging organization as the prize-winner in accordance to the rules and regulations set forth and established.''
the mailed material does not indicate when the sweepstakes winner will be announced, mrs. work said
mrs. work, who has three children and runs the country girl beauty salon in her home, said she planned to close her business and her husband considered quitting his job as a crew chief at manville corp. in waterville
it doesn't look good, but i'm happy inside,'' she said. ``i know good is going to come to pass.'' from reviewer, picking up 16th graf ``j. charles''</note>
a bill to require licensing of restaurant reviewers has been introduced in the legislature after an owner complained that her establishment was savaged by a critic who didn't know a bolognese sauce from bottled tomato sauce
lawmakers give the measure little chance of passage because of concerns that it would violate the first amendment right of free speech. however, the restaurant industry says debate over the bill helped accomplish its main purpose
we wanted to provide a message to reviewers, the public and some editorial people that ... some of the persons providing the reviews are less than capable,'' carroll j. hughes, executive vice president of the 700-member connecticut restaurant association, said wednesday
hughes persuaded lawmakers to draft the bill after lucille trzcinski, co-owner of casagrande restaurant in wallingford, complained that two ``grossly inaccurate'' reviews last month caused her business to drop 15-20 percent
hughes said he gets a dozen complaints a year from restaurant owners about reviews. no state licenses restaurant critics, he said
we have to stand helplessly by while people are allowed to make unfounded, unsubstantiated and gratuitous remarks,'' mrs. trzcinski told a legislative committee tuesday. ``the damage that these reviews do numbers in the millions of dollars. it is our business and it is our livelihood.''
alan neigher, an attorney who specializes in media law, called the proposal ``preposterous.''
it's nothing more than a temper tantrum by some lobbyists and their clients who don't have an elementary understanding of what the role of free speech in a free economy is about,'' neigher said. ``the courts have repeatedly struck down attempts to license the press.''
mrs. trzcinski, who has operated casagrande with her husband for 11 years, said her restaurant previously received high marks from some of the toughest critics in the state for its northern italian cuisine
she complained that two recent reviewers made numerous mistakes, even when praising aspects of her menu
one mistook a fine loin of veal for a veal pattie and complained about her bagna cauda, an elegant oil-and-anchovy dip, because he was expecting a more pedestrian dip, she said
another incorrectly suggested that her bolognese sauce was tomato based and flavored with cheese, when it's actually a pork sauce flavored with a little tomato, mrs. trzcinski said
i would say he probably couldn't recognize a proper bolognese because he's familiar with ragu,'' she said
the reviewer also made an ethnic joke about the restaurant's having a polish chef, she said
the reviewer, who uses the pen name r. alan richards in restaurant reviews for the new haven register, said he thought his review was ``fairly positive'' and blamed the dispute over the bolognese sauce on semantics and misinformation supplied by a waitress
licensing opinions is kind of silly,'' said richards, who has been reviewing restaurants for seven or eight years. neither he nor the new haven register would reveal his real name
j. charles mokrisky, an attorney and the part-time food critic who complained about the bagna cauda, defended his opinion
i call 'em the way i see 'em,'' said mokrisky, who calls himself a ``food fanatic.''
under the proposal, restaurant critics would have to be licensed through the department of consumer protection. a critic could be fined $500 for reviewing without a license
the proposed license requirements include experience in food-service operation and management, graduation from a recognized culinary arts degree program, or a combination of at least six years of experience and formal training
i have sympathy for her,'' said rep. john wayne fox, co-chairman of the general law committee that held a public hearing on the bill. ``but i just was not convinced it was a serious enough problem that we as a legislature ought to regulate it.''
a farmer-lawmaker is hoping his colleagues will hop to it and approve a bill that would give a tax break to frog farmers
farms for frogs should be exempt from local property taxes, just like any other place that has ``livestock,'' conservative michael colvin told a house of commons committee studying a local finance bill
as now written, the bill defines livestock as ``any mammal or bird kept for the production of food or wool, or for the purpose of its use in the farming of land.''
that's fine for mammals and birds, but where does the frog, an amphibian, fit in? asked colvin
the definition of livestock is most unclear. times have changed in agriculture,'' he said, suggesting that the bill substitute ``creatures'' for ``livestock.''
it would be a sad day if any government started imposing a tax on frogs,'' said colvin
getting the attention of the wausa high school girls basketball team is easy. just shout ``anderson!'' and the five starters will turn their heads
the anderson girls _ only two of them related _ may be the first quintet with the same last name to assemble on court in a nebraska high school basketball game
the lady vikings, 22-1, play exeter on thursday in the opening round of the state high school basketball tournament in lincoln, and fans will get a chance to see the five andersons and their eight teammates
everyone notices it,'' said becky anderson, a 5-foot-11-inch junior who plays center and forward
becky and her cousin lori are joined by collette, tiffany and laura anderson in the starting lineup
senior laura is the team's star, averaging 16 points per game. she says having the same name as four other players on the team hasn't caused the players any problems. but it's another matter for announcers
they get mixed up once in a while,'' she said
it's easy to tell them apart,'' said charles haag, the team's assistant coach. ``but we definitely have to use first names.''
ballet fans beware: a california legislator is trying to make the west coast swing, a space-saving variant of the jitterbug, the official state dance
under state sen. quentin kopp's bill, the west coast swing would join the ranks of gold, serpentine rocks, the desert tortoise, dog-faced butterfly and the saber-toothed tiger _ all officially recognized symbols of the golden state
gold is the state mineral, serpentine the state rock, desert tortoise the state reptile, dog-faced butterfly the state insect and the saber-toothed tiger the state fossil
west coast swing is an intricate dance, requiring a great deal of coordination, good timing and intelligent application,'' kopp, a san francisco independent, wrote to fellow lawmakers recently
according to oakland businessman walter harmon, who approached kopp with the idea of honoring the dance, west coast swing is a variation of the jitterbug, a jazz dance
the variation was developed because it takes up less room than the freewheeling jitterbug, and thus more couples can dance on a smaller floor, said harmon
it's a very complex, very beautiful dance,'' said harmon, legislative liaison director for the united states swing dance council
he also claims it is the only indigenous california dance to survive in essentially its original form, and is thus worthy of historical recognition and preservation. trail sted swift trial and fix typo in `assignment' in lead. picks up 5th graf pvs, `he now ...'</note>
john ehrlichman, a former white house aide who spent time in prison for his role in the watergate scandal, says his assignment covering the impeachment trial of gov. evan mecham for rolling stone magazine is ``a match made in heaven.''
i'm working on a novel and it has an impeachment scene in it, so i was going to come over and and take a look at this, anyway,'' ehrlichman said tuesday. ``it's a ready-made opportunity to observe. secondly, it's a subject that intrigues me. i certainly have some feel for the underlying issues.''
ehrlichman, a former top-ranking official for president richard nixon, resigned from his white house post in april 1973 and was convicted in 1975 for obstruction of justice, conspiracy and perjury in the attempted cover-up of the watergate burglary
ehrlichman, 63, spent 18 months at swift trail camp, a minimum-security federal prison south of safford, ariz., and was released in 1978
he now lives in santa fe, n.m., and is working on his seventh novel, a story about a fictional u.s. president
ehrlichman said he sees few correlations between the problems of nixon and mecham
here is a fellow (mecham) with a criminal proceeding, an impeachment and a recall all going on at the same time, all pretty much bottomed on the same facts,'' said ehrlichman. ``i think it's very different (from watergate). it raises all kinds of interesting legal questions about double jeopardy and things like that.''
more than 60 anti-apartheid demonstrators were arrested wednesday following a peaceful protest in front of the south african embassy
the arrests followed a rally protesting the south african government's decision to outlaw public dissent, which led to the arrest last week of nobel peace prize winner archbishop desmond tutu in johannesburg
randall robinson, a leader of the free south africa movement which has organized similar protests at the south african embassy since 1984, told a crowd of about 300 people that the demonstration marked ``the beginning of a new phase of the battle against apartheid.''
the rally was held down the street from the embassy to avoid violation of a district of columbia ordinance prohibiting demonstrations within 500 feet of foreign embassies
following remarks by members of congress, representives from the national organization for women, the afl-cio and other groups, a group of ``messengers'' approached the embassy
among those arrested were rep. john lewis, d-ga.; del. walter fauntroy, d-d.c.; u.s. civil rights commissioner mary f. berry; and robinson, who heads transafrica, a washington-based lobbying group on africa and the caribbean
robinson said the free south africa movement would continue to push for complete disinvestment of u.s. firms in south africa and urge congress to enact stronger sanctions
he said america needs to move ``the u.n. security council toward global sanctions and a president who will take the lead with our allies ...to totally isolate south africa.''
robinson said he hoped the new wave of protests would force presidential candidates to take a public position on south africa. he said only jesse jackson has been vocal on the issue thus far. 5th graf, ``the comnmissioner;'' inserts 3 grafs after 17th graf, ``most of,'' with bristol myers comment and background on existing ads</note>
prodded by the food and drug administration, pharmaceutical companies agreed wednesday to avoid any advertising that claims aspirin can help prevent a first heart attack, despite a report in a medical journal that drew this conclusion
fda commissioner frank e. young announced the agreement after he met for more than an hour with company representatives who came to his office in this washington suburb after he sent a letter reminding of the fda's power to regulate
at a news conference, young said he had told the manufacturers that if they promoted their products for a use not supported by an fda analysis, they could be guilty of mislabeling, and ``this mislabeling can lead to regulatory action by the fda.''
he said the manufacturers agreed to ``exercise voluntary restraint'' and to refrain ``from further promotion'' of aspirin as a protection against first heart attack. but young insisted that the action was not in response to ads that already have run
the commissioner said he was ``so busy'' in his job that he never read, listened or watched advertising and thus did not know if any ads run that violated the fda position have been run
he also said that no one had brought such ads to his attention
william c. macleod, director of consumer protection at the federal trade commission, which regulates drug advertising, refused repeatedly at the news conference to say if his agency had taken any action regarding ads by aspirin manufacturers. nor would he confirm that inappropriate ads had been run
young said the meeting was prompted by the publicity surrounding a study published jan. 28 in the new england journal of medicine
in the study, more than 11,000 physicians over the age of 40 took one aspirin every other day, while another group of physicians took placebos, or fake aspirin. at the end of 57 months, the study showed that those taking aspirin had a 47 percent fewer heart attacks
while refusing to say if the action was prompted by any ad that has run, young said the drug manufacturers had agreed to voluntarily ``refrain from further promotion of the study results.''
in a feb. 24 letter, young ``invited'' the drug manufacturers to attend a meeting at his fda office to discuss the aspirin findings
he wrote of his concern that ``the dissemination of certain types of information is clearly premature'' until the fda has analyzed the aspirin study and established ``appropriate'' labeling for use of the over-the-counter medication for the prevention of first heart attacks
the invitation letter also cited the federal law that forbids mislabeling of drugs
young said he told the manufacturers that all ads making any claims for uses of aspirin not approved by the fda were to be halted
from this time forward, any ads in the pipeline will not be grandfathered (escape enforcement),'' said young
both young and mcleod repeatedly declined to say if any advertising was being canceled as a result of the fda action, and the agerncy did not identify the drug manufacturers attending the meeting
most of those leaving the private meeting refused comment. an exception was dr. edward henry of squibb pharmaceutical products, who would say only, ``we're all in agreement. it was a very good meeting.''
marie-claude stockl, public affairs director for bristol-myers, said in a statement later: ``we agree with the fda that the final results need to be reviewed by the agency before communicating the use of aspirin for primary heart attack, and our actions to date have been consistent with that position.''
several drug companies have produced ads that promoted the use of aspirin to help prevent a second heart attack. these were based on a 1985 study that was analyzed by the fda. this earlier study has been incorporated in the agency's professional labeling statement on aspirin
but the study announced in january was the first to show evidence that aspirin could help prevent a primary, or first, heart attack
young said his concern is that the aspirin study involved a narrow group _ all physicians in good health _ and that an analysis of the study had not been completed
the fda said the aspirin therapy is not appropriate for everyone and ``could do more harm than good'' for some. young said the study showed that some subjects experienced stroke
he also said the aspirin therapy could harm the health of people with high blood pressure, gout, kidney or liver disease or peptic ulcer. aspirin also can cause intestinal bleeding, he said
this study used a healthy population of phsycians who could take their own blood pressure and who knew how to recognize intestinal bleeding,'' said young, and widespread use by patients without medical supervision could lead to serious complications
young said it will take about six months for the fda to analyze the study and then publish new professional labeling for aspirin
ford motor co. will comply with a court order and withhold profit-sharing checks scheduled to go to about 1,850 workers who are behind on child support payments, the automaker said wednesday
we're not a stakeholder in this. it's strictly between the individuals involved and wayne county,'' said ford spokesman mike moran
the order was issued by circuit judge richard kaufman on tuesday, four days after friend of the court of wayne county filed suit to obtain profit-sharing money in an effort to improve child support collection
friend of the court, which is involved with domestic relations cases and is affiliated with circuit court, ``has an obligation to insure compliance with child support orders,'' said its director, gerhard f. ritsema
the checks are to be distributed tuesday and are expected to average a record $3,700. more than 160,000 ford employees received the previous record profit-sharing checks of $2,100 in 1986
according to the court order, friend of the court will have eight weeks to settle the 1,850 cases
ritsema said eight weeks would be sufficient for wayne county's 35 circuit court judges to decide how much of each profit-sharing check will be given to the agency, adding that he hoped some people would opt to settle without a hearing
about $155 million in child support was collected in 1987, but 80 percent of the 225,000 parents supposedly paying child support are in arrears, ritsema said. he said the agency's action against ford employees could bring in as much as $4 million
kaufman's action disappointed many ford workers. four employees told the judge that child support already is being deducted from their pay. they said the agency should increase the deduction from their regular paychecks instead of going after their profit-sharing checks
the profit-sharing check is what we've realized after going eight years without a raise and turning ford motor company around,'' said robert morris jr., a 10-year ford employee
friend of the court is considering increasing the amount deducted from regular paychecks, ritsema said. but he said any such action would be in addition to pursuing profit-sharing money
friend of the court in washtenaw county has also moved to obtain profit-sharing money from ford workers who are behind on child support payments, moran said
he added that ford has rejected all 150 names on a list submitted by the southeastern michigan county agency, saying that not enough data was supplied for the automaker to verify the agency's claims
the army said wednesday it had stopped random drug testing for civilian workers to comply with a court ruling, but was asking the justice department to appeal the judgment
the service, in a brief statement, said it would limit its civilian drug testing for the time being to those instances in which ``there is a reasonable suspicion that a specific employee is under the influence of drugs while on duty.''
testing on a random basis, however, has been halted for now, the service added
the move follows a decision in u.s. district court in washington on tuesday in which a judge ruled that random drug testing amounted to an unreasonable search prohibited by the constitution
u.s. district judge thomas f. hogan said random checks of employees in so-called sensitive positions could not be justified by safety concerns, because the urine test used by the army did not indicate whether an employee was using drugs on the job
the army has asked the department of justice to appeal the ruling,'' the service said in its statement. ``the army has also requested that justice ask for a stay of the judge's order during the appeal process.''
hogan's ruling had no effect on the right of the armed forces to conduct random drug tests of active-duty personnel. delete redundant reference to higher prices.</note>
federal reserve board chairman alan greenspan told congress on wednesday it should consider trimming social security and other entitlement programs as it searches for ways to reduce the federal budget deficit
saying that such guaranteed-benefit programs ``account for nearly half of total outlays,'' greenspan held out little hope for major deficit reductions in other areas _ although he did propose a 15-cent gasoline tax
several rounds of deficit-reduction efforts already have taken care of the easy cuts,'' greenspan told the senate budget committee, which is considering president reagan's $1.09 trillion budget request for the fiscal year that begins oct. 1
greenspan said entitlement expenses, which include social security, medicare, medicaid and various forms of welfare, will rise dramatically in the early 21st century because of the ``increase in the beneficiary population.''
sen. kent conrad, d-n.d., told greenspan: ``baby boomers are going to be in for a big surprise when it's time for them to start collecting social security.'' baby boomers is the phrase given to the bulge in population from those born after world war ii and into the mid-1960s
greenspan, who as a private citizen chaired a bipartisan commission that helped overhaul social security financing in the early part of this decade, did not specify exactly which programs he would cut
but he said the effect of cuts in entitlement programs made now would be amplfied in years to come. he noted that some 38 million americans, or about 15 percent of the poplulation, ``are collecting social security retirmenet or disability benefits.''
despite the political problems associated with trimming benefit programs such as social security, greenspan told the committee: ``all the alternatives are known. the choices are political, not economic.''
i wish you well. and i don't think you need me to tell you how to go about it,'' he said
the reagan administration has projected a fiscal 1988 budget deficit of $146.74 billion. the congressional budget office, however, says it's likely to be about $157 billion, substantially above the $144 billion target called for in the gramm-rudman budget-balancing law
president reagan's budget recommendations for 1989 projects a 1989 deficit of $129.5 billion
social security spending is projected to reach $214.7 billion for the year, compared with $202.4 billion for 1987
other health and human services programs, including medicare and medicaid, spent $50.51 billion in the first four months of 1988, compared with $49.43 billion in the same period of 1987
interest payments on the $2.2 trillion national debt are expected to total $210.06 billion in fiscal 1988, accounting for 20 percent of total federal spending
greenspan suggested that not much more could be expected in the way of deficit reduction from further defense cuts or general tax increases
defense spending is approaching ``maintenance levels,'' greenspan said. and, as to new taxes, he testifed, ``there are upside limits to the share of income that can be taxed.''
for several decades, the overall federal tax bite has been fairly flat, at a bit less than 20 percent of gross national product. ... this stability is not a coinicidence but is indicative of the public's aversion to rising tax burdens.''
however, he suggested that a new 15-cent-a-gallon levy on gasoline prices would help ease the deficit in a small way, and might even promote more energy conservation
in other testimony, greenspan said:
_even if the fed wanted to drive down interest rates sharply at this time, ``we would find we would fail,'' because markets would likely resist such a move and ``would run away from us
_trade deficit improvements, led by higher import prices and surging exports, would continue even at current exchange-rate levels of the dollar
_there was some danger of increased inflation in the coming months, but higher prices do ``not appear to be on the order of a magnitude that should cause concern.''
_``there are no secret agreements'' among industrial nations involving interest rate levels in the united states that might be needed to support the goal of a stabilizing the u.s. dollar at its current rate of exchange. updating with new quotes in top 15 grafs, picking up in 12th graf pvs, mccloskey commenting</note>
pat robertson wants to drop his libel suit against a former congressman who questioned his war record because going to trial now would ``sacrifice his presidential campaign,'' his lawyer said wednesday. but robertson's accuser declared, ``he's chickening out of the trial just like he chickened out 37 years ago.''
former rep. paul mccloskey, r-calif., who has accused robertson of using his father's political influence to avoid combat duty in the korean war, has said in recent weeks he wouldn't settle the suit unless robertson paid the costs, which mccloskey estimates at $400,000, of defending against the suit
the trial, set to begin on tuesday, when robertson hopes to do well in delegate-rich southern primaries, would force him off the campaign trail for three weeks, attorney douglas rigler said
in dropping the lawsuit ``robertson does not intend to back away at any time from his denial of the charges that mr. mccloskey made,'' rigler said
he said that ``it is quite possible that mr. robertson will be asked to pay a substantial amount of court costs'' to cover the expenses of taking depositions from more than 50 witnesses
but rigler said he would likely appeal any such decision by u.s. district judge joyce hens green. he also suggested the $400,000 defense estimate of costs ``may be an artificial figure'' that includes lawyers' fees that robertson should not have to pay
mccloskey's lawyer, george lehner, said that, if anything, the defense estimate of its costs is ``artificially low.''
lehner said he will ask the judge to order robertson to go to trial on tuesday or force him to pay court costs as well as attorneys' fees
rigler said robertson will ask dismissal of the lawsuit because ``he is being asked to sacrifice his presidential campaign in order to vindicate his personal honor.''
robertson, in south carolina, said wednesday he wanted to press ahead with the suit but couldn't be in court and out campaigning for the republican presidential nomination at the same time
if the judge will give me about another month, i'd love to go into it,'' robertson said
the judge in january refused roberton's request to postpone the trial until june 20
i can't understand why a respected judge did it,'' rigler said. ``we think it is unfair.''
under rules of civil procedure, a plaintiff cannot drop a case without the defendant's consent once the lawsuit has been answered or without a court order dismissing the case
mccloskey, commenting wednesday on cbs-tv, said, ``the courtroom's a great place to learn the truth. now that he's up with the truth to be told and testimony under oath, he's backing off.''
i think the truth ought to be told. i don't know any better place to get the truth than in the courtroom. he invoked the process, he ought to go through with it,'' mccloskey said
the lawsuit was filed in 1986 following publication of mccloskey's allegations that robertson used the influence of his late father, sen. a. willis robertson, d-va., to avoid combat duty in the korean war
mccloskey, a decorated marine combat veteran who was aboard a troop ship from which robertson was removed in 1951 during a stopover in japan, also charged that robertson later served as the ``booze officer'' to a rear echelon unit after he did go to korea
a number of former marines have come forward since the lawsuit was filed to support mccloskey, though other witnesses deny that robertson invoked his father's political influence to be get his temporary reassignment to a special training unit in japan
mccloskey said wednesday that one reason he made the charges was that he feared a person who had avoided combat might try to make amends by becoming more warlike in later years
when you get a president in office who has evaded combat in his youth and all his advisers are saying `look tough against the soviets' ... i think there is a tendency to try to prove your manhood late in life,'' he said
a man like robertson wants to take on the commies anywhere they are, anywhere in the world,'' mccloskey said. it's ``a little dangerous to have a man like that in the white house.''
rigler invited mccloskey to submit the dispute over robertson's war record to an independent arbitrator, saying, ``if he refuses to agree to arbitration, it is mr. mccloskey who is afraid to have a determination of the facts.''
lehner said tuesday that robertson's attorneys rejected the idea of arbitration last fall when he informally suggested it. poison books</head> found on a library shelf.</note>
fingerprints found in a book about poisons match those of a woman accused of killing her husband by putting cyanide in a non-prescription drug, according to court papers released wednesday
a memorandum filed by u.s. attorney gene s. anderson also said stella nickell had failed a lie-detector test ``on whether she was the excedrin killer'' and that she apparently forged her husband's signature on life insurance applications
mrs. nickell is charged in the deaths of bruce nickell, 52, and susan katherine snow, 40, both of auburn. both died in june 1986 after swallowing tainted capsules of extra-strength excedrin. authorities have not suggested any other links between the victims
mrs. nickell was indicted in december on two counts of causing a death by product tampering and three counts of tampering with a product involved in interstate commerce. she has pleaded innocent
mrs. nickell checked out a book on poisoning from a library in mid-1984 without returning it, and pages on cyanide poisoning in a book titled ``deadly harvest'' that was found on a library shelf bore 84 fingerprints and three palm prints belonging to mrs. nickell, court documents said
the prosecutor's memo said the defendant and her husband, bruce nickell, had experienced ``intensified marital discord'' just before his death _ an assertion strongly disputed by ms. nickell's court-appointed defense attorney
in accompanying documents, federal public defender thomas hillier ii also disputed the government's claim that the polygraph test was conclusive
the maximum penalty on each death count is life, and the other charges carry maximum terms of 10 years. trial has been set for april 18
the prosecutor's memo, filed in support of the government's motion that mrs. nickell remain in custody pending trial, and accompanying documents had been sealed by u.s. district judge william s. dwyer because of concern that release of the information might make it harder to obtain an unbiased jury
the seattle times, seattle post-intelligencer and morning news tribune of tacoma appealed the order, which was overturned monday by the 9th u.s. circuit court of appeals
tainted capsules of pain relievers were found in both victims' homes and in bottles on the shelves of two stores in the suburbs between seattle and tacoma
mrs. nickell had sued excedrin's manufacturer, bristol-myers, and two stores where tainted capsules were found after an insurance carrier refused to pay benefits on her husband's death
shortly before he died, nickell obtained a life insurance policy that would pay his wife $31,000 if he died of natural causes and $136,000 for an accidental death
in september and october 1985, ms. nickell applied for two other life insurance policies for a total of $40,000, with she and her husband each the beneficiary of the other
handwriting examination has definitely concluded that bruce nickell did not sign what purports to be his signature,'' anderson's memo says. ``bruce nickell's fingerprints were not found on either insurance application
stella nickell's fingerprints were found in one of the two applications, and handwriting analysis conclusively established that she signed her husband's name to one application and probably signed his name to the second application.''
a state prosecutor and a former u.n. human rights delegate from nicaragua announced their defection wednesday and accused the sandinista government of torture, keeping political prisoners and rigging the judiciary
ivan villavicencio said he had been an appeals prosecutor in the district of managua, the capital, since march 1983
norman jose miranda, a foreign ministry official for eight years, was an alternative representative at the u.n. human rights commission in geneva during 1985-87 and said he left nicaragua to avoid holding the same post this year
the two men called a news conference to announce their ``resignation,'' timed to coincide with the u.n. commission's annual session
both said they remained sandinista supporters, but were disillusioned with the leftist government's ``deception'' of the nicaraguan people
they said they moved to the united states, where they have family and friends, in the last three months and would resign officially shortly
villavicencio said nicaraguan jails hold 8,600 political prisoners and said torture is used against peasants opposing government policies
he said a ``reprehensible permanent alliance'' exists between police and judicial authorities and judges are pressured to convict on the basis of fabricated charges. the government is pushing a pilot project to hand over the administration of justice to political commissars, he said
miranda said nicaragua is undergoing a ``stalinist social drama.''
he said the nicaraguan delegation at the human rights commission in fact took instructions from delegates of allies, such as cuba
the sandinistas came to power in nicaragua in a 1979 revolution that toppled dictator anastasio somoza. u.s.-backed rebels have been fighting the government since 1981
the decision by gop presidential hopeful pat robertson to seek dismissal of his libel suit against a congressman who questioned his war record calls into play an arcane provision of civil procedure in federal courts
rule 41 governs the dismissal of lawsuits by plaintiffs once the defendant has answered the complaint
a plaintiff can obtain dismissal of the suit voluntarily if he gets a signed stipulation from the defendant
without such a stipulation, as in robertson's lawsuit against former rep. paul n. mccloskey jr., r-calif., the plaintiff can ask for a court-ordered dismissal
robertson's lawyers said wednesday they will ask u.s. district judge joyce hens green to order dismissal of the case under this provision which provides that the case can be dismissed ``upon order of the court and upon such terms and conditions as the court deems proper.''
robertson's lawyer, douglas rigler, said his client expects to be ordered to pay mccloskey's court costs to cover the expenses of taking depositions from witnesses
but rigler said he doesn't believe his client should pay such costs or attorney's fees and he would likely appeal such an order if it were made by u.s. district judge joyce hens green
mccloskey's lawyer, george lehner, says the judge has the discretion to order robertson to pay both his client's court costs and attorney's fees. lehner says if the judge refuses his request to go to trial on tuesday, he will ask her to order robertson to pay both court costs and attorney's fees, which he says total more than $400,000
rigler conceded that an award of attorney's fees is always a possibilty but he said robertson's lawsuit doesn't ``fall within that category of cases'' in which such an award is appropriate
such cases includes lawsuits that are brought in bad faith or to harass the defendant
the judge has already refused to dismiss the case in mccloskey's motion to dismiss the case, ruling that robertson is entitled to go to trial on his charges that he was libeled by the former congressman
robertson charges that mccloskey defamed him by charging he used the political influence of his late father, sen. a. willis robertson, d-va., to avoid combat during the korean war. missile fired wednesday, bringing day's total to eight; picks up 4th graf pvs, ``fear not ... ^by martin marris</note>
iraq and iran battered each other's capitals with long-range missiles for a third day wednesday and the first iraqi rockets of the 7{-year-old war crashed into qom, seat of the iranian religious hierarchy
iran reported no casualties in qom, a holy city of 250,000 where ayatollah ruhollah khomeini once made his home. the 87-year-old revolutionary patriarch has lived for several years in jamaran, a northern tehran suburb
the iraqis said they fired eight surface-to-surface missiles wednesday, two of them into qom, bringing the total for three days to 24. iran said it hit baghdad with three missiles, for a total of eight in the same period
fear not,'' khomeini told iranians in remarks quoted by the official islamic republic news agency. ``it does not make any difference for a people who seek martyrdom whether they are killed by missiles, tanks or artillery.''
both sides reported civilian casualties in their capital cities, and iran said iraqi warplanes also raided a village near rasht 150 miles northeast of tehran. irna said ``several civilians'' were killed wednesday in tehran and bombs destroyed the mosque in the village
baghdad's official iraqi news agency said the iranian rockets killed or wounded civilians and demolished houses and shops in residential neighborhoods of the arab capital, but was not more specifics
iran said wednesday's hits on tehran wounded 15 people, bringing the total to 115. before the general report about casualties in tehran, it had reported 27 killed in the capital and five in the village near rasht
it said casualties included two newlyweds killed in the village and an 80-year-old woman wounded in tehran
western military analysts believe iraq uses soviet-made scud-b missiles fitted with strap-on boosters enabling them to reach tehran, which is 290 miles from the border. qom is roughly the same distance from the frontier
iran's weapons also are scud-bs, provided by its arab allies syria and libya, but without boosters because baghdad is only 80 miles from the border
this week's attacks by iraq are its first on tehran and qom with surface-to-surface missiles. president saddam hussein's government declared in august it had acquired missiles that could reach the iranian capital, a city of 6 million people
the iraqi air force, which has an estimated 8-1 advantage over iran's, has made many raids on iranian cities and bombed qom repeatedly in january 1987
thousands of civilian lives have been lost in the ``war of the cities,'' the periodic rounds of bombing and missile attacks in a conflict that has claimed at least 1 million casualties since it began in september l980
iran said its artillery batteries, in response to the rocketing of tehran, shelled military and economic installations in the iraqi cities of basra, ammara, badra, zorbatiya, ali sharqi and ali gharbi
dispatches from iraq said its warplanes bombed the western iranian town of dezful and karaj, a city near tehran, setting their targets ablaze. iran did not report the raids
iraq said it began the missile barrage of tehran in retaliation for two iranian rockets that hit baghdad before dawn monday. iran described the missiles as a response to iraqi air raids on the tehran oil refinery last week
a group of citizens asked for a ruling wednesday on whether president kurt waldheim's war record warrants murder charges, and waldheim ordered the seizure of a magazine that published the complaint
the left-wing weekly falter printed a text of the complaint by the 300 austrians along with three articles critical of the president, who has been accused of committing war crimes while serving as a german army lieutenant in the balkans during world war ii
under article 63 of austria's constitution, the president cannot be prosecuted unless both houses of parliament approve
waldheim's office said he instructed the state prosecutor's office to impound copies of the magazine on grounds the issue damaged his honor
police said late wednesday they had not yet received a judge's order to act
waldheim says he is innocent of war crimes
walter oswalt, a journalist and spokesman for the group making the complaint, said it was delivered to the prosecutor's office wednesday morning. a spokesman for the office said privacy laws prevented him from confirming such a document was received
gerhard litzka, spokesman for the justice ministry, said prosecutors must investigate any such complaint and tell the ministry whether there are grounds for legal action
as grounds for an investigation of possible charges, the complaint cited a law that says both those who commit crimes and those who assist in them can be held responsible for criminal acts
it quoted extensively from the report last month by an international panel of historians saying waldheim was in ``close proximity'' to nazi atrocities, knew of them and did nothing to stop them. the historians said they found no proof that the former u.n. secretary-general committed war crimes, but left the question of guilt open
waldheim has said the historians exonerated him from the accusations of war crimes which arose during the presidential election campaign two years ago
the complaint also quoted from an interview printed feb. 25 by the munich daily sueddeutsche zeitung with manfred messerschmidt, a west german historian who served on the panel
messerschmidt, who has legal training, said steps could be considered in connection with waldheim's role in the fate of six british commandos executed by the nazis in greece in 1944. prime minister margaret thatcher ordered british authorities last month to reopen an investigation of the case
israeli historian yehuda l. wallach said feb. 9 he thought the panel's report could serve as the basis of an investigation of whether to prosecute waldheim
a national lawyers group wednesday joined a challenge to federal sentencing guidelines that require judges to impose prison terms of particular lengths for certain crimes
the guidelines, established by a congressional commission, violate the constitution's separation of powers doctrine, says a friend-of-the-court brief filed by the national association of criminal defense lawyers
the association joined a challenge filed by assistant federal public defender stewart abrams, who represents a woman with no criminal record who under the guidelines must receive at least 6{ years in prison for smuggling cocaine
a judge may go outside the guidelines, which create a 43-level system of punishment based on the crime and defendant's record, only in extreme cases
u.s. district judge james king, chief of the southern district of florida, said all 15 federal judges in his district will rule together on the matter to avoid discrepancies from courtroom to courtroom. no hearing date has been set
it will be the first time the judges have sat together since they considered the immigration of 125,000 cubans to florida during the 1980 mariel boatlift
the sentencing guidelines have been challenged on constitutional grounds three times in the southern district of california since feb. 18 with different results, said nacdl representative benson b. weintraub
in the test case, beverly bogle, 21, was arrested after her arrival at miami international airport from jamaica on nov. 11 with 1.9 kilograms of cocaine she was carrying for someone else, abrams said
she was not profiting from it,'' he said. ``she was doing it for a person she perceived to be a friend.''
ms. bogle pleaded guilty to importing cocaine and has been jailed while awaiting sentencing march 25
under the anti-drug abuse act of 1986, congress set a minimum sentence of five years in prison for the offense
however, the u.s. sentencing commission, created in 1984, set a guideline ranging from six years and seven months to eight years and one month in prison for the crime, abrams said. the guidelines apply to crimes committed after nov. 1
in ms. bogle's case, the federal probation office wants to use the commission's guidelines, abrams said
