the ap</head> with new campeau offer; adds 3 grafs to update with federated chairman announcing plans to retire, $3 million `golden parachute' and to add four largest retailers.</note>
version moving on business wire
federated department stores inc. on wednesday chose r.h. macy &amp; co. over a rival suitor, agreeing to a marriage that would put famous retailers such as macy, bloomingdale's and bullock's under one enormous corporate roof
a rejected campeau corp. said it would proceed with its bid for federated, the nation's fifth largest retailer
federated said in a joint statement with macy, the nation's 10th largest general retail concern, that the two companies had signed a definitive agreement to create a new company, macy's-federated inc
macy operates 96 stores in 14 states, while federated has 650 stores _ including bloomingdale's, bullocks and filene's _ in 36 states
federated's choice of macy over campeau came as no surprise
analysts noted that the macy bid offered federated the opportunity for future growth, while campeau would bring with it a history of having bought and broken up allied stores corp
no matter who ends up controlling federated, the new owner is expected to sell its gold circle discount stores and ralphs supermarkets
several of federated's department store chains, which include burdine's, i. magnin., rich's, abraham &amp; straus and lazarus, also are expected to be sold after a purchase by either macy or campeau
abraham and straus and rich's were considered likely candidates for a sale by macy, because they are direct competitors with macy stores in new york and atlanta, respectively
the agreement provides for macy to begin a cash tender offer of $74.50 a share for about 80 percent of federated's 89.6 million outstanding shares, or a total of $5.25 billion, the companies said
the remaining federated shares would be exchanged for stock in the new company
federated's current management would have a strong voice in the new company, filling 40 percent of the seats on its board of directors
campeau, a toronto-based real estate developer and retailer, through its allied stores division, owns the jordan marsh, stern's, ann taylor and maas brothers chains
the retailer said in a statement that macy's bid was ``not competitive and we intend to prevail in the marketplace.''
late wednesday, campeau said it was amending its previously announced $66 cash tender offer. it said it would pay $75 per share in cash for 80 percent of federated's shares, and after a merger would pay $44 per share for the remaining 20 percent
campeau said its latest proposal, which was to expire march 15, had a combined value of $68 per share and a total value of $6.1 billion
the amended campeau bid was announced after the close of trading on the new york stock exchange, where federated stock fell $1 a share to $66.75
earlier, campeau repeated a charge that the macy offer was highly speculative because of the unknown value of the stock. macy is currently privately held, and it is difficult to know how much its shares are worth
wall street analysts said they found it hard to predict what shareholders would do, given the problem of putting a value on the stock portion of the offer
if you don't know that, it's really tough to figure out which is a better deal,'' said joseph ronning, a retail industry analyst with brown brothers harriman &amp; co
macy's bid, which came to light monday, was originally for $73.80 a share in cash plus stock, but the offer was increased before the agreement was reached
macy was taken private by a management group in a $3.6 billion leveraged buyout in 1986. its stores rang up $5.21 billion in sales during the fiscal year ended last aug. 1
federated chairman howard goldfeder said at a news conference wednesday he would resign after helping macy chairman edward finkelstein implement the merger
goldfeder said he expects to be paid $3.06 million when he leaves the company under a ``golden parachute'' approved by federated's directors. similar departure payments are due other top federated officers
the nation's four largest retailers are sears, roebuck and co., with $30.21 billion in sales during fiscal 1987; k mart corp., $25.63 billion; wal-mart stores inc., $15.96 billion, and j.c. penney co. _ $13.98 billion
