federal regulators' failure to require volkswagen of america to make public reports of sudden acceleration in audi 5000 cars appears to be a case of intentional deception, a new york congressman said wednesday
rep. george hochbrueckner, d-n.y., in letter to the national highway traffic safety administration and volkswagen, demanded the documents be turned over to congress, bypassing the agency responsible for the audi investigation
as a result of nhtsa's apparent cooperation with (volkswagen), the public has been denied the opportunity to study significant evidence which might highlight the ineffectiveness of a shift-lock device in the audi 5000 to curtail sudden acceleration incidents,'' hochbrueckner wrote. ``i find this deceptive behavior a shocking departure from the established practices in these matters.''
nhtsa in january 1987 ordered a recall of 255,336 1978-86 audi 5000s for installation of a device to fix reported throttle problems on the cars
the agency has received 1,750 complaints of alleged sudden acceleration in audi 5000s, resulting in 1,269 accidents, 430 injuries and five deaths
hochbrueckner said nhtsa requested the incident reports in june 1987. however, the documents were never turned over to nhtsa, which instead received summaries from vw, hochbrueckner said, calling the arrangement unprecedented
volkswagen issued a statement in response saying that ``nhtsa has not given us any special concessions, neither have we been relieved of any of the burden of responding to the agencies' requests for information.''
a nhtsa memorandum filed in the audi case said that at vw's request, ``the source documents were reviewed by (nhtsa) personnel and the summaries were found to be accurate summations of the very bulky source documents.''
an nhtsa official said wednesday there had been other instances in which the agency had requested summaries of complaints rather than the complaints themselves. the official, speaking only on condition he not be named, was unable to say how common the practice was
volkswagen's spokesman at its u.s. headquarters in troy, mich., joseph bennett, did not return calls for comment
hochbrueckner asked volkswagen to give congress all the owner reports, consumer complaints, surveys, investigations, field reports or other sources ``received or authorized by volkswagen, or of which volkswagen is otherwise aware'' during and after the recall
congress has no power to compel the documents be turned over, said andy kennedy, an aide to hochbrueckner
volkswagen said it ``will comply with congressman hockbreuchner's request for the data by making available to him all the data which we furnished to nhtsa on the same schedule.''
leftist guerrillas killed 14 people in three raids this week, part of the rebels' biggest offensive yet in colombia, authorities and news accounts said wednesday
about 100 rebels attacked pelaya town, about 250 miles north of bogota, on tuesday night, alfredo araujo said in a broadcast interview with the colombian radio chain rcn
araujo, administrative assistant to the cesar state government office, said the attackers stormed a police station, killed two officers and injured five people
the daily el tiempo of bogota reported that leftist guerrillas murdered eight peasants tuesday in the santa marta mountains in northern colombia
el tiempo quoted peasants there as saying the pro-soviet colombian revolutionary armed forces killed the eight for refusing to cooperate with the rebels
the santa marta mountains are on colombia's caribbean coast
araujo said that last sunday the national liberation army, or eln, attacked san jeronimo, another town in cesar state, and killed four ranchers for refusing to pay what the guerrillas call a revolution tax
the guerrillas also gathered townspeople in the town square and exhorted them not to vote in the march 13 nationwide mayoral elections
in the first two months of 1988 rebels kidnapped 14 mayors, attacked a dozen towns, killed 31 soldiers, 28 police and 80 other people, blew up oil pipelines and electricity cable towers and attacked oil company drilling camps
two of the mayors _ luis alberto gonzalez of pitalito and anibal pena of san agustin _ were freed in army attacks friday on guerrilla encampments near the southern town of san agustin, the defense ministry said
san agustin is popular with foreign tourists because of the many pre-columbian statues in an archaeological park there
the mayors were kidnapped feb. 25 by the national liberation army, which freed 12 mayors previously after telling them to do more for poor people in their districts
political violence has been worst in southern caqueta state, where 40 local leaders of the governing liberal party were killed in the last three months
party leaders said the rebels were trying to terrorize it into withdrawing from mayoral elections so the leftist patriotic union party will win
antonio serrano duarte, a congressman from the state, was shot and wounded tuesday night in florencia, the state capital, national police said in a communique. it said serrano was out of danger in a hospital
there are five leftist guerrilla groups in colombia
three members of the patriotic union party were murdered in caqueta state in the last month. right-wing death squads were blamed for killing nearly 500 of the party's workers in the last two years
it's not always the big names in the music business who capture the coveted grammy award as wednesday night's announcement of first-time winners showed: actor jack nicholson, veteran rocker frank zappa, ex-righteous brother bill medley and the south african vocal group, ladysmith black mambazo
first of all i thank god and then paul simon,'' said joseph shabalala, ladysmith's lead singer. the group performed on simon's breakthrough ``graceland'' lp, and simon produced the group's ``shaka zulu'' album which won for best traditional folk recording
nicholson won his grammy for best recording for children for his narration of ``the elephant's child.'' the actor was not at radio city music hall to accept the award bestowed by the national academy of recording arts &amp; sciences
joining him in the winner's circle for the first time was medley, who thanked god for his ``nine lives'' in the music business
i've waited 26 years for this,'' said the bass singer after winning best pop vocal performance by a duo or group for ``(i've had) the time of my life,'' a song he did with jennifer warnes
zappa defeated his son, dweezil, earning his first grammy _ for best rock instrumental performance _ after a career spanning more than two decades. bruce springsteen was also a runner-up to zappa in the category
the awards, announced off-camera prior to the televised show, also included a posthumous first-time grammy for reggae star peter tosh, who was murdered in his jamaica home last year
it is so unfair that peter tosh is not here. he deserved this very much,'' said his cousin pauline burgess, who accepted the award
professor longhair, the new orleans piano player, also won his first grammy with ``houseparty new orleans style,'' which won as best traditional blues recording
the union representing 6,700 northwest airlines flight attendants instructed members wednesday to begin a slowdown by doing everything by the book
the attendants have remained on the job since a deadline for a new contract passed friday
keep them busy, keep them guessing, keep them confused,'' jeff musto, a spokesman for teamsters local 2747, said in a recorded message on the union hotline
remember you have to have all luggage stowed before you can give permission to close the front boarding door. i think you get the idea,'' he said
northwest spokesman redmond tyler said the airline operated normally wednesday. ``we have seen no evidence of any disruption or attempt at disruption,'' he said
no talks are scheduled. the main stumbling block to a contract is a company proposal to delay the promotion of lower-paid workers to the higher bracket
linda mcmahon, operations manager for the five aaa travel agency offices in minneapolis, said she had not noticed any effect on business or service from slowdown tactics
i haven't heard any specific complaints at this point. i was certainly apprehensive when i heard about the `guerrilla warfare' this morning. everything seems to be going pretty much as usual,'' ms. mcmahon said
the threat of a strike has not deterred many travelers from flying northwest, she said
a lot of times there isn't comparable service on another carrier. they will take their chances that northwest will be operating because they want to fly non-stop,'' ms. mcmahon said
many business travelers are making alternate arrangements in case of a strike, but vacationers who bought discount tickets in advance have little recourse, she said
the unions representing the pilots and machinists, who are trying to negotiate separate contracts, have not said whether they would honor flight attendants' picket lines. picks up 13th graf pvs bgng, `the restoration'</note>
the house overwhelmingly passed a landmark civil rights bill wednesday that would broaden protections for women, minorities, the elderly and the handicapped, but president reagan has vowed to veto the measure
the civil rights restoration act, considered by many lawmakers the most significant civil rights measure in 20 years, was sent to the white house on a 315-98 vote. the senate passed it by an equally lopsided 75-14 vote in january
both chambers passed the bill by the two-thirds margin needed to override a presidential veto, but it was unclear whether the huge margins would hold up following reagan's vow wednesday to reject the measure
the restoration act was designed to reverse a 1984 supreme court decision that narrowed the scope of four major civil rights laws meant to prevent taxpayer financing of discrimination
supporters of the act said hundreds of discrimination complaints had been dropped or restricted since the decision
we have suffered far too long in waiting for this great and important day,'' said rep. john conyers, d-mich
in letters delivered wednesday to several house republicans, reagan said flatly he will veto the measure ``if it is presented to me in its current form.''
in the letters, sent from brussels, belgium, where reagan is attending a nato summit, the president said the bill ``dramatically expands the scope of federal jurisdiction over state and local governments and the private sector'' and ``poses a particular threat to religious liberty.''
in the case brought by grove city (pa.) college, the supreme court held in a 6-3 opinion that title ix _ a law barring sex discrimination in federally funded education programs _ applies only to specific programs or activities receiving federal assistance and not the institutions of which they are part
the restoration act clarifies that entire institutions and government agencies are covered if any program or activity within them receives federal aid. the broad coverage also applies to the private sector if the aid goes to a corporation as a whole or if the recipient principally provides education, health care, housing, social services or parks and recreation
the bill also says farmers getting crop subsidies, people on food stamps and other individuals receiving federal assistance are not required to comply with the anti-discrimination statutes
sponsors of the restoration act said congress always intended broad civil rights protections on the theory that ``those who dip their hands in the public till should not object if a little democracy sticks to their fingers,'' as rep. augustus hawkins, d-calif., put it
but opponents claim the bill goes far beyond restoration. like reagan, they complained that it is too intrusive into the private sector and religious organizations
the wording of the law is going to bring about unintended consequences like you could never imagine,'' said rep. george gekas, r-pa
house leaders provoked controversy by bringing the senate's version of the civil rights bill directly to the floor wednesday, bypassing house committees and limiting amendments to one gop substitute for the entire bill
we need a voting rights act for congressmen,'' sputtered rep. henry hyde, r-ill
but other members said there had been more than 40 committee hearings on the grove city bill since 1984. hawkins, chairman of the house education and labor committee and a senior member of the congressional black caucus, said 2,500 amendments had been offered over the years
all the compromises that can possibly be made have already been made. certainly all the ideas that could ever have been thought of have already been expressed,'' said hawkins. ``the time (to act) is now.''
the gop substitute, sponsored by rep. james sensenbrenner, r-wis., would have limited the bill's impact on corporations and allowed more educational institutions to escape compliance with the sex discrimination ban on religious grounds
sensenbrenner said he offered it in ``a spirit of reconciliation'' to end the four-year congressional ordeal over the bill. but it was defeated 266-146
an anti-abortion amendment adopted by the senate says nothing in the bill or in existing law requires institutions to perform or pay for abortions. the amendment invalidates 1975 regulations that bar discrimination against women who have had abortions or sought them and require college health plans to treat abortions like other temporary disabilities
feminists considered the amendment a setback but did not actively oppose the civil rights bill in the house. the national right-to-life committee called the amendment a great victory, saying wednesday that ``congress has emphatically rejected the legal doctrine that anti-abortion policies are a form of sex discrimination.''
the restoration act applies to the four civil rights laws affected by the supreme court ruling: title ix of the 1972 education amendments, barring sex discrimination in federally funded education programs; the 1964 civil rights act, barring racial discrimination in federally-assisted programs; the 1973 rehabilitation act, barring discrimination against the handicapped in any program or activity receiving federal aid; and the 1975 age discrimination act, barring employment discrimination against older people
the house passed the restoration act in similar form on a vote of 375-32 in 1984, shortly after the court decision. the bill was bottled up in a senate committee until last year. update with ministers reaching compromise on statement on short-range missiles. picks up 5th graf pvs bgng: according to ...</note>
nato leaders on wednesday demanded huge cutbacks in warsaw pact tanks and artillery that ``cast a shadow'' over europe, and endorsed president reagan's efforts to negotiate strategic arms reductions with the soviet union
defining strategy for a new set of east-west negotiations, nato leaders said soviet conventional forces pose the threat of a surprise attack and must be slashed to rectify an imbalance in military strength
the soviet cutbacks would entail, for example, ``the elimination from europe of tens of thousands of warsaw pact weapons relevant to surprise attack, among them tanks and artillery pieces,'' a nato communique said
meeting behind closed doors at alliance's heavily guarded headquarters, the leaders of the 16 alliance countries attempted to accentuate agreement. they did not want to highlight differences about the pace of modernizing short-range nuclear missiles left in europe after the elimination of longer-range weapons covered by a new u.s.-soviet arms treaty
british sources speaking on condition of anonymity said nato foreign ministers late wednesday agreed on compromise language for a final declaration thursday on the modernization issue
the summit participants will call for the short-range nuclear missiles to ``continue to be kept up-to-date where necessary,'' the sources said, a statement that avoids the word ``modernization,'' to which west germany objects
according to his spokesman, reagan quoted benjamin franklin, telling the nato leaders, ``if we do not all hang together, we will assuredly hang separately.''
security was so strict that a nato guard attempted to eject a reporter who asked reagan a question as the leaders posed for a ``family photo.''
emphasizing alliance unity, reagan said, ``there are no great fundamental differences there. i have never seen such harmony and togetherness as we have.''
reagan mixed nato summitry with middle east peace efforts. he ordered secretary of state george p. shultz to make a whirlwind return to the middle east after the summit windup thursday night to continue his efforts to set up arab-israeli peace talks
first, shultz will stop in london to see jordan's king hussein, and on friday will visit israel, egypt and syria, returning to washington early saturday morning
the nato meeting is the alliance's first summit since 1982
accompanied by their foreign ministers, the leaders gathered at a long, walnut-brown oval table in a conference room shortly after noon to hear an opening statement by lord carrington, nato's secretary general
for a minute or so, carrington's remarks were obscured by a loud hum on the translation earphones, causing foreign officials and their aides to pull the earplugs out briefly and switch channels for a clearer sound
carrington said reagan's effort to secure a 50 percent cut in u.s. and soviet long-range missiles ``has the alliance's full support.''
he spoke of soviet leader mikhail gorbachev as a man ``who is ready to reduce some tensions'' but expressed concern about the kremlin's military might and ``the denial of basic human rights and freedom to the peoples of eastern europe and the soviet union.''
the leaders held nearly three hours of formal talks, in addition to a luncheon and dinner, and issued a communique demanding that the soviet union reduce its advantage in conventional, or non-nuclear forces
the document highlights an issue of broad agreement within the western alliance _ directing the focus away from west germany's reluctance to move ahead with an alliance decision to modernize short-range nuclear weapons
west germany, which is most threatened by short-range weapons, is pressing for talks with the soviets to reduce the kremlin's large edge in those weapons
most of the other nato leaders _ including the united states and britain _ oppose such talks now, fearing they could lead to demands for eliminating all of the weapons, leaving europe exposed to the soviets' superior conventional forces
white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said most of the leaders, in their private remarks, touched on the issue of modernizing the short-range weapons. ``everybody has some feelings about that issue, some more supportive than others.''
a white house official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said west german chancellor helmut kohl spoke most directly on the issue, but that even his remarks were muted
on the question of conventional forces, there is no dispute in nato that the warsaw pact has an advantage: about 3-to-1 in tanks and artillery and nearly 2-to-1 in combat aircraft and troops, including reserves in the soviet union. moscow contends that east-west conventional forces are roughly equivalent
lt. gen. colin powell, reagan's national security adviser, said the conventional arms negotiations ``will perhaps be more difficult than any of the nuclear arms talks that have been held so far because we're talking about large asymmetries, we're talking about a large imbalance between our forces and those of the warsaw pact.''
reagan repeatedly denied there were any differences in the talks, but powell, in an interview with nbc-tv, suggested otherwise
he said that with 16 leaders, ``certainly there will be differences and there will be heated debate and discussion from time to time
however, powell said ``there was a sense of unity that was overwhelming
and any minor dispute that might exist, or some of the debates that are going on as to how one should characterize the modernization issue (with short-range nuclear forces), pales in comparison to the overall sense of unity that was conveyed at the meeting today,'' he said
in a six-page statement on conventional forces, the nato leaders said:
the soviet union's military presence in europe, at a level far in excess of its needs for self-defense, directly challenges our security as well as our hopes for change in the political situation in europe
thus, the conventional imbalance in europe remains at the core of europe's security concerns.''
the document sets the stage for negotiations to begin in earnest this fall in vienna, austria, with representatives of the warsaw pact consisting of the soviet union and six east european allies
our aim will be to establish a situation in europe in which force postures as well as the numbers of deployments and weapons systems no longer make surprise attack and large-scale offensive action a feasible option,'' the nato statement said
the new set of negotiations would replace 15 years of talks that have failed to produce agreement. nato wants the new talks to encompass the full european area, from the atlantic to the ural mountains, whereas the old talks were limited to the central front. ...'' to update with d'amato, kerry meeting with opposition leaders.</note>
the united states is taking legal action to prevent panama's military-dominated regime from withdrawing panamanian government funds from u.s. banks, a lawyer representing opposition forces said wednesday
meanwhile, assistant secretary of state elliott abrams raised the possibility that the united states will withhold the next payment due to panama for tolls, fees and services for panama canal operations
the two developments indicated reagan administration interest in accelerating a campaign of economic denial against the panamanian regime, dominated by the chief of the panamanian defense forces, gen. manuel antonio noriega
william d. rogers, a lawyer for ousted panamanian president eric arturo delvalle, told a news conference about the alleged u.s. effort to freeze panamanian government funds deposited in american banks
although no firm figures were available, $50 million was said to be involved
the state department had no comment on the reported action, but other officials, speaking only on condition of anonymity, confirmed that the measures outlined by rogers were being taken
asked about the u.s. position on that issue, abrams told the cable news network, ``we know who the legitimate government of panama is. if the government of president delvalle says to american banks, don't pay money to noriega, then all those banks are going to come to the state department and say, `who's got the authority here? noriega or delvalle?'
we're going to answer that question. delvalle is president of panama. and noriega has been fired and he does not have legitimate authority here.''
rogers, of the arnold &amp; porter law firm, said the administration action was being carried out to ensure that the banks may make disbursements only to the panamanian ambassador who served under delvalle, juan b. sosa. delvalle was ousted last week after he tried to fire noriega and has been in hiding in panama
rogers said the state department was issuing ``formal certifications'' that it regards sosa as ``the accredited representative of the recognized government of the country.''
state department deputy spokeswoman phyllis oakley said only that such certifications were being prepared. she declined to specify their purpose
at issue is the status of panamanian government deposits at five american banks. the attempt by sosa and his allies to prevent the transfer of these funds to the new panamanian government is part of an ambitious plan of economic warfare aimed at toppling noriega
delvalle was forced out last week after noriega, under federal indictment on drug smuggling charges, ignored delvalle's attempt to replace him
rogers said the banks believed to have panamanian government deposits are marine midland na, irving trust co., bankers trust co., the republic national bank and the bank of boston
every dime we can find is in those banks,'' rogers said. he added that any bank which ignores the order could be liable for whatever payments it makes to the current panamanian government
marine midland and irving trust refused comment on the purported state department action. another new york banking source, insisting on anonymity, questioned the legitimacy of the effort to block transfers of funds
sosa said the state department is seriously considering withholding from panama the next payment, due march 15, of the fees the united states gives panama for use of the panama canal. he estimated that figure at $8 million, but other sources said it was closer to $7 million
mrs. oakley confirmed that a request from the delvalle government to put the funds in escrow had been received and that the state department was consulting with other agencies on how to proceed
abrams indicated that no such request had been received but that the united states would respond positively if asked
if they ask us to pay the canal payments into a different account or delay it, i think we'd do that. we'd respond to president delvalle
if he tells us he doesn't want that money going to noriega, then we're not going to give it to noriega.''
several members of the house merchant marine committee, which has jurisdiction over the panama canal, called on president reagan to withhold the payment and threatened to legislate that step if he refuses to go along
rep. billy tauzin, d-la., said, ``they (the panamanian authorities) are in dire need of funds. if this payment is denied to them, the noriega regime will have great difficulty maintaining itself.''
the legislators said nearly $80 million a year is paid to panama by the united states under terms of the panama canal treaties
in new york, lawyers for delvalle sued in federal court to block the republic national bank from turning over millions of dollars to the new panamanian government
the lawsuit was dropped after the bank agreed to transfer the money, estimated at $10 million, to the federal reserve bank for safekeeping
in related matters wednesday:
_sen. alfonse d'amato, r-n.y. said the cia is conducting an internal investigation into allegations that it was the source of personal and political information on u.s. senators forwarded to noriega
the allegations of the cia-noriega link were first made at a congressional hearing last month by jose i. blandon, a former top panamanian intelligence official. u.s. law prohibits the cia from engaging in domestic spying on american citizens
two officials who identified themselves as being with the spy agency's office of the inspector general interviewed blandon last week, d'amato said
_ after meeting at the capitol with panamanian opposition political leaders, d'amato and sen. john kerry, d-mass., said they will offer on the senate floor on thursday ``a progressive plan of increased economic pressure'' against the noriega regime
ricardo arias calderon, president of panama's christian democratic party, said the campaign to restore democracy will prevail by combining ``peaceful people power'' in panama, international public opinion and ``the growing economic pressure that is being exercised on the illegitimate regime of gen. noriega.''
_financial experts in miami said billions of dollars in bank deposits have been taken out of panama for safer havens in the wake of noriega's drug indictment in miami last month
this certainly has destabilized panama as a banking center,'' said gonzalo valdes-fauli, senior vice president and manager of the miami office of london-based barclay's bank
one unidentified top banking expert told the miami herald that from june to october, panamanian banks lost $7 billion of the $36 billion they held. panama in the 1980s had come to be known as the switzerland of latin america, offering banking secrecy and stability to the region's investors and depositors
unlike other countries, panama cannot cover its cash shortages by printing new money becuase the dollar is the national currency
a 7-year-old born with no external eyes underwent surgery wednesday in another of a series of operations to create eyelids and sockets and allow her to see
dilek erdogan of turkey was born with a nose and a mouth, ``and that's it for her face,'' said dr. allen putterman, who performed the surgery at the university of illinois hospital eye and ear infirmary. her eyes are below the skin
dilek's left eye, which will always be sightless, will be replaced with an artifical one, but doctors hope to enable her see out of her right eye, putterman said
in august, putterman slit the skin over her right eye and placed a temporary insert between the skin and the eye to create some space around the eyeball. he then sewed the slit closed
on wednesday, he reopened the slit and began forming an eyelid. putterman said he also began the insertion procedure on the left eye
dilek was bought to this country for treatment more than a year ago
thunderstorms pounded oklahoma, arkansas and northern texas on wednesday, while snow fell from the rockies and the plains to michigan
more than a half-inch of rain fell during a half-hour in fort worth and aledo, texas, and flash-flood watches were posted over west-central and southwest arkansas, southern oklahoma, and northwest texas
colorado got heavy snow tuesday night and wednesday morning, with 10 inches reported near rockport, 7 near new raymer and 6 near wellington. up to 4 inches of snow fell wednesday in parts of nevada, new mexico, wyoming, upper michigan, nebraska, kansas, the texas panhandle
rain fell across parts of kansas, missouri, oklahoma, eastern texas, arkansas, tennessee, kentucky, indiana, ohio and pennsylvania
snowfall during the 6 hours ending at 1 p.m. est included 3 inches at denver and 2 inches at cheyenne, wyo. heavier rainfall during the same period included 1.20 inches at fort sill, okla., .86 inch at gage, okla., .75 inch at altus, okla., .65 inch at waco, texas, .60 at wichita falls, texas, and .59 at dallas
temperatures at 2 p.m. est ranged from 10 degrees at baudette, minn., to 83 degrees at fort myers southwest regional airport in florida. the morning low was 9 degrees below zero at massena, n.y
thursday's forecast called for rain along the oregon coast, rain and occasional thunderstorms from southeast arizona across texas, most of the southeast, the ohio valley and from the middle-atlantic states to southern new york, snow over the lower great lakes and cloudy skies over the upper great lakes, new england and the northern rockies
high temperatures were expected to reach the 20s and 30s from new england across the great lakes, the upper mississippi valley, the eastern half of the dakotas and the texas panhandle, the 40s and 50s from new jersey across the virginias, the ohio valley, from central missouri across arkansas, over the remainder of the northern and central plains, oklahoma and northern texas, the rockies, the northern plateau, the great basin and the pacific northwest, the 80s across southern texas and much of florida and the 60s and 70s elsewhere. updating with shamir comments attacking jordan. picks up 25th graf pvs, the haaretz ...</note>
israeli troops fired tear gas inside an arab hospital wednesday, forcing doctors to don gas masks and sending dozens of choking patients fleeing with their faces covered by arab headdresses
soldiers clubbed a palestinian teen-ager suspected of throwing rocks at troops from a barricade erected about 10 yards from the hospital's emergency room
an associated press photographer saw soldiers throw the youth head first down a flight of stairs, then sit on his stomach while beating him with a wooden truncheon
troops detained 20 arabs suspected of participating in demonstrations in ramallah, israel radio said
president reagan, meanwhile, ordered secretary of state george p. shultz to return to the middle east on thursday for further talks with arab and israeli leaders
in jerusalem, police detained 27 israeli students from the bezalel art school after their parade for the jewish holiday of purim turned into a protest against the israeli handling of unrest in the territories
defense minister yitzhak rabin defended israel's policy of using blows to subdue arab protesters, saying that of several thousand soldiers serving in the occupied territories, only 2 percent to 3 percent had commited excesses, the itim news agency reported
as a matter of policy, the army does not release exact figures on troop deployment
in ramallah, eight miles north of jerusalem, soldiers fired at least six tear gas canisters at palestinian protesters who used rocks and twisted metal to block a street outside government-run ramallah hospital and hurled stones at a dozen soldiers
one smoking canister landed in the emergency room reception area and a second in a hospital courtyard
two doctors donned gas masks and others held onions to their noses to counter the effects of the gas. about 30 coughing patients, including old men with canes, used arab headdresses to cover their faces
even the doctors couldn't breathe, so imagine the effects on the patients inside, many of whom are seriously ill,'' said one doctor, who declined to identify himself
soldiers detained three youths outside the hospital, dragging away one of them with a gash on his forehead and a blood-drenched shoulder
the tear gas attack was the second on the hospital in two days. on tuesday, three soldiers burst into the hospital, fired tear gas and struck two doctors with their rifles as they searched for demonstrators, the hospital director said
an army spokesman denied soldiers entered the hospital or beat doctors in tuesday's incident
palestinian protesters have used hospitals, schools and sacred mosques as hideouts to elude arrest and as staging grounds for anti-israeli riots, according to israeli officials and eyewitnesses
also in ramallah wednesday, police briefly detained three italian legislators who chained themselves to electric poles outside a refugee camp and distributed anti-occupation leaflets, israel radio said
in the gaza strip, palestinian organizers permitted merchants to open their stores for three hours a day following a three-month commercial strike, an arab reporter said
but the army forced the stores to remain closed, saying storekeepers were being intimidated, and the army would only permit them to resume business when they did it of their own free will. in the past, soldiers repeatedly tried to force stores to open to break the strike
on the diplomatic front, right-wing legislators said jordan's king hussein had gone back on previous understandings with israel by insisting the palestine liberation organization be involved in peace talks
king hussein says the plo must be involved in the peace process and he wants a full-scale international conference,'' likud legislator dan meridor, a close aide to prime minister yitzhak shamir, told israel television. ``if that's progress, i don't know what going backward is.''
foreign minister shimon peres agreed the plo should not be included in talks
shamir himself on wednesday accused jordan of siding with ``the most extreme elements in the arab world'' and said the ultimate goal of all arab leaders was to destroy israel
he spoke to members of the conference of presidents of major american jewish organizations
the haaretz daily reported that, in order to prevent excesses by soldiers, the army decided troops should not serve in the occupied territories for more than 1{ months at a time
the newspaper said the army believed frustration and anger built up during more than two months of serving in the territories had caused four soldiers photographed by cbs news to beat two bound arabs with stones last week
shamir said he was considering further restrictions on media access in the occupied territories, saying journalists have harmed israel. he did not say what steps he might take. soldiers now are authorized to temporarily close parts of the occupied territories to reporters
shamir also called on american jewish leaders to quell any criticism of israel within their ranks, saying it was ``non-jewish to join an anti-israeli front of non-jewish people.''
republican presidential hopeful bob dole implied wednesday there was a connection between vice president george bush's tenure as head of the central intelligence agency and speculation that panamanian strong man manuel antonio noriega was on the cia payroll. that drew a sharp response from bush
dole appeared with a dancing pineapple before a crowd of about 300 at a windy, rain-threatened rally in downtown new orleans
at least twice dole implied that bush, who was head of the cia from 1976-77, might have had some dealings with noriega
there's some evidence (noriega) was on the cia payroll as far back as 1966. that's all i know,'' dole said. he would not discuss what the evidence was or what he knew
bush, campaigning in baton rouge, la., criticized dole for bringing up the subject
i find it amazing that a united states senator will talk about cia matters. i took an oath of office to protect sources and methods of intelligence and i would never discuss anything i was doing at the cia that would affect the national security,'' bush said
there has been one charge after another in this campaign and i have just decided not to respond to mr. dole's charges.''
however, bush pointed to noriega's recent indictment on federal drug charges
i would point out that it's the reagan-bush administration under which mr. noriega is being indicted in florida for drugs.''
dole has grown increasingly critical of bush in the final days before the super tuesday round of caucuses and primaries in which the vice president has a comfortable lead
i need to convince a lot of people in the next few days there's only one candidate tough enough to do the job, and that candidate's bob dole,'' dole said
dole said if elected he would force his desire for a line-item veto into the courts
when the appropriations bill comes down, i'd line-item veto a few things ... and send it back to congress. then we'd have a constitutional question,'' dole said, which would throw the issue into the courts
if congress won't approve a balanced budget amendment, dole said he would go to the american people and call a constitutional convention to get one
dole also pledged to support american interests in the panama canal zone after the year 2000, when the united states is supposed to turn over control of the canal to the central american country
i sure am glad i voted against the panama canal treaty. that vote looks better every day,'' he said. ...'' to update with customs service to seize passports.</note>
two big obstacles in the war on drugs are low-level bureaucrats who don't have their hearts in the effort and an overbearing congress, two top administration officials contended wednesday
attorney general edwin meese iii, one of four cabinet officials appearing on a nine-member administration panel at the white house conference on a drug-free america, asserted there is no problem of leadership at the top
he called for more state and local financial assistance, less congressional meddling and more determination by federal employees to get with the programs outlined by their superiors
responding to written questions submitted by some of the estimated 2,000 people attending the conference, meese said there is no need for a federal drug czar to coordinate the battle
i thik this idea has been so discredited there is nobody that really believes in that any more,'' he said. ``what has happened is there is a drug czar in the united states, and that is the president of the united states.''
meese acknowledged that with several different agencies involved ``you're going to have differences of opinion,'' but he said there are mechanisms for resolving interagency disputes and that he is ``not worried about the organizational aspects.''
however, he continued: ``i am extremely concerned about the fragmentation that goes on in congress, the fact that we have 32 different committees in the congress with cognizance over the drug problem so that too many of the leaders who are seated on the stage here are spending their time testifying in front of congressional committees instead of leading the forces that ought to be out in the field working on the drug problem.''
william von raab, commissioner of the u.s. customs service, said too many bureaucrats lack enthusiasm for fighting the drug war
i have been flat out told by many bureaucrats that just because the president is supporting an effort it doesn't mean that money goes with it,'' he said. ``we don't need a bunch of bureaucrats that will deal with this war on drugs the way they dealt with the war in vietnam. we need heart in this effort ....''
there are still too many people who work for us _ in my organization as well _ who still have their noses too deeply buried in their old books,'' the customs chief said. ``these are the conscientious objectors, the shirkers and the fourth columnists in this war.''
meese associated himself with those remarks, but neither he nor von raab identified the people they were talking about
responding to another question, meese discounted any implication that he does not favor continued federal financing for federal drug treatment programs. but he said state and local officials need to do more
von raab said that starting march 15, the customs service will begin taking the passports of americans who try to re-enter the country with drugs. the passports are to be seized as evidence of a crime and forwarded to the state department, said customs service spokesman edward kittredge
among the other administration participants at the congressionally ordered conference was education secretary william bennett, who embraced the long-simmering idea of making more use of u.s. military forces to interdict the flow of drugs into the united states
as the greatest military and economic power in the world, we can do more to prevent criminals in foreign nations from growing or processing illegal drugs,'' bennett said
it is to be hoped we can do this in collaboration with foreign governments, but if need be we must consider doing this by ourselves,'' he said. ``and we should consider broader use of military force against both the production and shipment of drugs.''
congress has considered legislation since 1983 to authorize military intervention against drug shipments. the measure has passed the house in one form or another on three occasions, but has never passed the senate
the latest congressional action on the issue called for the general accounting office to study the impact on military readiness of having the defense department play a lead role in the anti-drug effort
during wednesday's session, new york mayor edward i. koch was rebuffed when he attempted to ask a question about the role of the military in the drug war from the floor rather than submit it in writing as others were required to do
what i saw was a lot of back-scratching,'' koch said later of the preceedings. ``it is incredible ... that they would stifle debate and not allow questions from the floor. it is a disservice to the mission.''
but koch, who said he was speaking for the u.s. conference of mayors, told reporters he liked what he heard from bennett and von raab _ especially the idea of using military forces against foreign drug dealers
we'll take care of the communists later,'' he said. ``they're not now seeking to invade the united states. it's the drug dealers.'' 8 grafs with hawaii endorsements</note>
massachusetts gov. michael dukakis fulfilled a boyhood ambition wednesday as he detoured from the beaten political campaign trail to make a pilgrimage to the boston red sox spring training camp
he didn't forget politics, also making a speech at a florida high school, celebrating his victory in tuesday's non-binding vermont primary and crowing in miami that ``we must be coming on strong folks'' when told that republican candidate george bush had criticized him in another southern state
bush, in mississippi, said dukakis wanted to reduce the number of navy battleships, which bush called a ``dumb idea.''
we'll have a strong, well-equipped navy, but we're not going to spend $36 billion on two super carrier task forces,'' dukakis said
the massachusetts governor began airing a new television commercial attacking rep. richard gephardt and mocking gephardt's populist slogan, ``it's your fight too.''
the advertisement says gephardt is taking campaign contributions from ``big establishment power brokers'' and adds: ``kinda makes you wonder, is dick gephardt fighting your fight or theirs?''
in winter haven, unlike ordinary tourists, the governor even got a turn in the big league batting cage, although he had little to show for it
the one-time freshman catcher on the brookline, mass., high school squad donned red sox jersey no. 1 and took 10 swings against a batting practice pitcher. he fouled off three balls, popped one into the batting cage, hit five grounders and whiffed once
i want you to work on your swing,'' advised outfielder dwight evans
at least i made contact,'' said the 54-year-old governor. he acknowledged to reporters, ``i'm a little rusty, as you can see.''
the self-described ``long-suffering'' red sox fan said, ``it's a great thrill to be here. i've never been to spring training. it's something all boston kids want to do.''
i'm very optimistic about the campaign and the red sox,'' he said. ``if we could both win our world series, that would be a (great) 1988.''
dukakis is doing well in many polls heading into tuesday's round of 20 primaries and caucuses, primarily in the south, but he said the red sox, like himself, should ``just keep working and don't pay any attention to the polls.''
outside a high school in apopka, fla., dukakis said, ``we're going to do well across the south'' with a campaign emphasizing ``jobs, good health care, the environment _ things that people care about in the south and all over the country.''
referring to rival albert gore jr., the tennessee senator who has geared his campaign to the south, dukakis said, ``if you put all of your eggs in one regional basket ... it becomes a lot more crucial that you do exceedingly well.''
he got an enthusiastic welcome at an assembly of apopka high school's 460-member senior class, but there were a few groans when dukakis defended his stands against aid to the contras and the strategic defense initiative
when dukakis asked, ``is it going to be star wars or housing for the homeless, is it going to be mx missiles or housing for the homeless?'' some of the teen-agers replied, ``star wars, mx missiles.''
nearly one-fifth of apopka's students are in a marine rotc program and several seniors wore their dress blues
dukakis also got a campaign boost in the super tuesday state of hawaii, where gov. john waihee has thrown the support of the state's democratic party leadership behind him
waihee had maintained an uncommitted stance until now
i think the game is on the line tuesday. we can stand on the sidelines and watch, or we can get into the game,'' waihee told a news conference wednesday in honolulu
the announcement came with dukakis listening in from miami, fla., on a telephone conference call
i'm sitting here glowing,'' dukakis said. he called waihee ``a man who has shown great wisdom in his choice of presidential candidates.''
waihee said the dukakis endorsement has the backing of hawaii's sens. daniel inouye and spark matsunaga and rep. daniel akaka, lt. gov. ben cayetano and other democratic leaders
hawaii's super tuesday precinct elections will include a presidential preference vote that will be binding on at least 20 of hawaii's 28 delegates to the democratic party national convention
before the dukakis endorsement, party leaders said they had expected jesse jackson to gain a plurality in hawaii's precinct elections, with dukakis and ``uncommitted'' splitting most of the balance. liaison and add that carlson was a former aide.</note>
a senator complained wednesday that gov. evan mecham sent an ``inappropriate'' letter proclaiming his innocence to every member of the arizona senate, which is sitting as judge and jury at his impeachment trial
an irate sen. jesus ``chuy'' higuera arose at the close of the third day of the first-term republican's impeachment trial and held up the letter
i hope governor mecham understands the oath we have taken,'' said higuera, urging other senators not to read the document. ``i hope mr. mecham would understand it's inappropriate to try to communicate with us.''
the five-page document was a copy of mecham's statement from a saturday news conference during which the governor pleaded his case and claimed it was unfair to try him on impeachment charges before a criminal case can be resolved
a cover memo on the governor's official stationery accompanied each copy
mecham, 63, was impeached by the house on charges of concealing a $350,000 campaign loan, borrowing $80,000 in state funds for his auto dealership and trying to thwart an investigation of an alleged death threat against a former aide
he also also faces a march 22 trial march on charges of concealing the loan and a may 17 recall election
one of mecham's lawyers, tom crowe, told the associated press he considered the governor's sending the letter appropriate
it's a political proceeding,'' said crowe. ``the senators have received communications from many people pro and con. i don't see why the governor should be any different.''
some senators who had voted to delay the impeachment trial said they had received notes from mecham thanking them for their support
in recent weeks, senators have asked that mecham stop making phone calls to their offices during the impeachment proceedings. they said they consider the calls inappropriate and did not talk the governor, who is suspended from office
on tuesday, a flap arose when it appeared that mecham had tried to contact a witness, but the governor later said the phone call was placed by mistake
during testimony earlier in the day, an attorney for mecham suggested that the alleged death threat to a grand jury witness was ``a political matter,'' not a crime
mecham's former security chief, testifying for a second day, said he considered the incident a potential felony and told mecham a crime could be involved
the criminal nature of it was primary in my mind,'' said department of public safety lt. charles ``beau'' johnson. ``i did not really think of it in the political sense.''
didn't you also believe this could be a political matter?'' defense attorney fred craft asked
i don't recall that that crossed my mind,'' johnson said
johnson and another former member of the governor's security detail have testified they were told that mecham's aide, lee watkins, threatened in november that the governor's former legislative liaison, donna carlson, might ``go on a long boat ride'' if she didn't stop testifying before a grand jury investigating mecham
mecham is accused of instructing the head of the dps not to cooperate in the attorney general's probe. watkins has denied threatening ms. carlson, and he has not been charged
mecham, who stayed away from the trial for a third day, has said he didn't know all the details of the incident, contended that he didn't know a potential felony was involved and blamed his security officers for not fully informing him
i told him it was a felony to tamper with a witness,'' johnson said. ``i didn't say the words `death threat.' but i said `tampering with a witness.' i have no doubts about that ... i was not hiding anything from the governor.''
he also said he thought the matter was ``being taken too lightly'' by the governor and his staff
when you took it to fred craft did he take it seriously?'' craft asked, referring to himself. craft was formerly mecham's lobbyist in washington
yes,'' said johnson. ``but i think the focus of your concern was embarrassment to the governor.''
craft's participation as defense attorney as well as a principal in the disputed events raised protests from some senators
republican majority leader robert usdane accused craft of misleading senators about his role when they agreed to let him join the defense. his participation as a lawyer bars him from being called by either side as a witness, although some senators believe they could call craft to testify
earlier, the trial's presiding officer, arizona chief justice frank x. gordon, said he would not allow the defense to introduce an affidavit intended to discredit a key witness by alleging he had an affair with an employee in 1982
the prospective witness, dps director ralph milstead, has said the allegations are ``ridiculous.''
i don't think it's necessary to go into old past history about someone's past sexual liaison, and he denies it,'' said gordon. ``it has no value to prove anything material to these issues.''
a two-thirds vote of the senate would be required to convict mecham on any count and remove him from office. the senate could, by another two-thirds vote, then bar mecham from holding any state office again. update with abrams comments. pickup 13th pvs: `cochez said ...</note>
an opposition leader said wednesday that gen. manuel antonio noriega was purging his army of suspected opponents, and doctors joined businesses in a general strike aimed at ousting the military strongman
guillermo cochez, a national legislator and vice president of the opposition christian democratic party, told reporters that noriega apparently had fired two senior colonels and two majors suspected of being disloyal
cochez said they included col. marcos justines, who as chief of staff was no. 2 in the panamanian defense forces and next in line to succeed noriega
for a second day, the strike was marked by violence in a middle-class neighborhood near the banking district. on tuesday, security agents destroyed an opposition radio station in the neighborhood, apparently because it broadcast an appeal for anti-noriega demonstrations
demonstrators gathered wednesday along the four-lane street in front of the station, set up barricades of burning trash, and set fire to a minivan and a car
anti-riot police chased the protesters into side streets and apartment buildings. chunks of concrete were hurled down at police from at least two of the apartment houses
police fired tear-gas grenades and pumped tear gas into the buildings from portable tanks, filling the entire neighborhood with the acrid, stinging fumes
the officer in charge stood in the middle of the street and shouted to residents, ``you'll come out like cockroaches!''
none did, and reporters on the scene saw no one injured
a spokesman for the panama canal commission said anonymous telephone callers warned tuesday and wednesday that a bomb was planted in commission headquarters
spokesman franklin castrellon told the associated press the building was evacuated and searched both days but no bombs were found
in washington, meanwhile, william d. rogers, a lawyer for a panamanian opposition group, said the state department was taking legal action to keep noriega's regime from withdrawing panamanian government funds from u.s. banks. about $50 million was said to be involved
assistant secretary of state elliott abrams raised the possibility that the united states will withhold the next payment due to panama for tolls, fees and services for panama canal operations
abrams also told the cable news network that ``if the government of president (eric arturo) delvalle says to american banks, don't pay money to noriega, then all those banks are going to come to the state department and say, `who's got the authority here? noriega or delvalle?'
we're going to answer that question ... noriega has been fired and he does not have legitimate authority there,'' abrams said
cochez said he could not ``absolutely confirm'' the firings, but several diplomatic sources said they also had heard the reports and tended to believe them
justines was chosen by president devalle on feb. 25 to replace noriega, but devalle's attempt to fire noriega backfired. noriega supporters in the national assembly instead voted to oust delvalle
justines then joined other ranking officers in pledging their loyalty to noriega, who is under indictment in the united states on drug trafficking charges
cochez said col. elias castillo, the army chief and the no. 4 man in the military hierarchy, also was fired, along with two majors, moises del rio and fernando quesada
i think the purge is good for the democratic process because it will show the other officers that he (noriega) is not interested in the institution, but only in himself,'' cochez said. ``most officers are supporting noriega because they consider it an institutional problem.''
the armed forces press office said it could not confirm the reported removals of officers
noriega has headed the 15,000-member defense forces, which includes the army, navy, air force and police, since 1983. he was seen as the real power behind delvalle's civilian government
most of the capital's doctors appeared to have joined the nationwide strike against noriega, which began monday
ap reporters visited four hospitals and clinics around the capital wednesday and found them taking new patients only on an emergency basis
the government, which through official media has been calling the strike ``a complete failure,'' tacitly admitted health care problems. the health ministry issued a communique calling on all unemployed physicians to report to ministry offices for assignment
calls to areas outside the capital indicated mixed participation in the strike
in colon, the country's other major commercial center, daniel delgado of the chamber of commerce said economic activity had proceeded almost normally monday and tuesday. but he said the chamber called on members to join the strike for 48 hours beginning thursday
in chiriquii province, on the costa rican border, the chamber of commerce reported a significant reduction in activity, with virtually all branches of capital-based stores and businesses shut down
in chitre, 90 miles southwest of panama city, horacio rodriguez, director of the association of executives, said about 60 percent of the city's economic activity was shut down
the national civic crusade, an alliance of about 200 business, labor, professional and political groups, claimed tuesday night that the strike had succeeded in shutting down 85 percent of the country's economic acivity. nicaragua without mediator; picks up 9th graf pvs, ``he also ...</note>
president daniel ortega on wednesday proposed holding the third round of nicaraguan cease-fire talks without the country's roman catholic leader, saying the mediator had failed to produce results
ortega said the talks, scheduled for next week, should be held in the nicaraguan town of sapoa, near the costa rican border. it was the first time the leftist sandinista government has agreed to talk to the u.s.-backed rebels in nicaragua
cardinal miguel obando y bravo has been mediating the talks on ending the 7-year-old war
ortega said his government decided ``to take the bull by the horns'' because obando y bravo's mediation had not produced any results
the cardinal himself had suggested some time ago that a direct meeting, and in our country, would be very important,'' ortega said
i told him that today i have decided to name the member of the national directorate of the sandinista liberation front and defense minister, gen. humberto ortega, as the chief of the (sandinista) delegation,'' he added. the defense minister is the president's brother
the contra rebels sent a message to the cardinal earlier wednesday, agreeing to his proposal to hold new talks on march 10-11
the last round of negotiations broke off feb. 19 in guatemala after the cardinal said the two sides had reached an impasse
after making his proposal, president ortega said: ``in this manner, we are testing whether there really exists the will to work for peace on the part of the so-called directorate of the counter-revolution, since it can no longer give any excuses.''
he referred to the directorate of the contra umbrella organization known as the nicaraguan resistance
ortega spoke with reporters shortly after meeting with obando y bravo in the evening, but there was no immediate comment from the cardinal
the sandinistas previously refused to hold the talks in nicaragua, saying the rebels should seek a government amnesty before being able to enter the country
obando y bravo sent a letter to ortega earlier wednesday hammering at the need to resume cease-fire negotiations
during the february talks, the cardinal increased his role by proposing a peace agenda. besides calling for a laying down of arms, he asked the sandinistas to grant total political amnesty, restore full press freedoms, revise the military draft law and reopen talks with the opposition political parties that remain active inside nicaragua
he also suggested the contras be permitted to enter designated cease-fire zones with their arms for a one-month truce
in their message wednesday accepting the new round of talks, the contras reiterated their acceptance of the agenda proposed by the cardinal, said jorge rosales, a spokesman in miami for the rebel coalition, known as the nicaraguan resistance
the sandinistas maintain they will not discuss political issues with the contras. they say amnesty will be granted after a cease-fire agreement is reached
talks with the internal political parties broke off in december when opposition members insisted on constitutional changes
the cease-fire and internal dialogue are outlined in a regional peace plan signed last august by the presidents of nicaragua, el salvador, guatemala, costa rica and honduras
the sandinistas want talks with the contras to center on the mechanics of how and where the rebels should lay down their arms
the government asked obando y bravo last november to mediate the talks. the church backed the successful sandinista struggle to overthrow the right-wing, pro-american somoza dynasty in 1979, but later became a firm critic of the sandinista government
the cardinal acted as go-between until january, when the sandinistas softened their position and agreed to hold direct talks with the rebels
in other developments, the defense ministry said wednesday that its intelligence sources reported increased u.s. military activity in central america and american troop movement along its borders
a u.s. embassy spokesman in tegucigalpa, honduras, said no american troops were near the border with nicaragua. the spokesman added, however, that engineering-training projects _ carried out annually in the dry season _ had temporarily increased the number of flights out of palmerola air base and the number of troops in honduras
he spoke on condition of anonymity
the ministry communique said ammunition and explosives were transferred recently from u.s. military installations in panama to costa rica, nicaragua's neighbor to the south
the communique said 1,000 u.s. army troops, including some from the 82nd airborne division, were moved to the nicaragua's northeastern border with honduras. it said special forces units were moved to the northwestern border
there've been no border troop movements,'' the embassy spokesman said
u.s. troops that participate in combined honduran-u.s. exercises are prohibited by u.s. law from going within 20 miles of the border with nicaragua
winners at the 30th annual grammy awards waxed poetic, gushed, cried, giggled and gave thanks to the music industry, their record companies, friends, family and god as they accepted their prizes wednesday night
i can't tell you how i feel,'' said a bubbly whitney houston backstage at radio city music hall after winning best female pop vocalist for her single, ``i wanna dance with somebody'' from her second lp, ``whitney.''
it's just so emotional. ... i'm nervous, very proud, very honored, excited; it's very great,'' said houston, who was a grammy winner two years ago for her platinum debut album
jody watley, who was named best new artist, thanked ``everybody at mca, my manager, i thank god, my producers ... my video director ... my publicist ... my attorney.''
veteran rhythm and blues performer little richard, who helped define rock 'n' roll more than three decades ago, stole the show by declaring himself the winner before opening the envelop to reveal watley's name
y'all never gave me no grammys and i've been singing for years,'' he shouted, strutting about the stage for an amused audience. ``i'm the architect of rock 'n' roll. ... being a brown jew from georgia, i had to tell the truth.''
little richard, who dropped out of the rock life years ago to become an evangelist, announced two years ago that he had converted to judaism
bono, lead singer of the irish rockers u2, whose politically introspective lp, ``the joshua tree,'' won two grammys including album of the year, said: ``we set out to make music _ soul music. ... that's not about being black or white. ... it's a decision to reveal or conceal.''
george michael, on tour in australia to promote his hit lp ``faith,'' was thrilled that he had won a grammy in the rhythm and blues category for his duo with soul queen aretha franklin
winning the r &amp; b category with aretha validates the tremendous influence r &amp; b music has had on my music, songwriting and creative process,'' michael said through his spokesman, phil lobel. ``not bad for a brit with soul.''
one of the best acceptances at the awards show came from pianist vladimir horowitz who walked off the stage with a twinkle and no comment after being handed the prize for best classical album for his ``horowitz in moscow.''
earlier, the esteemed artist thanked the national academy of recording arts &amp; sciences for president's special merit award: ``i am so very happy that classical music still has an appreciation.''
ray benson, leader of ``asleep at the wheel,'' a five-man band that plays western swing, said: ``it feels great. it feels amazing. it's like you've been down 10 to nothing in the 9th inning and winning.''
the band won for best country instrumental performance for the song ``string of pars,'' which benson said was for golfers. the band last won 10 years ago in the same category for ``1 o'clock jump,'' a count basie song in western style
he said it's sometimes difficult keeping a band together. ``everyday, if you're asleep at the wheel, you're in danger of a lot of things.''
suzanne vega, who was nominated for three grammys for her touching song about an abused child, ``luka,'' talked backstage at radio city music hall after learning she had lost the trophy for best female pop vocalist and song of the year. she also was nominated for record of the year, but didn't win
i was hoping it would win, but i was prepared for anything to happen,'' she said. ``i'm a little disappointed i guess.''
cynthia weil, who with barry mann won song of the year for writing the sweet ballad, ``somewhere out there,'' said: ``we wrote it for the mice. we didn't even think about a pop record when we wrote it.''
the song was written for the animated movie, ``an american tail,'' the story of an immigrant mouse family. it was recorded as a duet by linda ronstadt and james ingram, who were nominated as best pop performance by a duo or group. when asked if winning the grammy made up for losing an academy award last year for best song, weil said, ``it does. it's nice to win an award that comes from the music industry _ that's our home.''
weil and mann are the last songwriting team creating from the legendary brill building in new york, once a haven for american song
said narada michael walden, who won the producer award for the lp, ``whitney'': ``i think the world wants new faces in a way. ... whitney is an angel and it's purity, like this flower.'' he was carrying a red rose
i felt this was a very special year. my competition is my friends. quincy (jones, who co-produced the michael jackson lp, ``bad'') i love. u2 i admire very much. i think we are all great music lovers. i think we bring the spirit down. we are all brothers.'' news digest: brussels, belgium _ am-nato rdp; brussels, belgium _ am-nato summit-arms; new york _ am-grammys; undated _ am-political rdp; baton rouge, la. _ la congress; washington _ am_civil rights; toledo, ohio _ am-sweepstakes losers; phoenix, ariz. _ am-mecham; london _ am-ferry disaster; hartford, conn. _ am-restaurant critics.</note>
israeli troops fired tear gas inside an arab hospital wednesday, forcing doctors to don gas masks and sending dozens of choking patients fleeing with their faces covered by arab headdresses
soldiers clubbed a palestinian teen-ager suspected of throwing rocks at troops from a barricade erected about 10 yards from the hospital's emergency room
an associated press photographer saw soldiers throw the youth head first down a flight of stairs, then sit on his stomach while beating him with a wooden truncheon
president reagan, vowing to ``spare no effort'' in the pursuit of peace, ordered secretary of state george p. shultz on wednesday to return to the middle east for more talks with arab and israeli leaders
reagan made the decision to re-commit u.s. prestige to an effort that so far has not produced visible results after shultz reported on four days of diplomatic shuttling and a session tuesday in london with king hussein of jordan
it is clear all countries in the region believe it is useful for the united states to remain engaged in this process,'' reagan said. `we will spare no effort in our search for a comprehensive peace settlement.''
an opposition leader said wednesday that gen. manuel antonio noriega was purging his army of suspected opponents, and doctors joined businesses in a general strike aimed at ousting the military strongman
guillermo cochez, a national legislator and vice president of the opposition christian democratic party, told reporters that noriega apparently had fired two senior colonels and two majors suspected of being disloyal
cochez said they included col. marcos justines, who as chief of staff was no. 2 in the panamanian defense forces and next in line to succeed noriega
the united states is taking legal action to prevent panama's military-dominated regime from withdrawing panamanian government funds from u.s. banks, a lawyer representing opposition forces said wednesday
although no firm figures were available, $50 million was said to be involved
the state department had no comment on the reported action, but other officials, speaking only on condition of anonymity, confirmed that the measures outlined by attorney william d. rogers were being taken
prodded by the food and drug administration, pharmaceutical companies agreed wednesday to avoid any advertising that claims aspirin can help prevent a first heart attack, despite a report in a medical journal that drew this conclusion
fda commissioner frank e. young announced the agreement after he met for more than an hour with company representatives who came to his office in this washington suburb after he sent a letter reminding of the fda's power to regulate
at a news conference, young said he had told the manufacturers that if they promoted their products for a use not supported by an fda analysis, they could be guilty of mislabeling, and ``this mislabeling can lead to regulatory action by the fda.''
a study of massachusetts women who gave birth found that one in 500 was infected with the aids virus, and researchers projecting their findings nationwide say several thousand aids-infected babies could be born in the united states each year
most surveys of aids infection have concentrated on male homosexuals, drug addicts and others at high risk of catching the disease. estimating the prevalence of the virus in the general population has been difficult
this paper gives a more accurate way to judge the scope of the epidemic in women,'' said dr. rodney hoff. ``nothing else comes close to this in being able to measure the prevalence in the united states.''
pat robertson wants to drop his libel suit against a former congressman who questioned his war record because going to trial now would ``sacrifice his presidential campaign,'' his lawyer said wednesday. but robertson's accuser declared, ``he's chickening out of the trial just like he chickened out 37 years ago.''
former rep. paul mccloskey, r-calif., who has accused robertson of using his father's political influence to avoid combat duty in the korean war, has said in recent weeks he wouldn't settle the suit unless robertson paid the costs, which mccloskey estimates at $400,000, of defending against the suit
the trial, set to begin on tuesday, when robertson hopes to do well in delegate-rich southern primaries, would force him off the campaign trail for three weeks, attorney douglas rigler said
iraq and iran battered each other's capitals with long-range missiles for a third day wednesday and the first iraqi rockets of the 7{-year-old war crashed into qom, seat of the iranian religious hierarchy
iran reported no casualties in qom, a holy city of 250,000 where ayatollah ruhollah khomeini once made his home. the 87-year-old revolutionary patriarch has lived for several years in jamaran, a northern tehran suburb
the iraqis said they fired seven surface-to-surface missiles wednesday, two of them into qom, bringing the total for three days to 23. iran said it hit baghdad with three missiles, for a total of eight in the same period
negotiators on wednesday launched their latest and possibly last round of afghanistan peace talks, and the u.n. mediator said he was confident of forging a settlement to end soviet involvement in the country
this was a good session,'' pakistan's acting foreign minister, zain noorani, said as he emerged from the first closed-door meeting late wednesday. ``we are cautiously optimistic.''
pakistan is representing the afghan guerrillas in the talks
new home sales fell 9 percent in january, pushing sales activity to its slowest pace since the end of the last recession, the government said wednesday as the housing industry continued to stagger following the october stock market collapse
a downturn in housing has often been the harbinger of the onset of a recession, but analysts said they believed falling mortgage rates offered the hope of a rebound in home sales in coming months
in january, the commerce department said that sales of new single-family homes fell for the third consecutive month, dropping to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 535,000 units, 26 percent below a year ago and the slowest pace since the last recession was ending in december 1982
a mutiny broke out on among usually meek and patient london commuters, with passengers refusing orders to leave their delay-plagued subway train until its driver took them to their destination
only about a dozen rebellious passengers were involved in the tuesday night incident on the ``tube,'' as the subway system is known, but london regional transport said it was unprecedented, given the meek and humble nature of the british commuter
to the london evening standard newspaper, it was ``the great tube revolt,'' and the mutineers' unidentified leader was ``a superhero in the clark kent mold _ quiet, mild-mannered and unassuming.''
once again good news has intruded on the gilded dreams of gold investors, whose hopes for wealth depend on fears of inflation or economic collapse
the price of gold has fallen from $500 an ounce in mid-december to $430 an ounce this week, making it a particularly bad investment so far in 1988
what went wrong is that too many things went right in the aftermath of october's stock market collapse
jeffrey a. nichols, president of american precious metals advisors inc., ticks some of them off:
low inflation, a stronger dollar, stable world equity markets, a stronger u.s. bond market, rising confidence in the economic outlooks around the world, and, very significantly in the last couple of weeks, rising confidence in the federal reserve and chairman (alan) greenspan.''
good news for the general public, but bad news for gold bugs
so with good times breaking out, why is nichols still predicting that gold will reach $500 an ounce again within the next 12 months, and go ``perhaps significantly higher''?
an excess of supply that marked the first few months of 1988 is likely to end, nichols argues
he says the soviet union probably will sell less gold from now on because it has raised a large portion of the foreign currency reserves it will need for the year
mining companies will ease up on the downward pressure they put on gold prices through their sales of gold for future delivery in forward contracts, nichols says
and the spate of ``gold loans'' is likely to ease up somewhat, nichols said. newmont mining corp. dumped 1 million ounces of gold onto the market this year when it borrowed against future production and then sold the gold to raise cash and pay off debts acquired in a successful takeover defense
although an additional 2 million ounces' worth of gold loans are already in the pipeline, nichols said, the flood should diminish after that
on the demand side, investors in japan and elsewhere in the far east have taken a new interest in gold. the japanese imported 40 tons of gold in february alone, nichols estimates. the appetite for kilobars _ 31 ounces of pure gold _ is so great in the far east that he says fabricators cannot keep up
indians imported 100 tons of gold last year even though it is illegal to bring gold into india because of foreign-exchange controls, nichols said, declining to divulge where he got the information
new gold coins from the american eagle and canadian maple leaf to the chinese panda are increasing investors' and collectors' interest in gold, while various banks and investment houses have created accumulation plans that allow people to buy gold on schedule
and there is always the chance of more bad news _ which, of course, is good news
trouble in south africa tends to push up gold prices by threatening to cut off supplies at the source
and any hint that the next president will be fiscally irresponsible would do wonders for gold
even republicans can be fiscally stimulative, as we've seen from ronald reagan. but generally democrats have a reputation for not being fiscally conservative,'' said john norris, a citibank vice president in charge of precious metals
if somebody like jesse jackson ever had a chance of being elected, i think you'd see gold really start to move up,'' norris said
here are broadway's new and current shows. ticket supply as of march 4 is indicated as difficult or available. credit card holders can order tickets by phone or by calling telecharge, teletron or ticketron
telecharge's number is 212-239-6200 unless otherwise indicated. teletron's number is 212-246-0102. ticketron is 212-977-9020
for 24-hour information on theater, dance and music performances, call the theater development fund's new york city@on stage, 212-587-1111
when calling theaters directly, use new york area code 212. advance inquiries should be made, as ticket availability is subject to change
_ ``a chorus line,'' the longest-running musical in broadway history, is about the hard life and struggles of chorus-line members. shubert, 239-6200, same number as telecharge. ticketron. available
_ ``anything goes,'' a revival by the lincoln center theater of the 1934 cole porter musical. vivian beaumont, 239-6200, same number as telecharge. ticketron. difficult
