_ ``the nerd,'' a comedy by larry shue, author of ``the foreigner,'' about the limits of friendship. helen hayes, 944-9450. teletron. ticketron. available. advertising ``last weeks.''
_ ``the phantom of the opera,'' the lavish andrew lloyd webber musical about a deformed composer who haunts the paris opera house and the young soprano he loves. majestic, 239-6290, same number as telecharge. difficult
in the 1964 film, ``topkapi,'' peter ustinov and melina mercouri played thieves who descended into a museum in istanbul through a skylight to steal a jewel-encrusted dagger
that plot was repeated with stunning accuracy last month when burglars broke into manhattan's colnaghi art gallery through a skylight, shinnied down a rope and plucked 27 old master paintings and drawings off the walls
the stolen artwork was valued at $6 million, making it the biggest art heist in new york history. the most valuable pieces stolen were two panels by the 15th century italian renaissance master fra angelico worth $4 million
but unlike the cunning thieves in ``topkapi,'' those who broke into the colnaghi gallery on feb. 8 appear to have been unschooled burglars who had no clear idea of what they were stealing
if so, their fate is ironic: their booty may be impossible to sell at anything resembling its face value
art theft, long romanticized as a genteel form of larceny, is on the rise. some law enforcement officials and other experts believe it may rank second only to narcotics trafficking in value of ill-gotten gains
if you're talking about dollar value, it probably is,'' said one justice department official who specializes in crime statistics. he stressed that he was only speculating since art theft is not recognized as a separate category in federal statistics. he declined to give his name
it began to increase in the late '50s and the early '60s when the art market began to rise,'' said milton esterow, editor and publisher of artnews magazine. ``more and more thieves began to wake up and say, `hey! there's a lot of money here!'''
if there was a lot of money then, there's more now
masterworks often cost many times the value of the mansions where they're hung. vincent van gogh's painting, ``irises,'' set a record last november when it was sold for $53.9 million
art thieves usually fall into one of three categories, experts say
one is the professional thief who is commissioned to steal specific works of art
mr. jones might have fallen in love with one of these paintings and he wants it so bad he can just taste it, so he goes out and hires someone to steal it,'' explained retired insurance claims investigator jim mellors, who specialized in fine art claims
in these cases, mellors and others said, the stolen item may wind up in a private collection for years _ or even generations _ and no money changes hands except the fee paid by the collector to the thief
less common is the collector who steals art himself, such as the philadelphia doctor who was arrested in 1982 for ``shoplifting'' hundreds of thousands of dollars worth of art from new york galleries for his lavish personal collection
and then, probably most common of all, is the professional thief who steals art and tries to fence it. sometimes the thief is knowledgeable about art; often he is not, as appears to be the case in the colnaghi break-in, law enforcement officials say
it's no secret that thieves who are knowledgeable about art don't steal well-known pieces,'' said esterow, who is the author of the book, ``the art stealers.''
detective thomas moscardini, the new york police department's full-time art crimes investigator, agreed that the colnaghi thieves may have blundered when they chose works by fra angelico, jean baptiste simeon chardin and other old masters
i think it would be difficult to dispose of them because they were somewhat noted pieces,'' he said. ``you're dealing with 15th-16th century works of art (and) that in itself would bring some attention.''
according to the experts, smart thieves steal mid-range art, preferably works that are similar to others by the same artist. these works can be sold to unscrupulous or unwitting dealers who don't conduct thorough background checks. sometimes they are used in place of currency in drug transactions
the international foundation for art research maintains a list of art reported stolen. the list now contains 278,000 items and is regularly sent to law enforcement agencies, museums and galleries. between 150 and 300 items are added every month
in the case of a major theft like that from the colnaghi gallery, the foundation puts out a worldwide alert, complete with photographs of the missing pieces. the glare of publicity makes it hard for a thief, particularly one without connections in the art world, to sell the stolen goods except at an extreme discount to a crooked dealer _ or to an insurance company
what are you going to do with a fra angelico?'' asked esterow. ``how are you going to get rid of it, except by making a deal with the insurance company?''
esterow's remark brings up one of the touchiest subjects for those who deal with art theft
insurance adjusters routinely deny that they ever pay ransom to get back a work of art. ``no, no, no, they don't pay ransom,'' said independent claims adjuster william smith, who specializes in the fine arts. ``they pay rewards, which are a different thing. they will pay to retrieve property under acceptable circumstances. ... if, for example, an innocent (party) comes forward and gives them information that leads to recovery.''
but others say that policy is not strictly followed
in europe, (artworks) have been held for ransom for the insurance company to pay,'' said manhattan art dealer arnold herstand. ``that's arranged frequently. it's even arranged in new york city. that's fairly common.''
in the colnaghi case, the gallery has announced that its insurance company was offering a reward _ 10 percent of the value of the stolen pieces _ for their return
final determination of eligibility for payment of the reward will be made by the donor, not by the new york city police department or any other party,'' the announcement said
a spokesman for the gallery, vice president alan wintermute, said he couldn't say if the thieves were among those eligible for the reward, which could amount to $600,000. it was up to the insurance company, he said
the recovery rate for stolen art is probably no greater than 10 percent, experts say. enforcement is spotty. new york and los angeles each have one full-time police officer investigating art crimes; the fbi has one and the u.s. customs service has one. they represent the nation's war on art crime
it is a big business,'' said charles koczka, a retired u.s. customs agent who was that agency's specialist in fine art crimes. ``it has a minimal risk of being caught or, if you are caught, of going to jail. and unfortunately, if you are a victim, you're very unlikely to recover your property.''
members of the mormon tabernacle choir and church president and prophet ezra taft benson attended the inauguration of arizona gov. evan mecham, himself a former mormon bishop. mecham's beliefs are closely tied to church doctrine; his ties to church leadership strong. so when a storm of turmoil engulfed the governor, arizona's mormon community found itself at the center
steve benson has been a life-long mormon, active in church affairs. he is the grandson of church president and prophet ezra taft benson. few would question his devotion
few, except impeached gov. evan mecham and some of his supporters
benson happens to be the award-winning cartoonist for the arizona republic _ and a relentless critic of the embattled governor. mecham happens to be arizona's first mormon governor and an unwavering believer in conservative church doctrine
in arizona these days, politics and religion are mixing in the mormon community. mormon critics of mecham have been scorned by other mormons, who say they are not true to their religion. mecham even once told steve benson his salvation was in jeopardy because of the biting cartoons
sides have been taken and swords drawn,'' said the cartoonist. ``there have been instances of shunning. letters have been written questioning one's devotion to the church _ whether one has the moral rectitude to remain in the flock.''
with the turmoil have come fears that the brouhaha will damage the image of mormons, whose roots trace back to the settling of arizona
officially, the church has remained neutral on the governor's plight. some members say the only mentions of mecham from the pulpit have been reminders of neutrality, and the strife is limited to a small group of mormons
is the church worried? i think not. it's a matter that will pass in the next few months,'' said phoenix attorney dave udall, a church leader designated as the official spokesman
still, individuals within the community say passions run deep. some say families have been split by the issues
ed pagan, a mormon who is a history graduate student at the university of arizona and who criticized mecham in a letter to the editor, called the turmoil ``gut-wretching'' for church members
in a sense, his platform and ideology have the veneer of unofficial church position,'' said pagan, whose criticism drew letters questioning his own faith. ``there are those who say if you criticize mecham, you're ultimately criticizing god.''
an unofficial church newspaper, the latter-day sentinel, has supported mecham, and its editor, crismon lewis, is a sharp critic of the republic's benson. ``most of the church is extremely disappointed in him,'' lewis said
one cartoon that rankled mecham's mormon supporters showed an angel atop the mormon temple in salt lake city, utah. at the end of the angel's trumpet was a banner reading, ``resign, ev.''
some remember the controversy that surrounded benson's grandfather during eight years as agriculture secretary under president eisenhower
his grandfather was attacked so much by the press that he offered his resignation, but eisenhower kept him,'' said lewis. ``now, a couple of decades later, you've got the grandson doing the same thing.''
benson says his grandfather, a personal friend of mecham's, has never pressured him to back off. church-related pressure in arizona, he said, comes from an ultra-conservative sect of the church _ not the mainstream
some individuals _ and it's not unique to my religion _ unavoidably mix religion with politics and as a result think any mormon who does not agree with a fellow latter-day saint who happens to be governor is endangering his position in the church,'' benson said
it's intolerant, and it's silly.''
and benson has support among mormons _ even among some who support the governor
he's got his job to do,'' said republican state rep. jack brown, who voted against mecham's impeachment. ``he can do that and still be a good member of the mormon church.''
mecham, a 63-year-old native of duchesne, utah, was impeached feb. 5 by the arizona house of representatives on allegations of concealing a $350,000 campaign loan, misusing $80,000 from a special fund and attempting to thwart an investigation of an alleged death threat involving a state official
trial on the impeachment is under way in the state senate. if convicted, mecham would be removed from office. he also faces a criminal trial on the campaign loan charge march 22, and a recall election set for may 17
the ultra-conservative governor took office 14 months ago and immediately plunged himself into controversy by rescinding the martin luther king holiday for state workers and making statements that have offended women, homosexuals, jews and japanese
mormons believe church leaders receive divine guidance, and some mecham backers have suggested political leaders do as well. mecham himself has occassionally suggested he's received guidance from god
to shirley whitlock, active in the church and state leader of a conservative political group called the eagle forum, mormons who don't support mecham have lost their religion
i feel if there are other members of the church who do not support the governor they either have allowed themselves to be propagandized or are too liberal and don't understand their own teachings,'' mrs. whitlock said
if members of the church can't see this man is trying to do his duty, then there's false belief,'' she said. ``if they don't support the governor when he supports constitutional principles, then they better do more studying.''
passions ran high in the legislature, too, as the impeachment vote neared. rep. brown, a former mormon bishop, said he received letters from followers who tried to intimidate him
rep. mark killian, a conservative republican from mesa, a popular mormon area and site of the church's arizona temple, broke into tears as he blasted the governor's behavior, but voted against the impeachment because he didn't believe the evidence was strong enough
udall, the arizona church spokesman, said he cringes when mecham's religion is brought into the debate
is religion really a factor? i don't think it is,'' he said. ``and we'd prefer not to be getting the attention.''
brown said he worries about possible damage to the church
but i think people basically understand that you have different kinds of people in the church, and some are not reflective of the whole group,'' he said
it's a concern,'' said wayne arnett, an attorney and mormon. ``there will be those who know mecham is a mormon and think less of me because i'm a mormon.''
most mormons, mesa bishop bob goodman said, ``are sorry the church has been involved in it.''
ut i can't say it's hurt any of my members,'' goodman said. ``and i can't say it's hurt the church. the church is just too strong for that.''
scott mccartney is the ap southwest regional reporter, based in dallas
here are excerpts from basic speeches delivered recently by candidates for the 1988 republican presidential nomination:
i think the american people are going to be looking for leadership
you know my background _ combat pilot, serving in the united states congress, meeting a payroll, building a business, ambassador to china, ambassador to the united nations, running the cia at a tough time and head of the (republican) party, and seven years standing shoulder to shoulder as vice president with a president for whom i have great respect. ..
the presidency is different. it's not like congress. it's not business. it's not like anything else when that cable comes in, a plane's been hit, or an american ship's been shot at or you have to punish a marxist or a terrorist dictator like gadhafi, or have to take bold action to save american citizens' lives at risk in a tiny caribbean country. it's different. ..
i think the president took the proper steps (when he learned about the iran-contra affair). ..
covert action should not be run by the nsc (national security council). it should be run by the cia. ... i am worried about the erosion of presidential power. ... mistakes were made, but we must move ahead now. ..
let's try to hold the highest possible standards (of ethics). it is an honorable profession, public life. ... i want men and women of excellence to come and serve, not to profit. ..
i think that i would be the best for getting this (budget) deficit down, with a four-year freeze that allows for the growth and inflation, that will hold the line on taxes but doesn't freeze in bad programs. ..
i want to keep the united states strong, offering the hope of peace and freedom. ... when people go into that (voting) booth, they're going to be saying, who has the values that we believe in, who has the breadth of experience, the ability to get people to work together, and who has the integrity that we trust. ..
the question is what do we do in the future? ... i believe that i have had more real life experience than anyone else running against me, and i am proud to have stood with this president through thick and through thin, through good times and bad times, without cutting and running when the going got tough
i come from a small farming town. i was born and raised in the values that come from deep roots, deep faith and an abiding love of country. russell, kan., may be a long way off from atlanta on the map, but we share a lot of the same values
we know the importance of family, of neighbors helping neighbor, of sticking together in good times and bad. ... i learned ... that if you worked hard and really believed, you could overcome hardships and build a better tomorrow. and if your country called _ in war or peace _ you served. ..
that's how i've always tried to live my life. and that's the kind of president our country will need to lead us into the 21st century
values and leadership _ that's what this crucial election is all about. and, this year ... the south will play a key role in choosing the man who will sit across the table from mr. gorbachev. ..
the people ... must look at the record and decide which candidate has demonstrated the strength it takes to stand tough, to make the hard choices, to forge a consensus that will lead this nation forward
which candidate's leadership got president reagan's tax cut passed
whose leadership stopped the liberals from repealing those tax cuts
whose leadership put together the plan which saved social security from bankruptcy
whose leadership produced a majority of votes in the senate for aid to the nicaraguan freedom fighters
whose leadership lined up the votes to keep the president's strategic defense initiative alive
and whose leadership produced the 1985 farm bill to save the family farm
bob dole led each one of the battles in the u.s. senate. and we won. no other candidate in this race can match that record. no one
that's the true test of leadership. not how many jobs we've had, but what you've done in the jobs you've held. and that speaks volumes for what you'll do as president
there's no instant, magic formula to make the deficit vanish. but, with the right leadership, we can start solving the problem
there's no miracle cure to make freedom safe in a dangerous world. but the right leadership can do it
there's no quick fix to make america competitive again, an opportunity society where all our people can rise as high as their god-given talents will take them. but leadership can make it happen
there's no easy way out of the plague of drug abuse, the decline in values and education, the high cost of health care and so many other urgent problems. but they can be solved
these are all tough challenges. it's going to take tough, dedicated, understanding leadership to overcome them. ... i believe that i can deliver the kind of leadership we need
no public policy decision we make in the next 10 years ... will be as important as the decisions we make about defending and nurturing and strengthening the bedrock of western values _ our families and our children
there is no better school, no better engine of economic growth or job training, savings and investment than the traditional family. there is no greater moral teacher, disciplinarian, help for the weak, protector of the young, or builder of character than the family
our democratic friends urge us to look to government as mother and father, but they have it exactly backwards. ..
i believe that america needs a rebirth of respect and compassion for the value and the dignity and the sanctity of each and every child and every human life. ..
i have pledged that, as president, i will help lead america to its highest standards of educational excellence _ not by expanding budgets or new government programs, but through reforms that stress the abcs of education:
a _ restoring accountability by granting parents greater oversight and greater choice. ... b _ renewing stronger emphasis on a basic core curriculum of english, science, math, history and computer and vocational skills and expecting superior levels of achievement to be met. c _ building and developing character. ..
we've put forth a three-part plan to stop the spread of aids: first, routine testing to help identify those infected; second, confidential sharing of this information by public health authorities with those in danger of infection; and, third, common sense education that teaches right and wrong about the sexual behavior that spreads aids
we must do everything we can to find a cure. we must treat aids victims with compassion and give them care. but we must also give the american people confidence that we have a plan and that we will stop aids, now, not later. ..
our liberal friends tell us that we need ... activist judges. well, i agree. we need activist judges who actively support the constitution
we live in a democracy and it is the right and the responsibility of the people and their representatives to decide fundamental questions of public policy _ it is not, and must never be the right and responsibility of judicial elites to appropriate that right and responsibility to themselves
if we are to recapture the greatness of america we must go back to our fundamental faith in god. and when we train our children ... it is absolutely crucial that we teach them the moral values of our society. little children must once again be allowed to pray in the schools of america
when our ancestors came to these shores ... there was one thing that was uppermost in the minds of the people. they believed in individual self-reliance. ... when they went across these plains ... when they made an empire out of a wilderness ... when they fought disease and battled enemies, when they endured privation, hunger and starvation, they relied on their own initiative under god
and if we are going to be strong we must recognize that we as a people can do it ourselves. government doesn't give us our freedom. government can't take our freedom away from us. it is a gift of god given every one of us. ..
we have built in this nation with 200 years of labor a magnificent industrial base. but over the last few years of this decade we have seen our industries slowly crumbling, some of our basic industries going overseas to other nations. ..
recently i was in one of the southern states and i learned of 1,000 factories that have closed. i learned of 300,000 people who lost their jobs. and they told me about them, and they said: are you aware that imports to this country of the particular product they were mentioning, textiles, from mainland china have risen from 230 million yards to 1.8 billion yards. ... are you aware, they told me, that from january of 1986 until november of 1987 that imports of textiles from the soviet union had risen by 7,000 percent. ..
if the communist countries want to help their workers, that's fine. ... but i think the time has come in america when we no longer are going to allow our basic industries to be destroyed and our people put out of work in order to enhance the standard of living of communist china and communist russia. ..
recently, the congress of the united states refused to vote military aid to assist the freedom fighters of the contras in nicaragua. i do not think it is in the best interest of the united states of america to permit the soviet union to establish a land base in the north american continent
here are excerpts from basic speeches delivered recently by candidates for the 1988 democratic presidential nomination:
reaganomics isn't economic theory, it's theft from our children, it's a felony against the future, and it has played the hard-working, taxpaying families of middle america for fools
we're not going to get our fiscal house in order with more voodoo economics. and we're not going to meet the challenges of the 1990s by building walls around america. we tried that 60 years ago and it gave us the worst depression in our history
we need more trade, not less. one and a quarter million southern workers depend on exports for their jobs. they know that if we're going to make america no. 1 again, we've got to do more than wave a fist at our foreign competitors; we've got to roll up our sleeves, go to work, and beat them
they deserve a president who knows how to balance a budget and mop up republican red ink _ and has done it. a president who knows how to build a strong economy _ and has done it. a president who has been tested in the fires of debt and deficit and hard economic times. a president with the strength, the skills and the values to take charge of our economic future and get our nation moving again. ..
it's going to take hard workers, not high-rollers, to get america moving again
and it'll take star schools, not star wars, to conquer the next american frontier
the world is changing; we must change with it _ or we'll be left behind. we must invest in research. we must invest in new ideas. and we must turn those new ideas into new products and new jobs for our citizens and new markets for america. ..
american workers know that we're not going to beat the japanese and our other competitors by sitting on the sidelines; we're not going to beat them by pitting group against group and region against region; we're not going to beat them by investing in a fantasy called star wars; and we're not going to beat them unless we've got someone in the white house who looks a little farther into the future than the next vote on contra aid. ..
there are no shortcuts to greatness for america. because the best america does not hide; it competes. the best america does not waste; it invests. the best america does not leave some of its citizens behind; it works for everyone
if americans want leadership to trim and then tend to things as they are, they will turn to the republicans. our purpose, and our appeal as democrats, has always been to serve as an instrument of change. ..
the central issue of this campaign is whether americans will regain control of our own destiny. in recent years, that control has been lost to foreign powers and private interests. ..
first, we lost much of our steel industry; now we are losing whole segments of the computer industry. first, we were told that free trade permitted our farmers to sell abroad; now they are being locked out of the european market. we devalue the dollar, hoping to sell our goods cheaper abroad _ and then trade barriers still bar the way _ and the trade deficit with japan roars on. ..
we refuse to accept the decline of america. we are tried to hearing from those who say it is inevitable ... that we can't stand up for america anymore. and we are determined that we can and will reassert this nation's rightful role of leadership in the world economy. ..
on the central economic issues of this campaign, there is hardly a dime's worth of difference between governor dukakis and senator gore. and while i may disagree with jesse jackson in a number of important areas, let me say in fairness that he is speaking to fundamental questions _ and he surely does have something to say about them
the gore-dukakis approach is to distract the voters from those fundamental questions _ to divert the campaign to tactics, or drown it in generalities. ..
this approach is a political danger for democrats; the stale and standard rhetoric of a careful, conventional politics will never bring us back the voters we need for victory
but the true danger is to the nation. we can no longer afford to ignore the larger forces that could constrict our economy and our future. we have to revive america's productive might. ..
i am not willing to see america fall behind. i do not doubt the energy, the capacity, the strength or the talent of the american people. and i am certain that if they are given the chance, this nation can and will continue to lead the world
we want a nominee who doesn't just appeal to a collection of narrow interest agendas. we want a nominee who speaks common sense to voters at the grass roots level. ..
and my campaign is about bringing the democratic party back to the grass roots level. i want to put the white house back on the side of the average working men and women in this country. ..
voters ... have asked themselves: is the democratic party straying from its traditions? well, our traditions are economic growth, jobs, prosperity, social progress with a movement toward social justice and a strong, intelligent role for this country in the world
now that's the tradition of franklin roosevelt, harry truman and john kennedy. ... that's the approach that i'm taking in my campaign. ..
this is a time for fundamental change in america
we are facing a storm on the horizon. we must understand it clearly. ... we must become one nation, united in clearly recognizing that in order to compete more effectively overseas we have to batten down the hatches and make some major changes in this nation. ..
we have to create the best schools in the world. ... i look at children in all the states around this nation where i compete. their eyes are just as bright, their minds are just as sharp as those of the children of any nation on the face of this earth
are we to be satisfied that by the time children graduate from high school in america, on average they are two full grade levels behind their counterparts in other nations? are we going to allow that to continue? ..
it's time we had a president of the united states who didn't act the way ronald reagan does and every time a decision comes up ask, ``what is going to best for the executives in the board room?''
it's time we asked the democratic question, ``what's best for the guy on the assembly line, the guy on the farm, the woman behind the word processor, the woman behind the typewriter. ..
this is the challenge. ... we know from experience that if we follow policies that are designed to help the person at the grass roots level, ... if we consistently have the guts and fortitude and leadership and courage to stand by them and follow policies to benefit them, then in the long run that is going to lift the prospects of the entire nation
for more than a decade i've worked with others to create ideas that reform our public policies and systems. many of our society's institutions require reform. but reform is a threatening notion. it threatens long-established arrangements among individuals and institutions and powerful positions that some have fought long and hard to win
reform cannot be imposed from the top down, especially against a hostile institution. it must percolate from the bottom up. that means that ordinary people must provide the fuel for change. soldiers, nurses, teachers, workers are the key to reform. and that reform can only begin when people begin to think differently
we have to think differently about our relationships with the soviets and how we engage them in a new and different world
we have to think differently about how we provide better medical care and for whom we should provide
we have to think differently about how we educate our young people and what kind of education we are providing
we have to think differently about how we manufacture goods as well as what kind of products we ought to be making
we must raise non-traditional, non-conventional questions in this election year because the united states has been desperately trying to preserve an elusive status quo for 25 years while an often brutally contrary world prevents it. ..
resistance to reform and change is resistance to a new generation and a new way of thinking, and the resistance to me and my candidacy is in large part a resistance to a new generational understanding of a world where the old arrangements and old rules no longer work
but it's not simply an age question, it's an attitudinal divide. ..
although most in this race are of the same generation, there are real differences in outlook and attitude among the candidates. ..
this campaign _ like every other presidential campaign _ is about power, who will serve in the most powerful office on earth. but it's also about who has the power to elect our national leader
traditional politics says that party leaders, pundits and political experts should decide who the candidates will be. but reform politics, new politics, my politics say let's let the people decide
we gather here in this new south with new challenges. every generation has faced the challenge of securing for all citizens equal protection under the law, to have the umbrella of law broadened so when the rains do fall, all are protected
in 1960, four students in greensboro, at a&amp;t, (north carolina a&amp;t state university, jackson's alma mater) went to woolworth's lunch counter. they sat in to get hamburgers; they got handcuffs. they were challenged. they were arrested. they chose dignity even over degrees. they heard the call of their day
throughout that period, young america did not just rest in false comforts, or retreat through drugs ... young americans led the way, and assumed a front-line position. it's not enough for you to vote for me, young americans. you must register, vote, run for office, win and make a difference
things will not change automatically and inevitably. they will change because you work to make them change. you must make it happen. ..
we do have a public accommodations bill, and that's progress. we do have the right to vote, and that's progress. we do have open housing, and that's progress. we do have equal access to education, and that's progress. but then there is the unfinished business of economic justice and world peace
let us not forget the garbage workers in memphis had civil rights, had the right to vote. when they came home from work ... they did not have enough money to pay their basic family bills. the agenda there was economic justice for working people who did not want welfare, didn't want workfare, they wanted to get paid for working. the agenda was economic justice. they were abandoned by law. ..
now we need the law to raise the minimum wage ... to establish a national health care plan for the american people. we need to change the law and choose head start and day care over jail care and welfare. ..
we the people must come together. ... we must struggle to raise the standard of living for working people. stop drugs from coming in. stop jobs from going out
the challenge was to make certain that no one with a sheet and a hood would lynch us. today's challenge ... is not the rope, it's dope. coke. crack. heroin. pcp. every gain we ever made is threatened by drugs
it's a cop-out to just say to children, `just say no to drugs.' ... children do not buy $150 billion worth of drugs. ... children do not grow the drugs, do not run the cartels
the money involved in drug smuggling is corrupting whole governments. ... we must stop the flow of drugs into our country. it's corrupting our society. if elected, i will ... cut the supply of drugs. but you the people must cut the demand for drugs
we have to see that jobs are there for people, good jobs, primarily through the private sector
one of the things we have to do is deal with those who have fallen through the cracks
we have something in our society called the underclass. some people don't like the use of the term, but it is real, it is there. there is no sense fooling ourselves
we ought to give the people an opportunity. ... we can do better as a nation. we're not just talking statistics. ... we're talking about people
we're talking about the young man ... desperate for a job ... the man whose business has failed (who) asked the question, ``does anyone care?'' only he really wasn't asking a question. he was really saying, ``no one cares.''
i want a government that cares. i want a government that's going to fight for opportunities for our people and stand up for the less-fortunate
education has to receive much greater attention. ... one of things that has been happening is that there has been a substantial shift away from grants to loans
now, there are problems with that. one of the problems is that sometimes two of you who have loans fall in love and decide to get married. and that means that you have to postpone that dream of a family and a home
when you postpone that dream of a home you know what happens, among other things? for the lumber industry in the state of washington, all kinds of other things happen. it's also more costly for the federal government, believe it or not, than grants, because we have to subsidize interest for a great many years. and we have to pay for defaults. ..
it also distorts what people do. ... you have to make a decision to handle those loans. do you become an elementary school teacher? or do you become a lawyer. ... our society needs a great many more good elementary school teachers today than we need lawyers. ...
long-term care. ... let's talk about your grandparents, your parents. we have to take care of them if they need long-term residential care. ... no other major industrial society on the face of the earth doesn't take care of parents and grandparents when they need most any care. can we do it? of course we can do it
the government's chief barometer of future economic activity fell again in january, but an upward revision in december has eased some economists' fears that the nation was headed for a recession
the commerce department said tuesday its index of leading economic indicators dropped 0.6 percent in january. analysts discounted the sharp decline and instead focused on a revision that changed the index's showing in december from a 0.2 percent decline to a 0.3 percent rise
widespread weakness in all sectors of the building industry sent construction spending down 2.9 percent in january, the biggest decline in 10 months, the government says
the commerce department said tuesday that construction spending fell to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of $395.2 billion in january following a revised 0.4 percent advance in december
