j.p. stevens &amp; co., months ago a rumored takeover target, now finds itself fielding three rival offers from a management-led group, industry competitor west point-pepperell inc. and an undisclosed suitor
west point-pepperell said tuesday it had offered to pay $56 a share for stevens, or about $867 million, in a negotiated buyout
the textile company actually had delivered its offer to stevens late monday
on tuesday, the j.p. stevens management group led by chairman whitney stevens said it was increasing its own outstanding leveraged buyout offer to $55 a share in cash and securities, or about $850 million
stevens also disclosed it had received a third, unidentified offer
stevens stock jumped $6.25 a share to $54.50 tuesday on the new york stock exchange. west point-pepperell was unchanged at $30.50 a share
the management group offered to pay $40 in cash and $15 in securities for each of stevens' 15.5 million common shares outstanding in a leveraged buyout
the group, led by the fifth generation member of the family that founded stevens in 1813, initially offered on feb. 8 to pay a total of $43 a share in cash and securities, or about $666.5 million
west point said its $56 a share cash offer was not conditioned on the availability of financing and indicated it was considering the sale of certain stevens assets to avoid antitrust concerns
stevens indicated in a news release that its outside directors were reviewing the revised management proposal and had authorized the company's financial advisers to study the two outside proposals
jim franklin, a spokesman for stevens, declined to comment beyond the news release
a number of industry experts had predicted higher offers would emerge following the management group's initial offer, which widely was viewed as too low
stevens is one of the nation's biggest textile producers, concentrating on home fashion textiles such as sheets, towels and carpets under the brand names ralph lauren, laura ashley and pierre cardin. the company also makes automotive products and industrial fabrics
west point, based in west point, ga., also is a major household fabrics maker, producing brands such a arrow, martex, lady pepperell, burberry's and cabin crafts
joseph l. lanier jr., chairman of west point-pepperell, said an acquisition of stevens would be a natural step in his company's shift toward consumer goods and away from commodity textiles, which have lower profit margins and suffer from intense foreign competition
west point-pepperell acquired cluett-peabody &amp; co. in 1986 as part of the strategy
stevens undertook a similar strategy beginning in 1984, moving out of apparel fabrics and shifting its manufacturing to home textiles such as sheets and towels. the success of that effort is one factor that made stevens an attractive takeover target
that's one of the great strengths of j.p. stevens,'' lanier said in an interview. ``it's playing to our strength as we see it.''
during the quarter ended jan. 30, stevens posted an after-tax profit of $12.9 million, up from $11.9 million a year earlier. sales rose to $381.48 million from $361.67 million a year earlier
in the fiscal year ended oct. 31, stevens earned $56 million on sales of $1.6 billion. this compared with a profit of $53.7 million on revenue of $1.68 billion in 1986
west point-pepperell reported a profit of $25.5 million on revenue of $480.9 million for the fiscal first quarter, which ended dec. 26. that was up from $20.9 million in profit and $422.7 million in revenue during a year earlier
stevens said the securities portion of the management group's offer would include $10 in market value of junior subordinated debentures and $5 market value of preferred stock paying a dividend in cash or additional shares. heats up</head>
apollo computer inc. got a key jump on its competitors by developing a $70,000 desktop ``personal supercomputer'' the company says is faster than anything else in the market, industry analysts said
two other companies also announced new supercomputers tuesday, marking what promises to be a period of fierce competition among makers of sophisticated supercomputers used by scientists and engineers
this seems to be the year for the so-called `personal supercomputer,''' said gary p. smaby, who follows the industry for piper, jaffray &amp; hopwood in minneapolis. ``i think it's going to be an interesting horse race.''
apollo said it was producing a workstation for scientists and engineers with supercomputer power that outperforms anything in its price range of $69,900 to $130,000
analysts said the domain series 10000 returns the chelmsford, mass.-based company to the forefront of the highly competitive field of small, powerful workstations that combine extremely rapid ``number cruching'' with three-dimensional graphics
we think that this definitely positions them as the performance leader to beat in the new graphics supercomputing market,'' said david burdick, an analyst with dataquest inc. of san jose, calif
for a company that has been stuck in the saragasso sea in the past couple of years, it is very siginificant'' said donald bellomy of international data corp. in framingham, mass. ``they had been the industry leaders in every aspect and had fallen behind in every aspect.''
ardent computer corp., a sunnyvale, calif.-based start-up, announced its first product tuesday, a graphics supercomputer in about the same price and performance range as apollo's
convex computer corp. of richardson, texas, aiming at a pricier segment of the market, unveiled a more powerful new line of mini-supercomputers it hopes will cut into cray research inc.'s domination of that market
another recent start-up, stellar computer inc. of newton, mass., is expected to announce a similar graphics supercomputer in two weeks, and analysts anticipate a half-dozen more to follow
scientists and engineers are making pretty interesting use of these computers,'' smaby said. ``the question is how big a market is there for a $100,000 single-user computer.''
they're all vying for market share leadership in one niche or another and not all of them are going to come out with gold medals,'' he said
apollo, which pioneered workstations in 1980, said at a boston news conference that the new model speeds up complex numerical computations and its four-processor model allows several different programs to run simultaneously
ardent said its graphics supercomputer would range in price from $79,000 for a one-processor model to $150,000 for a four-processor model that will be available later this year
ardent, founded in 1985, is run by two prominent figures in the computer industry: allen h. michels, the president and chief executive, who previously founded convergent technologies, and c. gordon bell, the vice president of research, engineering and development, who did pioneering work in a 23-year career at digital equipment corp
but analysts agree apollo's 50,000 workstations and 1,800 software packages already on the market give it a competitive advantage. the company said it will begin selling the models in the third quarter this year and announce improved graphics system for the workstation later this year
convex computer introduced a line of six mini-supercomputers that range in power up to the level of conventional supercomputers. in san francisco, convex said it invented a new kind of parallel processing for its bigger models that keeps processors from being idle by allocating work among them efficiently
convex's new computers range in price from $275,000 to $1.3 million and are up to 10 times as powerful as its current models. convex claimed the most powerful model, the c240, is faster than cray research inc.'s x-mp 14, which costs $5.5 million
gaf corp. shareholders will have the chance to vote on a sweetened $1.4 billion leveraged buyout offer from a group led by chairman samuel j. heyman, but may get competing offers to consider
gaf's board of directors agreed tuesday to submit the offer to shareholders ``without endorsement,'' after the group increased its bid from a previous $1.35 billion cash and securities package
the company also instructed its financial adviser to seek out other potential purchasers, and left itself the option of accepting any competing, superior offer
the heyman group on tuesday proposed to pay $46 in cash and junior securities with a face value of $6.50 for each of gaf's 27.7 million outstanding common shares
in december, the heyman group offered $1.35 billion, or $40 in cash and $8.50 in securities per share
that offer was a downward revision from its initial $2.3 billion offer, made in september, of $64 in cash and $2.50 face value in debt securities. heyman revised the initial proposal due to rising interest rates stemming from unsettled conditions in the market for high-yield ``junk bonds'' following the october stock market crash
in order for shareholders to vote on the latest buyout offer, they first first vote on an amendment to the company charter. the amendment would allow shareholders to act in place of the board in considering a merger offer, as the heyman-led proposal has been presented
a special committee of the board of directors had rejected the initial $64-a-share proposal as inadequate. gaf said it had decided to let stockholders decide based on the favorable opinion of the offer by salomon brothers inc., the committee's financial adviser
the committee also instructed salomon to solicit other possible purchasers, gaf said. the committee said that if it receives an ``economically superior alternative proposal'' for gaf, it could cancel its agreement with the buyout group
we think the price is a fare and full price,'' heyman said. ``it's seven times the price of the stock only four years ago.''
gaf also said it had reached tentative settlements of lawsuits brought in connection with the buyout offer
gaf stock rose 25 cents to $50.25 a share tuesday on the new york stock exchange
heyman, who wrested control of gaf in 1983 after a bitter proxy fight to oust former chairman jesse werner, has said that taking gaf private would give the company more leeway to pursue acquisitions without having to worry about short-term shareholder value
since taking over gaf, heyman has led the company on unsuccessful but profitable attempted takeovers of union carbide corp. and borg-warner corp
heyman owns 2.8 million shares of gaf, or about 10 percent of its outstanding stock
ten years ago a monterrey company promoting membership at a new pacific coast resort hotel offered a special deal: ``buy now and your 10-year lease will be renewed at the same price in 1988.''
but inflation and the devaluation of the peso since then have made the deal even more special than anyone anticipated: the average 70,000 peso price for the leases in 1978, worth the equivalent of $3,182 back then, now equals just $30
hotel clients in this northern industrial city are complaining that the company is balking at renewing the time-sharing leases at the cheaper price
they estimate that about 1,000 people throughout mexico paid an average of 70,000 pesos in 1978 to spend one week each year at the luxury hotel club maeva in manzanillo in the pacific coastal state of colima
the hotel is run by casolar, the tourism division of the huge monterrey-based alfa conglomerate
alfa fell into a severe economic crisis along with the rest of mexico in 1982 and has seen the value of mexico's currency plunge from 22 pesos to the dollar in 1978 to 2,350 to the dollar now
the peso devaluation has made the 70,000-peso fee equal to $30, about the price of dinner for two in a nice restaurant. but clients here say they took the gamble a decade ago when they invested in a hotel complex that was under construction
we know it's very little money now. but, remember, nothing was built at the time. it was an enormous risk,'' said concepcion rodriguez de salazar, who sold herself one of the contracts 10 years ago when she worked as a casolar sales representative
her son, monterrey lawyer jorge salazar, says casolar now wants to charge 10 million pesos _ $4,255 _ to renew the contract. salazar is handling the complaints for about 60 hotel clients here
the company didn't have any idea that things were going to turn out as they did. but the people that bought there didn't expect the company to decide whether or not it was going to comply,'' salazar said
martha barrios of casolar said on monday and tuesday that officials involved in the contract dispute were in meetings or out of town and not available for comment
salazar said in a telephone interview late monday that his clients want him to negotiate with casolar, but he has been unable to locate company officials
these people had to sacrifice to pay the fee 10 years ago, but they thought they'd get 20 years of vacations,'' salazar said
he said the peso-dollar equivalent had nothing to do with the written contract. the renewal offer was in the contract as well as the company's advertising, he said
we don't earn dollars or spend dollars or do business in dollars,'' he said. ``we still have faith in what a contract says.'' 
kaisertech ltd. has taken the unusual step of suing its own chairman of the board, in an attempt to recover profits made from his short-term dealings in the aluminum company's stock
the suit filed tuesday against alan e. clore came a day after the reclusive british investor agreed to sell his 27 percent stake in kaisertech to texas oilman charles hurwitz, a move that appeared to irritate kaisertech officials and signaled management turbulence at the oakland, calif.-based company
clore acquired his position at kaisertech after a lengthy takeover struggle last year. hurwitz's intentions toward kaisertech remain unclear
asked if it was considered unusual that a company would sue its own chairman, kaisertech spokesman robert w. irelan said: ``it's the first time we've done it.''
kaisertech stated that its suit filed in a manhattan federal court resulted from clore's disclosures in a securities and exchange commission filing on monday about his sale of stock to a hurwitz-controlled company, los angeles-based maxxam group inc
kaisertech contended the sec disclosures showed clore and his affiliates made about $4 million in undisclosed profits via so-called ``short-swing trading'' _ trading done within a six-month period _ of kaisertech stock
under federal securities law, a company or its stockholders are entitled to recover such profits from a director or officer who engages in short-swing trading
clore, who usually resides in switzerland, could not be reached for comment on the lawsuit, which was part of a rapid series of events concerning kaisertech stock
in los angeles, the investment firm jefferies &amp; co. said it was selling 1.39 million shares of kaisertech stock to maxxam for $16.68 million or $12 a share
combined with the 6.2 million shares acquired from clore, plus an option to buy his 8.2 million convertible preferred kaisertech shares, acquisition of jefferies' stake would give maxxam about one-third of kaisertech's approximately 45 million shares outstanding
but wall street's reaction indicated skepticism about a possible takeover move. in composite new york stock exchange trading, kaisertech fell 12{ cents a share to $11.75, after rising $1.12{ in the previous session
kaisertech had stated monday it would have preferred that clore had sold his stock to a broader range of investors, reflecting concern about what maxxam intended to do with its stake. maxxam officials said it was premature to speculate on whether the comapny would attempt to acquire more kaisertech shares
clore's maneuvering to sell his kaisertech shares came against a background of heavy pressure on him to cut losses suffered in the october stock market crash
if clore hadn't found a buyer by a monday deadline, he could have faced default on loans he had obtained by using kaiser stock as collateral. after the stock plunged in october, lenders wanted repayment
his sale of stock came as the company was rebounding from six straight years of losses. kaiser has sold its chemical, oil and gas businesses, slashed debt and concentrated on its core aluminum business. risks</head>
the lorillard inc. tobacco company sought to downplay discounts that its insurance company affiliate was considering offering to non-smokers several years ago, according to evidence in a lawsuit against three cigarette makers
the contention was made tuesday as a federal jury heard testimony and read documents that allegedly show the tobacco industry sought to suppress information on the health dangers of smoking
the suit filed by antonio cipollone of lakehurst, claims lorillard, philip morris co. and liggett group inc., are liable for the lung cancer death of his wife rose, a 40-year smoker
cipollone alleges the companies failed to do enough research on cigarettes, did not reveal what they did know, failed to warn the public of health dangers and did not put a safer product on the market
one document released tuesday, dated march 3, 1980, was written by chicago-based cna insurance co. officials and discussed a recommendation for non-smoker discounts, according to marc z. edell, cipollone's attorney
at the time, cna was owned by loew's theatres inc., which also owned lorillard. loew's has since sold the tobacco company
it is recognized that the introduction of non-smokers discount could prove embarrassing'' to loew's and lorillard, the memo stated. in order to minimize the potential for embarrassment, it suggested that cna and lorillard jointly prepare a carefully constructed statement saying the discount ``in no way supports or refutes the contention that smoking causes health defects.''
cna should further refrain from advertising or otherwise promoting non-smoker discounts,'' it continued
the issue also was discussed in a letter dated nov. 5, 1979, from lorillard senior vice president and general counsel, arthur j. stevens, to cna chairman edward j. noha
stevens wrote that when the cigarette manufacturing trade group, the tobacco insitute, heard of allstate insurance co.'s plan to offer a non-smoker discount the institute sought help from cna ``in an effort to perhaps dissuade allstate from that course of action by supplying background data.''
lorillard spokesman chuck wall said lorillard and the institute did nothing improper but merely were trying to counteract anti-cigarette propaganda
according to another document released tuesday, a tobacco institute official stated in 1972 that the industry's defense against cigarette critics included ``creating doubt about the health charge without actually denying it.''
the internal memorandum describes the ``three major fronts'' _ litigation, politics and public opinion _ where the tobacco companies had fought to defend itself
the ``brilliantly conceived and executed'' strategy, used in all three areas, helped ``win important battles,'' said the memo
however, ``it is only fair to say that it is not _ nor was it intended to be _ a vehicle for victory,'' said the may 1, 1972 memo from fred panzer to horace r. kornegay, president of the tobacco institute
wall identified panzer as an institute vice president
the document says the industry had followed a ``holding strategy, consisting of:
_creating doubt about the health charge without actually denying it;
_advocating the public's right to smoke, without actually urging them to take up the practice;
_encouraging objective scientific research as the only way to resolve the question of health hazard.''
general motors corp.'s plastic-body, mid-engine pontiac fiero and the workers who make it have become the first victims of slumping popularity for sporty two-seaters
michael losh, pontiac's general manager, said tuesday gm will stop making the fiero after the 1988 model and will close indefinitely the single fiero plant here sometime this summer, idling 1,109 workers
the whole market's dead,'' said industry analyst chris cedergren of j.d. power and associates, blaming high insurance rates for a 30 percent drop in overall two-seater sales during 1987
the slump has not spared japanese automakers, who report slow sales of cars such as the sporty toyota mr2 and the mazda rx7, or europeans, whose victims include four-cylinder porsches
in addition to flagging sales, fiero had suffered problems that included frequent engine fires, which prompted gm to recall the entire 1984 mode production run late last year. but losh and cedergren suggested the market killed the fiero
we have seen a switch away from the high volumes of people who were willing to buy two-seat cars with limited luggage capacity,'' losh said. ``we led the world into this (market) segment and we may lead a piece of the world out of it.''
fiero sales peaked at 101,720 cars in 1984 and fell to 47,156 in 1987. sales for the 1988 model year, which began oct. 1, are less than 10,000, 41 below the same point in the 1987 model year
but before it died, losh said, the fiero helped create a new, performance-oriented image for pontiac. he refused to speculate on whether the fiero plant might reopen to build a new pontiac or gm product
union and city officials said they were surprised by the fiero decision despite the car's poor sales. when the fiero is gone, no pontiacs will be built in pontiac
uaw local 653 president harold cox said his plant was one of the first at gm to accept japanese-style team organization of workers under a contract that allowed the previously closed plant to reopen in 1983 to make the fiero
we're going to continue to try to persuade general motors to try to put something in there,'' cox said. ``it's a slap in our face that they rewarded us this way.''
gm already has closed a foundry, another car assembly plant, a heavy-duty truck plant and a bus plant in pontiac and had cut production at the fiero plant several times, putting more than 1,200 other fiero workers on layoff
dealers said they also were surprised by the announcement and some expressed disappointment
we don't have anything else in my opinion that would fit in that category,'' said buzz sawyers, owner of sawyers pontiac in lansing. ``it's like a cheap corvette.''
pontiac spokesman reginald harris said gm will make sure parts are available for the fiero into the future
gm's contract with the united auto workers union forbids permanent plant closings that were not announced before the contract was signed last fall, but permits laying off workers if sales slow
the fiero plant is the third gm has decided to idle since then. the first, in framingham, mass., will return to production in may. the second, in kansas city, mo., will shut down april 15, idling 1,600 workers
usg corp., a leading producer of building materials, has urged shareholders to resist a $1.9 billion tender offer from a partnership led by two texas oilmen
the $42-a-share offer for about 21.5 million shares of usg stock was unveiled tuesday by desert partners lp, which is headed by jack e. brown and cyril wagner jr
desert partners already owns about 9.9 percent or 5.08 million of usg's approximately 50.8 million shares outstanding
after the tender offer was announced, usg issued a statement asking shareholders to hold onto their stock until the board had a chance to act on the matter
the company has stated repeatedly that it wants to remain independent. lasat week usg rejected the partnership's lateset takeover proposal, also valued at $42 a share
in a separate filing with the securities and exchange commission, desert partners said it would seek to elect six directors to usg's 15-member board at the company's annual meeting in may
desert partners said wells fargo bank had pledged $500 million in financing for the offer and would attempt to arrange $525 million more in financing from other banks
wall street analysts have speculated that wagner and brown aren't interested in acquiring usg but want to boost the value of their stake, purchased last year for about $44.30 a share for an earlier takeover attempt that fizzled
in recent weeks usg stock had been trading around $28 a share, but the price started rising when rumors surfaced late last month that wagner and brown would make another run at the company
usg rose $2.75 to $40.12{ on the new york stock exchange tuesday
based in chicago, usg is a leading producer of gypsum and building materials, with about 100 plants nationwide
belgium's central bank on wednesday announced cuts in two key interest rates to reflect the current strength of the belgian franc and international trends
the belgian national bank said it will lower the discount rate to 6.5 percent from 6.75 percent and the lombard rate to 6.75 percent from 7 percent, effective thursday
the discount rate is the interest the central bank charges to member banks. the lombard rate is interest charged on central bank loans that use securities as collateral
the bank said in a statement the decision was made ``in recognition of recent rate cuts in the domestic and international money markets'' and due to the stability of the belgian franc
the bank last cut its lombard and discount rates on january 28
the three-month money market rate, the single-most important leading rate on the belgian market, also has been cut five times since the beginning of the year
foreign exchange dealers in brussels said the franc had not registered any noticeable reaction to the news
south korea's trade surplus more than tripled in february from a year earlier on the strength of exports, the government reported wednesday
the trade and industry ministry said last month's surplus rose to $524 million from $158 million in 1987. that brought the surplus for the first two months of this year to $810 million from $683 million last year, it said
exports in february rose 41 percent to $4.1 billion from, while imports grew 30 percent to $3.57 billion
the ministry did not provide a breakdown by country
during 1987, south korea posted a trade surplus of $6.26 billion
the teamsters union is urging northwest airlines' 6,700 flight attendants to use whatever measures they can to slow their performance without breaking the law or company rules
at this time we want to keep the company confused and very busy,'' said a recorded message that answered a union telephone tuesday
the recording urged tactics that included filing paperwork on each piece of broken equipment at each stop during a flight and slowing down everyday procedures the flight attendants have learned to shorten
what they're doing is not against regulations,'' said jeff musto, a spokesman for teamsters local 2747. ``it's just following the rules.''
the flight attendants, who are working without a contract, threatened to strike at 11:01 p.m. last friday, but no job actions have been taken against the company, said william wren, a northwest spokesman
talks broke off at dawn saturday, and no further negotiations were scheduled, spokesmen for both sides said
terry erskine, northwest's vice president for law and labor relations, said monday an unusually high number of flight attendants called in sick over the weekend. but he attributed the absences to attendants' fears they would be stranded by a strike, not to orders from the union
we're winding down operations here today, letting the dust settle for the time being,'' said musto. ``there's still a possibility of a strike and we're free to strike at any time,'' musto added
the main stumbling block to a new contract is a company proposal to delay the promotion of b-scale workers to the higher-paid a-scale bracket, musto and wren said
all northwest flight attendants were paid under one scale before a 1982 contract created the b-scale, musto said, while all employees hired since then have started as b-scale employees at rates of pay lower than the old system
the 1982 contract called for b-scale employees to jump to a-scale levels in their sixth year of employment, but the current company proposal would extend that wait until the ninth year of employment, musto said
such an extension would mean a loss off $16,776 over the three years for the average b-scale flight attendant, musto said
a new jersey company is offering to ``inoculate'' computers against ``viruses,'' or rogue programs that are designed to spread from computer to computer and damage data the computers store
the viralarm system was announced tuesday by officials of lasertrieve inc. of metuchen, n.j., during a microsoft corp. conference on a data-storage device known as cd-rom, short for compact disk, read-only memory
a statement issued by lasertrieve said that although the newer cd-rom disks are impervious to corruption because information on them cannot be altered, many computer users are concerned about protecting programs on hard disks or on conventional floppy diskettes
viruses are creating a growing fear among computer owners and users. authorities in israel recently announced the detection of a virus that, if left to spread unchecked, could have wiped out memory banks and disabled computers throughout the country on a given date
previous ``anti-viral'' programs only drew attention to changes, noted the size of a program or monitored the dates of program changes, and all were ``easily fooled by sophisticated viruses,'' the statement said
viralarm consists of a special program to protect another program, creating a software barrier
before anyone can use the protected program, viralarm checks to determine whether the program has been altered since it was inoculated. if there has been any change, viralarm then blocks use of the altered program, notifies the user and suggests a backup copy of the program be substituted
the protection is available for individual personal computers and works for most of the operating systems now available, the lasertrieve statement said. ^new home sales plunge in january</head>
sales of new homes plunged 9 percent in january, pushing the level of sales activity to its lowest point since the end of the last recession, the government reported today
the commerce department said that sales dropped to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 535,000 units. it was the third consecutive monthly decline and left sales 26 percent below where they were a year ago
the january decline followed decreases of 6.8 percent in december and 3.4 percent in november as the housing industry continued to be the sector of the economy that has been hardest hit since the october collapse of stock prices
consumers, worried about the future following the record 508-point drop in stock prices, stopped looking for new homes, analysts believe
housing is often the economic sector which turns down first before the start of a new recession. but despite the weakness in recent months, many economists remain hopeful that recent declines in mortgage rates will spur a rebound in sales and construction in the months ahead
if the rebound doesn't occur, then concerns about a possible recession this year could increase
in another weak economic report, the government said today that orders to u.s. factories for manufactured goods fell 0.6 percent in january, the first decline since a 1.4 percent drop last august
however, analysts said the january setback was not as weak as it appeared because it mainly reflected a huge swing in orders for aircraft, which had helped push factory orders up 2 percent in december
the 9 percent decline in new home sales in january was the steppest decline since a 10.9 percent drop last may. it left sales at the lowest annual rate since december 1982, when the last recession was ending
the big sales decline was accompanied by a sharp rise in prices, with the median, or mid-point price of a home climbing 9.7 percent to $120,000
the average price of a home rose to $149,000, up 10.5 percent from december. economists said such a big price surge is not uncommon during a period of falling sales because fewer, but higher-priced homes skew the averages
the sales decline was led by a 24.4 percent drop in sales in the south. sales were down 13.7 percent in the midwest. sales actually rose 23 percent in the northeast, a rebound from a 52.9 percent drop the month before. sales were up 0.6 percent in the west
the stock market showed a broad gain today, resuming its recent rally after a pause on tuesday
the dow jones average of 30 industrials rose 6.96 to 2,077.42 in the first half hour
gainers outnumbered losers by nearly 5 to 2 in the overall tally of new york stock exchange-listed issues, with 737 up, 309 down and 462 unchanged
volume on the big board came to 35.34 million shares as of 10 a.m. on wall street
analysts said the market was still benefiting from spreading confidence that a recession can be avoided despite the market's crash last autumn
one theoretical warning signal of a business slump was lifted tuesday, when the commerce department issued new figures on its index of leading economic indicators
with an upward revision of the december figure for the index from a decline to a gain, it no longer showed a string of three consecutive lower readings
brokers also noted that enthusiasm for stocks has been buoyed by a brisk pace of takeover activity
j.p. stevens rose 1{ to 56 in early trading today. west point-pepperell made a bid of $56 a share for the company tuesday, in competition with a management-led group that is seeking to buy it out
the nyse's composite index of all its listed common stocks added .58 to 150.76. at the american stock exchange, the market value index was up .90 at 289.81
on tuesday the dow jones industrial average lost 1.16 points to 2,070.46
declining issues outnumbered advances by 7 to 6 on the nyse, with 811 issues down, 696 up and 457 unchanged. big board volume totaled 199.99 million shares, against 236.05 million in the previous session
january new-home sales hit the lowest point since the last recession and factory orders fell for the first time in four months, the government said today in reports suggesting the economy weakened after the october stock crash
the commerce department said sales of new homes plunged 9 percent in january to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 535,000 units, the third straight monthly decline that left sales 26 percent below year-earlier levels
the report reflected a significant downturn in the housing industry, the area of the economy believed hardest hit since the collapse in stock prices five months ago. analysts believe many homebuyers stopped looking after the collapse, fearing economic uncertainty in months ahead
housing is often the economic sector that declines first before the start of a new recession. despite the weakness, however, many economists remain hopeful that recent declines in mortgage rates will spur a sales rebound
the commerce department also said orders to u.s. factories fell 0.6 percent in january, the first decline since a 1.4 percent drop last august and another possible sign of post-crash economic weakness
but some analysts said the report was misleading because it reflected a huge swing in aircraft orders, which helped push factory orders up 2 percent in december
discounting the aircraft element, factory orders would have risen 0.8 percent in january, reflecting a higher demand for american manufactured goods caused partly by the weaker dollar, which makes them more affordable abroad
the reports today appeared to have no dampening effect on domestic financial markets, where early stock and bond prices rose
on tuesday, the markets wandered aimlessly after the release of other economic statistics that gave no clear signals
the commerce department said its chief barometer of future economic activity fell in january, although an upward revision of december's figure eased fears that the nation was headed for a recession
the department also said construction spending fell an unexpected 2.9 percent in january, the biggest decline in 10 months, evidence of weakness in all sectors of the building industry
the dow jones average of 30 industrial stocks fell 1.16 points to 2,070.46, slipping from the post-oct. 19 market crash high it had reached on monday. it was equally quiet in the credit markets, with the yield on the treasury's bellwether 30-year bond edging up to 8.35 percent from monday's 8.34 percent
the dollar was narrowly mixed in foreign exchange
is a frog livestock? people wouldn't leap to that conclusion, a farmer-lawmaker suggested wednesday, arguing that frog farmers need tax protection
farms for frogs should be exempt from local property taxes, just as are any premises used for any ``livestock,'' conservative michael colvin told a house of commons committee studying a local finance bill
according to the bill, livestock is defined as ``any mammal or bird kept for the production of food or wool, or for the purpose of its use in the farming of land.'' all other farm premises are also exempt from the taxes
fine, but where does the frog, an amphibian, fit in? asked colvin, who said his acquaintance with a frog farmer prompted him to raise the point
the definition of livestock is most unclear. times have changed in agriculture,'' he said, suggesting that the bill substitute ``creatures'' for ``livestock.''
it would be a sad day if any government started imposing a tax on frogs,'' said colvin
local government minister michael howard pointed out that words aren't everything under law. after all, he said, ``snails are covered by the exemption for fish farms.''
the stock market pushed ahead today, resuming its recent rally after a pause on tuesday
the dow jones average of 30 industrials, down 1.16 points tuesday, rose 15.42 to 2,085.88 by 11 a.m. today on wall street
gainers outnumbered losers by more than 2 to 1 in the overall tally of new york stock exchange-listed issues, with 857 up, 407 down and 469 unchanged
volume on the big board came to 80.39 million shares at midmorning
analysts said the market was still benefiting from spreading confidence that a recession can be avoided despite the market's crash last autumn
one theoretical warning signal of a business slump was lifted tuesday, when the commerce department issued new figures on its index of leading economic indicators
with an upward revision of the december figure for the index from a decline to a gain, it no longer showed a string of three consecutive lower readings
brokers also noted that enthusiasm for stocks has been buoyed by a brisk pace of takeover activity
