customers who pay hundreds of dollars on fine china expect perfect curlicues, flawless border lines and unblemished garlands
perfection can be achieved electronically on a computer screen, but that's not good enough for the designers at lenox
in an era in which computers influence the shape of cars, lay out balanced newspaper pages and even make a superstar out of max headroom, lenox still has old-fashioned ideas about its designs
every line, squiggle or tiny dot in the prototype design is laboriously drawn by hand after weeks of research
we start with a strategist ... who analyzes the marketplace,'' said thomas r. mcinerney, lenox's vice president of marketing
some recent new designs, for instance, have been focused toward young cosmopolitan consumers ``who are less traditional, a bit more urban,'' he said
once a direction has been established, we draw up a design brief ... and the design department then takes that direction.''
at lenox, a design team of 17 people sits down to brainstorm. eventually it comes down to a designer at a drawing board, a blank circle waiting to be embellished
lenox will not reveal the names of its designers, ``for competitive reasons,'' said lenox spokesman peter cheyney
but the director of the design department explains some facts, such as a source of inspiration
we have a large library with books on architectural style, furnishings, fabrics,'' he said. ``we have color services who are constantly bringing us up to date with predictions for this season's hot colors.''
computers, he said. ``are not for us here. a computer could be used to help with color separations or to work out the permutations of design, but it's more of a graphic tool.''
lenox designs ``are done all by hand,'' the design director said. ``in some instances, a computer can help with key outlines, but it really comes down to the eye. ... a computer will never substitute for a person here.''
every few weeks, the design team produces 30 to 60 patterns that are test-marketed. of that group, about six are selected for production
the design team works closely with lenox's sculptors to ensure that the design will fit on a plate
the design is also checked with the factory to see if we're doing something manufacturable,'' the design director said
lenox china is a division of lenox inc., which is a subsidiary of the brown-forman corp. of louisville, ky. sales figures for lenox china products are included in the company's overall ``home furnishings'' report, which also comprises lenox crystal products, figurines and specialty products, not all of which are produced in the united states
the home furnishings category listed 1987 sales of $194.2 million, compared to $173.9 million in 1986
in a year, lenox will introduce about 60 new patterns. once a design is approved, it moves to lenox's massive factory about 10 miles outside of atlantic city where it is printed on decals and applied by hand
the assembly line for the decal application process consists of all women who make small talk as they work
for some reason, guys don't like to do this tedious work,'' said dorothy hickey. in her 33 years with lenox, she has risen to a spot of such seniority that she is entrusted with decorating first lady nancy reagan's presidential china and giftware
on a wet plate that already has been fired twice, the women center the designs and smooth out air bubbles
sometimes it still has a tendency to slide, especially on the curvature of the plate,'' said anna pinkney, carefully positioning tiny flowers scattered across the china
several feet away, the process of applying gold and platinum borders is so exacting that workers are allowed to get up and stretch frequently
it requires steady hands and steady nerves,'' said a 23-year lenox veteran, henry wise, as he spun a wheel to draw the gold off the brush and onto the china
mrs. hickey is especially proud of lenox's design selections. she keeps volumes of every design that lenox has produced, from the popular ``autumn'' pattern that features tiny hand-painted fruits to the more current presidential line _ monroe, buchanan and mckinley
after seeing hundreds of patterns, mrs. hickey laughs when asked if she has a favorite
do you want to know what i picked for my own china? i have the plain solitaire,'' she said. ``i just couldn't make up my mind what i wanted.''
eastman kodak co. says it has sold $1.1 billion of 10-year notes, making it the largest investment-grade corporate debt issue in the united states
the previous record was held by occidental petroleum co., which issued $1 billion worth of investment-grade debentures two years ago, according to morgan stanley &amp; co., kodak's underwriters
kodak said it had planned to sell $750 million worth of bonds, but demand was so great the amount was increased to the record level
the 10-year bonds were priced at par and carry an interest rate of 9.125 percent. the issue will be used to either retire about $1 billion of short-term loans or help finance the company's recent $5.1 billion acquisition of sterling drug inc., kodak said
kodak has traditionally tried to stay out of the credit markets
in 1981 the company had borrowed less than $100 million, but its current debt totals $3.3 billion, with much of that increase coming in the last two years
grain and soybean futures opened mostly lower today on the chicago board of trade as the slightly stronger dollar gave a weaker tone to the entire market
soybeans also retreated on new estimates for large soybean harvests in south america, while wheat came under pressure from the agriculture department's revised auction program designed to lower surplus stocks
the usda held the first of three weekly auctions tuesday. auctions also are scheduled for this afternoon and friday
the usda's announcement tuesday that the soviet union had completed all of its outstanding purchases of u.s. wheat weighed on wheat futures prices, said richard loewy, an analyst in new york for prudential-bache securities inc
in corn, there was some farmer selling overnight, but it's mainly just being influenced by the other grains,'' loewy said
