delvalle fired military strongman manuel antonio noriega last thursday but the defense chief ignored the order and rallied his allies in the national assembly against the president. on friday, the assembly voted to oust delvalle and installed education minister manuel solis palma in his place
noriega has been indicted on drug smuggling charges by two florida grand juries and has been under heavy diplomatic, economic and political pressure by the reagan administration to step aside and open the way for civilian-led constitutional rule
among the banks listed by rogers which would be affected by the order are marine midland na, irving trust co., bankers trust co. and the republic national bank. he said all have headquarters in new york
every dime we can find is in those banks,'' rogers said. he added that any bank which ignores the order could be liable for whatever payments it makes to the current panamanian government
the coalition of opposition leaders believes that the panamanian government is facing a grave cash flow problem and is extremely vulnerable to economic pressure from the united states
unlike other countries, panama cannot cover its cash shortages by printing new money because the dollar is the national currency
sosa said international opposition to the new government was evident earlier this week when, he claimed, only eight ambassadors showed up for a state of the union address. from the western hemisphere, he said, only cuba and nicaragua attended
lawyers for the ousted president of panama, eric arturo delvalle, sued in federal court today to block a new york bank from turning over millions of dollars to military strongman gen. manuel noriega
a federal judge issued a temporary restraining order, blocking the republic national bank of new york from transferring an estimated $10 million
a hearing on the matter is slated for monday before u.s. district judge lloyd f. mcmahon
the lawsuit, filed at federal court in manhattan by lawyers from washington, seeks to establish title to the funds held in the republic national bank account and ``to prevent their transfer into the hands of a military dictatorship ... which has attempted to seize power and overthrow the lawful authorities of the republic of panama,'' according to court papers
noriega, the military leader of panama, was indicted on drug charges by two u.s. grand juries in florida feb. 4
devalle sought to dismiss noriega feb. 25, but was himself ousted by the national assembly the next day and has gone into hiding
on tuesday, devalle froze all panamanian assets outside the country, and the united states, which still recognizes devalle as the legitimate head of panama, has supported the action. general news wires</note>
thousands of farmers wrestling with massive debts or being forced out of business may get another chance under new loan rules being drawn up by the federal farmers home administration, the agriculture department agency said today
joe o'neill, an fmha spokesman, said the new rules probably will be ready by june. in many cases, over-burdened borrowers could have much of their debt written off, trimmed back to reflect their assets in hopes of keeping them in business
however, o'neill said he had no estimate of how much debt the fmha might write off under the new rules
there's just no way of knowing,'' o'neill said. ``it'll be each individual case all the way through.''
at the end of last fiscal year on sept. 30, he said, 261,291 fmha borrowers owed the agency about $26 billion. of that, 127,671 were delinquent, owing $6.6 billion, including principal and interest
new rules governing how the agency deals with farmers who owe it money could help prevent 100,000 farms from going under, the new york times reported today, quoting fmha officials in washington. agency officials also said thousands of farmers who went bankrupt over the past 10 years could find themselves back in operation
the new rules are a result of a bill passed by congress in december calling on the fmha, an agency that serves as a ``lender of last resort'' for the nation's farmers, to go easier on farmers who are behind in their payments
the new law requires the agency to do whatever possible to restructure loans in order to keep fmha borrowers in business
our attitude is going to be different,'' said fmha administrator vance l. clark. ``we want to make the new act work, and we're going to have a lot of room to maneuver to restructure these loans.''
lynn hayes, an attorney with the farmers legal action group in st. paul, minn., said, ``i'm thrilled they are apparently taking this legislation seriously and are trying to make it work.''
the new regulations would enable debt-burdened farmers to stay in business through a number of loan restructuring options. according to agency officials, farmers would be offered the opportunity to pay off loans at a lower rate of interest over a longer period of time
as a last resort, the agency could write off debts in excess of a borrower's assets, o'neill said. for example, if a farmer's assets were $150,000 and debts totaled $500,000, the write-off could be as much as $350,000 if the fmha determined the farmer could handle the remainder by staying in business
it makes sense, then, to keep that person in business and write off the difference between what they owe and their assets _ if the government stands a chance of retrieving more by keeping that farmer going,'' o'neill said. picks up 5th graf pvs, legislation sponsored; also running on general news wires.</note>
members of the senate banking committee failed to unravel a tangled three-way dispute this morning that has blocked legislation to repeal the depression-era law separating commercial banking and the securities industry
committee members, after meeting more than two hours behind closed doors on tuesday, struck a tentative deal that balanced the interests of banks, securities firms and insurance companies, according to senate aides who spoke on condition of anonymity. but the agreement fell apart almost immediately
the compromise would have given bank holding companies more securities powers, but restricted their ability to expand into insurance, the aides said. however, it fell apart when senators on opposite sides of the insurance issue realized they had a different understanding of the agreement, the aides said
sen. william proxmire, d-wis., the committee chairman, called another negotiating session for later in the day. an aide said the nature of the restriction on banks' ability to enter the insurance business remained the sticking point in the talks
legislation sponsored by proxmire and sen. jake garn of utah, the committee's senior republican, would repeal the 1933 glass-steagall act, which forbids commercial banks from underwriting and selling most securities. it was passed in the wake of the 1929 stock market crash to preserve the safety of the banking system
affiliates of bank holding companies would be allowed immediately to begin underwriting mortgage-backed securities, commercial paper, municipal revenue bonds and securities backed by consumer loans
power to underwrite corporate debt would be postponed until jan. 1 and corporate stock underwriting by bank affiliates would begin in 1990
sen. donald w. riegle jr., d-mich., chairman of the securities subcommittee, was advocating more restrictive legislation that would have required separate congressional votes in 1989, 1990 and 1991 before bank affiliates could underwrite corporate bonds, stocks and mutual funds
the tentative compromise, according to the aides, would have automatically phased in power over corporate bonds and mutual funds and required a separate vote in the future only on stock underwriting
sen. christopher dodd, a democrat from connecticut, where insurance companies are important employers, was pushing an amendment that would prohibit state-chartered banks owned by holding companies from further expansion into insurance
opposition from banks to dodd's amendment, if passed, could kill the entire bill, aides said, but some senators were reluctant to vote against the amendment for fear of retaliation from insurance interests within their states
one version of the compromise on insurance, as described by the aides, would have allowed a state to permit its banks to underwrite insurance within the state even if the holding company that owned the bank was headquartered out of state. however, banks would not be allowed to locate in a state with permissive laws and then ``export'' insurance to other states
a second, more restrictive, version of the compromise would require both the bank and its parent company to be located within a state before state officials could allow the bank to underwrite insurance
proxmire and garn opened the all-day session tuesday with a plea to fellow senators to ignore pressure from special interest lobbyists
we are not here to merely broker a compromise between the various providers of financial services,'' proxmire said
garn, looking at a hearing room packed with lobbyists, said, ``it's time to forget all of you and your special interests and your greed.''
the proxmire-garn bill has been endorsed by the heads of all the relevant regulatory agencies and by president reagan, but it faces substantial hurdles even beyond the senate committee before it can be enacted
reps. john dingell, d-mich., and fernand j. st germain, d-r.i., who will have jurisdiction over the issue in the house, have expressed considerable reluctance about broadening bank powers too much
general motors corp. has fired several employees and disciplined others for accepting gifts from a major tooling supplier in the late 1970s and early 1980s, a trade publication has reported
this week's edition of metalworking news identified lamb technicon corp. of warren as the subject of a gm investigation
gm disciplined employees who helped make decisions concerning tooling purchases and who accepted gifts from lamb technicon, metalworking news said. gifts included paid trips with lamb technicon salesmen to resort areas or hotels
darlene sandlin, a spokeswoman for lamb technicon, confirmed the company had been investigated by gm. she said the company issued new guidelines on ethics in 1984
gm officials, citing a policy against discussing individual personnel matters, refused comment
technicon recently was selected as a major tooling supplier for gm's saturn corp. car project in tennessee
gerald a. johnston, a top executive of the mcdonnell douglas astronautics co., was elected president of mcdonnell douglas corp. during a board of directors meeting wednesday, the company announced
johnston replaces john f. mcdonnell, who became chairman and chief executive officer of the corporation wednesday when the retirement of sanford n. mcdonnell became effective
sanford mcdonnell, 65, announced his retirement earlier this year
johnston, 56, had been serving as vice president and general manager of the astronautics facilities in huntington beach, calif. his promotion became effective immediately
johnston, who joined douglas aircraft co. in 1956 as an associate engineer, became vice president and general manager of strategic systems in 1986 and vice president and general manager of the huntington beach facilities last year
sanford mcdonnell will continue on the board of directors
