first republicbank dallas lost more than 8 percent of its deposits as customers withdrew $599 million in one week last month amid speculation about the financial health of its parent company, regulators said
the dallas bank is the lead institution of first republicbank corp., whose officials said the situation subsequently appeared to be stabilizing
the bank held average total deposits of $6.87 billion during the seven-day period ended feb. 24, down 8.7 percent from $7.47 billion the previous week and down $1.5 billion from the period including dec. 31, 1987
gerald fronterhouse, chairman and chief executive of first republic, said the one-week outflow of deposits at the dallas bank was ``unusual,'' but added that the bank's funding situation ``appeared to be stabilizing.''
during the week covered in the report by the federal reserve bank of dallas, the bank holding company was the subject of published reports that takeover or bailout negotiations were under way, and that its lead institution had suffered deposit outflows
a 55-member team supervised by the office of the comptroller of the currency began auditing first republicbank, which lost $656.8 million in 1987 and finished the year with $3.92 billion worth of problem assets. bank officials later denied that the negotiations were taking place
fronterhouse said the dallas bank's recent deposit loss ``reflects mainly the impact of earlier false rumors and extensive adverse publicity
by the middle of last week, the sources of funds for the dallas bank and for the corporation as a whole appeared to be stabilizing,'' fronterhouse said
the dollar strengthened against most major currencies wednesday. gold prices stagnated or rose slightly
foreign exchange dealers said the dollar firmed on two rumors: that the u.s. administration would allow the dollar to rise if american trade figures continue to improve and that the soviet union was buying dollars
in london, the dollar gained against the british pound when the state-run bank of england sold an undetermined amount of pounds to keep the currency below 3.0 west german marks as the mark fell against the dollar
at the end of the day, one pound cost $1.7680, cheaper than $1.7775 late tuesday
other late rates for the dollar in europe compared with late tuesday rates included: 1.6945 west german marks, up from 1.6855; 1.4005 swiss francs, up from 1.3915; 5.7345 french francs, up from 5.7065; 1.9013 dutch guilders, up from 1.8940; 1,247 italian lire, up from 1,244.35; 1.2558 canadian dollars, down from 1.2570
