john f. bookout, who has served as president and chief executive officer of shell oil co. since 1976, announced wednesday he is retiring effective june 30
frank h. richardson, executive vice president of products, will be nominated to the shell oil board of directors to succeed bookout, the company said
shell is wholly owned by the royal dutch-shell group of companies, which is based in both london and the hague, the netherlands
bookout joined the houston-based shell oil as a geologist in tulsa, okla., in 1950. he was elected president of shell canada ltd. in 1970 and returned to shell oil in 1974 as executive vice president of exploration and production
shell said one of bookout's principal achievements was putting into place 10 years ago a strategic planning that served the company well during the volatile conditions the oil industry has experienced
normal retirement for shell's senior management is at 60, but bookout, 65, was given two formal extensions, shell spokeswoman kitty borah said
bookout has not announced any future plans, she said. he was out of town on business and could not be reached for comment
shell also announced wednesday that charles w. wilson will replace richardson as executive vice president of products effective may 1. he previously was vice president of refining and marketing
richardson spent the first part of his shell oil career in the exploration and production organization. he became vice president of corporate planning in 1978, executive vice president of administration in 1982 and assumed his present position in 1983
wilson joined shell oil in 1963, becoming vice president of production in 1964 then moved to shell western e&amp;p inc. as president in 1987. he returned to shell oil in his present position late last year
sears, roebuck &amp; co. said wednesday it was beginning a three-year overhaul of its flagship merchandise group to make each segment of its retail business more competitive
the restructuring, which will trim an as-yet undertermined number of people from the merchandise group's management, will make sears stores more responsive to customer needs and wants, officials said
the apparel business will be run differently from the hardware business,'' said spokesman philo holland. ``you need different organizational structures to compete in different businesses.''
michael bozic, chairman and chief executive officer of the merchandising group, said in a statement that the restructuring would reduce the number of management levels, making each segment of sears' merchandise business leaner and more independent
we are competing in many diverse businesses, each with its own unique structure, and (we) have been essentially using one organizational format to compete in all of these businesses,'' bozic said
the changes we make will result in a company that is better structured to maintain its position as america's premier retailer.''
officials said they had no estimate of the number of employees to be affected or the cost savings involved, because they were only beginning the restructuring procss
the ultimate size and structure will be determined by how we choose to compete in the different businesses we are restructuring,'' holland said
he said the reduction in management personnel would be achieved through attrition and a severance offer of two weeks' salary for each year of service, up to a maximum of 52 weeks
employees at least 50 years old who have been with the company at least 10 years will also be offered early retirement benefits, holland said
the reorganization is widely seen as an attempt to revive sluggish sales and profits within the merchandise group, which accounts for nearly 60 percent of the company's revenues
the stock market settled for a small gain today after a broad early advance faded
analysts said the market was still benefiting from spreading confidence that a recession can be avoided despite the market's crash last autumn
one theoretical warning signal of a business slump was lifted tuesday, when the commerce department issued new figures on its index of leading economic indicators. with an upward revision of the december figure for the index from a decline to a gain, it no longer showed a string of three consecutive lower readings
brokers also noted that enthusiasm for stocks has been buoyed by a brisk pace of takeover activity
but with all that, they said, many investors still seemed leery of chasing after an advance that has carried the market to its highest levels since the crash
