cocoa futures prices set new life-of-contract lows for the fourth consecutive day wednesday on fears that the international cocoa organization will be unable to control the effects of steadily rising production
on other markets, grain and soybean futures retreated; livestock and meat were mixed; precious metals were slightly lower; energy futures were mostly lower; and stock-index futures advanced
no news from the international cocoa organization's week-long meeting in london was perceived as bad news on new york's coffee, sugar &amp; cocoa exchange, where prices for future delivery of cocoa settled as much as $35 a ton below tuesday's final prices
the market continues to try and absorb prospects for surplus production,'' said sandra kaul, an analyst in new york for shearson lehman hutton inc. ``it's falling pretty sharply.''
cocoa producer and consumer nations are meeting to discuss withholding cocoa from the market to support prices, ms. kaul said
icco buffer-stock buying, a price-support mechanism that was resumed in january after a six-month suspension, has already exhausted the allocation of 250,000 metric tons for the 1987-88 marketing year, she said
world cocoa production has risen steadily since 1986 and is expected to total more than 2 million metric tons this year
cocoa settled $31 to $35 lower with the contract for delivery in march at $1,563 a metric ton
grain and soybean futures finished lower on the chicago board of trade after an attempt to rally the soybean market failed, analysts said
wheat came under additional pressure from the agriculture department's revised auction program designed to lower surplus stocks
the usda announced after the close it had sold 10 million bushels of wheat, the agency's targeted amount, on tuesday. auctions also were scheduled for wednesday and friday, and three more are set for next week
