the financially troubled dunes casino hotel project here has been sold to a florida company with its own troubled history of lawsuits, cash shortages and federal investigations, federal documents show
the royale group ltd., a company in the hotel and real estate business, recently bought out nearly all the stock in the dunes, according to documents filed with the securities and exchange commission and the u.s. bankruptcy court and reviewed by the press of atlantic city
the dunes project at the southern end of the boardwalk stalled in 1979 when the owners ran out of money. its bare steel girders have stood rusting ever since
developer jack bona arrived in 1983 to rescue the casino but was forced to file for bankruptcy protection in august 1985
since then, bona has tried several other plans to raise money to pay off his debts, including a sale of shares and private deals with investors. all have failed
royale's chief executive officer since 1981 has been leonard pelullo, a leader in the effort to restore a strip of art deco-style hotels on miami beach
pelullo and bona have tried to keep the deal for the dunes quiet. a royale group ltd. vice president refers all questions about the sale to company attorneys, who say they cannot provide details
so far, no one in royale has said anything about how the company plans to raise the approximately $250 million needed to complete the casino hotel
royale has been trying to break into the atlantic city casino industry for a decade. then called cavanaugh communities corp., the company first bought marina land in 1978 but was unable to put together financing for a casino
documents obtained by the press from the sec and u.s. bankruptcy court say that boardwalk to bay inc., a royale subsidiary, has purchased 99 percent of the dunes stock from bona and has an option to buy the other 1 percent
pelullo and his companies have been involved in nearly three dozen separate lawsuits and actions by government agencies, according to company documents filed with the sec. many were filed by banks over the alleged failure to repay millions of dollars worth of loans, the newspaper reported
pelullo's business dealings spawned a u.s. grand jury investigation in 1986, the newspaper said. according to royale's sec filings, the investigation centers on the circumstances surrounding a $13 million mortgage granted to royale by a california savings and loan
atari corp. on wednesday said its earnings rose 57 percent to $18.7 million in the fourth quarter of 1987 and credited part of the jump to its october acquisition of the federated group inc. chain of retail electronics stores
other factors contributing to the increase included strengthened computer sales in europe and booming video game sales in the united states, said greg pratt, company spokesman
the fourth-quarter figure represented 32 cents a share, on revenue of $277 million. that compared with earnings of $11.9 million, or 22 cents per share, on revenue of $92.6 million in the same 1986 period
sales of televisions, stereos, microwave ovens and other electronics equipment at federated's 68 stores in california, arizona and texas accounted for 47 percent of revenues, or $130.6 million
profits for all of 1987 rose 76 percent to $44.1 million, or 76 cents per share, from $25 million, or 53 cents in 1986
sales rose 91 percent, increasing to $493 million in 1987 compared to $258 million the previous year
video games were obviously a hot category this year,'' said pratt. ``there were no teddy bears or laser guns to take those dollars away. people went back to more traditional stuff and bought video games.''
federated stores now acount for 25 percent of atari corp., one of the world's largest manufacturers of personal computers and video games
new home sales dropped sharply and factory orders slipped in january, according to government reports wednesday that reflected weakness in the economy
bond prices strengthened in a typical reaction to news of a sluggish economy. the yield on the treasury's key 30-year bond slipped to 8.31 percent from 8.35 percent
on wall street, stocks rose marginally as the dow jones average of 30 industrial stocks edged up 0.83 to 2,071.29
in washington, federal reserve chairman alan greenspan took another opportunity to calm concerns that the central bank would respond to political pressure and ease credit too much in an election year
greenspan told the senate budget committee that even if the fed wanted to drive down interest rates sharply, ``we would fail,'' because markets would likely resist such a move and ``would run away from us.''
greenspan also called for new efforts to cut the federal budget deficit, including a 15-cent gasoline tax and measures to trim social security and other entitlement programs
in spite of the news of sluggishness on wednesday, stock analysts said wall street was still taking courage from a report on tuesday by the commerce department on its index of leading economic indicators
with an upward revision of the december figure for the index from a decline to a gain, it no longer showed a string of three consecutive lower readings
new home sales fell 9 percent in january, pushing sales activity to its slowest pace since the end of the last recession, the commerce department said wednesday
a downturn in housing has often been the harbinger of the onset of a recession, but analysts said they believed falling mortgage rates offered the hope of a rebound in home sales in coming months
in a second lackluster economic report, the commerce department said orders for manufactured goods fell 0.6 percent in january to a seasonally adjusted $212.6 billion
while this was the first decline in five months, analysts noted that it followed an unusually large 2 percent december increase, a gain which reflected a big jump in demand for jet airplanes
analysts said the one-month setback did nothing to change their view that american manufacturers are continuing to enjoy a sales boom led by increased demand for exports
james christian, chief economist for the u.s. league of savings institutions, said with ``mortgage rates moving in the right direction'' sales for all of 1988 should end up only 3 percent below the 1987 sales pace
but other analysts said it remained to be seen whether the drop in mortgage rates will be enough to attract new buyers. they noted that sales have been strong for the past three years and a lot of pent-up demand has been exhausted
we simply don't have the demand for housing that we had in the first part of the rcovery,'' said michael sumichrast, an economist and publisher of a construction industry newsletter. ``the south, which accounts for almost half of all new homes sold, is still weak and you won't see any significant improvement until that area turns around.''
banks recorded their least profitable year since the great depression in 1987, but a top federal regulator said wednesday he sees better days ahead
the year-to-year drop in earnings was due entirely to large banks adding to reserves to cover anticipated losses on loans to third world countries, said l. william seidman, chairman of the federal deposit insurance corp
a commerce department report that showed a slide in january new-home sales provided further evidence of a housing industry slump following the stock market crash five months ago. last week the national association of realtors said sales of existing homes in january fell for the third straight month
nevertheless, sales vary widely around the country, reflecting regional economies, interest rates and demand, random ap telephone queries of realtors suggested. here is a brief description of housing markets in six areas:
boston: sales were stronger in the last three months of 1987 compared with a year earlier, and preliminary figures for early this year suggest stability. fixed-rate mortgage rates have fallen slightly to about 9.75 percent, while prices are up more than 6 percent above year-earlier levels
dallas: sales fell more than 30 percent in the last quarter of 1987 from the year earlier level. prices have risen in a range of 2 percent to 8 percent. fixed mortgage rates vary between 9 percent and 10 percent
kansas city: sales have fallen slightly but there is no clear-cut trend. mortgage rates have fallen from 10.5 percent to about 9.5 percent and prices have risen nearly 10 percent from a year earlier
southern california: sales have fallen about 3.3 percent from a year earlier. fixed rate mortgages are expected to fall to 9.5 percent from 9.75 percent. prices have risen between 1 percent and 2 percent from a year earlier
new york-new jersey: sales have slowed, and recent drops in mortgage rates to the 10 percent level are expected to stimulate the market. prices have remained about the same
philadelphia: sales have improved since the start of the year and mortgage rates have declined slightly to about 9.5 percent. prices have remained about the same
an evenly divided supreme court ruled wednesday that an airlines may be forced to continue to collect union dues from workers after its contract with employees has expired
the justices, by a 4-4 vote, upheld rulings that forced trans world airlines to continue the dues check-off after a strike by flight attendants in 1986
such splits automatically uphold lower court rulings but set no national precedent. the twa case carried little impact for most employers, anyway, because it involved an interpretation of the railway labor act, which only applies to the airlines and railroad industries
most private industry employers' labor relations are subject to the national labor relations act
nonetheless, vicki frankovich, president of the independent federation of flight attendants, said, ``we are extremely pleased with this result.''
the ruling was not accompanied by any written opinion or by any indication of how each individual justice voted
justice anthony m. kennedy, who only recently joined the court, did not participate in the case
twa and the independent federation of flight attendants had a three-year contract that expired july 31, 1984. prolonged negotiations followed but the union called a strike on march 7, 1986
the strike ended on may 17, 1986, when the flight attendants offered to return to work. only some 200 attendants had stayed out for the entire strike
twa hired 2,800 new attendants during the strike, and about 1,200 others either never joined the strike or returned to work during it
the airline then cancelled the dues-checkoff provision of the old contract, meaning that it no longer would collect union dues
but a federal judge, upheld by the 8th u.s. circuit court of appeals, ruled that the airline must honor the old contract's provisions
the appeals court said the railway labor act bars employers from unilaterally cancelling union security and dues check-offs contract provisions. any such changes must be made in negotiations between the employer and its workers, the appeals court said
television producer burt sugarman said tuesday he is considering waging a proxy fight for one of three class a seats on media general inc.'s board of directors as a next step in his effort to gain control of the company
it would be interesting to have a true outside director on the board,'' sugarman said in an interview with the richmond times-dispatch, which is owned by media general. ``i would look forward to serving on the board.''
david l. jordan, a media general vice president, said the company was prepared any proxy fight mounted by sugarman
sugarman controls 9.8 percent of media general's 28 million shares of class a common stock and has offered $61.50 per share for the remainder of the company's class a and class b stock, or a total of about $1.75 billion
the class a shares rose $2.75 to $49 a share tuesday on the new york stock exchange
media general has only 559,168 privately-held class b shares outstanding, but they have the power to elect seven of the company's 10 directors
holders of the publicly-traded class a stock elected three directors at last year's annual meeting, while holders of the class b stock elected six
about 71 percent of the class b shares are owned by chairman d. tennant bryan and vice chairman j. stewart bryan iii. the rest is owned by relatives and others closely associated with them and media general
any change in control of the company would require approval from two-thirds of the class b holders
it's easy for lawyers to say you can't do something, but others would say the structure isn't fair or right,'' sugarman said. ``the shareholders might revolt.''
sugarman had asked media general to respond to his buyout offer by friday. shortly after the offer came in, the bryans issued a statement saying their shares ``are not for sale, for any price.''
sugarman made his offer through two companies of which he is chairman: barris industries inc. of beverly hills, calif., which produces television game shows, and giant group ltd. of harleyville, s.c., which makes cement
media general owns a number of daily newspapers, including the richmond (va.) times-dispatch and news leader, the winston-salem (n.c.) journal and the tampa (fla.) tribune, plus 32 weeklies in southern california. it also has a 40 percent interest in garden state newspapers inc., the owner of 18 dailies and four weeklies in eight states
media general's television holdings include wcbd-tv in charleston, s.c., wjks-tv in jacksonville, fla., and wxfl-tv in tampa
a pilots' union filed suit wednesday to stop eastern airlines from transferring aircraft to orion air in the latest legal move to block the transfer of eastern assets by its parent texas air corp
the air line pilots association's request for a temporary restraining order was made at federal court in washington
orion, a cargo carrier based in raleigh, n.c., has asked the federal aviation administration for certification to fly 26 eastern planes on eastern routes by april 1
i don't think there is any question that this is a blatant union-busting attempt,'' alpa spokesman ron cole said tuesday
eastern spokesman robin matell declined to comment on the suit wednesday. but a day earlier, company spokeswoman karen ceremsak said the airline had contracted with orion ``to protect itself against alpa'' in the event that its pilots refused to cross picket lines during a possible machinists union strike
eastern is in federal mediation on its contract with the machinists, the largest of its three unions
the unions earlier protested the spinoff of eastern's northeast shuttle as a separate texas air subsidiary and the airline's year-old call for $490 million in labor cuts
the carrier lost $182 million in 1987 following a $131 million loss in 1986. eastern cited those losses in firing 3,500 workers last november and another 600 in january
alpa charged there was evidence miami-based eastern may go through with the orion transfer, which it said violates its contract, even if a strike is averted
meanwhile, a group called the committee for positive action blasted rep. richard gephardt, d-mo., for his criticism of eastern management
a letter dated march 1 and signed by 11 eastern reservation agents and airport agents from across the country accused the presidential candidate of trying to ``achieve political gain at the expense of our company and jobs.''
during a miami visit last friday, gephardt said eastern cared more about ``quick paper profits'' than its employees and that its management decisions reflect ``the dismantling of a great corporation.''
